a chain-smoker who had been ordered by a judge not to puff in front of her children won the right to light up again
the appeals division of the state supreme court granted a stay of the order tuesday, permitting 41-year-old elizabeth roofeh to smoke in the presence of her husband and children pending a hearing scheduled for september
mrs. roofeh said wednesday she already is trying to kick the habit
i was only doing it (smoking) to annoy my husband,'' mrs. roofeh, who is seeking a divorce, said as she left for her first session at a non-smoking clinic. ``i'm coughing like crazy. i don't think it's good for the kids.''
mrs. roofeh's husband, jahanshan, an orthopedic surgeon, went to court last year, arguing that her smoking is harmful to their children, ages 6, 7 and 9. he said he tried unsuccessfully for 12 years to get her to curtail her habit
last month, judge ralph diamond ordered mrs. roofeh to confine her smoking to a small room in the couple's six-bedroom home. her attorney, joel brandes, appealed, contending such an order is unconstitutional
roofeh's attorney, stephen schissell, had no comment on the stay. woes</head>
being a second-string quarterback can be hard on business, as the washington redskins' jay schroeder has discovered
schroeder, backup to starter doug williams, says the restaurant operating in this washington suburb under his name ``was a business venture that didn't work out.''
the owners of j. schroeder's all-pro restaurant recently decided to close the eatery because of mounting debts. schroeder allowed his name to be used for the establishment in exchange for a small percentage of its profit and an agreement to appear there several times a week. he declined to discuss the closing, saying the restaurant's problems were ``for me to know.''
schroeder lost his position as the skins' starting quarterback in midseason last year. the skins went on to win the super bowl under williams
having the second-string quarterback's name on the restaurant did not help business,'' said bruce sandground, general manager at the sign of the whale, another falls church restaurant
former redskins' quarterback joe theismann owns three restaurants in the area that bear his name. but theismann began his career as a restaurateur just as his career was beginning to take off, while the opening of j. schroeder's last year coincided with schroeder's slump
schroeder said he was looking into other business opportunities
an ohio woman who watched a tv show on unsolved crimes supplied the tip that led to the arrest of a man wanted in the poisoning death of a california beauty queen, authorities said
steven paul mack, 39, was arrested without incident in this salt lake city suburb after a dozen squad cars closed in on his car tuesday, said police sgt. bill brusik. mack was being held at salt lake county jail on $500,000 bail
authorities in sacramento, calif., had been seeking mack, 39, in the slaying of karen grace winslett, 21, of carmichael, calif
winslett had won the title of miss english leather in las vegas, nev., shortly before she disappeared in 1987. her body was found 12 days later in her car, parked behind a north sacramento motel
detectives said she died of a large dose of percodan, a pain killer. they said mack was linked to the crime by physical and other evidence that the detectives would not detail
sacramento county sheriff's sgt. tennise allen credited the sunday night showing of fox broadcasting co.'s ``america's most wanted'' with bringing about mack's arrest
following the show, an employee of a country club in marion, ohio, called her local sheriff's department to say she recognized mack as having once worked at the club
she also recalled having received a telephone call from someone in utah in february asking for a man named sean paul lanier. a check of club personnel records had showed no one by that name had worked there
salt lake city police were alerted, and mack was arrested after he left a home been purchased by a sean paul lanier in november, authorities said. was unarmed and taken by surprise
the arrest is the fourth of an escapee or suspect stemming from the show, according to fox
mack, a forger and burglar who served two prison terms and was paroled in 1985, sells novelties and sports and clothing items, authorities said
sacramento police also said mack is a suspect in a similar slaying of a 19-year-old woman in marion county, ohio
in all, the ``america's most wanted'' episode generated 170 calls on a toll-free number shown on the screen
the show, which premiered earlier this year, has as its host john walsh, who has been active in the movement for better police efforts to trace missing children since his son, adam, was abducted and slain
another arrest stemming from the show was that of a murderer who had escaped from an indiana prison in 1986 was found last month working as a supervisor at a homeless shelter in new york city
a tough year for farmers is in the wind _ that is, if an old comanche indian legend holds true
according to the legend, the wind direction at precisely sunrise on the day after the first day of spring will tell what kind of weather and farming conditions the next year will hold for the region
if the wind, called taba'na yuna'e in comanche, comes from the east or northeast, good harvests should follow; if it blows from the north or northwest, conditions will be average. a west or southwest wind doesn't bode well, and a south wind is just plain bad news
records on the annual ceremony are said to show a 92 percent success rate since 1906, the first year settlers gathered to see what the winds had in store
chief'' frank runkles, who has been performing the ceremony for 15 years, began his dance tuesday with supplications to wakantanka, the father spirit, and mikeana, mother earth, as well as the winds
the mother earth is revered because she gives us food to eat,'' he said. ``wakantanka is the great father above _ we seek his blessings.''
as he spoke, a southerly wind blew so hard that indian dancers from an amarillo boy scout explorer post had to shield a ceremonial fire as it was ignited
the gusts died down as sunrise neared. seconds before runkles caught the first glimpse of the sun over the distant horizon, a gust whisked in from the north, then reversed direction at the moment of sunrise, giving an official reading of west-southwest _ bad news for farmers
despite the indians' claims of predictive accuracy, however, farmers don't necessarily need to worry
last year, smoke from runkles' fire indicated a south wind and poor conditions, but southern plains farmers ended up with one of the best cotton harvests on record
above a pawn shop in downtown toronto, patti labelle rips into a group of lackadaisical brooklyn high school students
in her first major dramatic role, the pop star is playing an inspirational teacher in a movie musical based on sing, the annual song-and-dance competition in brooklyn's schools
the legendary program at such schools as erasmus hall gave rise to such talents as barbra streisand and neil diamond. but with the urban decay of the past decade, only a dozen schools now take part
the struggle to preserve that old brooklyn spirit has inspired the film, ``sing,'' with a plot centered on education board plans to close a beloved high school where generations of immigrants got their start
with songs from the writer of ``footloose'' and ``fame'' and a tempestuous love story between a street-smart italian kid and a jewish princess, the tri-star pictures production now shooting in toronto is scheduled for release in february 1989
i'm hooked on it. i'm one of those people who think about community and pulling together and family,'' said labelle, the rhythm and blues artist who first hit the pop charts in the 1960s with the blue bells and later in the '70s with the trio labelle. she has appeared in two previous films, ``a soldier's story'' and the tv movie ``unnatural causes.''
in ``sing,'' she plays mrs. devere, an adviser who shakes her junior class students out of apathy
she's very uplifting to the kids,'' labelle said between takes of her chart-targeted big number, ``total concentration,'' in which she demonstrates how to put over a song
producer craig zadan and screenwriter-lyricist dean pitchford, who won an academy award for ``fame,'' said they created the part with labelle in mind and waited until she found time to do it
there's a real honesty there, nothing phony about her. in her own way she's lived through what this teacher has gone through,'' said pitchford
labelle has charmed the crew by introducing them to her own home cooking _ fried chicken and potato salad. but she's not sure about life as an actress
i'm not a cher. i don't know if i'd have enough patience to do another movie,'' she said, complaining about the number of retakes. ``it hurts enough some times that you want to cry. i like to perform live.''
however, director richard baskin, who co-produced streisand's landmark ``broadway album'' and is making his first feature film, said labelle looked great in the first rushes
co-stars include lorraine bracco who played tom berenger's wife in ``someone to watch over me,'' louise lasser of ``mary hartman, mary hartman'' fame and george dicenzo who was rob lowe's boss in ``about last night.'' the young lovers are peter dobson and jessica steen
for co-producer neil meron, a brooklyn and sing alumnus, the project is a labor of love
in the high school i went to, sing no longer exists,'' meron lamented. ``brooklyn is one of the oldest communities in america, and the way those communities found to express themselves was through music and dance.''
to research the film, the production team talked with veteran teachers in brooklyn and attended a sing performance at midwood high school where faculty member bella tillis launched the program in 1947
sing competitions involved reviews or skits created and staged by a committee from each class. the musical skits were judged on sing night when freshmen, sophomores, juniors and seniors got to strut their stuff. in the 1950s and '60s, when sing was at its peak, the competitions were fierce
lyricist pitchford also found inspiration in england, where he's been working with the royal shakespeare co. on the broadway-bound musical, ``carrie.''
after `fame' the last thing i wanted to do was another high school film set in new york about kids who sing and dance,'' he said
but england has tradition and history we can only approximate in america. the closest thing to that kind of longevity is in east coast settlements like brooklyn. sing became a metaphor for that tradition
i developed an enormous affection for sing and the neighborhoods of brooklyn and a real despair for the passing of this tradition.''
new discoveries by american archaeologists indicate that humans could have settled on cyprus around 9000 b.c., 1,500 years earlier than previously thought
the finds also indicate that some species of ancient animals survived here at least 1,000 years after they were believed to have become extinct
if proven correct, the discoveries mean that cyprus was one of the earliest human settlements north of africa, along with the island of corsica, also in the mediterranean
if these dates are corroborated, the site will have provided by far the earliest archaeological evidence for island colonization anywhere in the mediterranean,'' dr. stuart swiny, director of the cyprus american archaeological research institute, reported in a recent lecture
scientists had previously dated man's arrival on cyprus around 7500 b.c
but archaelogists digging on a slope near the sprawling british air base at akrotiri on cyprus' south coast recently found pygmy hippopotamus and dwarf elephant bones, some mixed with shells, flint and ash
archaelogists believe the flint, an early cutting tool, was used to slice meat from the animals. the ash indicated cooking fires
carbon dating placed the remains at around 9000 b.c., a millenium after those species of animals were believed to have died out
swiny said that the animals, common to many mediterranean islands thousands of years ago, were wiped out by climatic changes during the last ice age that ended around 12,000 years ago
we thought ... these animals died out because of natural causes _ they couldn't get enough food or enough water,'' swiny said in an interview after the lecture
but now it looks as if man was also responsible for wiping them out.''
the akrotiri excavation is sponsored by the university of nevada and the american schools of oriental research, which sponsors the cyprus american institute. the dig is under the direction of dr. alan simmons, who currently is in nevada
the original discovery was made in 1980 by a british security officer at akrotiri, maj. brian pile, then a lieutenant, while he was training his men to seek out unusual objects
underground excavation at the site, eight miles south of the port city of limassol, started last july and will continue this summer
swiny said the actual age of the site will remain questionable until results of further tests are obtained
the finds are only some of the important discoveries unearthed by american archaeologists in the last few years on cyprus, the center of trade routes between europe and the middle east for centuries
the island is studded with relics of a history that spans more than 10,000 years, during which more than a dozen civilizations, including achaean greeks, egyptians, romans, armenians, venetians and ottoman turks left their imprint
americans are involved in six of the 20 digs currently being made in the greek-controlled southern part of cyprus
the cyprus american institute provides logistical help at one sponsored by brandeis university, of waltham, mass., at the late bronze age town of kalavasos-ayios dhimitrios, 18 miles northeast of limassol
it was one of the biggest bronze age settlements on cyprus and a center for the island's ancient copper trade. cyprus is the phoenician word for copper
last summer archaelogists uncovered the remains of a 13th century b.c. building, covering more than 10,764 square feet and once at least two stories high, that was apparently destroyed by fire
it's the biggest and most important building at the site and one of the biggest of that period in cyprus,'' said dr. alison south todd, the dig's co-director
we also found some inscriptions which are very rare to the period in cypro-minoan script,'' she added
cypro-minoan, which resembles the script used in minoan crete 4,000 years ago, has never been deciphered
the presence of these inscriptions and the huge storage capacity of the building, known as building x, suggest it was either a palace or a town hall
the storage room, more than 60 feet long and 24 feet wide, consists of an outer wall and six stone pillars that once supported the roof
the shards of at least 47 jars, some once as tall as six feet, have been found. all apparently had been smashed in the fire. but six intact jars were later discovered in pits below the floor
todd discovered a tomb, considered one of the richest and best preserved ever found on cyprus, while digging an exploratory trench out from the building
the oval-shaped tomb contained the skeletons of three young women, a child about 3 years old and three infants. they apparently had social status and wealth
the women had been buried with gold and silver jewelry, bronze and bone artifacts, containers of wine with small cups inside and cylindrical ivory cosmetic boxes. reports</head>
an experimental treatment for enlarged prostate glands shows promise as an outpatient alternative to surgery that hospitalizes about 400,000 american men a year, researchers say
an enlarged prostate makes urination difficult by constricting the urinary tract, and the experimental procedure widens the narrowed portion by inflating a balloon, said flavio castaneda of the university of minnesota
test results show complete or significant resolution of the urination problem in about 80 percent of patients with the most common type of enlargement, he said
the half-hour procedure is done with only a local anesthetic and without an overnight stay in the hospital, he said
standard surgery requires general anesthesia or a spinal injection that numbs the lower part of the body, and a hospital stay of several days
the prostate is a walnut-sized gland that surrounds the urine-carrying urethra. in older men, it frequently enlarges and puts pressure on the urethra, making urination more difficult
the experimental technique is to be described thursday by castaneda's colleague, wilfrido castaneda-zuniga, at a meeting of the society of cardiovascular and interventional radiology in orlando, fla
more than 60 patients have been treated with the experimental procedure, called balloon urethroplasty, at the university of minnesota, castaneda said in a recent telephone interview
the patient takes a tranquilizer and the urethra is numbed with local anesthetic. a thin, flexible tube with the balloon on its tip is inserted into the urethra and guided to the narrowed portion, where the balloon is inflated
for the minnesota patients, the urination problem was erased or significantly eased in almost 80 percent of cases in which most enlargement was from the side lobes of the prostate, rather than the middle lobe, castanada said. most patients have predominant enlargement of side lobes, he said
when the main problem was the middle lobe, the success rate dropped to about 30 percent to 40 percent, he said
no recurrence of symptoms has been seen in any patient helped by the procedure, he said. forty-eight have been followed for more than six months after the procedure, including one followed for three years, he said
we're at this point unable to know how long it (symptom relief) will last on the average,'' castaneda said
abraham cockett, professor and chairman of the urology department at the university of rochester medical center in new york, called the concept interesting
but he said more patients must be studied, and for periods longer than at least a year following the procedure, to better assess its effectiveness
removing prostate tissue with standard surgery relieves symptoms for some 15 years, said cockett, who is secretary of the american urological association
in another presentation at the meeting thursday, participants are to discuss an experimental alternative to removing gallbladders
about 500,000 gallbladders are removed in the united states annually. gallstones are the most frequent reason, said eric martin, director of cardiovascular and interventional radiology at the columbia-presbyterian medical center in new york
in two patients, italian scientists have instead guided a flexible tube through the skin and into the gallbladder, used it to remove gallstones and injected a solution to turn the gallbladder into scar tissue
i still think it needs a lot of work, but it's exciting,'' said martin
he noted that machines called lithotripters, now used to pulverize kidney stones, are also being studied for destroying gallstones
it is too early to tell how lithotripters and the surgical technique tried in italy will fit in to future management of gallbladder disease, he said
a ostrich farmer thinks county commissioners may have their heads in the sand for failing to agree that an ostrich has as much value as a turkey
the dispute is over an ohio law that allows farmers to be reimbursed by the county if dogs kill their farm animals
michael erwin of morrow filed a $600 claim for two ostriches killed by dogs
but warren county commissioners said tuesday damages can be collected only on animals that provide meat, eggs, or feathers, and ostriches didn't
no one could think of any (agricultural value of the ostrich),'' said commission president george terwilleger
he invited erwin to appeal, and erwin said he would
i think that ostrich farming has as much credibility as cattle farming or sheep farming,'' said erwin, 32
he said ostrich hides and feathers are sold in ohio, and he plans to breed ostriches for meat. he said the meat is more of a bargain than turkey
you get a lot more bird for your money.''
one of two drug charges against john zaccaro jr., the son of 1984 vice presidential candidate geraldine ferraro, has been dismissed for lack of evidence
district judge francis mccaffrey on monday threw out a charge of possession of cocaine with intent to sell
after zaccaro's 1986 arrest, mccaffrey ruled inadmissible eight grams of cocaine and records of drug transactions seized by police from zaccaro's car. the judge said at the time that the search warrant was based on insufficient evidence
zaccaro still faces an april 4 trial on a charge of selling a quarter-gram of cocaine to a state trooper while zaccaro was a student at middlebury college
mccaffrey also said defense attorneys cannot claim at the trial that zaccaro was a victim of selective prosecution because the issue does not relate to guilt or innocence
oscar the grouch, the guru of garbage on television's ``sesame street,'' has been asked to remove all recyclables from his trash can home
the famous character on the long-running pbs-tv children's show recently received a letter from paula s. barnabie, who works for the camden county office of solid waste
every day, ms. barnabie wrote, the clank of aluminum, the crunch of newspapers and the tinkle of glass can be heard as oscar fights his way to the surface of his trash can to snarl at sesame street residents
i watch the program every day with my nephew and i just couldn't take it any more,'' she said. ``it would be so much nicer and environmentally sound for you to have a recycling bucket near your trash can.''
camden county will even give the tetchy titan of trash one of its brand new recycling buckets, she informed oscar. the bright yellow buckets ``can be dirtied up in no time flat'' to match the rest of his dirty, dented decor, she said
the producers of sesame street are considering ms. barnabie's suggestions, said gail y. miyasaki, a spokeswoman for children's television workshop, the show's producer
ms. barnabie said she has not heard from oscar, however
if he recycled, he'd be able to find a pen and paper in that can to write back to me,'' she said. ``i hope he doesn't tell me to go `scram.''' 
don bailey's face and burt reynolds' body have been sprawled across the side of a warehouse for 10 years, but city commissioner vicki coceano says she wants to beautify the area _ starting with bailey
the 19-foot wide mural on bailey's carpet store has bailey's head superimposed on reynolds' body _ a takeoff on the actor's centerfold pose in cosmopolitan magazine several years ago. the body reclining on a shag rug is nude except for flesh-tone bikini trunks
he needs to be dressed or he needs to get off the rug,'' ms. coceano said tuesday
the issue arose when the commission rejected bailey's request for a variance to expand his store. ms. coceano said the city has chosen to start its beautification program with him
people know me for this sign,'' bailey said. ``i'll put a dark swimsuit on this next time, but skimpier.''
suzanne carrell beat a filing deadline by 10 minutes to become a candidate for town moderator, a job most residents had forgotten existed and which rarely has any duties
the unpaid job calls for her to moderate at town meetings, if they ever are called under telluride's custom-made home-rule charter, which gives either the town council or residents the right to call a town meeting twice a year
there have been only three such town meetings in the last nine years, although there was an attempt to call one last year. that failed for lack of a quorum
it is not a job with a lot of use,'' confirmed town clerk leslie sherlock, who admitted forgetting about the opening until someone brought it to her attention for this year's election
carrell, who works in a liquor store and a bookstore, said she decided to file for the post on tuesday because she didn't have the time to serve on the town council
but she said she was surprised to learn she may not have any work to do
transportation secretary james h. burnley iv says the federal aviation administration sometimes needs ``the bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod'' to move on safety issues
in an unusual condemnation of an agency by the cabinet officer who oversees it, burnley accused the faa of frequently harboring ``institutional resistance'' when the time comes to move harshly against the nation's aviation industry
at times, he said, ``it has been necessary to use the bureaucratic equivalent of a cattle prod to get the faa to take needed safety actions.''
burnley blamed the problem on the agency's structure and not its employees. the faa is charged with writing and enforcing safety regulations for u.s. aviation, running the nation's air traffic control system and promoting american air commerce
because the faa is charged with promoting and protecting the industry's commercial interests, it is sometimes reluctant to take safety and enforcement actions that impose significant costs and burdens on that industry,'' burnley told the senate aviation subcommittee
as an example, burnley said faa officials and industry representatives opposed a 1986 proposal that airline and airport employees be screened by security devices, arguing that the plan was ``too burdensome.'' even when the proposal was changed, the faa delayed implementing the proposal for a year, he said
two weeks ago, burnley told reporters the faa was not being strict enough in punishing airlines whose employees did not effectively screen passengers for weapons. he sent faa administrator allan mcartor a memo march 8 asking him ``to give his personal attention to this matter.'' mcartor agreed, burnley said wednesday
often it takes someone from outside the organization to insist that there may be ways to enhance safety that are being overlooked,'' he said
burnley said the faa ``is filled with competent, dedicated professionals'' who are placed in ``an inherently untenable position'' by the agency's structure
asked after the hearing if he believed mcartor was responsible for any of the agency's problems, he said, ``allan's doing a fine job, doing an outstanding job.''
in a statement, mcartor said the faa is taking steps to improve its efficiency. ``the current system for dealing with aviation issues is too slow and cumbersome,'' he said
the faa has been criticized by some lawmakers in recent years for failing to move quickly enough to expand the number of air traffic controllers and for a lack of aggressiveness in making other safety improvements
sen. wendell ford, d-ky., chairman of the aviation panel, has introduced legislation that would make the faa an independent agency in hopes of giving it the ability to respond more quickly to problems
burnley said the faa could do a better job if its promotional duties and the air traffic control system were removed from its responsibilities. the agency should continue overseeing safety as a part of the transportation department, he said, so, ``if you don't get what you want out of an administrator, there's a secretary you can collar.''
the united states is losing influence in africa by letting its military aid to the continent drop to an unprecedented low while the soviets provide 17 times as much assistance, administration officials say
sudan has asked the united states to remove its emergency military stockpiles and facilities, and somalia has rejected the visit of a top-level military delegation, the officials say
u.s. military aid levels to africa this year have dropped to an unprecedented low of $25.2 million, said deputy assistant secretary of defense james l. woods
we have since last year lost our prepositioning rights in one important african country, and have had important military'' negotiations canceled in another, woods told the house subcommittee on foreign operations wednesday
although he declined to name either country, another official who spoke only on condition he not be named identified the first country as sudan. he said the non-aligned government of sadiq mahdi was unwilling to honor political arrangements made by his predecessor gaafar nimeiri, who was deposed in april 1985
u.s. relations with sudan, strategically placed in eastern africa on the red sea coast, have been strained by sudan's warming ties with libya
as a result of congressional budget cuts, as well as the less cordial ties with the khartoum government, u.s. military aid to sudan was canceled in fiscal 1988, along with six other african countries. the administration will seek a renewal of the aid for fiscal 1989, said the official
somalia, upset with a drop of its military aid to $5 million from some $20 million in 1986, rejected a visit by a high-level u.s. military delegation, the official said. but the visit will probably be rescheduled, he added
woods warned that if the military aid for africa remains at the current level, ``we can no longer operate a meaningful aid program to africa.''
the administration has asked for $740 million in economic and development aid for africa next year and $83.7 million in military assistance
assistant secretary of state chester crocker told the panel that ``the perception in africa is that we're opting out. and that creates strains.'' u.s. military aid to africa accounts for only 3 percent of the total military assistance to the continent, crocker said
in contrast, the soviet union has poured $15 billion into african states since 1980, more than 17 times the u.s. input, he said
in addition, the soviets maintain 6,500 military advisers in africa, and cuba has some 45,000 troops there, most of them in angola
properly funded, the (u.s. military aid) program reduces reliance on soviet bloc hardware and advisers,'' woods said
trade minister ariel sharon warned that palestinian violence could lead to war with neighboring arab states, in which case israel might expel palestinians from its occupied lands and from israel itself
he made the comment thursday, when israeli security forces shot and killed another two palestinians and seven were reported wounded in clashes throughout the occupied west bank
israeli troops also rounded up hundreds of arabs in an attempt to silence the leaders of the four-month uprising, arab sources said
in lebanon, israeli warplanes divebombed palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of sidon for almost an hour, the second air raid in two days. israel radio quoted lebanese sources as saying 30 people were killed in the attack
also thursday, the labor party re-elected foreign minister shimon peres as its leader and candidate for the premiership. he said he would appeal to the nation to support the u.s.-initiated peace process _ in essence an exchange of land for peace with the arabs
in the balata refugee camp near nablus, border policemen opened fire on demonstrators throwing rocks, concrete blocks and iron bars at them. two protesters were killed, the army and the israeli news agency itim reported
a palestinian was shot in the leg and three border policemen were injured by rocks in the clash, itim reported
thursday's fatalities raised the palestinian death toll to 109 by u.n. count since violence broke out in the occupied territories dec. 8. one israeli soldier has been killed
sharon told journalists in tel aviv that, by failing to halt the disturbances at their onset, israel had lost its deterrent capability. as a result, he said, arab states could launch a surprise attack against israel
the hawkish former general, a leader of the right-wing likud bloc, hinted that in such a war, israel might expel palestinians and israeli arabs
sharon referred to israel's first prime minister, david ben gurion, saying ben gurion refused to allow arabs who fled the country during the 1948 middle east war to return to their homes
the rule that ben gurion determined then applies now too,'' sharon said. ``those who began the war in december 1987 must remember that they are fully responsible for its results ... remember this well, not just the residents of (the west bank towns of) halhoul and qalqilyeh but also those of jaffa (in israel) and (israeli-annexed arab east) jerusalem.''
peres, who was re-elected by an overwhelming majority of the labor party's 1,250-member central committee, accused the likud of frightening the nation into believing yielding occupied territories would threaten israel's existence
we will opt for a political solution,'' he said. ``the camp of intimidation rejects any political solution. the camp of hope believes in such a solution.''
speaking at the same party gathering, defense minister yitzhak rabin said: ``peace is a more central element of security than (occupied) territories.''
in other developments thursday, israeli troops converted west bank schools into detention centers as they continued a campaign of mass arrests in the west bank and gaza strip, which israel seized in the 1967 middle east war
among those detained in the overnight roundups thursday were several palestinians allegedly responsible for drafting and publishing the latest underground leaflets, police ministry spokesman nahum mendel said
he declined to say how many suspects were arrested
in the west bank city of hebron, an islamic official said israeli troops detained about 200 imams, or moslem relgious leaders, in nighttime roundups this week. the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said most of those held were members of the fundamentalist islamic jihad movment
in gaza, israeli officials rounded up at least 15 palestinians wednesday night, bringing to more than 110 the number of arabs arrested there in the last four days, the gaza lawyers' association said
meanwhile, the roman catholic patriarch of jerusalem decided to suspend the palm sunday procession because of the possibility of violence along its narrow, winding route through arab east jerusalem, said the rev. caudio baratto, director of the christian information center
in another development, the government temporarily banned publication of israel's communist party daily, al ittihad
amos gilboa, prime minister yitzhak shamir's adviser on arab affairs, said the 40-year-old newpaper's ``statements had become far more extreme... and completely changed in character,'' since the anti-occupation unrest began
the communist party has four representatives in parliament. it has organized demonstrations and protests against israel's handling of the unrest and in favor of a palestinian state to replace the occupied territories' military government
two passenger trains collided thursday in a shanghai suburb, killing 27 japanese students on a school trip, the japanese embassy said. other reports said more than 100 other people were injured
china's official xinhua news agency said one of the trains had ignored a stop signal when it left shanghai station
there were discrepancies in death and injury reports. foreign ministry officials in tokyo, citing reports from the japanese consulate in shanghai, said the death toll of 27 included a victim that was possibly chinese
a total of 47 japanese and 57 chinese passengers were injured in the crash, government officials in tokyo said
shigekazu sato, an official with the japanese embassy in beijing, said the injured included 36 people from gakugei high school in southern japan's kochi prefecture
the crash, in the shanghai suburb of fengbang, occurred at 2 p.m. when a northbound train leaving shanghai for hangzhou collided with a southbound train arriving from changsha, said fu fenghao, spokesman for the shanghai foreign affairs office
fu said it had not been determined if there were other foreigners on the train
the departing train's first two cars and the luggage car of the other train were knocked off the tracks. most of the victims appeared to be in the first cars of the departing train, fu said
xinhua said the departing train ``rolled out of the kuangxiang station, ignoring the prohibiting signal, and collided with the train that was entering the station.''
kazuyoshi shoji at the japanese consulate in shanghai said one of the dead japanese was hideo shimomura, identified by television stations in tokyo as a 16-year-old student
the 193-member gakugei high school group was traveling on the hangzhou-bound train. shoji said the group was in the car immediately behind the engine
we were playing cards and suddenly there was a loud bang, and things went flying all over the floor,'' said an unidentified male student interviewed in shanghai by the japan broadcasting corp
there was a huge bump, and then one of our teachers came into the car and told us to get out,'' said another student. ``we broke the windows and climbed out.''
the train tracks were blocked seven hours after the accident, fu said. he said soldiers, police and medical workers took the dead and injured to nearby hospitals and that investigators were at the scene
it was china's fourth fatal train accident this year. three train accidents killed 141 people in january
lawmakers are crediting the budget summit accord between congressional leaders and the white house for the bipartisan ease with which the house sent a $1.1 trillion budget for fiscal 1989 to the senate
the spending plan, which alters some of the domestic priorities president reagan had included in his own proposed package last month, was approved 319-102 on wednesday by the democratic-controlled house. in contrast to last year, when budget writers toiled several weeks longer amid staunch opposition by republicans, gop lawmakers this time voted 92-78 for the resolution
i think it would have been impossible without the summit,'' rep. delbert latta of ohio, ranking republican on the house budget committee, said afterward
democrats and republicans in the house are trying to work together,'' said rep. william h. gray iii, d-pa., chairman of the budget panel
the spending plan would produce a deficit of $134 billion. it would thus avoid spending cuts that would be required under the gramm-rudman balanced-budget law should the deficit miss the 1989 deficit target of $136 billion by more than $10 billion
to achieve that $134 billion figure, however, lawmakers agreed to use economic forecasts made by the administration. had the legislators used the more pessimistic projections from their own congressional budget office, there would be $35 billion more in red ink, triggering spending slashes that are considered particularly untidy in an election year
shortly after the dow jones industrial average plunged 508 points last oct. 19, administration officials and congressional leaders held four weeks of closed-door bargaining aimed at slashing the federal deficit
the pact they emerged with last nov. 20 set broad outlines for federal budgets for fiscal 1988, which ends sept. 30, and for fiscal 1989
their agreement settled in advance many of the disputes that typically spawn bitter, long-running debates among lawmakers, such as over how much money the government should spend for defense, domestic and foreign assistance programs, and whether new taxes are necessary
the 1989 budget resolution approved by the house precisely met those summit targets, according to budget committee numbers
thus, the package provides $299.5 billion for the pentagon in budget authority, the amount up to which the military can commit itself in new contracts, and $294 billion in outlays, or money to actually be spent next year
in addition, it provides $148.1 billion in budget authority and $169.2 billion in outlays for domestic programs that are not controlled by automatic formulas. and it allows $18.1 billion in budget authority and $16.1 billion in outlays for foreign aid
the $14 billion in new 1989 taxes called for by the summit have already been enacted into law. lawmakers envision no additional taxes for the year
the budget would grant a hefty increase to space and science programs, although only about half as much as reagan wanted. it would also grant major increases in spending for education, the homeless, battling drugs and research and testing for aids
the legislators ignored reagan's proposals to end federal assistance to amtrak, the northeast passenger railroad, and to some development programs, and his effort to dramatically slash aid to mass transit programs
most federal agencies would be given a bit less money than they would need to keep up with inflation. but many urban and rural aid programs such as the farmers home administration's rural development grants and loans, which reagan had slated for substantial cuts, would receive the same amounts of money as this year
and many programs geared toward helping low-income people, such as job training, would receive enough money to keep up with the rising cost of living
military and civilian federal employees would be granted 3 percent pay raises
the budget resolution does not require presidential approval and sets spending targets. the actual money will have to be provided in later legislation
senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., said wednesday he did not expect full senate action on the budget before the second week of april
representatives of states vying for the superconducting super collider are seeking only about one-third of the funding initially planned for the project next year, in what they describe as a bow to political reality
rep. carl pursell, r-mich., said wednesday that lawmakers from six of the seven states still in the running for the $4.4 billion physics research complex agreed to press for around one-third of the $363 million requested by president reagan in his 1989 budget
representatives from the seven states formed a task force last week to support the project, which has been attacked by congressional critics as likely to siphon away money needed for research in other areas. the dispute comes as both congress and the white house are trying to reduce the federal budget deficit
during a private meeting, the representatives discussed funding ``somewhere around the bottom of $100 million plus,'' pursell said. ``we have not fixed on exact figures.''
they also discussed target dates in their drive to ensure that the project survives congressional budget cuts, pursell said
as long as we've got good support from the leadership, we're sure we can get through the budget process,'' pursell said
the representatives will meet soon with house speaker jim wright of texas and house minority leader robert michel of illinois to discuss appropriations, pursell said
officials have predicted that the super collider, centered on a 53-mile-round particle accelerator, will produce 4,000 jobs and have an annual operating budget of about $280 million
physicists at the center will study subatomic particles and the physical nature of the universe
states that remain in the running for the project are arizona, colorado, illinois, michigan, north carolina, tennessee and texas
arizona was unrepresented at wednesday's meeting, pursell said
the energy department has said it plans to decide in november where to build the super collider
the reagan administration is resisting calls to raise the level of u.s. diplomatic contact with vietnam, saying it wants to maintain pressure on the vietnamese to withdraw their troops from cambodia
sen. john mccain, r-ariz., and rep. tom ridge, r-pa., on wednesday called for the establishment of a ``working u.s. presence'' in vietnam. they said little progress has been made on numerous issues which remain as the ``legacy'' of the vietnam war, despite numerous visits to vietnam by congressional and administration delegations
the administration, however, said it opposed the lawmakers' call for the creation of ``interest sections,'' which are typically established between nations that don't recognize each other but acknowledge mutual concerns
the united states and cuba, for example, have interest section personnel stationed in third-party embassies in each others' nations
we continue to believe that political and economic isolation is the most effective way of pressing vietnam to end its occupation of cambodia,'' the state department said in a statement released wednedsay
we are prepared to discuss normalization with vietnam, therefore, only in the context of an acceptable settlement in cambodia which includes the withdrawal of vietnamese troops,'' it said. vietnam's military occupation of cambodia is in its ninth year
mccain and ridge are both vietnam veterans and mccain is a former prisoner of war. they issued their call for greater diplomatic contact with vietnam on the 15th anniversary of mccain's release after five years of captivity
mccain said establishment of interest sections ``falls far short of diplomatic recognition, and certainly implies no approval of a nation's policies.''
he said that if no progress is made on issues such as americans still listed as missing from the southeast asian conflict, then ``the option of further normalization'' could always be set aside
mccain said several members of the administration had indicated privately that they supported better communication between the nations, but that he expected that the administration's ``official'' position on vietnam would remain the same
mccain and ridge said greater contact also is needed to administer a two-year program to bring 8,000 to 12,000 children of american soldiers to the united states
there is a tremendous logistical problem and barrier to progress, just by the fact that all of our technical people must travel in and out of bangkok every time there is to be communication,'' ridge said
the house interior committee is chopping away at the huge timber harvests in alaska's tongass rain forest, the nation's largest national forest and the timber cutting programs's biggest money loser
the panel gave voice vote approval wednesday to legislation pushed by hard-lobbying conservation groups to scrap the 1980 law guaranteeing that the u.s. forest service gets at least $40 million a year to spend on tongass timber sales
the money, much of it for logging roads to ancient stands of huge trees, was mandated as part of the compromise that apportioned public lands in alaska for various uses, including commercial development and wilderness
the compromise gave protected wilderness status to 5.4 million acres of the 17.9 million acre tongass, which has the nation's largest populations of bald eagles and grizzly bears
the 1980 law, in what backers said represented economic guarantees for southeast alaska, set a goal of commercially harvesting 450 billion board feet of tongass trees every 10 years from non-wilderness sections
no other national forest has a congressionally mandated harvest goal or gets its appropriations without the year-by-year review congress gives to spending requests for other federal forests
rep. bruce vento, d-minn., said that because of low demand and falling prices for wood pulp from tongass, taxpayers have lost 99 cents for each $1 in sales, with some old trees going for $2 apiece
vento called the 1980 law ``a mandate to overcut ... one of the world's only temperate rain forests.''
we're changing the entire environment when we cut 400- and 500-year-old trees,'' he said
approved by the committee was a package put together by rep. george miller, d-calif., to scrap the 1980 timbering guarantees and assure that the tongass is subject to the same timber-harvest planning practices applied to all other national forests
the bill would put a five-year moratorium on commercial logging in about 1.7 million acres considered by the southeast alaska conservation council to be prime fish and wildlife habitat threatened by timbering
miller's plan also would require the agriculture department to renegotiate its long-term contracts to supply tongass timber to two large mills owned by louisiana pacific-ketchikan corp. and alaska pulp corp
about two-thirds of the tongass production goes to these mills, which convert it to pulp, principally for export to japan. critics say the 50-year contracts, executed in the 1950s, give the companies a regional monopoly and too large a voice in forest service management decisions for the tongass
miller said the tongass now is ``almost a scandalous operation.''
we have a process that is not driven by rational forest management,'' he said. ``we have cuttings driven by a political bargain.''
don young, alaska's only house member and the ranking republican on interior, opposed miller's plan because ``it basically shuts down the mills. ... we're talking about 6,000 jobs.''
young said the committee was being unduly influenced by conservation groups such as the wilderness society and sierra club, which have made the tongass and a proposal to drill for oil in the arctic national wildlife refuge their major capitol hill battlegrounds in 1988
young called the environmental groups ``special interests'' and said, ``the national environmental community is jerking our string.''
surgeon general c. everett koop says old people don't have to suffer poor health just because they're old
the whole theme of this meeting is it's never too late to start prevention,'' koop said wednesday at the close of a three-day workshop on health promotion and aging
how do older people maximize their health? the same way younger people do, said koop: don't smoke, don't drink too much, rest, eat right and exercise
old age is not a disease and there are many oldsters who are disease free,'' said koop. ``you don't necessarily have to have your kidneys fail, you don't necessarily have to have dementia. ... my plea would be to separate old age and disease. they don't necessarily go together.''
smoking is a prime example of the never-too-late approach, said koop
there is a tremendous tendency on the part of physicians to say, `well he's over 65, he hasn't got many vices, hasn't got many years left, why bother the poor old fellow?''' he said
but if they would just look him straight in the eye and say, `you're not going to live as long or have as good a quality of life as if you stop smoking,' if he stops he will note an immediate benefit.''
koop, 71, said he is convinced older people will shift to healthier diets and exercise more if properly counseled by their doctors
i do think you can change a person's behavior,'' he said. ``if somebody is willing to look at him from a bird's-eye view and try to rearrange his life and point out how he could do these things and what the benefits would be, people listen and they benefit.''
even though the u.s. population is aging, he said, it is not becoming less healthy
as we see people who are now in middle-age come along into the graying years they are going to be far healthier than this generation was when it entered the 65-and-older group,'' he said
these are the people who are jogging and swimming and hiking. these are the people who are snacking on salad and yogurt. these are the people who are wearing sensible shoes. they have stopped smoking. they have given up hard liquor. they wear seat belts. they understand the things they can do to preserve the quality of life and the function they already have.''
brahms and berlioz will be featured in the concert halls, but the european community youth orchestra has also been asked to belt out the u.s. and canadian anthems at a baseball game between the atlanta braves and the montreal expos
the orchestra's brass ensemble is scheduled to play at an exhibition game march 31 at municipal stadium in palm beach, fla
the orchestra's 140 musicians, aged 14 to 23, come from all 12 countries of the european community: britain, france, west germany, italy, ireland, denmark, belgium, holland, luxembourg, spain, portugal and greece
for the orchestra's 10th anniversary, it is making its first tour of the united states, arriving from london in palm beach on monday
they've asked us to send the brass ensemble for the game,'' explained boston-born joy bryer, the orchestra's secretary general. she has lived in britain for 31 years
we've mailed the scores to them all around europe. they don't know anything about america but what they see on television. now they'll be finding out more for themselves.''
the brass section consists of 20 instruments _ trumpets, french horns and others that furnish a maximum of volume
mrs. bryer gave reporters details about the trip on wednesday in washington
during its stay in florida, the orchestra will also send groups to schools, hospitals and a community center at belle glade on lake okeechobee, where the audience will be mostly migrant farm workers
its first formal concert will be on april 10 in the west palm beach auditorium. later concerts will be at clearwater, fla., april 11; new york's avery fisher hall on april 13; boston's symphony hall on april 15; and a final performance at the kennedy center concert hall in washington on april 17. the conductor will be erich leinsdorf
part of the proceeds will go to anti-drug efforts and to very special arts, the fund set up by violinist itzhak perlman to help handicapped musical students
lt. col. oliver north is beginning his retirement with more notoriety than most officers, but he is still entitled to the same benefits as any of the other more than 1.5 million men and women drawing military pensions
north, the former national security aide who was indicted last week in the iran-contra affair, announced two days later he had decided to retire on may 1 from the marine corps
north said he was taking the step because he would probably have to subpoena high-ranking government officials to mount his legal defense and didn't want to do so as a military officer
by specifying a may 1 retirement _ a request that has been approved _ north will have completed the minimum 20 years of active duty required to retire with a pension
unless an officer has served 20 years, he is not eligible to receive any type of pension. starting at 20 years of service, the size of the pension for officers of north's age is computed on a rising scale _ going from 50 percent of basic pay up to 75 percent of basic pay after 30 years' service
in north's case, the lieutenant colonel is drawing $3,693.60 in basic pay a month, or $44,323.20 a year. with exactly 20 years of service, he will be entitled to 50 percent of that as a pension payment
north's former boss, rear adm. john poindexter, retired in december with more than 29 years of service and is drawing a pension of more than $52,700 a year
north will have to pay federal income tax on his pension payments. but unless he goes back to work for the federal government, he's free to collect his military pension without limit for the rest of his life
like his other former brothers in arms, north also will be eligible for a number of other benefits to help ease his entry into private life
for example, if he wants to continue shopping at a military commissary or exchange, he'll have that right. the former marine will also be able to relax at military officer clubs, use military recreation facilities and read books at military libraries
if he wants to shop for liquor at a military package store or take in a movie at a theater on base, he can do that, too. and he can also drop off his laundry at a base dry cleaning store or buy new clothing
as a retired officer, north also is provided the right to medical care at a military hospital, but only on a space-available basis. active-duty servicemen are given first priority
if he can't gain admission to a military hospital, north will be covered by the defense department's champus health insurance plan. when he uses a private hospital and champus, however, he'll have to pay an annual deductible and 25 percent of his bill
as a retired officer drawing a pension, north also will be eligible for burial in a national cemetery. ^by richard carelli</byline>
united auto workers president owen bieber says the supreme court dealt a ``blow to working families throughout america'' by upholding a law limiting food-stamp eligibility for striking workers
the high court said wednesday a 1981 federal law imposing food stamp limits on strikers' families does not violate any constitutional rights
the 1981 law, amending the food stamp act, generally bars a family from becoming eligible for food stamps at a time when one of its members is on strike. families already receiving food stamps when a member goes on strike are not dropped from the program but are barred from receiving additional food stamps despite the loss of income
the law was challenged by the uaw and the united mine workers, and some of the unions' members. they said the law violated strikers' freedom of association and speech, and denied equal protection to strikers' families
the court, by a 5-3 vote, disagreed
bieber said wednesday's ruling ``serves only the interest of those who wage economic warfare against working people.''
he added, ``in a democracy which affords its citizens the legal right to form trade unions and engage in peaceful strikes, it is hypocritcal and inconsistent to punish the family members of those who choose to exercise that right.''
writing for the court, justice byron r. white said: ``union strike funds should be responsible for providing support and benefits to strikers during labor-management disputes. it was no part of the purposes of the food stamp act to establish a program that would serve as a weapon in labor disputes.''
but justice thurgood marshall contended in a dissenting opinion that the 1981 law amounted to such a ``weapon'' for management
no other purpose can adequately explain the especially harsh treatment reserved for strikers and their families by the 1981 enactment,'' marshall said
the food stamp act generally excludes benefits for people, and the households of people, unwilling to work. but marshall noted that people who can prove they quit their jobs for ``good cause'' may collect food stamps if otherwise eligible _ while strikers may not
white was joined in upholding the law by chief justice william h. rehnquist and justices john paul stevens, sandra day o'connor and antonin scalia
justices william j. brennan and harry a. blackmun joined marshall's dissenting opinion
justice anthony m. kennedy did not participate in the decision
the nation's food stamp program, paid for by the federal government and administered by the states, has supplemented the food-buying power of millions of low-income families since 1964
participating households receive food stamp coupons that can be used for food purchases at retail stores. eligibility for food stamps is based on income and several other factors
two agriculture department economists say the soviet union's agriculture is still in trouble, despite a couple of back-to-back bumper grain harvests
at the request of the united states, the soviets opened talks here last weekend on a new long-term grain agreement to replace the current pact which expires on sept. 30. the agreement commits moscow to buy at least a specified minimum amount of u.s. grain each year
the preliminary one-day session was adjourned without anything conclusive announced or any indication as to when and where the negotiations would be resumed
but chris foster and ed cook of the department's economic research service note that the soviet union ``doesn't always meet the provisions of the agreement'' by failing to buy the specified minimum amounts
last year's total soviet grain harvest was 211.3 million metric tons, up slightly from 210.1 million tons in 1986, the first time that two consecutive grain crops of more than 200 million tons have been produced by the soviet union
however, foster noted that last year's soviet harvest was of ``poor quality and contained above-average amounts of moisture.''
cook said soviet agriculture still has many basic inefficiencies and that soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev has had only slight success so far in his efforts to reform his country's agriculture
gorbachev seems now to be taking a less radical approach to agricultural reform than was anticipated a year ago,'' cook said
there has not been a dramatic shift toward a ``market economy'' and the promised increases in local autonomy for farm managers has been slow to materialize. rather, cook added, ``the focus now seems to be on making adjustments to the traditional system.''
cook, whose comments appear with foster's in a forthcoming issue of farmline magazine, said the soviet system historically has been hampered by a lack of incentives and authority for farm workers and managers. policies have been decreed from above, with little reward for greater efficiency
gorbachev's reforms ``have succeeded somewhat in reducing paperwork associated with agriculture, but incentives and autonomy remain inadequate by our standards,'' cook said
in the soviet union, money is still taken from profitable farms and given to unprofitable farms, in part to even out differences in farm wages, he said. large disparities in income are avoided, but there is little incentive to make a farm more profitable
agriculture department on-site reviews of farmers home administration operations in texas have turned up sex discrimination and severe shortcomings in the hiring of blacks and hispanics in agency offices
the prevailing view expressed by female employees during interviews is that sex discimination often enters into employment decisions,'' the report said wednesday. ``this perception is corroborated by the number of sex discrimination complaints lodged and by the lack of women in higher graded positions.''
the review was made last year under the usda's equal employment opportunity (eeo) program, which calls for compliance checks of several department agencies in various states, including fmha, soil conservation service and the agricultural stabilization and conservation service
reports on the reviews have been released periodically by the department's office of advocacy and enterprise
in addition, the usda office released a number of reports on civil rights compliance by the agencies in louisiana and oklahoma. in each case, the on-site review found the operations ``generally in compliance'' with civil rights requirments and regulations
however, most of the civil rights reports noted numerous deficiencies in the employment of women and minorities, and shortcomings in outreach programs
a study of last year's wheat quality showed that 76 percent of the hard red winter wheat samples graded no. 1 or no. 2, compared with 70 percent in 1986, the agriculture department says
for hard red spring wheat, 75 percent graded no. 1, compared with 70 percent in 1986, the department's federal grain inspection service said wednesday
the annual survey involved 12,739 wheat samples from the 1987 crop, said w. kirk miller, administrator of the agency. the samples were taken during the first four weeks following local harvests around the country
yields on two-year treasury notes have risen in the government's latest auction to the highest level in two months
the average yield in wednesday's auction was 7.39 percent, up from 7.16 percent at the last auction on feb. 24. it was the highest rate since two-year notes averaged 7.4 percent on jan. 27
the notes will carry a coupon interest rate of 7] percent, with each $10,000 in face value selling for $9,997.30
a total of $8.53 billion in notes were sold out of bids totaling $25.08 billion
congress never intended to outlaw state rules against retaliatory firings when it gave the federal government the authority to protect union workers, the lawyer for a southern illinois woman says
paul alan levy told the supreme court that lower courts erred in ruling that illinois could not penalize a company for firing a union employee who filed a workers' compensation claim
he asked the court to overturn the decision and rule in favor of jonna lingle, a machinists union member dismissed from her job at the norge division of magic chef inc. in herrin, ill
the right of (state) action is available to both union and non-union employees alike,'' levy told the court in oral arguments wednesday. ``that right is independent of the rights enjoyed under a collective bargaining agreement.''
illinois is one of 21 states with laws against retaliatory firings
but a lawyer for norge said the federal labor-management relations act makes enforcement of union contracts _ through the decisions of an arbitrator _ the province of the federal government
if independent state laws were enacted that flew in the teeth of a labor contract, they were pre-empted,'' attorney charles c. jackson told the court. ``permitting the illinois law to stand would be an incentive to undermine collective bargaining.''
jackson conceded that states may act on health and safety matters but said mrs. lingle's firing was a contract issue covered by federal labor law
according to court records, the woman notified the herrin-based norge in late 1984 that she was injured on the job and asked the company to pay her medical bills, as provided for by the illinois workers' compensation law
norge fired mrs. lingle a week later, contending she filed a false claim
however, the machinists' contract with norge contained a provision protecting workers from dismissal without just cause, and the union filed a grievance the day she was fired
an arbitrator later ordered her reinstatement with back pay
but in the interim, mrs. lingle filed a circuit court lawsuit contending the dismissal violated illinois law and seeking additional compensation
the relief available through the illinois court was greater than what she could receive through arbitration, which did not include punitive damages and compensation for lost overtime
norge shifted the case to u.s. district court, where a judge threw out mrs. lingle's lawsuit, ruling that state law was pre-empted by the arbitration remedy provided by federal labor law
the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals in chicago upheld the dismissal in june 1987
the supreme court is expected to rule on the appeal in july
the state and local legal center in washington said 21 states and the district of columbia have laws protecting workers who file compensation claims
it identified the states as california, connecticut, hawaii, illinois, louisiana, maine, massachusetts, minnesota, missouri, montana, new jersey, new york, north carolina, ohio, oklahoma, oregon, south carolina, texas, virginia, washington and wisconsin
disabled motorists suffer from a patchwork of state regulations that leaves them vulnerable to parking tickets when they drive to other states, say advocates of a national parking symbol for the disabled
it is ludicrous for us to remove one barrier to the handicapped by offering handicapped parking spots, only to erect another by refusing an out-of-state resident the right to park there,'' rep. sam gejdenson, d-conn., told a house subcommittee wednesday
if a person is disabled in one state, does not logic dictate that the same person is disabled in another state?'' he asked
gejdenson has drafted legislation that would require states to use a national handicapped access symbol and have reciprocity with all other states. states that do not comply would have federal highway safety funds withheld
a measure to withhold 2 percent of a non-complying state's highway safety funds was approved by the senate last year. the house has not acted
gejdenson said he raised the issue after being contacted by ruby degiovanni of middletown, conn., who started a campaign against the system three years ago after she was ticketed in lynn, mass., while parked in a handicapped zone
when states are allowed to ticket people for merely exercising their right to a handicapped parking space, it discourages handicapped people from going out,'' mrs. degiovanni told the house public works and transportation subcommittee on surface transportation. she called the current system ``ridiculous'' and discriminatory
there are 6.5 million disabled americans who use special parking permits. only 15 states honor handicapped parking permits from every state, according to a federal highway administration study conducted last year
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis has a respected new ally in his presidential campaign: sen. bill bradley of new jersey, who hopes his dukakis endorsement will end speculation about a last-minute bradley bid
dukakis picked up fellow democrat bradley's endorsement here wednesday. the two held a news conference near the statue of liberty staged to highlight the presidential hopeful's immigrant roots
bradley said he believes the massachusetts governor is the best democrat to beat republican front-runner george bush
i believe michael dukakis can win. i believe he will be the next president of the united states,'' bradley told a crowd of reporters and supporters at liberty state park
the senator promised to campaign for dukakis both in new jersey _ which holds its primary on june 7 _ and around the nation
bradley said dukakis can defeat the vice president ``because he is tenacious, innovative, resilient and disciplined.''
this is a very important endorsement because it comes from one of the most respected and one of the most accomplished public figures in america today,'' dukakis said, adding that bradley would be ``very, very important to our success.''
bradley said he hoped the endorsement would end talk about his entering the race. the senator, a former rhodes scholar and new york knicks basketball star, has said repeatedly he does not feel ready for the white house
the plan i have for 1988 is helping michael dukakis,'' bradley said
he also said he did not expect to be considered as dukakis' running mate. bradley said such a ticket would be too heavily weighted toward the northeast
i think massachusetts and new jersey have a lot in common, but i don't think they go together on a national ticket,'' bradley said
bradley jokingly pushed aside a common criticism aimed by some at him and dukakis: that they are boring
it has been said of michael dukakis that he is dull, a charge with which i am not unfamiliar,'' said bradley, known as a somewhat wooden speaker. ``but governance is not an amusement park.''
bradley also praised the other democrats seeking the nomination, singling out jesse jackson as ``running a campaign that challenges the best in all of us.''
nagging disputes in afghanistan, central america and the middle east are casting a long shadow over the moscow summit only two months before president reagan sets out on his first trip to the soviet union
the outlook for a pact to sharply reduce long-range nuclear weapons is not all that bright either. the u.s. strategic defense initiative has not been swept away as an obstacle, and differences remain over how the bombers, submarines and missiles would be scrapped
i wouldn't want to lay you odds,'' was secretary of state george p. shultz's hesitant response wednesday night to whether the treaty would be ready for reagan and general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev to sign during the may 29-june 2 summit
mobile missiles and sea-launched cruise missiles are hard to spot. that makes verifying compliance with the 30 percent to 50 percent arms reductions more difficult than last year's treaty to ban medium-range nuclear weapons
experts on the two sides are still trying to mesh conflicting drafts. u.s. and soviet negotiators in geneva were directed by shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze to keep working at the verification problem and to report to them at their next meeting in moscow april 21
a treaty signing is not a prerequisite for a successful summit. reagan and gorbachev have plenty of issues to discuss at their fourth meeting
but the report shultz gave at a news conference of his talks with shevardnadze was generally bleak. it suggested the two leaders might not have much to celebrate
shultz seemed taken with a promise by the foreign minister to consider changes in the way the soviets deal with religious observances and with visa applications. emigration of ethnic germans and armenians is up, shultz noted
but he said jewish emigration had reached a plateau. besides, shultz said of the promised reforms, ``what we are interested in is delivery.''
when he turned to regional disputes, the clouds turned darker
gorbachev is committed to end the red army's occupation of afghanistan after more than eight years of bloody strife with u.s.-backed rebels
but shultz said the united states would not concur in an agreement to end the war unless the soviets also suspended military aid to the marxist government in kabul
the main purpose of the u.s. demand is to make it easier for an estimated 5 million refugees to return home. had moscow accepted, the united states would have stopped supplying stinger missiles and other weapons to the resistance
the moratorium would be in effect during the soviet troop withdrawal and for three months afterward
they didn't feel they could agree to that,'' shultz said
and yet, he said, ``those conditions are needed for us to be able to sign as a guarantor'' of an international agreement to end the conflict
at the soviet embassy, meanwhile, shevardnadze was taking a stiff stand
the aid is required by a soviet treaty with the kabul government. ``those are legitimate supplies, and we are not going to rescind that treaty,'' he said
the picture in central america and the middle east wasn't brighter
shultz said the soviets wanted u.s. military aid to an unspecified number of central american governments halted as a condition for them to stop supplying nicaragua for its war with contra rebels
it did not seem something we could pursue,'' shultz said
on the middle east, he said shevardnadze envisioned an active role for moscow in arab-israeli negotiations
shultz said that would get in the way of talks between the two sides. ``the soviet concept is sharply different from ours,'' shultz said
and in the persian gulf, shultz offered only hope that javier perez de cuellar, the u.n. secretary-general, would be able to persuade iran and iraq to end their 7{-year war
referring to pictures of iranian victims of alleged iraqi chemical weapons, shultz said: ``the horrors of this war are just being borne in on us practically every day. it's hard to think it might get worse, but it does get worse.''
for eight months, the united states has sought to persuade the soviets to support an international arms embargo against iran, which refuses to accept a cease-fire. but shevardnadze evidently did not give in
barry schweid is head of the ap's state department staff
moonlighting'' stars cybill shepherd and bruce willis were left speechless by the 2{-week scriptwriters' strike, but filled a five-minute gap in their latest script by rocking to the tune of ``wooly bully.''
miss shepherd and willis kicked and sang along as curtis armstrong, who plays novice detective bert viola, danced about in a pharaoh's outfit, mouthing the words to the 1965 song by sam the sham &amp; the pharaohs
the script for tuesday night's abc-tv show was written before the writers guild of america struck march 7. but when it was filmed last week, the producers discovered it fell about five minutes short. so the cast improvised
remember on the ozzie and harriet show?'' willis told the audience. ``see, sometimes their show would be short and then they would bring ricky nelson out and he would sing a song.''
co-executive producer jay daniel said there are no more scripts left, so ``moonlighting'' probably will go into reruns
no new talks are scheduled between the 9,000-member guild and the producers
