here, at a glance, are some highlights of the fiscal 1989 budget approved wednesday by the house
_total spending: the budget envisions $1.098 trillion in government spending in the fiscal year beginning oct. 1. total new budget authority, which would stretch past the end of the fiscal year, would be $1.232 trillion. the totals are roughly the same as in president reagan's proposed budget
_revenues: the government would collect $964 billion in taxes and other revenues, based on reagan administration estimates. that includes $14 billion in new taxes already enacted into law for next year, beyond which no new levies are anticipated by congress this year
_deficit: $134 billion in red ink would be added to the national debt, under the goal of $136 billion in the gramm-rudman budget-balancing law
_programs eliminated: none. the president had proposed abolishing several subsidies, including amtrak, urban mass transit, and some urban and rural development programs
_domestic spending increases: budget increases for aids research, airline safety, education, science and space, anti-drug programs, and a pot of $100 million for possible boosts in medicaid and other entitlement programs
_federal pay: federal civilian and military employees would get a 3 percent pay increase. reagan had requested 4.3 percent for the military and 2 percent for the civil service
_defense spending: $294 billion, $8.6 billion over the current year but short of the amount needed to keep pace with inflation
_foreign aid: $16.1 billion
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,781.28 points, down 113.95 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on thursday
spending for politicial advertisements in michigan, which holds democratic caucuses on saturday, has varied widely among the candidates, with some making an all-out effort and others hoarding their resources for later races
leslie dach, a spokesman for massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, said the campaign was spending about $200,000 on michigan television
dukakis is using two television ads _ a biography and another spot stressing his executive experience in balancing budgets and creating jobs. dach said a new and ``wholly positive'' ad around the jobs theme would be introduced today
missouri rep. richard gephardt, his campaign floundering after super tuesday, has much at stake in michigan. he is running ads in the state, but his campaign declined to say how much money he is spending
gephardt was using a tv biography and his ``hyundai'' trade spot. the bio features rep. claude pepper, d-fla., the oldest member of the house and a champion of elderly causes
in the trade ad, which helped gephardt win iowa last month and should have appeal in a car-producing state, gephardt alleges that tariffs boost the price of a chrysler k-car to $48,000 in south korea. he asks how many $48,000 hyundais the koreans could sell here
as far as negative ads are concerned, ``there will be no first use here in michigan but certainly a willingness to respond,'' dach said
by wednesday, no candidate had triggered anything like the punch and counter-punch ads that characterized the races leading up to super tuesday, march 8
jesse jackson planned a $70,000 television campaign in michigan starting today, with half of the money to being spent in detroit. the centerpiece was a bill cosby endorsement which he has used before. jackson also is spending $20,000 on radio, said spokeswoman pam smith
country singer johnny cash was praising sen. albert gore of tennessee in radio spots around michigan. gore is focusing more on the april 5 wisconsin primary and spokesman paul risley said he was unlikely to spend money on michigan television, although ``you can still buy time. i wouldn't rule it out.''
the fifth democrat still in the running, sen. paul simon of illinois, is also making a stand in wisconsin and plans no tv advertising in michigan. spokesman terry michael said simon, who won last week's illinois primary, is making new ads for wisconsin and expects to raise enough money in the next 10 days for a $100,000-plus tv campaign there
some 370 blacks and women who were rejected for jobs at honda of america manufacturing inc. will be receiving checks from the company averaging $16,200 to settle a discrimination complaint
roger lambert, a spokesman for the automaker, stressed that all the workers involved had been hired over the past few years and that the $6 million settlement had not been prompted by anyone suing the company for alleged discrimination
the matters in this agreement were not raised by any individual at honda of america manufacturing,'' lambert said wednesday in a telephone interview from company headquarters in marysville, ohio. ``they were raised by the eeoc. no one went to the eeoc.''
nevertheless, honda and the eeoc reached agreement in a settlement signed by the commission tuesday and announced by both parties wednesday
i think the very fact that it has been reached in good faith and announced indicates that both sides feel it is a fair, just and reasonable agreement,'' lambert said
the settlement ``provides $6 million in monetary relief and seniority adjustments to the approximately 370 specifically identified black and female individuals who applied for jobs at honda between 1983 and 1986,'' eeoc chairman clarence thomas said in a statement
it's a significant, large sum that fits into what we considered a just settlement,'' said jay friedman, director of the eeoc's systemic investigations division that had worked on the case since september 1984
in addition to the $6 million in back pay, honda also was required to provide jobs for all those people by feb. 29, friedman said
they've all been hired in the last couple of years, and they're still working here,'' lambert said. ``we have not been required to hire any additional people as a result of this agreement, and we have not hired anyone any earlier than required by our production needs.''
the settlement was among the larger monetary agreements reached in cases where no lawsuit was involved, but the $6 million is dwarfed by some other eeoc cases, commission spokeswoman renee devine said
we settled a similar charge in 1983 with general motors for $42 million,'' ms. devine said. there was no litigation in that race and sex discrimination case, which involved hundreds of people
in a pan am world airways age discrimination case that did involve a lawsuit, the eeoc settled feb. 3 for $17.2 million shortly before a jury was to return a verdict, she said. the case involved about 100 people
the agreement is the second eeoc-honda settlement in less than a year. the two parties reached agreement in june 1987 on an age discrimination investigation that provided back pay totaling $461,610. that case involved 85 people
friedman declined to say whether additional discrimination investigations against honda were pending
honda also agreed in the new settlement:
_to expand its recruitment area to cover columbus and expand specific recruitment efforts for blacks;
_to change promotion procedures and make a commitment to promote additional black and female production workers;
_to teach honda managers about discrimination law
honda employs about 5,900 people at manufacturing plants near marysville, outside columbus, and in anna, ohio. lambert said he expects the employees to number about 8,600 by 1991 when the company completes a $600 million expansion of an engine plant in anna and a $380 million new auto plant in east liberty, ohio. more details of agreement; background. edits to trim and conform. no pickup.</note>
the leftist sandinista government and u.s.-supported contra rebels signed an agreement wednesday for a 60-day cease-fire to start april 1, both sides announced in a joint communique
it was the first concrete step toward ending a six-year-old war that has killed more than 40,000 people. both sides scheduled a meeting in managua, the capital, for april 6 to start negotiations on a definitive truce
i think, i hope and i believe that we have made a start, a firm start to end this war that is killing ... sons of the same country, sons of the same mothers,'' said contra leader adolfo calero
president daniel ortega said he hoped a regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of five central american nations would ``bury once and for all the military confrontation'' and ``end the hate and strengthen the brotherhood of nicaraguans.''
as president of nicaragua, i hope this peace plan becomes a reality,'' said ortega, who had arrived unexpectedly for the announcement
within the first 15 days of the 60-day truce, the rebels agreed to move into specified zones in nicaragua. delegations from both sides scheduled a meeting in sapoa on monday to work out those zones
the issue of the rebels laying down their arms will be discussed at the april 6 talks
the contras agreed to accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization. that would exclude military aid from the united states, which has been supporting the contras since the war began in 1982
in washington on wednesday, president reagan tried to revive his stalled effort to get congress to resume aid to the contras, which ended feb. 29
joao baena soares, secretary-general of the oas, announced the details of the agreement after cardinal miguel obando y bravo, the roman catholic archbishop of managua, offered a brief prayer asking that nicaragua be blessed for ``all it has suffered.''
both men attended the three days of talks as observers and signed the agreement as witnesses. gen. humberto ortega, the defense minister and head of the sandinista delegation, signed for the government and calero signed for the contras
the sandinistas agreed to release 100 contra prisoners on sunday and said the rest of the 1,500 jailed rebels would be released at a date to be worked out at the april 6 meeting
the 1,800 former national guardsmen in prison will be released after a final truce agreement is reached. the army was called the national guard under the late president anastasio somoza, who was overthrown by the sandinistas in july 1979
the government also said it would guarantee freedom of expression without restrictions, in accordance with the regional peace plan. many press liberties were barred for almost six years under a state-of-emergency decree
the nicaraguan government said it would grant gradual amnesty and allow all political exiles to return to the country without fear of persecution. it agreed to discuss the issue of military service in a national dialogue with the internal opposition
the meeting at sapoa, a town on the costa rican border, was the first time the two sides met on nicaraguan soil
both contras and sandinistas earlier had agreed to a battlefield truce while the negotiations, which began monday, took place. a reported contra breach apparently did not affect the talks
the voice of nicaragua radio said earlier that contras ambushed an army truck at 2 p.m. tuesday near mulukuku, in the northern province of matagalpa, killing two soldiers. it did not appear affect the negotiations
contra spokesman bosco matamoros told reporters earlier that ``there could be isolated'' truce violations, ``but there is a clear will from both sides to respect that decision.''
u.s. troops in honduras again held military exercises staged as what officials called a show of force against nicaraguan aggression. white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said the withdrawal would be ``gradual.'' pentagon officials said they expected it to come next week
the u.s. troops were sent to honduras as the request of the honduran president, who charged that sandinista soldiers had penetrated honduran territory chasing contra rebels as part of a major military offensive. the contras maintain base camps in honduran territory
at the time, nicaragua said it had forced 2,000 contras out of its territory. contra forces number an estimated 10,000 troops
at the start of the talks, the sandinistas had said they would only discuss a cease-fire. two previous rounds of talks ended in stalemate when the government maintained that position while the contras insisted on broadening discussions to include political reform within nicaragua
but they agreed to discuss political issues with the rebels on monday after signing an agreement with eight opposition parties in nicaraguan
the national dialogue as well as the cease-fire are included in the regional peace plan signed by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, costa rica, guatemala and honduras
the peace plan seeks to end civil wars in nicaragua, in el salvador and guatemala. it also calls for amnesties, democratic reforms and an end to logistical and strategic support for insurgencies
wearing a favorite pink sport jacket, a 62-year-old used-car salesman fired over what his boss said were his loud and ugly clothes signed an out-of-court agreement to end an age discrimination suit
i believe i have proved my point,'' lee grant said wednesday after ending the lawsuit known in courthouse circles as ``the dress of a salesman.''
terms of the settlement, reached the day the trial was scheduled to start, cannot be disclosed by either party under the agreement, said nancy donnellan, who represented grant in his lawsuit against darby buick of sarasota
but she said, ``we got a good settlement.''
darby's attorney, william sizemore, didn't immediately return telephone calls to his office wednesday by the associated press
grant charged he was forced out of his job at darby buick because of his age even though he was the top salesman with 30 years experience
grant said his attire led to his firing in may 1985, 1{ years after c. conrad darby jr. took over management of the dealership from his father, conrad sr
the younger darby started a ``new image'' campaign and required that sport coats be worn for a more professional look
the 6-foot-8 grant bought jackets he described as a pale pink and a rainbow plaid. the latter, he said, has every color in it and goes well with his gray slacks or green or red or blue
sizemore, however, contended in court documents that grant was stubbornly resisting the new image campaign
one jacket was multi-colored ... and the other was a loud fuchsia,'' he said
sizemore said grant had other irritating habits, such as catnapping on the job. grant said he only took a few winks, a habit he acquired when the elder darby was in control of the dealership
i wanted those sport coats vindicated,'' ms. donnellan said. ``they aren't really that bad.''
the house ethics committee has formally rebuked rep. charles rose, d-n.c. for improper use of campaign funds but recommended against further punishment for his violations of house rules
the ethics panel wrote rose on wednesday that it found ``clear and convincing'' evidence he improperly borrowed funds from his campaign and then failed to report the loans on his public financial disclosure reports
in addition, rose wrongly pledged a certificate of deposit from his campaign as collateral on a personal loan and failed to report liabilities to financial institutions on his public disclosure statements, the committee found
the panel, formally the committee on standards of official conduct, said those actions violate house rules
the personal benefit rose received in each instance of borrowing, and the lower interest rate received from use of the certificate of deposit, ``are the kinds of abuses'' the rules are designed to prevent, the committee said
the panel told rose his behavior was ``deserving of reproach.'' but in concluding no further punishment was needed against the eight-term lawmaker, the committee noted that rose tried to correct his mistakes
the committee recognizes and takes into consideration the fact that all funds borrowed were replaced in full without the insistence of this committee, and that this action was taken by you prior to this committee beginning a preliminary inquiry,'' rose was told in the letter, signed by panel chairman julian c. dixon, d-calif. and ranking republican floyd d. spence of south carolina
furthermore, the committee recognizes that the campaign certificate of deposit in question is no longer encumbered, due to restrictions placed on it in connection with your personal financial dealings.''
rose said, ``i am very happy that the committee found that no further action was warranted, other than the letter to me.''
he said he would not resign and described his violations as ``technical.''
a house rule restricts the use of campaign funds to bona fide campaign purposes. the committee called the requirement ``crucial to maintaining public confidence in the fund-raising system governing house members
the use of your campaign funds, as alleged and proved, is entirely inconsistent with this principle,'' the committee letter said
rose, 48, was first elected to the house in 1972. he is chairman of the house agriculture subcommittee on tobacco and peanuts
the lawmaker said he was disappointed the committee did not accept his contention that money he took from his campaign amounted to repayment of loans
he said he apologized for signing his name to the certificate of deposit, contending he hadn't known doing so violated house rules
the dollar closed lower against the japanese yen in tokyo thursday, while stock prices also fell moderately
after opening at 126.75 yen, the dollar slid further and closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen from its close of 127.15 yen on wednesday. it ranged between 126.15 and 126.81 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, a 52.48-point gainer wednesday, lost 113.95 points, or 0.44 percent, and ended the day at 25,781.28
foreign exchange trading was quiet in tokyo today without any notable movements,'' said an official of a major commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the dollar's marginal decline in tokyo followed a lower closing in new york. analysts attributed the shift to a remark wednesday by martin feldstein, former economic adviser to president reagan, predicting the dollar could fall to a level of 120 yen or lower over the next six months
stock investors appeared to be staying on the sidelines to wait out the results of the current fiscal year, which ends march 31, said hiromi yoneyama of wako securities
but yoneyama said many market participants remained optimistic about market conditions after april
share prices on the first section were mixed in lackluster trading of about 500 million shares in the morning session
more than 15 percent of inmates entering state prison from new york city have tested positive for the aids virus, officials say
the finding, from anonymous blood tests of 500 inmates over two weeks early this year or late last year, will prompt further anonymous tests, said peter slocum, a spokesman for state health commissioner dr. david axelrod
the blood tests were part of a state program to check more than 100,000 blood samples statewide in an attempt to determine how far acquired immune deficiency syndrome has spread, slocum said wednesday
the blood samples are being collected at prisons, where all entering inmates are tested, as well as at family planning clinics, tuberculosis clinics and other health centers, he said
about 70 percent of the prison system's 41,559 inmates come from new york city, which has the nation's highest concentration of aids victims
the inmate test results were disclosed after state sen. israel ruiz met with axelrod and corrections commissioner thomas coughlin, and called for the prison system to offer aids tests to inmates about to be released
ruiz said axelrod told him that tests had indicated between 15 percent and 20 percent of the inmates might be carrying the aids virus
the senator said that with about 16,000 inmates being released annually, there could be 2,400 or more who are infected and don't know it
slocum said ruiz was making ``a crude extrapolation based on very limited data'' that might not give a clear picture of the prison system as a whole
slocum said ruiz must have been basing his projections on what axelrod had told him about blood tests from inmates entering the system at downstate state prison in dutchess county, about 50 miles north of new york city
corrections spokesman james flateau said inmates are now tested for the virus only on a doctor's orders for diagnostic purposes
flateau said that as of the end of last year there had been 597 confirmed cases of aids among inmates. of those, 346 died in prison, 152 had been released and 99 remained in custody
coughlin, axelrod and gov. mario cuomo have resisted calls for mandatory aids testing of inmates and have thus far refused to permit voluntary testing in prisons. ruiz said he would propose legislation to require it
slocum said inmates about to be released are given counseling about aids
some researchers have estimated that up to 50 percent of those testing positive for the virus will develop the deadly disease, which cripples the body's immune system and leaves victims susceptible to infections and cancer
most cases of aids have appeared in homosexual men and intravenous drug abusers. by march 21, 57,024 aids cases were reported in the united states, and 31,836 victims have died
most of the presidential candidates have agreed to take part in a new york primary eve question-and-answer televised session with mayor edward i. koch
the mayor announced wednesday that he had lined up the candidates, except for republican vice president george bush, to appear on the special program on april 18, at 11 p.m. on wnyw-tv
he said he has gotten commitments from the field of democratic candidates and kansas sen. robert dole on the gop side, but that bush opted out
koch said bush explained to him in a telephone call that when he ran in the republican primary against ronald reagan eight years ago, he had consented to a joint appearance and was defeated
he said bush said he did not want a repeat at this late date when he is leading in the primary results
gov. mario cuomo says that jesse jackson would be ``good for the ticket'' as the democratic vice presidential candidate
if he doesn't become the democratic nominee (for president) and wanted to become vice president, i don't think he'd be a burden to the ticket,'' said the new york governor during an interview wednesday with albany's wamc radio. ``i think he would be good for the ticket. i would hope that all the candidates who aspire for the presidency feel the same way.''
cuomo is one of several prominent democrats who may play kingmaker in negotiations leading up to the democratic national convention in july. the governor has also not ruled out accepting a draft for the presidential nomination himself if there's a deadlocked convention
for his part, jackson hasn't ruled out a possible run for vice president if he doesn't win the presidential nomination
the vice president option would be a serious consideration,'' he said last year during an appearance on the ``donahue'' television show
connecticut voters overwhelmingly favor vice president george bush in the republican presidential race and strongly support massachusetts gov. michael s. dukakis in the democratic contest, according to a hartford courant-connecticut poll
the survey showed that bush is favored by 64 percent of likely gop voters polled, while his nearest opponent, sen. robert j. dole of kansas, is the choice of 20 percent. fourteen percent of those polled were undecided and 2 percent selected former television evangelist pat robertson
among likely democratic voters, dukakis leads jesse jackson, 50 percent to 16 percent of likely voters, with 27 percent undecided, the poll showed
trailing far behind were sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee with 3 percent, sen. paul simon of illinois with 3 percent, and rep. richard a. gephardt of missouri with 1 percent
the institute for social inquiry at the university of connecticut conducted the random telephone poll between march 9 and sunday. the final sample consisted of 990 people statewide who said they were likely to vote in tuesday's primary. at stake in the primary are 52 democratic delegates and 35 republican delegates
four contenders for the democratic presidential nomination have accepted invitations to attend the state party's jefferson-jackson day dinner april 30, according to indiana democratic chairman john b. livengood
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, sens. albert gore of tennessee and paul simon of illinois and rep. richard gephardt of missouri have committed to attend the dinner, the indiana party's largest annual fund-raiser
no formal response has yet been received from jesse jackson, who also was invited, livengood said wednesday
the dinner at the indiana convention center is being held three days before the may 3 primary when 79 delegates to the national convention will be at stake
nebraska republicans questioned in a recent survey said they favored george bush as their party's presidential nominee, while nebraska democrats said they favored michael dukakis as their nominee, according to the omaha world-herald
forty-five percent of 347 registered republicans surveyed in the telephone poll last thursday and friday said they would vote for vice president bush. thirty-two percent said they would vote for sen. bob dole of kansas, while 5 percent chose former television evangelist pat robertson and 18 percent refused to answer or said they were undecided, the newspaper said in its wednesday editions
among 278 democrats surveyed, 36 percent chose massachusetts gov. dukakis, 14 percent chose the rev. jesse jackson and 13 percent chose rep. richard gephardt of missouri, the newspaper said. six percent backed sen. albert gore of tennessee and 28 percent refused to answer or said they were undecided, the newspaper said
sri research center inc., a subsidiary of selection research inc., conducted the random survey of selected registered voters for the world-herald
the poll had a margin of error of plus or minus 5.1 percentage points for the republican primary and 5.5 percentage points for the democrats, the newspaper said
michael dukakis has a comfortable lead among pennsylvania democrats, while republican george bush leads his closest rival by a 3-1 margin, according to results of the pennsylvania poll
with more than a month to go before the april 26 state primary, the massachusetts governor took a 2-1 lead over jesse jackson, his closest competitor, among all democratic respondents, the pittsburgh post-gazette reported in today's editions
on the republican ballot, the vice president led sen. bob dole of kansas by more than 3-1, the newspaper said. dole followed bush with 18 percent and former television evangelist pat robertson had 5 percent, while 11 percent said they were undecided
among all democrats, dukakis led with 37 percent, followed by jackson with 18; rep. richard gephardt of missouri with 8; sen. albert gore of tennessee with 7; and sen. paul simon of illinois with 6. about 24 percent said they were undecided
the pennsylvania poll is sponsored by the post-gazette and the philadelphia daily news. the telephone survey of 1,094 randomly selected registered voters from across the state, 563 democrats and 531 republicans, was conducted march 16 to march 20
the margin of error is plus or minus 4 percentage points on figures from all respondents, and plus or minus 6 points for the 293 democrats and 293 republicans identified as those most likely to vote in the primary
whether people die young or have normal lifespans appears to be ruled more by their genes than their upbringing, a study today concludes
the research, conducted in denmark, was based on a followup of infants who were separated from their parents at birth
if the biologic parents died at an early age, there was an increased chance that their children would die during their first five decades, as well. but there was no such link with the deaths of adoptive parents
we conclude that premature death in adults has a strong genetic background _ especially death due to infections and vascular causes,'' wrote dr. thorkild i.a. sorensen and colleagues from hvidovre university hospital in copenhagen
by contrast, they wrote in the new england journal of medicine, they found that early death from cancer appears to be associated with behavior learned in the family
researchers have long known that some diseases, such as heart attacks and some forms of cancer, run in families. but it is often unclear how much of the risk is inherited and how much results from living habits that people pick up from their parents
the danish study, based on people who never lived with their biological parents, helps sort out these factors. it suggests that genes play the largest role in determining whether people will die at unusually young ages
the researchers wrote, ``the family environment apparently had no effect'' on the overall mortality rate from natural causes, although such influences cannot be ruled out
the researchers studied 960 families who gave up their children for adoption between 1924 and 1926. they looked at whether the adoptees died between ages 16 and 58 and whether their biological or adoptive parents had died of the same causes by age 50
among the findings:
_if a biological mother or father died of natural causes before age 50, this doubled the risk of premature death for their child. however, there was no association between the deaths of adoptive parents and their children
_if a biological parent died of an infection before age 50, the mortality rate among the adoptees from infections was five times higher than usual. the researchers said that suggests the strength of people's immune systems is inherited
_vascular disease that underlies heart trouble and stroke also were strongly influenced by inheritance. if a biological parent died early of this disease, the child was five times more likely than the others to die of this cause
_in cancer, the situation was reversed. those whose adoptive parents died before 50 of cancer had a five-fold increased risk of dying themselves of cancer. but the adoptees' cancer death risk was not increased if the biological parents died of cancer
in an accompanying editorial, dr. roger r. williams of the university of utah said the research provided ``splendid data.'' but he said it should not be used to argue that family habits don't contribute to heart disease or that genes never play a role in cancer
here is an abridged version of the text of a cease-fire agreement signed wednesday night by sandinista and contra leaders
it was translated from spanish by the associated press
an agreement between the constitutional government of nicaragua and the nicaraguan resistance (contras):
1. to cease offensive military operations throughout the national territory for a period of 60 days beginning april 1, 1988. during this period will occur negotiations to achieve a definitive cease-fire, and its effective implementation will be carried out jointly with the other commitments contemplated (in this accord) for the purpose of ending the war. both parties agree to meet again at the highest levels april 6 to continue the definitive cease-fire negotiations
2. during the first 15 days, the resistance forces will locate themselves in zones whose areas, size and modus operandi will be mutually determined through special commissions meeting in sapoa beginning monday, march 28, 1988
3. the nicaraguan goverment will decree a general amnesty for persons tried and convicted of violating public security law as well as for ex-members of somoza's national guard imprisoned since july 19, 1979
in the case of the former, the amnesty will be gradual... during holy week, on palm sunday, it will begin with the release of the first 100 prisoners
later, when it has been verified that the forces of the nicaraguan resistance have entered the mutually agreed upon zones, 50 percent of the prisoners will be released. the remaining 50 percent will be released at a later date at the moment when the definitive cease-fire is signed ..
the release of the prisoners mentioned in the second part of the first paragraph of section three will begin with the signing of the definitive cease-fire depending on prior decision of the inter-american commission on human rights of the organization of american states ..
4. to guarantee food and basic supplies for the irregular forces (the contras), exclusively humanitarian aid will be solicited and received ... and will be channeled through neutral organizations
5. the nicaraguan government will guarantee unrestricted freedom of expression..
6. when the nicaraguan resistance forces are concentrated in mutually accepted zones, they will send to the national dialogue (with the internal political opposition) as many as eight delegates. in the national dialogue, among other topics, issues related to military service will be treated
7. it is guaranteed that all individuals who for political or any other reasons have left the country can return to nicaragua and incorporate themselves into the political, economic and social life without any conditions other than those laid down in the laws of the republic
they will not be tried, punished or prosecuted for any political-military activities in which they might have engaged
8. the consititutional government of nicaragua certifies that the individuals who will have been reintegrated into normal civilian life will be able to participate, under equal conditions and guarantees, in the central american parliamentry elections and the municipal elections, on the dates scheduled for them, as well as in nationl general elections on the dates which have been determined in the poltical constitution
9. for the purpose of verifying the compliance with this agreement, a verification commision will be formed with the participation of ... cardinal miguel obando y bravo (nicaragua's roman catholic leader), and the secretary general of the oas, his excellency ambassador joao baena soares ..
in addition, both parties agree to prolong to april 1, 1988, the cessation of offensive militry operations agreed to by both parties on march 21
signed,
for the nicaraguan government:
gen. humberto ortega saavedra, minister of defense
hans juergen wischnewski, adviser
paul reichler, adviser
for the directorate of the nicaraguan resistance:
adolfo calero portocarrero
alfredo cesar guirre
aristides sanchez herdocia
witnesses:
cardinal miguel obando y bravo
ambassasoor joao baena soares
dallas county officials say they probably will let the chips fall where they may in the meadow muffin match up, which could be an illegal lottery
about 2,000 people have bought $5 tickets for a chance to win $1,500 on april 30 when a cow is allowed on the coppell high school football field
the field is divided into a grid, and the owner of the first square with a cow hit will receive the prize money
the event is sponsored by the coppell high school parent-teacher-student association, and money raised will go toward a college scholarship fund and the purchase of a school laminating machine
county officials downwind from the suburb caught a whiff of the event and said it is gambling
i don't write the laws, i just enforce them,'' said jeff keck, assistant district attorney. ``i think it's got some real liability problems.''
but keck said officials may ignore the event and let ticket holders take their chances
no one is likely to file a complaint,'' keck said
an official with the state attorney general's office said that although the money is being raised for a good cause, it is still gambling
but ptsa president brenda robertson said, ``i can't imagine anyone being ornery enough to try to stop us from trying to help our kids.''
sandra burton, a ptsa member, said some parents thought the event was a little off-color
i have to admit that at first i thought it was a gross idea,'' she said. ``but we all went home and thought about it ... and we were able to see the humor in it.''
ms. burton said the ptsa first considered using a horse instead of a cow. ``but horses drop a lot,'' she said. ``and we would end up owing the world a lot of money.'' soldiers fired mortars and howitzers. pickup 4th graf pvs, ``officers from...'' ^laserphoto teg1</note> ^by cam rossie</byline>
amid the deafening boom of live mortar fire and the sizzling heat of a honduran spring, american soldiers practiced for battle but thought about going home soon
a honduran artillery school in the sprawling pine-covered mountains of south-central honduras, was the setting wednesday for training exercises between american and honduran troops
about 120 soldiers worked together, loading and firing mortars and howitzers, radioing messages from the field, plotting diagrams of make-believe enemy positions and cheering when the artillery hit its mark a mile away
officers from both countries said the training was worthwhile
we're learning to adapt our ways to different areas,'' said cpl. charles schneider, 22, of washington, d.c
i'm learning spanish,'' said sgt. scott craig, 25, of charlotte, n.c
col. rene fonseca, commander of the honduran company taking part in the exercises, said his soldiers do not often get a chance to use live artillery. money is scarce in this country, so the exercises are u.s. funded
we don't have enough ammunition to last the whole year, so while they're here we take advantage of the opportunity to use live ammunition,'' he said
all the u.s. soldiers training at zambrano, 25 miles north of the capital of tegucigalpa, are from the 82nd airborne division based at fort bragg, n.c
president reagan rushed 3,200 american soldiers to honduras last week after honduran president jose azcona hoyo said sandinista troops from neighboring nicaragua had pursued u.s.-backed contra rebels into honduran territory
the reagan administration said the americans were in honduras as an emergency training exercise meant to show support for azcona
late wednesday, a honduran military source, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said about 300 nicaraguan troops entered honduran territory in the region where sandinista soldiers had fought contra rebels last week
because of that, the state of alert continues for all combat units of the armed forces,'' said the source
the location was given as the san andres de bocay region in olancho province, but no other details were available
pentagon officials in washington said earlier wednesday that, unless the military situation in the region changed, the u.s. soldiers tentatively will return home early next week
cpl. rodney brooks, 22, who took time out from artillery practice to read letters from his fiancee in north conway, n.h., said he hoped he would be home in time for his june 18 wedding
he said he was ``relieved, very relieved'' when he learned that sandinista forces had retreated last week and that truce talks between the sandinistas and contras had begun in sapoa, nicaragua
we came down here to do what we had to do in any way, shape or form,'' he said from behind a 105mm howitzer
but if we can keep from firing one shot and the problems still get resolved, then that's great,'' he said
some soldiers said their trip to honduras, one of central america's poorest countries, had been an eye-opener
the children come running up to you for chocolate and money. and the way they live _ it makes you feel lucky to live in a house,'' said spec. 4 james holt, 20, of washington
it makes you want to get back home so badly.''
the only general assembly members to vote against a resolution condemning a u.s. attempt to close the plo's united nations observer mission were israel and the united states
the non-binding resolution was approved 148-2 on wednesday, a day after the justice department filed suit in federal court seeking to close the new york city townhouse where the plo has its offices
the palestine liberation organization vowed to fight the attempted closure, mandated by an anti-terrorism law passed by congress last year
the u.n. resolution calls on the united states to obey the international u.n. headquarters treaty, which permits foreign missions to operate and calls for arbitration of any dispute with the host country
what pride do you have in throwing your guests out?'' shouted plo envoy zehdi labib terzi after the vote
is this the message the u.s. delegation wants to bring to the world? that guests have no respect, the united nations has no respect, international law has no respect?'' he asked
the u.s. government said it will not take any physical steps against the plo until the issue has been settled in court
let me assure you, we will not disregard the summons by the u.s. district court,'' said terzi. ``but we will tell the court this is a dispute between the united nations and the united states, and that the only forum where such a dispute can be settled is found in section 21 of the headquarters agreement.''
israeli ambassador johanan bein rose to denounce the plo for, as he put it, seeking the protection of the u.n. charter as it pursues a goal contrary to that charter: the destruction of israel
the plo, since its inception, has been the principal terrorist organization of our time. it has systematically targeted and murdered innocent civilians,'' said bein
the plo, which has retained former u.s. attorney general ramsay clark as its counsel, has 20 days from the filing of the lawsuit on tuesday to respond
the united nations announced it will file a brief in support of the plo's defense motion. it retained attorney keith highet, who is also president of the american society of international law
sixty-five american organizations and citizens filed suit on wednesday in federal court in manhattan challenging the anti-terrorism act
they included former beirut hostage rev. benjamin weir, author studs terkel and actor ed asner, and the american friends service committee, the arab-american institute and the international jewish peace union
the lawsuit argues that the law infringes on the constitutional right of americans to hear all sides of the middle east controversy by barring the plo from public debate
a march 29 hearing date was set in u.s. district court in manhattan
wednesday's vote was the third time the general assembly condemned u.s. legal attempts to close the plo mission. the world body also condemned the anti-terrorism law last december after it was passed by congress, and rebuked the united states on march 2 after the united states announced that it would seek to close the plo mission
an australian company that developed an in-vitro fertilization technique celebrated its second anniversary with a party attended by some of its success stories
fifty-four babies and toddlers, all from the new york area, gathered with their families at a manhattan party wednesday. all were conceived through the programs of the ivf australia company, which has fertility clinics at united hospital in chester and another in alabama
all we see are positive pregnancy tests in ultrasound scans,'' said dr. john j. stangel, the program's medical director. ``we never get to see the babies.''
nurses, doctors and other members of the medical team handed out stuffed koala bears to the children, and a birthday cake was rolled out with 168 blazing candles to represent the number of babies born using the ivf australia technique
the oldest on hand wednesday was 16-month-old matthew martinez. the youngest was 5-week-old michael kiddo, who slept through the party
the ivf technique involves removing mature eggs from a woman's ovary, fertilizing them with sperm in a petri dish and implanting them in the woman's uterus
multiple births are more common in such pregnancies, with between 15 and 20 percent of ivf australia births being twins. the procedure costs $5,000, usually covered by medical insurance
witnesses in the armenian capital of yerevan today said red army helicopters circled the skies to guard against unrest after the government described armenian claims to an area in neighboring azerbaijan as intolerable
moscow dissident valery senderov said a correspondent for an unofficial human rights journal had called from yerevan to say that helicopters were patrolling the city, but that there was no widespread disorder reported
regyen sarkisyan, a senior editor of the communist party newspaper kommunist in yerevan, confirmed in a telephone interview with the associated press that there were helicopters overhead, but described the city as calm
he said most armenians were showing patience in awaiting resolution of the contentious national issue
armenians want the nagorno-karabakh region of azerbaijan annexed to armenia because more than three-quarters of the population in the region is armenian
the annexation appeal was rejected by the party central committee in early february, which triggered massive demonstrations in the region that is smaller than the state of delaware
the unrest spread to yerevan in late february, when hundreds of thousands of armenians marched through the streets bearing banners linking the nagorno-karabakh issue with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev's social reforms
the yerevan demonstrations subsided after gorbachev appealed for calm and promised a party review of the annexation question. but the issue touched off rioting in the azerbaijani city of sumgait on feb. 28, when at least 32 people were killed in a rampage by ethnic extremists
soviet officials reported earlier this week that 197 people were injured in the sumgait rioting and that more than 400 have been arrested or charged in murders, rapes, looting and other violent acts
armenian activists claim the casualties were much higher and predominently among armenians at the hands of enraged azeris, the dominant population of azerbaijan
sarkisyan, the newspaper editor, said soldiers were deployed around yerevan to ensure order today, but no outbreaks of unrest had occurred to his knowledge since a government statement on the issue was made public wednesday night
the demonstrations had subsided until early this week, when reports in the party daily pravda said the annexation drive had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.'' activists in yerevan said about 7,000 people protested that report, and one of the journalists whose name had been attached to it disavowed it
as recently as march 17, party officials in nagorno-karabakh appealed for permission to join the armenian republic
activists in yerevan had called for another show of support for the annexation appeal with demonstrations and strikes beginning saturday, when a self-appointed committee of activists and officials plans to meet and discuss a future course of action
sarkisyan, a 32-year-old candidate for membership in the communist party, said he supports the proposal for returning nagorno-karabakh to armenia, but doesn't expect the matter to be resolved soon
i believe that some day it will be united with armenia, but in the nearest days i don't expect this to happen. it is a very complicated issue, and i think most people understand that now,'' he said
he said he did not expect a large turnout at the demonstrations or widespread participation in the strikes called for by activists, although moscow-based dissidents say they've been told thousands plan to show their support for the nagorno-karabakh appeal by taking to the streets
the soviet government on wednesday rejected as ``intolerable'' the armenian campaign for annexation, indicating it would not bend to the pressures brought to bear by demonstrations and strikes
the meeting, attended by gorbachev, president andrei a. gromyko and other senior party officials, was held after carefully orchestrated appeals by subordinate legislative bodies in 13 soviet republics _ all but armenia and azerbaijan
the official tass news agency said the presidium of the supreme soviet, the nominal parliament, considered it ``intolerable when it is attempted to resolve complicated national-territorial issues through pressure on state authorities, in an atmosphere when emotions and passions are whipped up.''
the statement did not categorically deny the appeal, but declared that such issues would be resolved on the basis of economic concerns rather than ethnic differences
nightline'' anchor ted koppel has agreed to a long-term contract that will keep him at abc news but allow him to produce his own prime-time programs, a newspaper reported today
koppel had been working without a contract since last year, and there was spculation he might leave abc to start his own production company to make a syndicated version of ``nightline,'' according to the new york times
he has anchored the late-night program since it started in 1980 and has been linked to its success largely through his diplomatic yet confrontational interviewing style
under the new arrangement, koppel will get similar benefits as he has now, with abc agreeing to broadcast ``nightline'' five nights a week. koppel will be host for most, but not all of the broadcasts
in addition, koppel will get his own production company, which will produce each year at least four hour-long news programs to air in prime-time. abc will pay him for the right to broadcast those programs
koppel's company also will have the right to produce television programs that could be broadcast outside abc, according to the unidentified executives by the times
roone arledge, president of abc news, said wednesday the deal was agreed on but not signed. koppel did not return several telephone calls to his washington office, the times said
a convicted former wedtech corp. executive, who has confessed to stealing $1.5 million from the bankrupt defense contractor, admitted he has not had to give back any of his illegal earnings
under cross examination by the defense at the racketeering trial of rep. mario biaggi, d-n.y., and six others wednesday, mario moreno was asked about his plea bargain with federal prosecutors
biaggi attorney james larossa got moreno to admit he sought to avoid a racketeering charge ``which could carry up to 20 years in prison and forfeiting your assets.''
and you told your lawyer you didn't want that, right?'' asked larossa, ``and that is one of the things they negotiated and got for you, isn't that right?''
yes,'' said moreno, who later admitted his lawyer also got ``one of the most lenient judges'' to take his guilty plea
moreno is among four ex-wedtech officials who have admitted bribing public officials and other state and federal crimes in a plea bargain for leniency. all are cooperating witnesses for the prosecution. none have yet been sentenced
moreno faces a maximum 15 years in prison after pleading guilty to federal charges of bribe conspiracy and mail fraud. he also faces an additional seven years after pleading guilty to state larceny and bribery charges
larossa also got moreno to admit that ``not a penny'' of his assets have been seized or forfeited despite his numerous guilty pleas
biaggi, his eldest son, richard; wedtech founder john mariotta and four others are charged with turning wedtech, a bronx defense contractor, into a vehicle for paying millions of dollars in bribes to obtain government no-bid contracts
wedtech, currently in bankruptcy proceedings, grew from a small machine shop into a $100-million-a-year business through a series of no-bid contracts set aside for companies controlled by minority group members
earlier, moreno claimed attorneys at the firm of squadron, ellenoff, plesent and lehrer were aware of another wedtech scheme to make it appear the company was minority controlled in order to qualify for no-bid contracts
he said the lawyers knew the agreement to sell majority control of the stock to mariotta, who is of hispanic descent, was ``a sham.''
so they participated in your fraud, is what you are telling us, right?'' asked larossa
yes,'' replied moreno after a short pause
howard squadron, a partner in the firm, later issued a statement calling moreno's testimony ``untrue.''
neither he nor anybody else from wedtech advised anybody at this firm that mr. mariotta had agreed not to buy shares of stock pursuant to the purchase agreement,'' said squadron, noting that moreno previously testified he and other wedtech officials concealed other illegal activities from the law firm and ``if there was such an agreement with mr. mariotta, it too was concealed.''
high winds and snow today buffeted mountain areas of wyoming and colorado, which braced for gusts up to 80 mph and more than a foot of snow from a fast-moving cold front
strong winds blew through sections of south dakota, california, washington state, the midwest, and the east coast. showers and thundershowers fell in much of the midwest
a warning for heavy snow was issued for the northern mountains of colorado, where 8 to 14 inches was expected. the snow and winds predicted to hit 80 mph were expected to create blizzard conditions
an advisory for snow and blowing snow was posted for the mountains of southeastern wyoming, where 4 to 8 inches was expected
on wednesday, the front spawned 80 mph winds in the northwest, forcing army officials to cancel military helicopter flights and training with anti-tank missiles at the yakima firing center in central washington
up to 18 inches of snow fell wednesday in the cascade range, and a snow advisory remained in effect for the mountains
the high winds have been blamed for the death of a 15-year-old portland girl, who was struck by falling trees at a state park in oregon on tuesday
showers and thunderstorms extended from northeastern missouri and southeastern iowa across northern illinois to northern indiana, and were scattered over the lower mississippi valley. showers fell over minnesota and the lower great lakes region
today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms in the mississippi valley, the eastern plains, alabama, the lower great lakes and the northern ohio valley; severe thunderstorms with tornadoes possible from arkansas and eastern oklahoma northeastward to the middle mississippi valley; rain from the northern pacific coast to northwest montana, with snow in some higher elevations; scattered rain and snow showers in the northern and central high plains and strong, gusty winds in the rockies, the high plains and the middle mississippi valley
temperatures were expected to reach the 50s, 60s or 70s for most of the nation; the 40s from the northern and central rockies across the northern plains, from northern minnesota to the upper great lakes and across sections of northern new england; near 80 degrees over the central gulf coast states, the florida peninsula and southern west virginia; and the 80s to near 90 degrees over the desert southwest and much of texas
temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. est ranged from 17 degrees at marquette, mich., to 73 degrees at key west, fla
