israeli troops shot dead an arab today and wounded four others, including a 12-year-old, in clashes across the occupied territories, hospital officials said
overnight, troops swept through the occupied lands in a mass arrest of palestinians
majid mohammed ahmed sawalma, 21, died of two bullet wounds to the chest and heart during a clash in the balatta refugee camp near nablus, al ittihad hospital officials said
among the four palestinians wounded in scattered clashes frm hebron to nablus was a 12-year-old girl from the village of tamoun, 10 miles west of nablus, the officials said
arab media reports said troops were using several west bank schools as detention centers
the army said it was checking the reports of casualties and declined to comment on reports that schools were being used as detention centers
in lebanon, israeli warplanes attacked palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of sidon for the second straight day. there was no immediate word on casualties
it was the third israeli strike against palestinian bases in lebanon in a week and the fifth this year
because of the ongoing violence in the west bank and gaza strip, monsignor michel sabbah, jerusalem's roman catholic patriarch, decided to cancel the traditional palm sunday procession from the mount of olives to jerusalem's old city
prime minister yitzhak shamir, acting in his capacity as interior minister, ordered the haifa-based al ittihad, a communist newspaper, closed until the end of the month on charges it was inciting arab unrest
an israeli court ordered the army to return film confiscated earlier this week from time and newsweek magazines and the reuters news agency but said israeli authorities had the right to process the film first. the film, taken sunday, showed an israeli soldier moments after he was shot and killed in bethlehem
the soldier was the first israeli soldier to be killed since the unrest in the occupied territories broke out dec. 8. according to u.n. figures, 107 arabs have died in the unrest, most of them killed by israeli gunfire
we're not satisfied with the decision,'' said robert slater, a time correspondent and chairman of the foreign press association. ``we had demanded the return of the film immediately without it being processed.''
israeli officials rounded up at least 12 palestinians in the occupied gaza strip overnight, bringing to more than 107 the number of arabs arrested there in the past four days, the gaza lawyers' association said today
one attorney, raji sourani, said the lawyers' association counts only those reported by family members and estimated the actual number of arrests in the past four days in gaza at about 350
an islamic official in hebron said israeli soldiers had detained more than 150 imams, or moslem religious leaders, in nighttime roundups this week. the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said most of those detained were members of the fundamentalist islamic jihad movement
the army has confirmed it is making arrests but has refused to give details. israeli officials have said the tactic has reduced arab violence
the patriarch decided to suspend this sunday's procession because of the possibility of violence along its narrow, winding route through arab east jerusalem, said the rev. cladio baratto, director of the christian information center in the old city. the procession commemorates jesus' entry into jerusalem before his crucifixion
prudence suggests this decision. it was a personal decision of the patriarch and no other forces influenced him,'' baratto told the associated press
baratto denied reports that sabbah, jerusalem's first arab patriarch for latin-rite catholics, had been pressured by the underground leadership of the palestinian unrest to call off the ceremony, which has been canceled only three times since 1932
baratto told the jerusalem post there were fears that christians from the occupied territories would be prevented from attending due to curfews
