northwest airlines' bold step in banning smoking on most of its flights is not expected to be followed soon by other major u.s. airlines, industry analysts say
northwest, the nation's fifth-largest airline, announced wednesday it will prohibit smoking on all its domestic flights except those to and from hawaii and on some foreign routes
the ban makes eagan, minn.-based northwest the first major u.s. airline to mandate a smoke-free environment, surpassing federal regulations that on april 23 outlaw smoking on all domestic flights less than two hours
it does run the risk of some loss of business,'' said james v. cammisa, publisher of travel industry indicators, a new york-based newsletter. ``i guess they (northwest officials) really stuck their neck out.''
wall street seemed unimpressed by northwest's move. the airline's stock closed on wall street at $45.75 a share, down 12{ cents from tuesday
several smokers waiting to depart on northwest flights wednesday from minneapolis-st. paul international airport said they don't object to the smoking ban
it's probably a good idea,'' said janice davis, a boston real estate broker. ``i can get by without smoking.''
some northwest flight attendants who are smokers said the new policy might help them quit smoking, the st. paul pioneer press-dispatch reported today
the new policy, ``northwest clears the air,'' takes effect april 23 with the new federal regulations. it applies to flights within the contiguous 48 states and to and from alaska, mexico, canada, jamaica and the cayman islands
the longest flights covered by the smoking ban are four or five hours, the airline said. about 30 percent of northwest's domestic flights and about 20 percent of all domestic flights last more than the two-hour federal duration. northwest flights to and from hawaii and overseas will offer smoking sections because those flights ``carry a greater proportion of foreign passengers who feel differently about the issue,'' the airline said
a.b. magary, northwest's marketing chief, said the ban accedes to passenger and employee requests. the policy is not risk-free, he said, but ``we believe more nonsmokers will switch to northwest than smokers will leave.''
that wasn't the case for muse air corp. of dallas, a regional carrier that failed to establish itself as the only non-smoking airline in 1985. its research showed the policy diverted as many as 35 percent of potential fliers
surveys showed customers find ``price, convenience and service more important than non-smoking'' in an airline, muse spokeswoman shari cohen said at the time. the policy ended when muse was sold to southwest airlines co
no. 2 american airlines is watching northwest's lead but, ``we have no plans to follow that move,'' said american spokeswoman mary o'neill. its surveys indicate a significant number of people want to smoke on planes
american and other big airlines contacted wednesday said their no-smoking policies would meet the new federal law, which mandates civil fines of as much as $1,000 for smoking, $2,000 for tampering with lavatory smoke alarms
we are ready to implement our no-smoking policy ... in line with the federal law,'' said dan sheehy spokesman for united airline, the nation's largest airline
airline analyst anthony hatch of argus research corp., said he did not expect other carriers to match northwest's policy. ``it's a gutsy move and most airlines don't make gutsy moves,'' he said. ``it could alienate some people.''
the alienated include the great american smoker's club of dallas, which on april 22 offers smoking flights and the same fares as southwest airlines from dallas to such cities as austin, houston, new orleans and oklahoma city
using leased planes from las vegas-based royal west airlines, the club hopes to serve 63 cities from five hubs with 60 planes in two years, said club president glenn herndon
when the smoking ban begins, we want to offer smokers an alternative _ and, hopefully, make some money,'' he said. non-smokers will be allowed on board, but they will have to be ``tolerant,'' the club says
the new president of the southern baptist alliance says he intends to continue working within the southern baptist convention, though he says his group is taking on the appearance of a separate denomination
the alliance represents a moderate group within the 14.7 million-member convention, which is dominated by fundamentalists
we are not a fringe group, we are not an avant garde faction of the southern baptist convention,'' the rev. john thomason said wednesday. ``the great majority of sba members are denominational loyalists.''
thomason said, however, that the alliance may appear to be headed toward denominational status because of its publishing activities and its discussions concerning the possible need for a new seminary or divinity school
whenever we take specific steps like that, we are acting independently of the institutions of the southern baptist convention and that gives the appearance of independence, but it is not our desire to forge a permanent split with the sbc,'' thomason said
nevertheless, he said, the alliance has to be an ``advocate for groups and causes we feel are disenfranchised. ... if this means acting independently of the existing agencies and channels of sbc life, then for the time being, we are willing to do that.''
thomason is pastor of the 561-member northminster baptist church in jackson, miss., the third church to join the alliance after its formation in february 1987. the alliance has grown from 22 founders to more than 25,000 members, including 40 churches in 11 states and more than 2,000 individual members
the fundamentalists have gained control of the southern baptist convention hierarchy by electing their presidential candidates for the past nine years. the president has broad appointive powers, naming hundreds of people annually to various baptist institutions, including the boards of the six seminaries and the five major operating agencies of the denomination
while both groups generally are conservative, they disagree on key issues, including biblical inerrancy and ordination of women. fundamentalists, who oppose ordination of women, say the bible is without factual error, not only in matters of faith but also in science and history. moderates maintain there is room for interpretation, especially in non-religious areas. pvs, a survey</note>
the federal election commission today agreed to grant federal matching funds to the presidential campaign of political extremist lyndon larouche, who is standing trial on a charge relating to alleged irregularity in his 1984 campaign
the commission on a 5-1 vote said that larouche has fulfilled the requirements for eligibility to receive matching funds
commissioner joan aikens, voting against the majority, said that an fec survey of larouche contributors raised ``a question of patent irregularity'' in fund raising
but commissioner scott thomas said there was not enough evidence to deny certification, and he added, ``presidential candidates and campaigns can come in many different shapes and colors.''
a survey by the fec's audit staff found that several people whose checks ended up in larouche's 1988 presidential coffers did not intend to contribute to his campaign
that was the response of 6 percent of the 713 larouche contributors who answered the fec's survey
in describing the responses, the fec audit staff wrote in a report:
many of the responses included unsolicited written comments wherein the individuals described instances where he@she 1. felt pressured into making a contribution, 2. made contributions believing that the contribution was for a specific purpose other than furthering lyndon h. larouche jr.'s presidential nomination campaign, 3. made loans to the campaign, and 4. had contributed to a number of larouche's interests, while making all checks payable to ldc.''
the audit staff recommended the commission find that larouche is not eligible for matching funds
but the fec's legal staff came up with the opposite recommendation, stating that the ``patent irregularities indicated by the survey results do not justify an unfavorable eligibility report.''
the commission was expected to make its decision at a meeting early today
fec legal counsel lawrence noble's written opinion said some of the responding contributors seemed confused, or contributed to larouche thinking he was a republican or independent candidate instead of a democrat, which he is. those responses should not have been considered negative, noble said, because the donors did apparently intend to give money to a presidential campaign
the auditors contacted 1,062 of those contributors, after finding that some of the checks he submitted with his application for federal matching funds were made out simply to the initials ``l.d.c.''
in some cases, those initials were written over the initials ``sdi.'' and some checks contained memo notations regarding aids or sdi _ which generally refers to president reagan's strategic defense initiative _ indicating the donors may not have intended to give money to a presidential campaign, but to one of those causes
some contributors contacted by the associated press said they were under the impression they were contributing to an anti-aids campaign when they gave checks to larouche solicitors
while the survey results raise serious questions regarding whether contributions submitted by the larouche campaign were made with the requisite donative intent, they do not show a clear pattern of fraud or patent irregularities,'' noble wrote. he also said the percent of negative responses _ 39 out of 713 _ was ``arguably small.''
nonetheless, the counsel recommended that the commission take special precautions in approving larouche's submissions for matching funds. instead of the usual five-day approval period, a review period of 25 days should be allowed for the larouche submissions to give the fec staff time to check for irregularities in the checks before giving him any money, the counsel recommended
the recommendation also suggests that any checks written out simply to ldc, or those with memo notations ``indicating lack of donative intent'' should be automatically declared unmatchable
to be certified for matching funds, a candidate must raise $100,000 across 20 states in individual contributions of $250 or less. after becoming eligible, the candidates can receive matching funds for each contribution of $250 or less that they raise privately
larouche is on trial in boston, charged with conspiracy to obstruct a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud and other irregularities in his 1984 campaign
yugoslavia's ruling body today called for the first time for a ``radical'' reduction of state interference in the economy as a way to solve the nation's worst economic and political crisis in history
the lengthy statement from the presidency also urged new regulations on joint ventures with foreign partners, more private business in the nation's economy and changes in the tax policy which would stimulate economic growth
the unusual statement, carried by the official tanjug news agency, marked the first time yugoslavia's ruling body had called for changes in the running of the economy of this nonaligned communist nation
the statement appeared designed to give guidance to the government for tackling the economic and political problems expected to arise when a wage and price freeze imposed last november expires in may
there have been increasing calls for the state and the communist party to relinquish control of the economy
with the current annual inflation rate of around 170 percent and a foreign debt exceeding $20 billion, yugoslavia is faced with its worst economic and political crisis in history
the presidency demanded that ``a program of measures and activities'' be made by the federal government to strengthen market forces and called for ``radical reduction of state regulations ... in order to overcome the dominating role of the politics over the economy.''
the statement said the implementation of this program is of ``prime interest'' and should be monitored by the presidencies of yugoslavia's six constituent republics and two autonomous provinces
critics of yugoslavia's unique system of self-management, whereby factories, farms and offices are nominally run by the workers, say the system is hampered by interference from the state and the communist party
the government last year imposed a series of price and wage freezes in an attempt to control inflation and stabilize sinking living standards. however, 1987 saw a record 1,500 strikes as workers protested low wages
the government of yugoslav premier branko mikulic has recently faced sharp criticism even in the state-run press for its economic policies. there have been repeated calls for the premier and his cabinet to step down _ something that has never happened in communist yugoslavia
the statement by the presidency said such calls ``represent an unacceptable political campaign'' that hurts the government's domestic and foreign activities
the presidency demanded, without specifying, an ``urgent'' passing of new joint venture laws
according to current law provisions, foreign companies can own no more than 51 percent shares in their joint ventures with yugoslav enterprises and have no right to manage the companies
the current law attracted little investment by foreign partners since the unstable economic situation in this balkan country frightens off possible investors
according to a draft of a new joint venture law, which has been waiting for a long time to be passed by the parliament, foreign partners may be allowed to hold up to 99.9 percent of shares in joint ventures and the right to manage such companies
the ruling body also called for ``substantial'' reduction of administrative curbs on private business and changes in the income tax policy. back to zeebrugge and restores dropped word `the' in 2nd graf. picks up 3rd graf, `coast guards ...</note>
a blaze erupted today in the engine room of a british ferry shortly after it left the belgian port of zeebrugge with 348 people aboard, but tugs towed the ship to port and no one was injured
p and o, owners of the 18,000-ton nordic, said the two-hour fire wrecked the ferry's power system
coast guards called a major alert after the nordic, on a six-hour english channel crossing from zeebrugge to the english port of felixstowe, reported fire aboard 30 minutes before it had been due to dock
the nordic, surrounded by a flotilla of tugs and life boats, was stranded for several hours five miles off the coast before tugs got the vessel under tow and brought it to felixstowe, in southeast england
three life boats were dispatched and a helicopter was put on standby,'' said john davies, coast guard spokesman at the nearby port of harwich
a p and o spokesman said the fire was put out by automatic firefighting equipment and the crew. the fire was confined to the engine room
everyone on board was very calm and there was no danger to anyone,'' said p and o spokesman chris lamming
last march, another p and o ferry, the herald of free enterprise, capsized after leaving zeebrugge, killing 193 people
