iran and iraq fired eight missiles into each others' capitals today, and tehran claimed new victories in heavy fighting in northeastern iraq
iraq said it fired six long-range missiles into tehran at a rate of one a minute in retaliation for iranian artillery bombardment of iraqi cities. iraq said it was destroying tehran ``piece by piece.''
iran reported at least 10 civilians dead and 100 wounded after the missiles hit two schools, two mosques and two hospitals as well as shops and houses
iran's official islamic republic news agency, monitored in nicosia, cyprus, said iranian revolutionary guards fired two missiles into baghdad in reprisal
there was no immediate confirmation of those missile strikes from the iraqi capital
in the persian gulf today, a ship put out a distress signal and appeared to be the victim of an iranian attack, maritime salvage executives said
the executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the friendship reported its engine room was on fire. if it was the victim of iranian attack, it would be iran's 10th attack on neutral shipping in the gulf since last friday
iran also claimed its troops routed two iraqi commando brigades and four armored battalions early today and advanced to within five miles of the mountain town of sayyid sadiq. the reports came in the latest phase of iran's 9-day-old offensive into northeastern iraq
iran said today's ground assault retaliated for iraqi chemical bomb attacks last week that killed 5,000 iraqi kurds whose hometowns were overrun by iranian troops fighting with the autonomy-seeking kurds
tehran's news agency said the iranians repulsed a counterattack by iraq's 5th army corps, killing or wounding 1,000 iraqis, capturing 400 and knocking out 30 tanks and armored vehicles
but the official iraqi news agency, also monitored in cyprus, said ``thousands of iranians were killed'' in artillery barrages and air strikes
the charlatan regime in tehran is reaping today the harvest of its crimes,'' said an iraqi military communique broadcast by the agency
iranian jets flew 14 ground attack missions against iraqi forces in the battle zone and shot down an iraqi warplane, tehran's news agency said. it said ground fire downed an iraqi helicopter gunship, but baghdad denied losing any aircraft
iraq has said it has fired 42 al hussein missiles into tehran since march 15 in what is known as the ``war of the cities.'' iran has retaliated by lobbing 14 missiles into the iraqi capital, which has a population of 5 million
scores of other cities on both sides have been hit with missiles, air raids and shellfire, with hundreds of civilians killed or wounded on both sides
the iranian news agency said the latest phase of the offensive, the heaviest fighting in the northern part of the 730-mile front, was launched in retaliatiation for iraqi chemical bomb attacks on halabja, khormal and dojaila, three of the kurdish towns captured last week
the iranians claimed the poison gas attacks killed 5,000 kurdish civilians and injured 5,000. western reporters flown to halabja by the iranians this week reported seeing hundreds of dead civilians there with no obvious wounds
the correspondents reported that many people had died of asphyxiation in their homes. survivors were seen suffering from burns consistent with poison gas
u.s. state department spokesman charled redman charged in washington wednesday that iraq had used chemical weapons, banned under a 1925 geneva agreement, and urged the united nations security council to mount an international protest
declaring the iraqi action ``a particularly grave violation'' of the geneva protocol, redman said there was evidence the iraqis had also fired chemical shells into iran
the iranian news agency said earlier this week that iraqi warplanes had dropped chemical bombs, believed to contain mustard or phosgene gas, on eight towns in northwest iran, causing scores of civilian casualties. picks up 7th graf, `feldman said ...</note>
an israeli court today convicted former nuclear technician mordechai vanunu of treason and espionage for telling a british newspaper his country possessed nuclear weapons. he could receive a life prison term
the verdict, read behind closed doors in a courtroom with boarded-up windows, climaxed the saga of the 34-year-old israeli who said he revealed his country's nuclear secrets for the good of mankind
mordechai is not desperate. he still wants to fight,'' said defense attorney avigdor feldman as he emerged from the five-minute session. he said vanunu sat silently as the verdict was announced, showing little emotion
i guess it was kind of inevitable,'' said vanunu's younger brother, asher, who was not permitted into the secret proceedings. ``but i'm surprised they convicted him for treason.''
vanunu was hustled into the courtroom more than an hour before the session, amid the same tight security that accompanied the trial since it began in september. the three-judge panel had refused an open trial, saying it would harm state security
prosecutor uzi chasson said he would ask the court for a life term, which in israel is limited to 20 years. sentencing is scheduled sunday
feldman said he would appeal the verdict to israel's high court of justice
vanunu, a former technician at israel's nuclear facility in dimona and a jewish-born convert to christianity, was charged with treason and espionage for describing israel's nuclear capacity in an interview with the sunday times of london. based on vanunu's information, the newspaper concluded israel had stockpiled the world's sixth largest nuclear arsenal
israel has never responded directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to introduce nuclear weapons into the middle east
vanunu has insisted he made his revelations to alert the middle east and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons. the state argued he intended to harm israel's security
feldman said earlier he thought vanunu had been given a fair hearing, but complained about ``an atmosphere of guilt, with all the attention and the crazy precautions taken around him.''
each day of the trial, vanunu was taken to the jerusalem district courthouse from his jail in central israel in a white van with painted-over windows
his head was often covered with a motorcycle helmet to prevent contact with waiting reporters, and police cars blared sirens as he was hustled indoors
in prison, vanunu has been held in near isolation, permitted to see only his attorney and relatives. at one point, he went on a hunger strike to demand the right to see his american girlfriend, judy zimet
vanunu's mysterious saga began in 1985 when he was fired from the dimona nuclear center in southern israel, where he worked for nine years. he went to australia, where he became acquainted with a priest and converted to christianity
vanunu later traveled to london, but disappeared in october 1986, just days before the sunday times published his revelations. israeli officials acknowledged several weeks later he was in custody in israel
details of vanunu's dramatic journey back to israel were revealed by his brother, meir, who said vanunu was lured from london to rome by an american woman named cindy, who promised him sex. in rome, he was abducted by israeli agents and spirited home, meir said
at a pre-trial court appearance, vanunu managed to flash reporters a message scribbled on his hand which told of the alleged abduction. the incident led to increased security precautions
during the trial, feldman presented witnesses who said vanunu had not harmed state security because the information he revealed was already available in the academic world
other defense witnesses testified vanunu's revelations actually bolstered israel's security because they created the impression among the country's arab enemies that israel was a nuclear power, providing a deterrent effect
feldman argued alternatively that if israel had nuclear weapons, it was acting outside international supervision, a position that was morally and legally unsound
in a surprise move, he also subpoenaed foreign minister shimon peres and senior legislator abba eban in an effort to show israel's leaders kept the decision to build nuclear weapons from the parliament and the people, thereby violating israeli law
authorities will ask gov. bob martinez to appoint a special prosecutor to handle the case of an assistant state attorney who police say tried to bully an officer into letting her go
chief assistant state atorney mack futch also said he is suspending jan bamping until state attorney frank schaub returns next week from vacation and reviews his decision
police say ms. bamping, 32, and a passenger, assistant state attorney jerry blevins, 27, threatened an officer in an attempt to avoid getting into trouble, the bradenton herald reported wednesday
their car had been pulled over by bradenton beach patrolman ron robertson early sunday after a 1{-mile chase at speeds of up to 90 mph, police reports said
robertson said he believed ms. bamping had been drinking, but didn't order her from the car for a sobriety test because she was naked from the waist down
when he asked ms. bamping why she was partially nude, robertson said, she became upset and answered that it's ``not against the law to drive nude.''
robertson charged ms. bamping with fleeing to elude an officer and improper passing
she threatened (his job) right away,'' said acting police chief bill tillner. ``in my opinion, (blevins) did try to influence the officer with his position.''
she said because she was with the state attorney's office, she should not be treated like this,'' robertson said. ``i told her she had no right to endanger other people because of her job.''
ms. bamping demanded his name and identification number and said ``she would see me in court,'' he said
robertson's back-up officer, patrolman john cosby, confirmed robertson's account, tillner said
no charges were brought against blevins
ms. bamping's telephone number is not published, and she could not be located for comment. the herald also said it had been unable to reach her
but blevins told the herald: ``i don't think we did anything improper as far as using this office.''
ms. bamping's case was scheduled for may 11 in traffic court
the lawyer for a man charged with sexually assaulting his daughter says the allegations are more of the same from the man's ex-wife, who last year went to jail rather than let him visit their children
mark russell murabito, 33, of derry pleaded innocent wednesday in rockingham county superior court to the charge of felonious sexual assault. bail was set at $5,000 personal recognizance on the condition that murabito have no contact with the daughter, now 5, or her 3{-year-old brother
murabito since march 1987 has had unsupervised visits with the children, after a judge found no evidence to back jesse murabito's claims that murabito sexually abused their daughter
a grand jury last week indicted murabito based on events since the judge's decision, county attorney carleton eldredge said
after wednesday's arraignment, raymond kellett, murabito's lawyer, said the charge ``is simply an extension of the divorce proceedings ... the same type of thing that the court has already ruled on in hearings last year.''
i am fairly convinced by the evidence, or i wouldn't have gone to the grand jury, that these children are being sexually abused,'' eldredge said, adding that he has an ``obligation, in my job and my conscience, to alleviate that situation.''
eldredge blamed the media for ruining any chance he would have had to negotiate an out-of-court agreement with murabito that would result in ``long-term meaningful protection of the children without public fanfare or trial.''
in march 1987, superior court judge douglas gray ruled after a seven-day civil hearing that mrs. murabito and the experts she marshaled had not proved murabito sexually abused the girl
in a 19-page divorce decree, gray admonished both parents to stop ``tearing (the children) to pieces'' and gave murabito unsupervised visits, alternating weekends and holidays, as well as two weeks each summer
gray did not return a telephone call seeking comment on wednesday
a month before the divorce hearing, gray had jailed mrs. murabito for a week _ and gave murabito temporary custody _ when she refused to obey a court order to let her husband see the children during supervised visits. gray released her after she agreed
sen. joseph r. biden jr., d-del., left the hospital today, smiling, joking and saying he feels better than he looks
i've decided to re-enter the race for president,'' he joked. the senator dropped out of the democratic race last fall
biden had been in walter reed army hospital for 11 days so surgeons could implant a small umbrella-like filter in a vein to prevent blood clots from reaching his lungs
a clot formed in the wake of surgery biden had on feb. 12 to correct the ballooning of an artery that supplied blood to his brain
he was to have a second operation for a similar but smaller aneurysm on the other side of his head but instead returned to walter reed on march 13 and doctors discovered a blood clot in his lung
the clot itself was absorbed into the body without any damage, a hospital spokesman said, but to prevent any further problems a team of doctors last friday inserted a tiny filter in a major vein. the small device was implanted in the vena cava, an area just below the breast bone
biden said doctors will allow him to work two to four hours a day at home in delaware and that he should walk as exercise
he said that for the first time in years his waist size is 34
a judge has blocked the ku klux klan from holding a rally in a predominantly black neighborhood, citing zoning laws that prohibit public gatherings without special permission
we consider (the klan) similar to clubs and other organizations such as churches or synagogues'' which cannot hold public gatherings in residential areas without special permits, said superior court judge william fleming
fleming on wednesday enjoined the klan from holding a rally and cross-burning friday in the yard of robert long, grand dragon of the christian knights of the ku klux klan
the judge ruled that the gathering was public because klan members had distributed flyers inviting the public
the group could ask for a special exemption from the zoning board, but long said the rally will be moved instead
the richmond county commission and sheriff charles webster had gone to court to oppose the rally
last april, county investigators interrupted a cross-burning in long's yard and filed charges of terroristic threats and acts against 13 people, including long. that case is pending
twenty-eight current and former health inspectors were named in complaints today accusing them of extorting hundreds of thousands of dollars from restaurants to ignore sanitary code violations, authorities say
the charges in the federal complaint involve at least one-third of the city health department's inspection force of 70 and 300 restaurants in all five boroughs, u.s. attorney andrew j. maloney of brooklyn said in a news release
the arrests this morning culminated a three-year undercover investigation by the fbi, the city department of investigation and the u.s. attorney's office. this week agents confronted a number of suspects to get them to wear microphones to gather evidence against the leaders of the bribery ring
a report today in the new york daily news said the operation was code-named alternatively ``operation kitchen'' and ``operation fork-it-over.''
the restaurants paid the bribes to avoid citations for violations either real or invented, authorities said. the names of the restaurants were not made public, but they ranged from fast food restaurants to famous eateries, they said
the investigation also found that on-site inspectors split their take with supervisors, who allegedly would punish inspectors who were reluctant to share the extortion money with them, authorities said
in one incident, inspectors demanded $1,400 from a restaurant owner so his restaurant would not be closed for serious health violations, according to the news release. in another, inspectors charged a restaurant $1,200 to allow it to reopen despite serious violations
payoffs reached hundreds of thousands of dollars altogether. the news said the restaurant owners are considered extortion victims and are not being charged
inspectors and supervisors are paid $25,000 to $30,000 annually by the city. more than 15,000 food establishments are inspected each year for compliance with health and cleanliness standards
four military leaders imprisoned for an alleged coup attempt against mao tse-tung in 1971 have been released, a government spokesman said today
all four were top assistants to defense minister lin piao during the ultra-leftist cultural revolution that began in 1966, and all were convicted of aiding him in an aborted attempt to murder mao and seize power
the releases leave only the ``gang of four'' still in prison from among the 10 fallen cultural revolution power brokers convicted in 1981 after a lengthy show trial
lin was mao's designated successor, a key creator of the mao cult and author of the ``little red book'' of quotations from mao. he allegedly died in a plane crash in mongolia while fleeing arrest
zeng tao, a spokesman for the national people's congress, china's legislature, disclosed the releases at a news conference
he said former air force commander wu faxian, former navy political commissar li zuopeng and former army gen. jiang tengjiao were released on bail for medical treatment, but he did not say when or disclose the nature of their illnesses
qiu huizuo, former director of the military's general logistics department, completed his 16-year term in september and was released, zeng said
he did not explain why as recently as january, the ministry of public security insisted that all four former military leaders remained in prison. wu's and li's terms end this year, while jiang's ends in 1989
zeng said two of the gang of four members _ mao's widow jiang qing and former vice premier zhang chunqiao _ were being treated in prison for unspecified ``geriatric diseases.'' jiang qing is 74 and zhang is 70
the gang of four, which also included former politburo members wang hongwen and yao wenyuan, was accused of ordering illegal arrests during the decade-long cultural revolution and trying to seize total power after mao's death in 1976
their arrest shortly after mao died marked the end of the cultural revolution, an era of bloody persecutions of intellectuals and anyone suspected of lacking revolutionary fervor. legislation</head>
landmark aids legislation described by sponsors as a model for america has gone into effect in washington, aimed at protecting the disease's victims and stopping its spread
the measure, funded by an appropriation of more than $5 million, will tackle the killer disease through education, testing, counseling, civil rights protection, and prosecution of people who intentionally spread acquired immune deficiency syndrome
gov. booth gardner signed the bill wednesday and it took effect immediately
we must recognize that aids is only beginning to take its toll on human life and in costs to our society. by acting now, especially with a strong public education program, we hope to save many of our citizens' lives,'' the governor said
key provisions of the measure are:
_a 10-year prison sentence for intentionally spreading the aids virus
_mandatory aids education in grades 5 through 12 and availability in colleges and trade schools. mandatory aids training for all public school personnel, emergency services crews and health professionals
_mandatory testing and counseling for all convicted of sex crimes, prostitution or intravenous drug use. violent prison inmates would be tested at the request of the prison and approval of the local health officer
_a procedure is created for confronting, examining, detaining and confining infected individuals who refuse to modify their behavior so they don't pose a threat to others. due process protections are provided
_regional service networks will be set up in the six most populous counties by oct. 1
_those who carry the aids virus, or who are perceived to have it, will be protected from discrimination
jule sugarman, head of the department of social and health services, said he already had followed the bill's directive and created a new office on aids. he said he began to confer with county health officials on setting up regional aids service centers across washington
those centers will do the mandatory and voluntary aids testing, counseling, public education, and outreach to ``street kids'' and other target populations. they also will plan and coordinate services to aids patients, develop volunteer networks and notify partners of infected people
this bill will make an enormous difference,'' said jim holm of the privacy lobby and the gay rights dorian group. ``we've taken a step toward making it safe to know your antibody status, whether you're at risk, and safe to seek public health (services)
in this state we've finally said civil rights and public health go hand-in-hand.''
the important thing is that we did get a statewide policy on aids,'' said state sen. alex deccio, co-sponsor of the measure. ``it's the first omnibus bill of its kind in the country, so i guess it's the best available.''
checks that disintegrate into confetti shortly after being deposited have cost banks nearly $50,000 this year, the chicago clearing house association says
it warned banks this week to be on the lookout for dissolving checks, and the fbi has been asked to determine whether the chemical used to destroy the checks is harmful to humans
northern trust bank has been hit by a number of the checks, an association memo says
in one case, a northern customer deposited a $4,000 check in a savings account on feb. 16, then withdrew the same amount a week later from one of the bank's branch offices, the memo said
the $4,000 check was returned to northern in a check carrier on march 2, but by then it had been ``reduced to mere confetti, small bits of paper that appeared to be treated with chemicals that caused the paper to break into pieces to a point where it was impossible to identify any information on the check,'' the memo said. vote</head>
a union negotiating committee has voted to submit a tentative contract for ratification by northwest airlines' 6,500 flight attendants, says a teamsters official
the 15-member committee met at teamsters headquarters in bloomington and approved the vote wednesday night, said jeff musto, a teamsters spokesman
my personal feeling is that yes, they will ratify it,'' musto said
it will take about 30 days to complete the vote, he said
musto declined to release details of the tentative accord, although he earlier confirmed that the contract will require all flight attendants to join the union
both sides said the march 29 strike deadline, set by the flight attendants last week, provided the impetus for an agreement
the key issue has been northwest's two-tier wage structure. the airline had proposed extending the lower-paid, b-scale to eight years from the current five years
b-scale flight attendants said the airline was trying to break a promise that they would earn a-scale wages after five years
the star tribune of minneapolis, citing unidentified sources, reported today that the tentative agreement calls for b-scale employees to move up after seven years
a man whose conviction on a charge of failing to comply with peacetime draft registration rules was overturned says he has spent quite enough time in jail
i think there's a strong argument to be made that the government should not retry this case at all, since i've already served more time than most people convicted of failing to register,'' said gillam kerley, whose conviction was thrown out wednesday by the 7th u.s. circuit court of appeals
kerly served four months of his sentence
the appeals court ruled that u.s. district judge john shabaz gave the jury flawed instructions
shabaz sentenced kerley to three years in prison and fined him $10,000, one of the most severe sentences in a draft case since the vietnam war
u.s. attorney patrick fiedler said he would review the decision before deciding whether to seek a new trial
kerley pleaded ``not guilty by reason of sanity'' in 1982 to a federal indictment for failing to register. he fought the government for 4{ years as his own attorney before being convicted last april. 0620</first> gephardt's...</note>
richard gephardt will end his campaign for the democratic presidential nomination and file for re-election to his missouri house seat if he doesn't win the michigan caucuses on saturday, a campaign aide said today
speaking on the condition of anonymity, the aide said gephardt would probably announce the end of his campaign on monday and file for re-election to his house seat by the tuesday afternoon deadline
he will be out if he doesn't win in michigan,'' said the aide
while gephardt's spokesmen officially denied any decision has been made, the congressman's wife told a radio interviewer that the end may be near
i think dick has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race, because at some point if you don't do well here, it becomes difficult to raise money,'' she told wtvb radio in coldwater, mich. ``dick's message will be very popular in the industrial states, but if we don't do well here, we will not be able to continue.''
gephardt is running third in the polls in michigan behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson. gephardt is badly in need of a win after a weak showing in the super tuesday contests earlier this month
the aide also said some consideration was being given to gephardt's ending his presidential bid even if he wins in michigan
only as rep. gephardt can he raise the money to pay off the debts'' from the presidential campaign, the aide said
spokesmen for gephardt denied that a decision has been made
this notion that the decision has been made before the results are in is false,'' said mark johnson in washingon
johnson also said that the campaign ``does not have a large debt. we have virtually no bank debt. ... we have some vendor debts.''
there's never been any question that if the presidential effort was not successful that dick would probably run for his house seat,'' said ali webb, gephardt spokeswoman in detroit. ``he's going to pursue his political agenda and his issues for this country from the house, if not from the presidency. but right now, he's running for president.''
publicly, gephardt on wednesday refused to link his showing in michigan to his candidacy
asked if his saturday's results would make or break his campaign, gephardt said, ``that's unthinkable.''
all decisions are made in due time,'' he said
earlier, a st. louis democratic leader said a weekend meeting was scheduled among the democratic contenders for gephardt's congressional seat
the dallas times herald reported today that the participants at that meeting would be told gephardt was preparing to seek re-election to the house instead of the white house
we're getting the major candidates together and talking about procedure and unity, said the democratic leader, tony ribaudo. ``that's normal in st. louis politics. i don't know what dick gephardt's going to do.''
state rep. philip barry of st. louis county, one of the leading contenders for the congressional seat, told the times herald the meeting would be attended by six candidates who have filed for gephardt's seat, plus a st. louis alderman who is expected to file if gephardt decides not to seek re-election
one of the candidates, george kerry, an administrative aide in gephardt's st. louis office, told the assoiated press wednesday night that he knew nothing of the meeting
kerry, who has said he would drop out of the race if gephardt files for re-election, said he understood gephardt was waiting to see how he fared in michigan on saturday before making a decision
the nation's federally insured savings institutions lost $3.2 billion in the last three months of 1987, pushing the industry's losses for the year to a post-depression record of $6.8 billion, the government said today
the industry, composed of 3,147 thrift institutions, had earned $132 million a year earlier. the 1987 loss was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous record of $4.6 billion, set in 1981, when the prime lending rate soared above 20 percent
the fourth quarter loss compared to a loss of $1.8 billion in the third quarter, 1.9 billion in the spring quarter and a profit of $100 million in the first three months of 1987
james barth, chief economist of the federal home loan bank board, which released the figures, said losses were heavily concentrated in the southwest, which is dependent on the ailing oil and gas industry
sixty-six percent of the institutions nationwide reported a total profit of $1.3 billion in the fourth quarter, while the 1,058 unprofitable s&amp;ls lost $4.5 billion in all
for the year, the profitable two-thirds of the industry earned $6.6 billion, which was more than offset by the $13.4 billion deficit of the money-losing s&amp;ls
the percentage of the industry earning a profit has steadily declined for two years, from 81 percent in the first quarter of 1986 to 66 percent at the end of last year
barth said the worst 20 institutions _ most of them in the southwest _ lost a total of $2.1 billion in the final quarter of last year, accounting for two-thirds of the overall industry loss
barth said 345 of the s&amp;ls were insolvent at the end of 1987 under regulatory accounting principles and 510 were insolvent under the stricter, generally accepted accounting principles that will be used beginning next year
an institution is considered insolvent when its loans and other assets are worth less than what it owes to depositors and other creditors
the federal savings and loan insurance corp., the fund backing deposits up to $100,000 in federally insured s&amp;ls, has been hampered in closing insolvent s&amp;ls by lack of money. congress in august authorized a three-year, $10.8 billion recapitalization
last month, the bank board announced a plan to spend $6 billion to $7 billion in insurance fund money to close insolvent texas institutions or merge them into healthier s&amp;ls. the bank board is still accepting applications from private investors to participate in the restructuring and doesn't plan any announcements before early april
the nation's 13,700 federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7 billion last year, their lowest profit since 1933, the federal deposit insurance corp. reported earlier this month
the senate judiciary committee approved by voice vote today legislation designed to restore legal rights to individuals who were exposed to radiation when the united states tested atomic weapons
the measure, whose chief sponsor is sen. paul simon, d-ill., would repeal a provision of a 1985 defense department bill that curtailed sharply the legal rights of civilians and veterans who participated in the atomic testing program
until 1985, radiation victims could file suit against contractors who participated in the testing programs. the 1985 act shifted the target of radiation suits from defense contractors to the federal government. version also moved on the financial wire.</note>
david a. stockman, the former white house budget director, is leaving the investment firm salomon brothers to join its smaller rival blackstone group, it was announced today
stockman, a managing director at salomon since leaving the white house in 1985, will handle all merchant banking activities and merger transactions for the blackstone group, the company said
his departure from salomon comes against a background of turmoil within the venerable investment firm, a partial result of the uncertain outlook for wall street in the aftermath of the stock market crash five months ago
several other high-ranking executives also have quit salomon recently, although stockman was quoted by the new york times today as saying his departure was unrelated to the company's problems
my experience at salomon was absolutely agreeable and i have a high regard for (salomon chairman) john gutfreund,'' stockman said. ``...there's one thing i couldn't do there _ which is have my own shop.''
former commerce secretary peter g. peterson, chairman of blackstone, said that stockman will take charge of a jointly owned firm called ``stockman &amp; co. _ a blackstone group affiliate.''
peterson said he wanted stockman to bolster blackstone's emerging merchant banking business in japan
dave stockman will be an immensely valuable asset in meeting that goal,'' he said. ``he brings a global perspective on business and financial issues as well as intimate familiarity with both u.s. and japanese government policies.''
blackstone recently represented sony in a $2 billion acquisition of cbs records late last year and represented firestone tire &amp; rubber co. in its $2.6 billion acquisition by japan's bridgestone corp
stockman, 41, was white house budget director from 1981 to 1985
