two passenger trains collided head-on today in a shanghai suburb, killing 12 people and injuring more than 40, the state-run xinhua news agency said. it was china's fourth fatal train accident in three months
china's second official news agency, the china news service, said only seven were dead, including five japanese, a chinese soldier and a railway worker. it said 40 to 50 people were hospitalized
the japanese embassy confirmed that a 193-member japanese high school tour group was on one of the trains. it said the japan travel bureau, which arranged the tour, reported two japanese killed and 29 injured
xinhua said 11 japanese were killed
the cause of the collision in the shanghai suburb of fengbang was not immediately clear, said fu fenghao, chief of the shanghai foreign affairs office's public relations division
xinhua, however, said one of the trains ignored a stop signal when it left the shanghai station
the crash occurred at about 2 p.m. when northbound train no. 311, leaving shanghai for hangzhou, collided with southbound train no. 208 arriving from changsha, fu said
no. 311's first two cars and the luggage car of no. 208 were knocked off the tracks, he said
television footage by japanese camera crews broadcast in japan showed the luggage car resting on one end of the other train's engine. the china news service said the two first-class passenger cars behind the no. 311 engine were crushed together by the force of the collision
the news service said shanghai had rain and heavy fog today but did not say if this was believed to have contributed to the accident
xinhua said the no. 311 train ``rolled out of the kuangxiang station, ignoring the prohibiting signal, and collided with the no. 208 train that was entering the station.''
kengo kobayashi of the japanese embassy in beijing said two people from a high school in southern japan's kochi prefecture were among the dead, and 29 others were injured
fu confirmed that japanese students were among the dead and injured but said the number was not yet determined
we haven't heard any information about other nationalities,'' he added
we were playing cards and suddenly there was a loud bang, and things went flying all over the floor,'' said an unidentified male student interviewed in shanghai by the japan broadcasting corp
there was a huge bump, and then one of our teachers came into the car and told us to get out,'' said another student. ``we broke the windows and climbed out.''
the train tracks were blocked seven hours after the accident, fu said. he said soldiers, police and medical workers took the dead and injured to nearby hospitals and that investigators were at the scene trying to determine the cause
shanghai vice mayor huang ju also went to the scene, the china news service said
in january, three separate train accidents killed 141 people. china's minister of railways resigned this month to take responsibility for those accidents
this year's train accidents, together with a plane crash outside chungking in january that killed all 108 people aboard, have prompted severe calls by the beijing government for greater attention to safety
a pair of barges loaded with a flammable liquid today slammed into the end of the pensacola fishing pier, a former bridge billed as the world's longest fishing pier
the barges were wedged into the l-shaped vehicular turnaround at the tip of the pier, formerly a highway bridge across pensacola bay connecting pensacola and gulf breeze. the bridge was divided into two sections, each becoming fishing piers. the pensacola pier is 1.5 miles long
the wind caught it and blew him into the bridge (pier),'' said grey jewett, risk manager for escambia county, which owns the pier. ``it destroyed the end of the pier, a turnaround. it's not reparable.''
the pier is only 75 feet away from the new pensacola bay bridge. officials said they planned to block traffic on the new, four-lane bridge while attempts were made to pull the barges, which were tied together along with a towboat, from the pier
the barges were loaded with benzine, a colorless, flammable liquid used as a motor fuel and solvent in dry cleaning
none of the benzine apparently leaked, but officials were worried about possible fire or explosion
it's not the benzine, it's the vapor,'' said chuck ramsey, an engineering technician for the county. ``it would go with one spark.''
one of the barges was pushed into the shipping channel, blocking navigation traffic
six disneyland hotel workers who rebelled against the magic kingdom's ban on facial hair were suspended for three days without pay and given an order to shave or be fired
the hotel's 1,600 workers recently came under the famed amusement park's dress and grooming codes when their former boss, the wrather corp., sold the property to the walt disney co
the dress code, established in 1957, bans facial hair on men, mandates short haircuts and bars women from wearing heavy makeup, long fingernails or excessive jewelry
the six suspended wednesday have until monday to shave or lose their jobs, said disneyland spokesman bob roth
a dozen male employees have been issued warnings for facial hair, and although half of those shaved, all 12 filed grievances with their unions
earlier wednesday, the five unions representing hotel workers united in opposition to the disney dress code, but wouldn't say whether they were willing to strike over it
a hindu occult priest strangled a 7-year-old girl to offer her blood to a goddess in a ritual and stored her body in his temple complex, it was reported thursday
the priest, narayan gangadhar poojary, and four others were arrested after residents of manpada village in the central indian maharashtra state complained of a foul smell and called police, the hindustan times and patriot newspapers said
police inspector r.m. patil said the body of the girl, identified as nandita shinde, was found in the loft of a building near the temple. it was hidden in fodder and cow dung
police said the priest apparently called the girl inside the temple friday, the newspapers said. he was believed to have strangled her and cut an artery in her left leg to draw blood for the ritual offering aimed at pleasing a goddess, they said
human sacrifices are outlawed in india, but still occur from time to time, mainly in rural areas
this is one of a series of periodic reports compiled by associated press bureaus on how the u.s. presidential election campaign is viewed abroad
here's a sampling of what newspapers abroad are saying about the u.s. presidential election campaign and the candidates seeking the republican and democratic nominations:
_the times of london (conservative), on democrat michael dukakis: ``the rest of the world should start thinking about a possible president dukakis. and a possible president dukakis should start thinking about the rest of the world
his apparent ignorance of it will provoke the traditional censoriousness about american politicians, not just from europeans, but from well-bred americans. ..
unlike most american politicians, mr. dukakis speaks a foreign language (spanish). this means he addresses the newly-important hispanic vote in its mother tongue. if it means much else, it is something to worry about. if american politicians start addressing special groups of voters in languages unintelligible to the majority, it is one more denial of the notion of america as melting pot.''
_the independent of london (independent), on george bush: ``it is tempting to conclude that he achieved this pre-eminent position because of the errors and failings of his opponents rather than through his own efforts. it is true that his chief rival, sen. robert dole, has had a disastrous campaign following his one transient success in iowa. but to give mr. bush credit, his campaign has been almost faultless and it was largely due to his good organization and well-lined campaign coffers that he was able to recover so convincingly after the setback in iowa.''
_la repubblica, national (liberal): ``the dilemma that confronts the candidates is not between the `poor' and the `rich.' ... the dilemma is in the schizophrenia of middle america, divided by the desire not to change anything and the fear of not being able to stay the same
this uncertainty, more than the fear of confronting the unknown in the cursed equation `italian equals mafia', is the real calculation that has kept mario cuomo out of the competition. his capital of expectations and fascination is too big to be gambled today on the roulette of the american mood in 1988.''
_new straits times of kuala lumpur, english language (pro-government): ``democrat richard gephardt terrified americans about the invasion of cheaper foreign goods
his clarion call to raise high the trade barriers in retaliation for unfair trade practices summoned few followers to the barricades, and his campaign should be spluttering to a halt soon.''
