the george bush `express' seems unstoppable. ... however, he's not as bad as brazilians might imagine. he's from the east coast elite. and there was a time when this liberal elite dominated, or at least heavily influenced, the republican party.''
a 20-year-old east german scaled a 10-foot fence under thick fog in northern bavaria to escape his communist homeland, west german police said thursday
the escape took place wednesday night in the upper franken section of the region, according to munich police. the man was not identified
east german guards were seen searching the area after the escape over the steel-mesh fence. they apparently were tipped off by electronic sensors on the barriers, police said
at least 20 east germans have fled over their homeland's fortified barriers into west germany this year
an iranian slashed his wrists thursday minutes before he was due to board a flight deporting him to turkey, officials said
the iranian, who was not identified, was taken from heathrow airport to a nearby hospital. a foreign office spokesman said he there was no word on how badly the man was injured
the iranian was being deported to turkey after being turned down for political asylum in britain, largely because he had already applied for asylum in turkey where he had been living
the iranian came to britain while turkish authorities were still considering the application, said the spokesman, adding, ``clearly he was returnable to turkey.''
the spokesman, who in accordance with british practice declined to be identified, said the iranian had been living in turkey for five months and his wife was there
a fire in one of india's largest munitions depots detonated artillery shells thursday, forcing evacuation of two villages and closing an airport
shivraj patal, minister of state for defense production, told parliament that the blaze, which began wednesday in the central indian depot's underground sheds, was largely under control. but he said sporadic explosions of ammunition continued
army officials told the united news of india news agency that the blasts in the two sheds could continue for up to 10 days. at least 10,000 rounds reportedly were stored in the burning areas, mainly for 105-mm artillery guns
patal said the two villages were evacuated as a precaution after the blasts in madhya pradesh state 155 miles east of bhopal, the state capital. jabalpur's airport 28 miles away was also closed
two depot workers suffered minor injuries in fighting the blaze, patal said. there was no word on its cause. i would hope.</note>
the senate foreign relations committee today rejected a move by sen. jesse helms to require new intelligence studies of what helms says are soviet missiles unaccounted for by the u.s.-soviet treaty on medium-range atomic weapons
the committee voted 15-2 against helms' amendment to the treaty which would have required president reagan to certify the accuracy of the soviet claims that there are 650 ss-20 missiles. the declared weapons will have to be destroyed after the treaty takes effect
helms, r-n.c., argued that up to 300 more ss-20s are ``hidden,'' and he cited defense intelligence agency reports which he said support his claim
but sen. daniel evans, r-wash., said, ``i don't believe president reagan would have signed this treaty'' if he believed the soviets had successfully hidden a large force of ss-20 missiles
the vote was the latest decision in which the panel decided by large bipartisan majorities to reject attempts by helms and sen. larry pressler, r-s.d., another conservative critic, to change the treaty
sen. claiborne pell, d-r.i., chairman of the committee, said the panel was headed toward overwhelming approval of the pact
i would hope _ and i think _ that we will continue to show strong bipartisan support,'' said pell after the panel voted by lopsided margins wednesday to reject amendments by helms and pressler
helms had originally proposed 36 amendments and pressler offered three more, despite appeals from the reagan administration for the senate to approve the treaty without changes
after it became apparent he had few votes on his side, helms said he planned to drop most of his amendments
pell announced that the committee will finish voting on all amendments by tuesday afternoon next week and will then decide on the treaty itself
when the measure finally reaches the floor, overwhelming approval is expected with no more than 10 to 12 of the 100 senators expected to vote against it. ratification requires a two-thirds vote
the intermediate-range nuclear forces treaty, signed dec. 8 by president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev, requires the elimination within three years of all missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. it includes on-site inspection among its strict verification provisions
helms dropped many of his amendments after he came under fire from fellow republicans, some of whom claimed he was trying to delay a final senate vote until after the next summit meeting between reagan and gorbachev
that meeting has now been set for may 29-june 2 in moscow, the white house announced wednesday
sen. richard lugar, r-ind., said: ``we're just in a delay, stall situation which i find disagreeable. ... if you don't have the votes and just try to overload it with amendments, that isn't fair.''
meantime, pell and other democrats tried to work out some type of compromise between congress and the white house over the chief remaining hurdle, a dispute about the legal power to interpret treaties
senate majority leader robert byrd, d-w.va., said in a floor speech that it will be necessary to add a reservation or an understanding which spells out the senate position
this matter is not going to be resolved, in my judgment, by any exchange of letters, because a future administration can say, `we don't agree with that interpretation at all,''' byrd said
reagan asserts that the executive branch can unilaterally change the u.s. intepretation of a treaty, a view disputed by the senate. the fight arises from a difference in how to interpret the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
as it worked through the treaty, the panel:
_voted down, 12-3, a helms proposal to change the treaty and allow the united states to deploy non-nuclear cruise missiles. the treaty bans all cruise missiles, whether equipped with nuclear or conventional warheads, because there is no effective way to verify which warheads are on the missile
_voted down, 12-2, a helms amendment which would include the soviets' scud b missile as one of the banned weapons. the missile is not now banned because it has a shorter range than 300 miles, but helms claimed scud b missiles sold by the soviets to iraq have been fired at ranges which would fall within the inf ranges
_rejected, 13-2, a helms plan that would prohibit either side from testing missiles in the inf range
_defeated, 15-2, a pressler amendment which would block the treaty from taking effect until reagan certifies that there is parity in europe between nato and warsaw pact forces. the soviets have a large advantage in some categories of non-nuclear weapons and pressler and other treaty critics say the elimination of medium-range atomic missiles will take away a major nato deterrent to a soviet attack
a philosophy student who outraged people with his threat to publicly kill a puppy to demonstrate the brutality of war said today the whole thing was a prank
it was a prankish threat to kill one mythical animal,'' said david read
but he said his threat to burn to death a 10-week-old dog at the university of wisconsin-madison campus monday served its purpose in getting attention. the threat drew protest calls to the dane county humane society and local radio stations
people panicked to save the life of one mythical puppy while thousands (of people) were dying'' elsewhere, read said
the student said he opposed cruelty to animals and never intended to carry out his threat, despite earlier claims he was serious that prompted humane society officials and university police to investigate
police said wednesday they would consider seeking an injunction against read's plan to kill the dog
earlier, read said burning the puppy would be ``an exhibition of what suffering and cruelty is all about,'' he said. ``i think our attitudes about war and human suffering are complacency and numbness. this is one thing that will combat that numbness.''
read, 26, is chairman of the nihilist workers party, a campus organization the university said does not have its official recognition
he said the group, organized two years ago, has about 12 active members who advocate nihilism, a belief that existing social institutions need destroying to make room for a new order
the group announced the puppy-burning plan tuesday. radio stations, humane societies and police said wednesday they were flooded with telephone calls
read said he anticipated the reaction. ``i'm quite pleased,'' he said. ``i'm the most reviled character in town.''
he said he had nicaragua in mind when he conceived of the idea of burning the dog to demonstrate suffering. he said people living in the united states lead sheltered, comfortable lives and avoid thinking about the horrors occurring in other nations
i want them to get down and wallow in the filth, which is truth,'' he said
shock is the best method of making people aware of ugliness, he said, calling peaceful protest a waste of time
his organization has distributed obscene posters on the campus, including one portraying adolph hitler pointing a gun and reading: ``i love you.''
former federal reserve board chairman paul volcker cautioned presidential candidates on thursday to avoid ``washington bashing'' in their campaigning,
volcker spoke to a house civil service subcommittee as chairman of the national commission on the public service. his 37-member panel is working on recommendations for making civil service more attractive to talented individuals
while the presidential candidates don't seem to be ``running against washington'' this year, volcker hinted he's ready with a strong lecture for anyone who tries such an approach
we're never very far from the telephone,'' volcker said. ``we will try to keep after those candidates. ... we will urge them to stay on the high road.''
he suggested attacks by candidates on washington institutions have hurt the image of public service. volcker called it ``the washington bashing syndrome.''
too many of the best at the upper ranks have been leaving government, with not enough of quality being recruited at the entry level,'' said volcker, who retired from government service last summer
volcker, who worked for the governmment most of his life, including eight years as head of the nation's central bank, recently became a professor at princeton university and chairman of a small new york investment firm
rep. patricia shroeder, d-colo., chairwoman of the subcommittee, told volcker: ``hopefully, we can head off a race in which everyone sees how bad a thing they can say about public service.''
the last two presidents have gratuitously slandered the bureaucracy,'' said ms. schroeder, who was mentioned as a possible 1988 presidential contender herself before she withdrew from consideration
norman ornstein, a political analyst with the american enterprise institute who serves with volcker on the commission, told the subcommittee that ``we've been seeing a change'' toward the positive in public attitudes toward government service
part of this is the ironic success president reagan has had in getting people to feel better about the government. it's ironic because i don't think he meant it that way. he had two campaigns against washington.''
no candidates this time have picked up on the theme of bashing government and bashing bureaucrats,'' ornstein added. ``there is a good climate to create a different set of attitudes.''
members of the commission also include former president gerald ford and former vice president walter mondale
a landslide from a trash heap crashed down onto a rail line in the western ukraine, burying the tracks under a giant layer of dirt that in spots was as said a special commmision is investigating the cause of the landslide. loans; picks up 2nd graf pvs, bgng: the gore...</note>
sen. albert gore jr. said today he was willing to release information on more than $1 million in loans taken out by his presidential campaign, but members of his staff who heard the senator's remarks said no decision had been made on the matter
gore's pledge to release the material came in the wake of a report in a nashville, tenn., newspaper that his campaign had put up the proceeds of future fund-raisers and federal matching funds as collateral for almost $1.5 million borrowed from banks about two weeks ago
i have no problem with telling you the amount of the loans and which banks they came from, be glad to,'' gore said at a news conference
gore said details of the loans would be contained in reports to be filed in the next two or three weeks with the federal election commission ``so if you can wait two or three weeks all of that will be available, but as for now i have no problem with giving you the amount of the loans, the banks et cetera.''
however, gore aide mark armour said as the candidate was leaving the news conference that no decision had been made on releasing the information
the gore campaign previously has acknowledged only that it had established a $1 million line of credit to be used as necessary for television advertising on super tuesday
gore borrowed $750,000 from sovran bank-d.c. national, a washington-based bank which handles his campaign accounts, the tennessean reported. the remainder of the loans came from a collection of small banks in tennessee, the democrat's home state, the newspaper said
each of the banks has strong democratic party and gore ties, the paper said. officials at each of the banks refused to comment on whether gore had received a loan
gore's staff has refused to give any details of campaign loans
gore pledged future federal matching funds against the sovran loan, a standard presidential campaign procedure, the tennessean reported, quoting sources familiar with the transaction
at the tennessee banks, the candidate pledged the proceeds of future fund-raising events, and in at least some cases, guaranteed 10 percent of the note on his personal signature, the report said
the gore campaign has made complete disclosure of our finances every four weeks as required by the federal election commission,'' campaign manager fred martin said wednesday
for me to disclose the details of our finances before the fec reporting date would be to give key strategic information to the other candidates a full month before they are entitled to have it and that would be a disservice to my campaign,'' he said
the next fec reporting date is april 20. the loans were taken out after feb. 29 so they did not have to be disclosed march 20
gore campaign officials talked with a number of tennessee banks about participating in the loans, which were used to finance a media blitz before the march 8 primaries and caucuses in 20 states, the paper says. gore won five of those contests
federal election commission laws and regulations require that any loans be transacted ``in the ordinary course of business,'' have a written instrument, have a due date or amortization schedule, and be subject to ``the usual and customary rate of interest'' charged by the bank
the due date for the gore loans is july 15, three days before the democratic national convention begins in atlanta
the latest gore fec disclosure, made public sunday, covers the period from feb. 1 to feb. 29
it shows that, to date, gore has spent $6 million on his presidential bid, and had $342,964 in cash on hand as of feb. 29
campaign sources have said gore's bid raised almost $1 million in the first 15 days of march, the paper reported
about 350 government workers demonstrated thursday in a week-old strike that has virtually halted ferry service across the english channel
a delegation of protesters met with pierre-olivier drege, chief of staff for the secretary of state for maritime affairs, where the protest was held
government officials refused to comment afterward, saying the conflict must be settled by the sailors' employer, the state-run railroad
railroad officials have said they will not negotiate with the strikers until they end their occupation of the ferry nord-pas de calais
the strikers are protesting what they say is a threatened privatization of their company and loss of purchasing power. on the other side of the channel, about 2,200 employees of p and o european ferries have been striking for seven weeks
thursday's demonstrators arrived in buses from the french port cities of boulogne, calais, dieppe and dunkirk. they represented about a third of the 990 officers and sailors working on ferries for the railroads' maritime arm
traffic remained backed up at channel ports on the french side thursday, where only one ferry _ with a british crew _ was in operation between calais and the british port of dover. says</head>
time after time, the big jackrabbit avoids attacks by the five harris hawks that dive and feint with the precision of a military unit. but finally, the rabbit is exhausted and a powerful talon slashes quickly. the hunt ends and winged predators feed together
in a report to be published friday in science magazine, biologist james c. bednarz said he repeatedly witnessed such coordinated hunting by harris hawks. it is, he said, the first documented proof that hawks are able to organize and cooperate with almost human skill in such a complex series of manuevers
people have suggested it in the past, but this is the first documentation of it,'' said bednarz, who is director of higher education research at the hawk mountain sanctuary in kempton, pa., and an associate professor at the university of new mexico
we expected to see two hawks hunting together. i was amazed to see units of four, five and six hawks. ... we got to see it repeatedly,'' bednarz said in a telephone interview
cooperative hunting, in which predators work together to kill prey larger than they could bring down individually, is well known among lions, wolves, hyenas, wild dogs, killer whales _ and humans. but bednarz said his study shows that hawks also are able to hunt together for their mutual benefit
in more than 400 hours of observations at the los medanos raptor area near carlsbad, n.m., bednarz said he watched groups of five to six hawks use two basic coordinated attacks to bring down rabbits
bednarz said the most common tactic, which he called the surprise pounce, required the hawks to attack a rabbit from several different directions at once, forcing it to stay away from cover
they will work the rabbit in such a way that it becomes mentally and physically exhausted,'' bednarz said. ``they keep it moving and keep it making decisions until it makes the wrong decision.''
bednarz said if the rabbit leaves its back unprotected, a hawk swoops in and delivers a lethal blow to the back of the neck. that's the only way, said bednarz, that a harris hawk, which weighs about 2 pounds, can kill a jackrabbit, which can weigh as much as 7 pounds
another tactic bednarz observed is what he calls the ``flush and ambush.''
a team of hawks, e said, will chase a rabbit until it finally takes cover. two or three hawks will perch nearby and a pair of the birds will land near the rabbit and try to flush it from the cover. when the bunny finally flees, the perched hawks drop swiftly for the kill
even dinner time is coordinated for the harris hawks, bednarz said
when the hawks are feeding, two of the group will remain at a nearby high place, on the lookout for eagles or ospreys or other species who might try to steal the kill. when an intruder is spotted, the sentinel will sound an alarm and the harris hawks rise and attack together, usually chasing away the invader
bednarz said most of the hawk groups that hunt together are extended families that may include a mated pair, yearlings and older offspring. the group usually is no larger than six
the female is the larger of the harris hawks and usually dominates the group, bednarz said. but on the hunt, the female is less likely to attack the prey and more likely to play ``a distractor role.''
she distracts the prey and keeps it in play for the other hawks, forcing it back into the area of vulnerability,'' the researcher said
he said birds seem to communicate with body movement. as the hunt begins, he birds will perch hundreds of yards apart. when one of the hawks sights a possible meal, its movement quickly attracts the other birds and the hunt is on, bednarz said
harris hawks live in the deserts of texas, arizona and new mexico. they feed on rodents and lizards during part of the year, but apparently hunt together to bring down jackrabbits and desert cottontail rabbits in the winter months
the federal judge in the iran-contra case indicated thursday that trial of a florida lawsuit that accuses former government officials of collaborating with colombian drug dealers may be postponed
the civil lawsuit is set for trial june 26. the 29 defendants in the case include richard v. secord and albert hakim, two businessmen who have been charged with conpiracy and theft in the iran-contra case
secord and hakim, along with oliver l. north and john m. poindexter, were arraigned before judge gerhard gesell thursday in u.s. district court
during the proceedings, secord's lawyer, thomas green, told gesell about a potential conflict in scheduling between the iran-contra case and the case in miami's federal court
it will not go forward,'' gesell said. ``a criminal case takes precedence. this case has got to take priority.''
gesell said: ``i've cancelled every case i have and i've cancelled my vacation.''
secord and hakim are accused of helping north and poindexter, two former white house aides, secretly sell weapons to iran and divert the profits to the nicaraguan contra rebels
the florida lawsuit was filed by martha honey and tony avirgan, two freelance reporters based in costa rica. they are represented by the christic institute, a liberal policy group
the lawsuit accuses the defendants of drug-trafficking, gun-running and plotting assassinations. the defendants have denied the charges
billions of locusts are moving across north africa in the worst plague since 1954, blotting out the sun and settling on the land like a black, ravenous carpet to strip it clean of vegetation
algeria, morocco and tunisia have put aside political differences to fight the locusts, with help from the united states, western europe and the soviet union, but a u.n. official said thursday it may not be possible to save the food supply
as many as 250,000 of the insects settle on each acre whent the horde alights. they devour 100,000 tons of crops and other vegetation at each stop, according to the food and agriculture organization, a u.n. agency based in rome
wind currents pushed the insects into northeastern africa from their breeding grounds, the fao said. they fly in waves of up to 50 million per square kilometer over 400 square kilometers, which means as many as 20 billion covering an area of 160 square miles
we are facing a very dangerous situation, which may affect north africa's food production for years to come,'' said lukas brader, director of fao's emergency center for locust operations. ``we are not optimistic that the situation can be effectively controlled.''
he said the current infestation is worse than the 1950s plague, which lasted more than 10 years. breeding has been aided by abundant rains and heat in the area, brader said
edouard saouma, director-general of the fao, said in a statement: ``we are in a state of general alert. swift and decisive action is needed to avoid a major regional food crisis later this year.''
brader said $30 million had been donated by the united states, western europe, the soviet union and others to finance the spraying of pesticide on infested areas. he said at least $150 million will be needed to fight the plague, which he said may peak in late summmer
algeria has sprayed more than 494,000 acres of land and morocco has been treating about 62,000 acres a day. no figures were available for tunisia
published reports in algiers say more than 40 aircraft have been provided by libya, the soviet union, france and spain to spray crop and pasture land threatened by locusts
spraying has been hampered by inadequate and outdated pesticide and equipment, the presence of nomads in some infested regions and the difficulty of detecting locusts in areas of sand, rock and scrubland, officials said
no estimate was available of the total damage to crops
specialists say the locusts originated near the red sea, invading sudan and chad and then swarming through the sahel countries below the sahara desert before moving north ``in a tidal wave.'' libya and mauritania also are threatened
to coordinate logistics the algerian agriculture minister, noureddine keddara, visited tunisia on wednesday and driss basri, morocco's interior and information minister, was in algiers
until about two weeks ago, a long-standing territorial dispute over the western sahara had stymied the exchange of information between morocco and algeria about the common danger
the nation's poorest families, with incomes averaging less than $8,600 a year, pay five times as much of their earnings for state sales and excise taxes as those who make more than $600,000, a research and advocacy group reported thursday
the less you make, the worse you do,'' robert s. mcintyre, director of citizens for tax justice, said in releasing a comprehensive study of taxes in the 50 states. the unfairness is especially bad in states that impose heavy taxes on food, utilities, tobacco and fuels, he said
it is not just the poor who spend a disproportionate share on sales and excise taxes, such as those applying to alcohol, gasoline and tobacco, the study found. a four-member family earning $31,000 a year spends three times as much of its income on these taxes, compared with the richest americans
sales and excise taxes generally are at a flat rate, meaning that in a state with a 5 percent tax that applies to food, for example, the rich and poor would pay the same $1 tax on a $20 bag of groceries
citizens for tax justice, which is financed by labor unions and liberal social organizations, opposes such ``consumption taxes'' because they are not based on ability to pay. there is some support in congress for a national sales tax to replace at least part of the income tax
mcintyre, whose organization was a major influence in the thorough revision of the federal income tax enacted in 1986, said some ``tax reformers'' spend too much time in pursuit of the perfect income tax while ignoring the onerous burden that sales taxes create for the poor
that's a mistake, because the worst state income tax in the nation is still a far sight fairer than any state sales tax,'' he said
in 23 states, the disparity between shares of income taken by sales and excise taxes is worse than the national average, the report said
the poor in south dakota and mississippi pay about seven times as much of their earnings in sales and excise taxes as do the rich; in tennessee, alabama and louisiana, almost six times as much
the study found:
_the poorest 20 percent of four-member families, averaging income of $8,581, paid 5.4 percent of their earnings in sales and excise taxes last year
_the second one-fifth, averaging $20,535, paid 3.9 percent
_the third, averaging $31,497, paid 3.3 percent
_the fourth, averaging $44,910, paid 2.9 percent
_the highest-earning one-fifth, averaging $66,912, paid 2.5 percent
_the top-earning 5 percent, averaging $187,316, paid 1.6 percent
_four-member families averaging $612,122 a year _ the richest 0.7 percent of americans _ paid 1.1 percent of their incomes for sales and excise taxes
until states begin relying more on income taxes, mcintyre said, sales taxes can be made less onerous by extending rebates to the poor. the taxes also could be applied disproportionately to services that are generally used by the well-to-do, such as club memberships and home-improvement services, he suggested
only six states have sales-tax credits for the poor, and only in new mexico does the credit offset more than half of the burden for low-income people. the other five are kansas, vermont, idaho, hawaii and north carolina
sixteen states, including the 10 with the most onerous sales taxes on the poor, all tax food, the study found. they are alabama, mississippi, georgia, north carolina, south carolina, arkansas, tennessee, south dakota, virginia and hawaii
the poor spend 6.2 percent of income on electrical bills, more than double the rate of the middle-income family. but that middle-income family pays three times as big a share for electricity as do the rich, the study found
the portion of the $600,000-a-year family's income spent for tax on take-home beer is only 15 percent of the $8,600 family's share
on cigarettes, the upper-income family's share is 1 percent of the low-income family's; on gasoline, 4 percent; on fresh flowers, 98 percent; on legal fees, 100 percent; jewelry, 259 percent; wine for home consumption, 324 percent, and out-of-town lodging, 613 percent. burner</head>
a panel of mideast experts on thursday urged the next u.s. administration to place mideast peace talks high on its foreign policy agenda and to include negotiators approved by the palestine liberation organization
a prolonged impasse in the peace process could endanger american national interests,'' the panel of 19 academicians and former state department officials said in a report issued by the brookings institution, which sponsored the study
we would like to see a steady, high-level commitment of american resources to the arab-israeli peace process,'' the report said
samuel lewis, who served as u.s. ambassador to israel from 1978 to 1985, said the panel ``has a very strong sense that it's going to take a protracted investment by senior levels to achieve even partial success.''
speaking at a news conference, lewis said the mideast peace plan offered in 1982 by president reagan lacked sufficient preparation, while the one currently being proposed by secretary of state george p. shultz may be the victim of bad timing
any future u.s. plan must be presented at a time when both arabs and israelis are ready for peace talks, he said
the palestinians may be too ``eupohoric'' over their success in the 3{-month uprising against the israeli occupation of the west bank and gaza strip to be ready for the compromises each side must make in negotiations, lewis said
william quandt, a senior research fellow at brookings and the project's coordinator, said the mideast peace issue has not been high on the u.s.-soviet agenda so far. it should be explored in that framework further to see if it can yield some solutions, he added
the report's authors agreed that israeli-arab peace talks should be conducted within an international framework, although such a forum would not be empowered to impose solutions. the shultz plan contains a similar proviso
palestinians should be represented in any negotiations with israel by spokesmen of their own choosing, whether in a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation or in some other configuration,'' the report said
the shultz plan envisions palestinian representation as part of a jordanian delegation in peace talks. ``the tone, though, seems to be that jordan can choose the palestinians,'' quandt said
palestinians are unlikely to come forward to negotiate with israel without having the implicit endorsement of the palestine liberation organization,'' the report said. israel and the united states refuse to negotiate with the plo directly
quandt said panel members differed on whether the plo should be included in negotiations, and also could not agree on whether palestinians should be given an independent state. some argued that inclusion of the plo and the establishment of a palestinian state would be ``irritants'' that israel would reject, he said
the experts believe substantial preparation is needed to get the parties ``to be willing to make hard choices'' before bringing them to the negotiating table, quandt said
shultz and other officials have conducted preparatory talks with israeli and arab leaders since january, but the united states is pressing for negotiations to begin by may 1
dozens of honest citizens showed up at police stations across the city thursday to return thousands of dollars in cash that fell out of an armored truck, police said
we have a lot of very honest people here,'' said inspector jim shaw
on wednesday night, however, money-grabbing chaos erupted on toronto's gardiner expressway after the rear door of the armored truck flew open and spewed a blizzard of bills that blew onto windshields and covered the highway
drivers stopped their cars in the middle of the road in the rush for cash, and traffic was tied up for miles
a guard in the loomis armored car service truck eventually had to pull his gun to halt the free-for-all
two bags that each contained $75,000 _ worth about $60,000 u.s. _ were scooped up by drivers who threw the booty into their cars and sped away and have not been returned, shaw said
a third bag holding the same amount broke open, spreading the cash in the air
shaw said auditors were counting up how much was returned. under canadian law, the cash belongs to loomis and not whoever finds it
one cab driver was charged with theft for grabbing some of the money
jurors couldn't decide on the best english-language novel this year, so the $50,000 prize in the ritz paris hemingway literary contest will go to charity, it was announced thursday
the three nominees for this year's annual prize were the south african writer nadine gordimer for ``a sport of nature,'' american novelist toni morrison for ``beloved,'' and ``in the skin of a lion,'' by canadian writer michael ondaatje
to choose the best novel of the year is always a difficult task,'' said pierre salinger, the abc news journalist who served as jury president. ``this year, three excellent authors of great reputation were nominated. but none of the works received a majority of the votes from the 10 jurors.''
the contest's rules thus call for the money to go to charity. half was donated to the georges pompidou foundation, which helps the elderly. the other half went to the franco-american volunteer association, which helps handicapped children get involved in sports
the first ritz paris hemingway award was given in 1985 to peruvian writer mario vargas llosa. the other winners were marguerite duras of france and peter taylor of the united states
detroit mayor coleman young, long at political odds with jesse jackson, is striking a more conciliatory tone toward the democratic presidential candidate this year
i'd be a fool not to recognize the massive contribution jesse has made to the electoral process, and putting some color _ finally _ in the rainbow,'' young said. ``obviously ... that's not enough to win, but it's an important beginning.''
young still argues that jackson's candidacy represents wasted votes, political polarization and help for the republicans. but he also credits jackson for reaching some whites with his more mainstream democratic candidacy this year, and expressing surprise at his degree of support from blacks
young is supporting jackson's chief rival michael dukakis in michigan's statewide caucuses saturday. he says his is not so much an endorsement as a statement of whom he supports _ a distinction young says means the political organization that has served him for 15 years as mayor of detroit is free to do as it wishes
jesse has a tremendous emotional appeal to the black community in this city,'' young said in an interview wednesday in his office with several out-of-town reporters. ``i think that the chief objective ... is to win the white house.''
dukakis is airing radio ads featuring young's support, targeted at black audiences in detroit. he is bidding to win delegates in the city's two largely black congressional districts, the 1st and 13th, which requires winning at least 15 percent of the vote in those areas
young maintained that he has ``truly'' released his organization to go as it pleases and says he's not asked key supporters to report back on whether they are siding with dukakis, jackson or another candidate
some politicians aren't so sure, however. state house speaker gary owen of ypsilanti, backing albert gore jr., said he understood young was ``coming down hard'' on his supporters to produce for dukakis, particularly in those key congressional districts
in announcing his support for dukakis a week and a half ago, young said, ``anybody who respects my opinion will do likewise.'' and young's top political aide, larry l. simmons sr., said last week that young would ask his staff members to inform him of their actions in the presidential campaign
young, who has seen his city's optimism decline with the fall in federal urban aid under the reagan administration, said a democratic victory in november is his paramount concern and his reason for supporting the massachusetts governor
dukakis, he said, has the best chance to win. jackson, he said, ``can't win.''
young finds fault with jackson's lack of government experience, but said no black candidate could be elected this year or in the immediate future because of white resistance
i think it's rooted in race _ i don't have to look anywhere else,'' young said
even if he should win michigan's caucuses, young said, jackson would achieve at best a plurality of the democratic vote, not a majority
the great majority of the black votes will follow jesse off to one side, whereas the great majority of the white vote will be split among the other candidates,'' young said. ``that is the essense of polarization
i think the overall thrust of jackson's campaign might very well be to help the republicans,'' he said
young endorsed walter mondale in 1984 over jackson, and he has remained apart from jackson this year even as some other black leaders who were cool toward jackson four years ago have been won over. while there may be political risks for himself, young said he thinks voters' attitudes toward him won't be affected
i'm trying to preserve the unity _ i do not want to be responsible for creating any disunity in the black community,'' young said
secretary of state george p. shultz today called the nicaraguan cease-fire agreement ``an important step forward'' and said there is ``no excuse'' for any additional soviet bloc weapons deliveries to the sandinista government
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater reacted with cautious optimism to the agreement while house speaker jim wright hailed it as ``a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn country.''
shultz urged congress to immediately approve additional humanitarian aid to the contra rebels while they negotiate terms for a definitive cease-fire with the sandinista government
he said the agreement would not have been possible without years of sacrifice by the rebels
their strength and perseverance have created this opportunity for peace and freedom,'' shultz said. ``we consider this agreement to be an important step forward.''
under questioning, shultz said he feels the agreement may be a ploy on the part of the sandinistas to disarm the contras. he said that if the sandinistas don't carry out their promises under the agreement, the united states would have to reevaluate its policies
both the white house and wright promised to seek quick action on a humanitarian aid package for the contra rebels
we're glad that it occurred,'' the fitzwater said, when asked whether the administration was embracing the plan
there is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and i'm trying to balance those two off,'' fitzwater said
we're beginning the process. we need to watch it. we've seen processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. ``this seems like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be hopeful. but i do not want to play down the skepticism side of it either because we are skeptical.''
wright said he would meet monday with house republicans and representatives of the white house to begin drafting a bill to send food, clothing, shelter and medicine to the rebels before easter
fitzwater said the white house, too, hopes an aid package can be passed ``on a bipartisan basis'' before the recess
wright said the precise form of the aid package remained to be worked out, but that it would have to conform to the cease-fire agreement announced wednesday night in sapoa, nicaragua, after three days of talks
that agreement calls for ``exclusively humanitarian aid'' to be channeled through a neutral, international relief organization
wright refused to speculate on whether there would be gop demands to include in the package some standby procedure for authorizing new military aid for the rebels should the peace process become derailed
republicans, contending nicaraguan president daniel ortega cannot be trusted to fulfill his promises without such a threat, have insisted on such a provision in previous debate on the issue
i think it would be counterproductive to talk about it,'' wright told reporters. ``we don't want to rekindle the war.''
he said he envisioned quick action on ``some minimal something that both sides (democrats and republicans) can wholeheartedly embrace.''
for heaven's sake, if the nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, then surely republicans and democrats can agree,'' he said
wright began discussing ideas for an aid package on wednesday in conversations with house minority leader robert michel, r-ill., and white house chief of staff howard baker. but he said no deals had been made
the cease-fire talks have made it possible, by entering into an entirely new era, to bury our hatchets in the same trenches where they're burying their machetes in central america,'' wright said
the aid bill likely would be similar to a $30 million package rejected by a narrow margin on march 3, although house majority leader thomas foley, d-wash., said it was unclear whether the dollar amount would be the same
the rebels' last u.s. aid expired on feb. 29
earlier, interviewed on cbs television, wright said nicaragua is wracked by poverty and needs to begin diverting its slender resources to educate, feed, and clothe its people
both sides were war-weary but were ready if they could to find an accommodation to guarantee the integration back into their society of these people who have been estranged from it,'' he said
problems remain, wright said, but ``there is a disposition on both parts to enter into a more peaceful society and a more democratic society in which freedom of the press and of expression will be guaranteed and the rights of those who formerly made war against that government will be fully protected.''
those of us in our congress are anxious to do whatever we can to encourage the fulfilment of the democratization of that country,'' he said
meanwhile, rep. edward feighan, d-ohio, said three officials from the general accounting office were leaving for honduras today to track the disposition of small arms, ammunition, jeeps and other materials that were brought to honduras by u.s. troops sent last week to respond to a sandinista incursion
my concern is that the deployment of american troops and weapons to honduras could in fact be another diversion of arms to the contras,'' said feighan, who requested the gao investigation
six members of a laboratory group who were detained during a search for a missing frozen head have filed false arrest claims with the county totaling $225,000
the six claims, filed individually at various times this month, stem from the december beheading of 83-year-old dora kent so her head could be frozen to preserve it for theoretical revival using as-yet undiscovered medical techniques
the six members of the alcor life extension foundation were detained by police jan. 7 during a search of the premises. they were questioned at the police department then released
all six say they were arrested for investigation of obstruction of justice
filing a claim is a preliminary step toward suing. riverside county has the option of settling the claims, or rejecting them after they are reviewed by claims adjustors
in one claim, five alcor members contend they ``suffered emotional stress arising from the purposeful, wrongful conduct of the coroner's investigators.'' they seek damages totaling $125,000. the sixth person filed a separate claim for $100,000
during two searches at the lab, authorities found mrs. kent's hands and some equipment allegedly stolen from the university of california, los angeles. her head never was found
last month, the coroner's office ruled the woman's death a homicide, finding she had been killed by a lethal dose of barbiturates. alcor officials contend the woman was dead when they began their procedure
the case was sent to the district attorney's office, but prosecutor jay thompson hanks said thursday no decision regarding charges has been made
west german opposition leader hans-jochen vogel today praised president reagan's arms-control advances and said the atmosphere had greatly improved since their last meeting five years ago
vogel, chairman of the social democratic party, told reporters after a 20-minute meeting with reagan at the white house that he and the president had discussed arms control, the economy and human rights
we had a very friendly and constructive conversation with the president,'' he said. ``i ... said, remembering five years back, we are very impressed especially by the inf (intermediate nuclear forces) treaty, by the cooperation which developed with the soviet union.''
vogel said he told reagan he hoped he and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev also would be able to agree soon on reducing long-range nuclear forces
he said the president ``seemed to be satisfied about the work, what has been done in the last two or three days. they worked very hard, they worked very (thoroughly) through the details.''
he was referring to a visit by soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze, who has been meeting with secretary of state george shultz and reagan in washington this week
remembering my visit five years ago, it is a remarkable change. it was a relaxed conversation. there are still some points of different views and different opinions, but there are points which we join and which we agree (on).''
in '83 we were in the middle of the argument about the deployment of pershing ii and there have been some other fields of different opinions. many of them are gone. the president making the inf treaty and preparing start is a president more close to us than some remarks and some positions of '81 or '82 or '83,'' vogel said
the social democrats were part of the widespread opposition to nat0's deployment of the u.s. medium-range pershing ii and cruise missiles in europe to counter soviet ss-20 missiles aimed at western europe. the inf treaty would eliminate both the u.s. and soviet land-based medium-range missiles
vogel said reagan listened but didn't comment when he told him that west german social democrats, like the coalition government, oppose modernization of short-range nuclear weapons in europe. he said he made clear that the social democrats go further than the government in urging negotiations to eliminate the weapons
i think he was not surprised,'' vogel said
west german chancellor helmut kohl, of the ruling christian democrats, advocates a reduction in the number of the missiles but not their elimination
the united states, britain and france favor the modernization of the short-range weapons as part of nato's nuclear deterrent against a soviet bloc attack on western europe
a bill introduced in parliament on thursday would allow britons to demand to be segregated from smokers at work
the measure lacks the support of the conservative government of prime minister margaret thatcher and was given little chance of passage, but it reflected a growing anti-smoking campaign
smoking must now be treated like any other industrial heath hazard,'' said george foulkes of the opposition labor party, who introduced the health and safety at work bill in the house of commons
he said there was ``overwhelming'' public support to ban smoking at work except in designated areas
the bill would not require companies to set up non-smoking areas in offices, but it would forbid them from firing or disciplining any worker who refused to work alongside a smoker
smokers are rarely segregated in british restaurants and other public places, although smoking has been banned in london subways and the number of british rail cars where smoking is permitted has been reduced from 25 percent to 20 percent
the independent newspaper said a private survey of 1,000 companies found that almost half had either a voluntary or formal agreement on no-smoking areas
in a report released wednesday, the independent scientific committee on smoking and health said passive smoking, or non-smokers' exposure to smoke, may cause several hundred lung cancer deaths a year. it said passive smoking increases the risk of lung cancer by 10 to 30 percent
in government reaction to the report, junior health minister edwina currie said, ``the government accepts the thrust of the report, which reflects established policies of voluntary arrangements.''
the state-funded health education authority launched a $457,000 advertising campaign thursday with full-page advertisements in major newspapers urging non-smokers to stand up for their rights
the ads say, ``if you're a non-smoker who works with smokers, you probably suffer in silence. yet everybody has the right to a healthy working environment.''
for 58 hours after jessica mcclure tumbled into an abandoned well, hundreds of rescuers worked together to free her. but now they are divided over tv movie rights and have formed two rival groups
jessica, now almost 2 years old, was trapped 22 feet down an abandoned well after she fell in oct. 14 and rescued after teams bored through rock to reach her. rescuers dug a parallel shaft and then a tunnel into the well near the spot where jessica was stuck
one of the associations formed over a tv movie is committed to producer larry spivey, president of highland communications group inc. the group's 32 members, most of them rescue volunteers, have been asking all participants to join them
the group, called the jessica mcclure rescuers' association, is headed by kragg robinson, chief of robinson rathole inc. of albuquerque, n.m
robinson diverted a rathole rig from a nearby texas department of highways and public transportation project to dig much of the parallel shaft
robinson's mother, yvonne, said today that no plans have yet been announced by the group
i don't think they have accepted a proposal,'' said mrs. robinson
the second group, the mcclure rescue association, is comprised of municipal workers, including police chief richard czech, fire chief james roberts and paramedic robert o'donnell, who plucked the child from the well and brought her to the surface
some rescuers have decided to stay neutral
i personally don't feel that i should join any association until a uniform group is together,'' said bruce peeler. ``and that means all people involved, whether they are with the police department, the fire department or the lady who made hamburgers at three in the morning.''
peeler is president of air master equipment corp., a midland company that donated jackhammers and other pneumatic equipment for the rescue
he and another neutral participant, charles boler, president of boler construction of midland, said they have attended the volunteers' weekly meetings for about six weeks
attempts to bring the two groups together have been frustrating, they said
the municipal workers' group has yet to commit its rights either but interviewed six producers and narrowed its preference down to one, said attorney martin allday of midland
the girl's parents, chip and cissy mcclure, have said they are not interested in exploiting jessica's story for profit but did not want to stand in the way of other plans
the son of a mosaic designer has gone to court to try to prevent the city from altering the art work's portrayal of a smiling black man celebrating his freedom from slavery
edward a. kane jr. filed suit this week seeking a preliminary injunction barring the city from changing the mosaic outside city hall ``because of the love i have for my father's memory,'' he said wednesday
i don't want to see the change made because in my opinion you set a precedent to change paintings, books,'' kane said. ``it offends me. if you don't like the smile on the mona lisa, are you going to change it?''
a hearing was set for friday in madison county circuit court
in his lawsuit, kane said alterations to his late father's ``work of art'' would violate constitutional rights to free speech and artistic expression
the 10- by 40-foot mosaic shows white settlers in covered wagons and a freed slave, with a broken rope hanging from his wrists, celebrating his freedom
complaints about the portrayal began in 1986. opponents contend it was demeaning to blacks because it does not show them making any contribution to the city
in october, city council agreed to remove the man's smile, add other facial features and replace the ropes with a hoe. groups favoring the change said they would pay for alterations
tim early, chairman of the city's human rights commission and a supporter of the change, said work would begin as weather allowed
early also said the mosaic, constructed in the mid-1960s, was not the work of edward kane sr. alone but had been designed by a committee. ``i'm sure his father assisted in terms of artistic direction. but to give him full credit is just wrong,'' early said
a priest who was invited to baptize nicaraguan president daniel ortega's seventh child says the ceremony was delayed when 3,200 u.s. soldiers were airlifted to honduras
they went into a state of alert and the baptism was called off,'' the rev. ray bourgeois said here wednesday
he said he had given up was preparing to leave managua on friday when he got a call from foreign minister miguel d'escoto, a fellow maryknoll priest, who said the ceremony was on
we drove to the president's house. it was comfortable, but no mansion. kids were running around all over the place. his mother lydia was there, his wife, rosario, and the godparents,'' bourgeois said
ortega was watching the cbs evening news via satellite
after some small talk, everyone moved outside to the patio where camila, ortega's first daughter, was baptized
i asked him (ortega) to share one of the readings about the greatest commandment, to love god and your neighbor as yourself,'' bourgeois said
bourgeois, 48, said ortega extended the invitation to managua in december, about a month after they met at an organization of american states meeting in washington
he said ortega wanted to meet him because bourgeois had recently been released from a prison term for trespassing on government property during a protest against the contra rebels
the baptism was no different from the hundreds of others i've done,'' bourgeois said. ``it was a family affair. a religious event, not a political event.'' california, picking up 5th graf pvs, `mack was arrested ....' corrects name to paul steven, sted steven paul, in 2nd graf.</note>
a man arrested in the poisoning death of a california beauty queen on a tip resulting from a tv show waived extradition today, saying he wanted to ``get it done with.''
during a three-minute hearing before 5th circuit judge paul g. grant, paul steven mack, 39, said he wouldn't oppose efforts to return him to sacramento, calif., to face charges in the 1987 slaying
i am fully knowledgeable of the extradition proceedings and i wish to waive it and get it done with,'' a handcuffed mack told grant
deputy salt lake county attorney bud ellett said he expected mack, accompanied by sacramento county sheriff's officers, to be flown out of salt lake city later in the day
mack, who had been working as a restaurant chef for the past eight months under the name sean paul lanier, was arrested tuesday near his home, said police sgt. bill brusik
he was wanted in the slaying of karen grace winslett, 21, of carmichael, calif., who disappeared in february 1987, shortly after winning the title of miss english leather in las vegas, nev
mack was arrested by police acting on a tip from a marion, ohio, woman who watched fox broadcasting co.'s ``america's most wanted'' program sunday night and recognized mack as having once worked at a country club where she worked
the woman also remembered receiving a call from a man in salt lake city who wanted information about a man named lanier, said sharon telles, a spokeswoman for the sacramento county sheriff's office
she ``put two and two together and called authorities,'' telles said
ohio authorities contacted sacramento county officials, who alerted salt lake city police. a check revealed that a sean paul lanier had been involved in an october 1987 traffic accident and had produced an ohio driver's license
sacramento police contend mack lured winslett to his apartment to be photographed for a possible calendar spread, then killed her with an overdose of the painkiller percodan, telles said
winslett's body was found in her car in the parking lot of a north sacramento motel 12 days after she disappeared. detectives said mack was linked to the crime by physical and other evidence that they would not detail
mack also is sought for questioning by ohio authorities in the 1981 slaying of a young woman who had worked as a secretary for him at the marion country club
salt lake city police detective don bell said records showed mack has used six or more aliases and has been married seven or eight times, including a marriage last month to a utah woman
telles said police view him as a con artist who dabbled in ``all kinds of fraud schemes.'' a convicted forger and burglar, mack served two prison terms and was paroled in 1985
sacramento county sheriff's detective bob bell said the ``america's most wanted'' show generated 170 calls, most of them involving ``look-alike'' tips about men who resembled mack
the arrest was the fourth stemming from the ``most wanted'' show, according to fox
hundreds of hospitals will offer free blood cholesterol testing may 4 in the first national screening for the fatty substance that is a leading contributor to heart disease and strokes
the program, organized by the voluntary hospitals of america, was outlined thursday at a news confrence. officials said they were announcing the national program well in advance to give people plenty of time to learn where they can go for testing
about 400 not-for-profit hospitals that are members of the association have agreed to participate, and organizers estimate 400,000 americans will get the test
while most will do the test free, a few will charge $3
a public service television spot promoting the program, called ``countdown usa,'' will begin airing next week
it includes a toll-free telephone number _ 800-634-9541 _ for people to call weekdays from 9 a.m. to 6 p.m. (est) to find out which hospitals in their areas will offer the testing
we want every american adult to know his or her cholesterol level and if it's high, do something about it,'' said dr. dewitt s. goodman, professor of medicine at the columbia university college of physicians and surgeons and a member of the staff at new york city's presbyterian hospital
blood cholesterol levels below 200 milligrams are associated with a low level of coronary heart disease. levels over 240 milligrams double the risk. twenty percent to 25 percent of americans have cholesterol levels in this range, the american heart association says
goodman, who heads the hospital organization's screening effort, said one valuable bit of information researchers hope to gain is insight into which people respond. ``we really don't know who will come to be screened,'' he said
don l. arnwine, chairman of the voluntary hospitals of america, acknowledged that the estimate that 400,000 people will be tested is little more than a guess
if 4 million show up, it may be the third or fourth day before we can get to everyone, but we will try to serve them,'' arnwine said
the screening program was developed in association with the national heart, lung and blood institute to assure uniformity from city to city
former national security aides oliver l. north and john m. poindexter and two businessmen pleaded innocent thursday to charges they ran the iran-contra affair as a vast criminal conspiracy and defrauded the government of $17 million
one by one, the defendants were called before u.s. district judge gerhard gesell at their arraignment, and asked by courtroom clerk barbara montgomery, ``how do you wish to plead?''
not guilty,'' replied poindexter, president reagan's former national security adviser; and north, a top assistant to poindexter
not guilty, your honor,'' responded retired air force maj. gen. richard v. secord and albert hakim, who controlled the money and procured the arms for the once-secret iran-contra operation
all four defendants were released on their personal recognizance and told to report weekly by telephone to a pre-trial agency. although criminal defendants are often asked to surrender their passports, gesell said he would not impose that condition
dressed in conservative business suits, the four men made their first appearance in court since a federal grand jury, convened by independent counsel lawrence e. walsh 14 months ago, handed down a 23-count indictment march 16
north, retiring as a marine lieutenant colonel may 1, and poindexter, a retired navy rear admiral, embraced before the judge entered the crowded courtroom
the defendants are charged with conspiring to defraud the united states ``by deceitfully ... organizing, directing and concealing'' a program of support for the nicaraguan contras rebels at a time such assistance was banned
the indictment also said the defendants ``knowingly did embezzle, steal and convert to their own use'' part of the proceeds generated by the sale of weapons to iran
although no exact figure was specified in the theft count, it was reported elsewhere in the indictment that the arms sales generated proceeds of some $30 million while the government was paid only $12.2 million for the weapons
gesell set no trial date but said he would hold an early hearing to determine whether evidence gathered by walsh is free of taint and therefore admissible
all the defendants except secord testified before congress under a grant of immunity from prosecution, preventing walsh from using any of that testimony
walsh has said fbi agents assigned to his staff made sure that he wasn't exposed to any new stories involving the hearings or later developments. as he obtained his independent evidence, he filed it under seal with the court. walsh has the burden of proving that his evidence was not tainted
the court has an independent obligation to determine ... whether the prosecution up to this stage is or is not tainted ...'' gesell said. ``this ought to get resolved and get resolved quickly.''
gesell ordered written motions on the taint question to be filed by april 7, and set a preliminary proceeding for april 12. a full hearing would likely be held later in april, he said
walsh pointed out he has hired retired federal judge herbert stern to argue such motions, and said he was ready to move ahead
gesell told the lawyers he would not allow a civil suit arising from the iran-contra affair, in which secord and hakim are defendants, to interfere with the criminal case. the civil trial had been set to begin june 27
it will not go forward,'' gesell said. ``a criminal case takes precedence. this case has got to take priority.''
outside the courtroom, a crowd of demonstrators gathered to show support for the defendants. sen. steven symms, r-idaho, called on president reagan to issue ``an immediate pardon'' of north and poindexter
the defendants were met by a mob scene of reporters and supporters as they left the courthouse
as poindexter stood by silently, attorney richard beckler said, ``we are going to vigorously contest this case with all our strength and might.''
north left through a separate door and did not get close to reporters. however, television cameramen and still photographers mobbed his gray limousine as it drove by the building. north waved and smiled from the car
before the arraignments, some 30 supporters of the defendants chanted as poindexter, the last of the four to enter the building, walked through the front door
god bless you, sir. god bless john poindexter,'' shouted one demonstrator
the group chanted, ``fund the contras, not the lawyers'' and waved signs reading ``investigate communists in congress'' and ``$10 million witch hunt.''
we're here to support ollie north. i think he's a man of action and a true american citizen,'' said katie collins of arcadia, calif
peter flaherty, chairman of citizens for reagan, said the demonstrators represented several organizations, including young americans for freedom, the national defense council and the coalition for america. he said they wanted to ``show friendship and support for ollie and solidarity with him.''
industrialist armand hammer says eight soviet and american medical specialists will discuss the latest treatment for cancer during a fund-raising program to be broadcast in both nations, western europe and the middle east
the satellite television conference is an outgrowth of the 1986 summit conference between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail gorbachev and is part of an effort to raise $1 billion a year for cancer research in the united states
hammer, chairman of occidental petroleum corp. and head of the president's cancer panel, recently helped establish the non-profit stop cancer foundation whose goal is to raise $500 million a year for cancer research
i know many people have said they hope to find a cure for cancer,'' hammer said during an interview wednesday
but this time i believe we are truly on the verge of conquering it. we just need more money.''
hammer, 89, said he believes a cure can be found within 10 years, adding, ``i hope to celebrate my 100th birthday ... knowing i have achieved the last remaining mission in my life by ridding the world of this scourge.''
the two-hour teleconference on tuesday will link cancer specialists in washington and moscow. about half of the conference will be composed of film clips of medical researchers and cancer patients plus taped comments by reagan, gorbachev and other political figures
the full conference will be broadcast to more than 1,250 hospitals in the united states for the benefit of doctors, researchers and staff members
it also will be beamed to 43 cities in countries throughout europe and the mideast by the u.s. information agency, and will be broadcast in a shortened, one-hour form on soviet television, which reaches 150 million people
u.s. doctors participating in the conference will be vincent t. devita jr., director of the national cancer instititute; steven a. rosenberg, chief of surgery for the nci; robert gale, director of the ucla bone-marrow transplant unit, who treated victims of the 1986 chernobyl nuclear plant disaster in the soviet union; and richard j. steckel, director of the jonsson comprehensive cancer center at ucla
hammer said wednesday that he and nine wealthy acquaintances agreed to donate $100,000 each to the stop cancer foundation as ``seed money.''
some of the leaders of violent student demonstrations at columbia university will gather at the campus for a 20th anniversary reunion next month, university officials said
among those expected to attend are mark rudd, a former leader of the students for democratic society who later became a member of the radical weather underground, surrendering to police in 1978 for his role in chicago demonstrations in the summer of 1968. he is now a teacher in arizona
fred knubel, the university spokesman, said the april 22-23 reunion was not an official function, but was being organized by the school's episcopal chaplain, the rev. william starr
knubel said wednesday that the university is ``a changed place'' from the days when 700 students were arrested on campus after they took several university officials hostage and seized some campus buildings
richard and andrea egan, who got married at a sit-in at one university building, have confirmed they will attend the reunion, he said
the protest was sparked by university plans to build a gym in nearby morningside park and grew into a general demonstration against the vietnam war and government contracts for scientific research. prison</head> conference of mayors. subs 8th graf, `alexander would ...,' to add surrender date and alexander to be sent to medium-security federal prison.</note>
former mayor lee alexander was sentenced to 10 years in prison today for extorting $1.5 million in kickbacks from businessmen during his years as the city's top elected official
alexander, 60, pleaded guilty jan. 6 to charges of racketeering, conspiracy to obstruct a government investigation and tax evasion in connection with what federal prosecutors called one of the biggest public corruption cases ever uncovered in new york state
at his sentencing, alexander, who once served as president of the u.s. conference of mayors, also was ordered by u.s. district judge thomas j. mcavoy to pay $100,000 in restitution to the city of syracuse in lieu of a $100,000 fine recommended by federal prosecutors
i've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' alexander said before sentence was pronounced
alexander said his demise occurred when an effort to build a political war chest was ``allowed to grow into a cancer.''
before alexander's 10-minute speech to the judge, his attorney, harold boreanaz, made an impassioned plea for leniency
boreanaz rebutted statements made by prosecutors that alexander had not fully cooperated with the government's efforts to identify and turn over his assets
alexander would be eligible for parole after serving a third of his sentence. u.s. attorney frederick scullin said alexander must surrender by april 14 and would serve his sentence at a medium-security federal prison that has yet to be determined
the former mayor faced nearly seven centuries in prison after being named in a 40-count federal grand jury indictment that accused him of 65 separate acts of extortion
alexander earlier surrendered to the government more than $1.4 million in assets the government has linked with the extortion-kickback scheme he admitted running during his four terms as syracuse's chief executive between 1970 and 1986
the former mayor was to have been sentenced on march 10 but questions by the government about whether alexander had withheld any assets caused mcavoy to delay sentencing until today. alexander met with government attorneys for more than 20 hours and submitted to at least two polygraph tests during the past two weeks
alexander was indicted july 16, 1986, by a special grand jury investigating public corruption in syracuse. alexander initially denied the charges, but the the overwhelming and highly detailed evidence, including testimony from alexander's pick-up men and other co-conspirators, caused him to seek a plea bargain
six religious activists seeking greater religious freedom in the soviet union called thursday for a new russian orthodox church leader to replace the ailing patriarch pimen
the activists, led by the rev. gleb yakunin, sent an appeal to the 78-year-old pimen asking that he step down because senility and poor health make him incapable of fulfilling his duties
the group, who met with reporters, said they have noted some encouraging changes in official tolerance of religion and believe it is time for a change at the top
they also sent their appeal to the church synod that meets next week, yakunin said, in the event pimen does not choose to leave. the synod is responsible for making church appointments
yakunin acknowledged that it would be unprecedented for the church hierarchy, which is subordinate to the communist party government, to oust the church leader against his will
on the shoulders of the church leader rests the heavy weight of spiritual and historical responsibilities,'' the appeal reads. ``you, your supreme holiness, are not up to bearing this weight.''
pimen's office recieved the appeal, church chancery director irina a. tsyganova told the associated press
i can't say whether it will be discussed by the synod or not,'' she said. ``i rather doubt it as the synod's business agenda has been determined for a long time.''
she said pimen, who is widely reported to be in poor health, was not available for comment
i doubt he will leave of his own accord,'' yakunin said. ``but we sent the letter with the hope that those around him who assist him in carrying out church duties will be able to influence him.''
religious activist andrei bessmertny said pimen rarely appears in public and his crucial role as liaison between the russian orthodox church and the government is filled by an unknown cast of supporters
he has been seen by foreign visitors to ask his deacons where he should go and what he should do,'' bessmertny said. ``he has to be led around like a very old man.''
yakunin and fellow priest nikolai gainov said they were not appealing for any particular church official to succeed pimen
yakunin, who was imprisoned for six years because of religious activism in the 1970s that authorities considered to be dissident behavior, was restored to the ministry last year after 20 years of exclusion
more than 200 churches have been reopened recently for the observance of the 1,000th anniversary of the coming of christianity to russia. whether that trend will continue after the formal observances in june is not clear, the activists said
yakunin also said church activists have found it easier now to receive religious materials from foreign affiliates, including bibles and magazines that once were deemed anti-soviet
the appeal to pimen also noted the positive trends, although it criticized the dearth of monasteries, seminaries, churches and priests
paradoxically, it is not the church but the government that is taking the initiative in drawing believers into the social mainstream,'' the appeal to pimen said. ``society has survived a spiritual crisis and the russian orthodox church can play a significant role in its recovery.''
while there have been encouraging signs of change, none of the laws instituted in 1929 to break the church's influence with the peasantry has been repealed, yakunin said. those laws prohibit charitable work by churches as well as religious education, arguing that such work violates the principle of separation of church from state
the religious activists said 54,174 churches were open at the time of the 1917 bolshevik revolution, and now there are about 7,000. the number of russian orthodox priests has declined on a similar scale
president p.w. botha issued a stinging attack thursday on anti-apartheid clergymen, saying they praise guerrillas who commit horrendous atrocities
the accusation came in a five-page letter released by botha in response to a letter from the rev. frank chikane, general secretary of the south african council of churches, who defended the clergy's growing role in anti-government protest
the exchange of letters is the latest round of a bitter church-state confrontation that began last month when the government banned all activities by 17 major anti-apartheid organizations. chikane, anglican archbishop desmond tutu and other clegymen vowed to fill the void created by the bannings
on feb. 29, chikane, tutu and 23 other church leaders were arrested while trying to march to parliament with a petition protesting the crackdown
chikane, in a letter to botha a week ago, defended the clergymen's decision to protest against ``ungodly acts of oppression.''
botha, in his response, described himself as a devout christian. he said his government, which denies the black majority a vote in national affairs, strove to broaden democracy and remove discriminatory laws
referring to the outlawed african national congress and south african communist party, botha said to chikane: ``you love and praise the anc-sacp, with its marxist and atheistic ideology, landmines, bombs and necklaces perpetrating the most horrendous atrocities imaginable, and you embrace and participate in their call for violence, hatred, sanctions, insurrection and revolution
in the name of god,'' added botha, ``i call upon you to be messengers of the true christian religion and not of marxism or atheism.''
necklacing'' is a form of execution in which a gasoline-soaked tire is placed around a victim's neck and set alight. in nationwide unrest from 1984 through 1986, many blacks suspected of collaborating with the government were necklaced by black militants
the anc, which wages a bombing and sabotage campaign aimed at undermining white-minority rule, repudiated necklacing last year and the method has been used infrequently in recent months
at an emergency meeting tuesday, anglican bishops from across south africa pledged support for tutu in his confrontation with botha. the bishops said they rejected the president's efforts to depict the dispute as a choice between marxism and the government's programs
sen. joseph r. biden jr., d-del., thin and full of good cheer, left the hospital thursday saying ``i feel good'' despite a setback that has delayed a second operation on an artery in his head
i've asked you all to come today because i've decided to announce that i am re-entering the race for president,'' the delaware senator joked to reporters waiting outside walter reed army hospital where he had spent the last 11 days
biden dropped out of the democratic campaign last sept. 23
he had undergone surgery to correct an aneurysm in an artery that supplies blood to the brain on feb. 12 and was scheduled to have a second artery similarly repaired early in april
but on march 13 he re-entered the hospital for a suspected blood clot in his leg. it turned out the clot had lodged in biden's lungs, where it dissipated and was absorbed by the body
to prevent more such clots, which occur frequently after medical intrusion into the artery, doctors last friday implanted a tiny, umbrella-like filter in a large vein that conveys blood to the right atrium of the heart. the arterial surgery now probably will be the end of may
they don't want me working, but do want me walking,'' biden said. ``the most disturbing part of the intermediate step i've had is the delay of the second operation for a month or so. the second operation should be a relatively easy piece of cake.''
he said he won't be back in the senate until he recovers from that surgery
biden looked thin and said he is now down to a 34 inch waist
i probably don't look very hot, but i feel fine,'' he said
he declined to talk politics, saying that ``if you are out of the loop more than a couple of days in this race, you are really out of the loop.'' and of the race, he said: ``i think it would be much better if i were still in it.''
the senator wore a baseball cap with the letter ``d.'' he had worn the same cap on his first hospital release and said he'd gotten mail asking why he was a detroit tigers fan
this is a university of delaware baseball hat,'' he said. ``i hope this will put an end to the most serious problem i've confronted in the last six weeks.''
and, added the senator, who is nearly bald, ``the reason for the hat is that they kind of took some of my hair off and i didn't have a lot of hair to begin with.''
walt disney world has handled hazardous waste materials in a sloppy and potentially dangerous way, the state department of environmental regulation reports
the der told the company it would be fined $174,399 unless it can show that the violations are not as serious as the state agency contends
it looks as if they (disney supervisors) do not have good control of their hazardous waste,'' said george gionis, enforcement section manager for der's central florida district
a two-day inspection of the 43-square-mile tourist attraction in january found nine violations, seven classified as major. the der wants the company to test for possible groundwater contamination in two of the nine areas inspected
disney spokesman john dreyer said thursday the company had ``always tried to comply with der regulations, and we will make whatever improvements are deemed necessary.''
the inspection was conducted after the der received an anonymous complaint
much of the criticism involved a maintenance yard in the epcot center section, where toxic paints, solvents, pesticides and other chemicals are stored
the der described the maintenance yard as an ``uncontrolled, unsupervised, unmanaged and unposted site.''
state inspectors said they found steel drums stored indiscriminately and filled with waste and unknown chemicals. many drums were unlabeled, rusty, open or lying on their sides, with their contents running off a concrete slab where they could contaminate groundwater
there were no precautions to guard against fires, explosions or spills, the inspectors said
such dangers, plus a possible contamination of groundwater, ``could threaten human health or the environment,'' according to the report
inspectors found only one employee that had received training in handling the materials, and the der asked that disney set up a training course on hazardous-waste management
the park passed similar inspections in 1984 and 1985. no inspections were made in 1986 or 1987. in 1981 and 1983, it was cited for minor violations
disney officials have 10 days to meet with the regulatory agency to set up a plan for correcting violations and negotiate penalties. it could take months or even years to make some of the changes requested, gionis said
fire officials on thursday investigated a blaze at an abandoned house used by crack cocaine addicts, the fifth such fire which officials said may be the work of anti-drug vigilantes
i don't have a gut feeling whether it's the same person,'' said fire lt. john gilbert. ``it could be one person or four different people. i do know that whoever it is is not serving the community.''
as in the other cases, police found little evidence to aid their investigation of the fire which broke out tuesday in a working-class neighborhood, according to fire spokeswoman cristy hickman
investigators believe the blaze may be related to fires that gutted three houses march 17 and another house two weeks ago near coral gables, a suburb of miami, ms. hickman said thursday
one firefighter suffered a heart attack during one of the fires last week and is still hospitalized, she said. six other firefighters and one civilian have also sustained minor injuries
the latest fire was confined to a small area of a vacant two-story house and appeared to involve a flammable liquid. no injuries were reported
although not in the same neighborhoods, the fires have all involved vacant buildings that were hangouts for vagrants and crack users, and all involved a flammable liquid, fire officials said
people seem to know where they are,'' gilbert said of the crack houses. ``police know where they are, too. they try their best but as soon as they close someone down, someone else moves in.''
gilbert is concerned that more people could get hurt, or even killed, and that copycats may prompt more fires, especially since avenging arsonists are gaining prominence around the country
two men who recently set fire to a crack house in their detroit neighborhood were featured on three national news magazines and a national morning television show
i resent all this attention they're getting,'' said lt. jon bozich of the detroit fire department. ``the more you make heroes out of these guys the more problems we're going to have. everybody wants to be a hero.''
representatives of the recreation and small aircraft industries and other insurance users claimed thursday that insurance costs have skyrocketed in the past four years because of problems with the legal system, not because of insurance company conspiracy
the groups stopped short of directly criticizing lawsuits filed tuesday by eight states that accused dozens of insurance companies of conspiring to curtail insurance coverage. instead, the groups told reporters that the suits, filed in federal court in san francisco, served to draw attention from what they believe is the main problem: high damage awards by the courts and frivolous suits
we would love to find a simple solution to this,'' said derrick crandall, president of the american recreation coalition. ``unfortunately, having lived with this crisis for the last four years, we've concluded there are many factors involved
we don't believe this is an issue of insurance companies colluding,'' crandall continued. ``if that were the case, why can't some recreation companies find insurance at any cost?''
edward w. stimpson, president of the general aviation manufacturers association, echoed crandall's contentions
many of our companies are now self-insured or self-insured for the first $50 million or $100 million,'' stimpson said. ``so, our problem is not an insurance problem, but what's going on in our courthouses and legal system.''
he presented figures showing that the number of fatal accidents involving small planes decreasing in the past decade, while the amount of paid claims rose significantly
william kronenberg, president and chief executive officer of environmental compliance services inc., which manages insurance programs for companies involved in storing, cleaning up and disposing hazardous wastes, agreed that the court system is to blame
kronenberg said ``it is clear that many of the insurance companies did not have an adequate understanding of the pollution industry'' when they originally wrote policies and then sharply increased rates or stopped writing insurance when they realized their risks
blair childs, executive director of the american tort reform association, which says it represents more than 400 trade associations, businesses and professional groups, said his group has been pushing for several pieces of legislation at the state level, among them one that would give judges more power to impose sanctions on lawyers who bring frivolous lawsuits
the white house said today that the upcoming summit between president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev will be ``quite productive'' even though the two sides are separated by a wide range of major differences
white house spokesman marlin fitzwater denied that reagan had scheduled his fourth summit with the soviet leader merely as a wrap-up to the president's second term
the may 29-june 2 moscow summit ``will be well prepared; there will be substance to discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' fitzwater told reporters
he added that ``there will be a number of important and substantive and meaningful issues to be resolved and all of those things will occur at the moscow summit. it meets all the criteria that needs to be met.''
if u.s. and soviet negotiators can unravel disagreements over the next nine weeks, reagan and gorbachev will sign a sweeping pact to cut long-range nuclear weapons arsenals
i think this summit will be quite productive, well defined, well prepared,'' the spokesman said without citing any specific areas of agreement
fitzwater was queried about summit prospects amid indications from both secretary of states george shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard shevardnadze on wednesday that little agreement was found on an array of troublesome issues
prior to reagan's first summit sessions with the soviet leader, the white house had repeatedly insisted reagan would not meet with gorbachev unless substantive progress on matters such as arms control could be achieved
fitzwater said the success of the shultz-shevardnadze sessions this week lies in the fact that both sides had ``faced all the tough problems'' and that there is no confusion about where both sides stand
we made enough progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days ahead,'' the spokesman said
fitzwater also announced that reagan had accepted an invitation from the finnish government to travel to helsinki from may 26 to may 29, prior to the summit. afterward, he will stop in london on the way home
the president will deliver an address while in helsinki and might deliver another in london, the spokesman said, but he gave no other details
shultz, in a meeting with reporters wednesday evening, was asked about chances for reaching an arms control agreement in time for it to be signed at the summit
i wouldn't want to lay you odds,'' he responded
the road to the summit is also littered with divisions on central america, the middle east, and above all, afghanistan, where plans by the soviets to end their 8-year intervention have hit a snag
reagan has been talking about going to the soviet union since the autumn of 1985 when he and gorbachev were in geneva for their first meeting. not since president nixon visited moscow in 1974 and president ford went to vladivostok later that year has an american chief of state traveled to the land reagan once called ``an evil empire.''
the summit's proposed highlight would be the signing of a treaty to scrap 30 percent to 50 percent of the superpowers' long-range bombers, missiles and submarines. but major differences remain, despite pronouncements that progress was made during shevardnadze's three days of talks in washington
asked if a treaty would be ready in time, reagan said, ``i have no way of answering that.'' shevardnadze called it ``a possibility.''
the envisioned treaty would set a ceiling of 6,000 warheads on long-range missiles and bombers, but the two sides must still set sub-limits on the various types of weapons and decide how to verify compliance with a pact
the compliance issue is especially thorny because the weapons are among the hardest to detect in the superpower arsenals: sea-launched cruise missiles, ballistic missiles on submarines and cruise missiles launched from bombers
shevardnadze said progress has been made on verification, but ``much more work needs to be done,'' at the continuing round of talks in geneva and at two more shultz-shevardnadze sessions, first in moscow april 21-25 and then in the middle of may at an unspecified site
shultz and shevardnadze portrayed their governments as working with a common purpose to fit pieces of the arms control puzzle in time for the summit. they made no effort to hide their sharp disagreements over regional issues like afghanistan
the soviets rejected shultz's proposal for a freeze in supply of military aid to the afghan government during a withdrawal of the soviet union's 115,000 troops and for three months afterward. the united states would stop aiding the afghan resistance during the same period
shevardnadze adamantly rejected the offer, telling reporters the soviet backing for the afghan government was codified in a treaty and ``we are not going to rescind that treaty.''
the soviet union has pledged to withdraw the troops, which went into afghanistan in december 1979, but lack of agreement on aid cutoffs has complicated the process
shultz said the soviets were willing to withdraw forces by the end of the year, beginning with a 50 percent pullout during the first three months. but unless the soviets stop aiding the marxist government at the same time as it withdraws, afghanistan will remain unstable, he said
the two foreign ministers also apparently hit a dead end in talks about central america
the united states wants the soviet union to stop supplying weapons to nicaragua, but shevardnadze wants the united states to stop doing the same for other central american nations before the soviets will stop helping nicaragua, shultz said
orchestra conductors don't expect to have weekends off, but james conlon faces a saturday that's close to ridiculous
in the afternoon, he will conduct mussorgsky's ``khovanshchina'' at the metropolitan opera and in the evening he'll be next door in avery fisher hall conducting the new york philharmonic in an all-mahler program
he knew about the double workshift about a year ago, conlon said thursday. ``i thought, `i can do that.'''
he'll be free between 5:30 and 8 p.m., conlon said. ``i'll go home, shower, dress again, sit quietly for an hour and a half.'' he says he won't even need a snack between performances
it is actually less exhausting to do this than to rehearse all day,'' said conlon, 38. ``rehearsals are very intense. they take a lot out of you
concerts wind you up and give you energy. i find, after a concert or particularly after an opera, physically you can be extremely stimulated, for several hours to come.''
the agriculture department proposed thursday a national grower-financed program to promote more watermelon eating
officials said the plan was endorsed by the national watermelon association to implement the 1985 watermelon research and promotion act. it would be financed by an annual levy of 2 cents per 100 pounds on watermelon handlers and farmers who grow five acres or more
public comments, in quadruplicate, can be sent by may 23 to: hearing clerk, room 1079-s, usda, 14th and independence, washington, d.c. 20250. meteorites</head>
scientists have used lasers to identify organic chemicals in meteorites, and say the new technique may revolutionize analysis of certain pollutants, oil-bearing rocks and other chemicals
the procedure is much faster than standard chemical tests, requires only a tiny sample and doesn't destroy the material, said a statement by the scripps institution of oceanography
the technique was developed by chemist richard n. zare and colleagues at stanford university
its use to identify organic compounds in six meteorites was outlined in a study, published in friday's issue of the journal science, by zare and his colleagues at stanford and by jeffrey l. bada, a marine chemist at scripps, which is part of the university of california, san diego, located in la jolla
the problem with standard chemical techniques for doing organic analyses of meteorites and other rare materials is that they are laborious, destroy the sample and require one to 10 grams of the material to be tested,'' bada said
a gram is about one-30th of an ounce
our method can reduce the analysis time from a month or more to just a few minutes, and we need only one millionth of a gram to do the test,'' he said. ``in addition, the technique does not require the use of solvents that can contaminate the sample, and is non-destructive to the sample.''
the new method may be used widely to analyze meteorites, cosmic dust, environmental pollutants and oil-bearing sediments, the scripps statement said, adding that the technique ``may revolutionize the way certain chemical compounds are analyzed.''
the study found wide variation in the content and relative amounts of organic substances known as polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons, or pahs, in the meteorites that were tested
scientists believe meteorites are remnants of the young solar system, and analyzing their contents may provide clues as to why life arose on earth but not elsewhere in the solar system
the researchers placed tiny amounts of meteorite samples on a teflon-coated probe, then inserted the probe into a vacuum chamber. each sample was hit with a 10-millionth-of-a-second burst from a carbon dioxide laser, which heated the samples to about 1,000 degrees fahrenheit
the heat released molecules of the samples into the vacuum chamber, where they then were struck by an ultraviolet laser beam. that electrically charged the organic compunds in the meteorites so the chemicals could be separated and identified by matching their masses with masses of known substances. it</head> by iranians, adds identity of ship. picks up 6th graf pvs, `the executives...</note>
a supertanker put out a distress signal in the southern persian gulf today and appeared to be the victim of an iranian attack, but the captain denied it had been hit, maritime salvage executives said
the executives, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the 267,589-ton friendship l reported in a radio contact that its engine room was on fire. the captain did not say what caused the fire
in a later contact, the captain denied his vessel had been the target of an iranian raid. the iranians have launched nine attacks on neutral shipping in the southern gulf since friday
the ship attacks are part of the so-called tanker war, an offshoot of the 7{-year-old iraq-iran conflict. about 500 ships have been attacked by both sides, according to the london-basec lloyd's shipping intelligence unit, which monitors worldwide navigation
salvage tugboats rushed to the friendship l, which gave its location between the southern gulf emirates of ajman and ras al-khaimah, close to the strait of hormuz, said the executives. the strait is the sole entry to the gulf. there was no immediate word on the extent of damage
the executives said the vessel in distress was in almost the same area where a cypriot freighter, the odysseas h, was attacked by two iranian gunboats on wednesday. eight other attacks on freighters and tankers of different nationalities were hit by the iranians in the past week, all in the same vicinity
salvage tugboats were still struggling to contain a blaze in the crew quarters of the odysseas h, 24 hours after the attack. no casualties were reported on board
strong winds were whipping up the flames and impeding the salvage operation, the executives said. reports indicated the vessel was being steered in the direction of omani waters for shelter where the salvage operation would be completed. line.</note>
the du pont co. plans to end production of chlorofluorocarbon compounds, the most potent destroyers of the earth's ozone shield, the company said today
but the company's chairman, in a letter to several senators, did not say when the production would cease
du pont chairman richard e. heckert told sen. robert stafford, r-vt., that the company decided on ``an orderly transition to the total phaseout'' of the compounds following a report last week that they probably were responsible for a 2.3 percent decline in the thickness of the earth's ozone shield from 1969 to 1986
the ozone shield, generally 15 to 25 miles high, blocks harmful ultraviolet rays from the sun that can cause skin cancer
the compounds are used for refrigeration fluids, plastic foam blowing agents and cleaning solvents, and aerosol propellants outside the united states
the united states ended aerosol use in 1978, which caused worldwide production to dip, but production resumed its upward climb in the early 1980s
in 1985, the nations of the world produced 2.28 billion pounds, about 30 percent in the united states
the report, by a panel of scientists assembled by the national aeronautics and space administration, constitutes ``important new information'' justifying du pont's reversal of its previous position that an end to cfc production was not justified, heckert said
the letter was made available by stafford's office. similar letters were given to sens. max baucus, d-mont., and david durenberger, r-minn
it's a very responsible move. du pont must now press their industry colleagues'' for similar action, baucus said in a statement
the three senators challenged du pont on feb. 22 to live up to the company's mid-1970s pledge that it would end production of cfc compounds if a threat to health were demonstrated. heckert wrote back on march 4 repeating the pledge but adding, ``at the moment, scientific evidence does not point to the need for dramatic cfc emission reductions.''
today's letter said du pont was encouraging other producers to ``join us in pursuit of this goal,'' and would ``urge all nations to treat this new scientific information seriously.''  
the united states moved 250 more military police into panama this week, more than doubling the number of security personnal assigned to the strife-torn country since march 14, the pentagon said thursday
pentagon spokesman dan howard said the latest deployments brought to 670 the total of extra security personnel airlifted to panama, ``and that's it.''
at least, that's it for the interim,'' howard said. ``this was part of a general, supplemental deployment of military policemen, and that supplemental deployment has now come to an end. so i don't expect it to go any higher.''
the u.s. southern command, which is headquartered in panama, had about 600 security personnel assigned to it before the united states stepped up its campaign earlier this month to oust strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega. the new deployments thus more than double the number of security personnel in the country
howard, asked why the pentagon thought it needed to airlift additional personnel when there were already 10,000 u.s. servicemen in the country, said the concern was having sufficient ``people who are trained as military policemen. ... they're trained to handle riot control and all sorts of things. and this has to do with the physical security of our military installations, housing areas and the like due to civil unrest and potential for civil unrest in the country.''
capt. nancy laluntas, a pentagon spokeswoman, said thursday the latest group of approximately 250 mps had been drawn from the 503rd military police battalion at fort bragg, n.c
earlier this week, the pentagon announced it had dispatched about 212 soldiers from that unit to panama, at the time bringing the ``security augmentation'' to 420
although no moves have been reported against american servicemen or their dependents, defense officials are said to be concerned that noriega might lash back at the united states by attacking or sabotaging facilities there. second charge, picking up 7th graf, `asked by ....'</note>
the prosecution rested its case today in the second of three impeachment allegations against gov. evan mecham being tried before the arizona senate
after the prosecution called its last witness, presiding officer frank x. gordon jr. denied a defense motion to dismiss the charge that mecham misused $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund by loaning it to his auto dealership
the defense called as its first witness roger hagadorn, a valley national bank vice president who said he had loaned money to members of the mecham family for decades and none had ever defaulted
earlier today, sen. tony west said the allegation that mecham loaned public money to his auto dealership is serious and could have been the subject of a criminal investigation
west spoke as former state attorney general jack lasota testified that he believed the $80,000 loan from the governor's protocol fund was illegal
your testimony, if accurate, is either a nuclear explosion or at least devastating,'' west said
a criminal charge that mecham misused public money would be a class 4 felony carrying a penalty of up to $150,000 and five years in prison, the senator said
jeffrey colville, a developer and mortgage banker, testified today that there were three previous liens totaling $3.7 million on the mecham pontiac property, in addition to the deed of trust for the $80,000 loan
the property was appraised at $3.35 million a year earlier, colville ssid. in the event of a foreclosure, the previous liens would have to be paid off before the $80,000 loan could be repaid, he said
however, defense lawyer jerris leonard questioned whether the appraisal was low as part of a general industry practice
asked by prosecutor paul eckstein if he would have made the $80,000 loan to mecham pontiac based on that information, colville said, ``i would have to answer no.''
the prosecution has contended the auto dealership needed the money badly, and that the $80,000 loan was not simply a business deal intended to benefit the protocol fund as the defense said
lasota, who was attorney general under the republican governor's predecessor, democratic gov. bruce babbitt, testified wednesday that the loan violated several state laws
earlier, an accountant who examined the records of the dealership said it would have been overdrawn at its bank had mecham not borrowed the $80,000 on july 17, also contradicting the governor's previous testimony
unless these funds had been paid from the protocol fund, mecham pontiac would have had an overdraft the following wednesday in excess of $60,000,'' said accountant randall sorensen
mecham's lawyers contend the protocol fund, created with fund-raising proceeds from the governor's inauguration, is private money and the loan was merely a good business deal intended to provide a higher interest rate to the fund
the prosecution, however, says the protocol fund is state money since it is intended for the purchase of ceremonial state gifts and other means of promoting arizona's image
in january, mecham testified before a house impeachment committee that his dealership did not need the money to pay its bills
however, sorensen said his analysis of the dealership's records showed that it paid first interstate bank $81,309 owed for six cars on the day it received the $80,000 from the protocol fund
defense attorney jerris leonard suggested the dealership could have had other assets which could have been converted to cash, but sorsensen said he had found no such assets
lasota testified that he had examined the way the protocol fund was set up and the applicable state laws and concluded it was public money, even though it was not officially turned over to the state treasury
the $80,000 loan violated state laws against loaning state money, failing to keep the fund intact until it was properly disbursed and transferring money when not authorized by law, lasota said
mecham, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades, also has been charged with obstructing the investigation of an alleged threat and concealing a $350,000 campaign loan
the first-term governor also faces an april 21 criminal trial on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan and a may 17 recall election
a two-thirds vote of the 30-member senate is required to convict mecham in the impeachment trial
the winds of change are shifting fast in french fashion
having barely coaxed women into knee-baring minis, several important designers did an about-face to long skirts in winter ready-to-wear collections
the different lengths shown over eight days give a wealth of options to women who choose to bare or hide their legs
influential creators such as yves saint laurent, valentino, christian lacroix are among those whose fashions still are above the knee
but saying he's tired of minis, karl lagerfeld showed some nearly ankle-length skirts in his own collection. his skirts for chanel were both short and long
yohji yamamoto's somber looks were all long. but many others, including rykiel, kenzo and ungaro, offered optional lengths
trousers are back in a very big way, another boon to women who have never given them up for city wear, no matter what paris has decreed lately
claude montana featured nearly all slim pants, and only a few ankle-length skirts, in his sharp collection. the ``clothes sculptor'' outlined his handsome jackets with enormous funnels or big collars turned down to eclipse the shoulder, the waist looking tiny over trumpet-shaped jacket hems
other pants ranged from gray flannel and straight with pleats from the waist, as at scherrer, saint laurent and cerruti. at chanel they appeared full, as ``pant-skirts.'' at ungaro they were slightly draped
besides these developments, there's a big range of silhouettes, although a note of sobriety has crept in. in a competitive market characterized by a shaky and lower dollar, designers are aiming to sell to a more cautious consumer who is looking for wearability rather than gags in their clothes
overpadded shoulders are out. belted or boxy coats were topped with big bertha collars or wraps, which were handsome in dazzling colors at lacroix. ankle or knee-length princess or redingote styles swept down the runways, as did tent-like greatcoats, plus capes and caped shoulders
suits came back in force, silhouettes lean and sophisticated, or full-skirted for ingenues. jacket options were often fine for adventurous businesswomen who like to dress with style, in everything from lively boleros to sharply pointed spencers. saint laurent's stunning classics were fronted with geometric or cubist patchwork effects
christian lacroix topped his high-waisted checked suit with a cropped v-neck bolero. lagerfeld opted for very long jackets for his own and the chanel collection, along with good short jackets at the latter. another easy topper is a wrapped surplice blouse or sweater
shawl collars, shoulder wraps and fur-trimmed lapels were frequent favorite details on suits or coats
the new quiet looks featured plenty of easy lines in jersey. there were belted bicolored tunic outfits at saint laurent, layers of flowing a-line jerseys at issey miyake. even fashion's former ``bad boy'' gaultier went into easily fluid clothes, leaving behind his weird padded corset-looks
ungaro varied his complicated, waist-cinched puff-sleeved looks with a big line of flowered babydoll flyaway dresses in light fabrics, which should please the full-figured woman. he also brought back the chemise, shaped mainly by a low knotted drape in back
daytime fabrics featured bright windowpane plaids, gray or black and white checks, chevrons, tweeds and pinstripes. dressier were the flowered light wool fabrics at lanvin and ungaro. paisleys looked lovely in the new suits, as did tapestries or oriental-rug motifs at lacroix
the fabrics bonanza also included smooth or stretch lycra jersey, cashmere, cable-knits, mohair, broadcloth or serge, lots of suede or lambskin, and curly mongolian lamb for warm-looking coats
daytime colors abounded in browns from beige to chocolate, all shades of gray, plus grayish pastels. autumnal notes of burgundy, plum, grape, siena and ochre contrasted with the luminous colors: flame red, royal blue, emerald, tangerine and lemon
for evenings, there were sexy styles, although simpler clothes were offered along with the fancy
body-hugging little black suits and dresses were dolled up in all sorts of ways: chandelier crystals at saint laurent, billiard balls, silver nails or pearly hearts at patrick kelly; sequins, lace, bows and rhinestones nearly everywhere
the lacroix influence in puffs, bubbles and strapless bustier-topped mini dance dresses is still on the party circuit. flounced taffeta or faille gowns, knee-baring in front with trains in the back are adding gala touches at laroche and saint laurent
besides ubiquitous black, the opulent late-day clothes came out in zingy shades of yellow, amethyst, green and fuschia taffeta and faille. lots of black velvet and guipure or heavy lace starred as well, along with some shimmery flower prints
less elaborate evening choices were some strikingly simple at-home or dinner outfits. they were great at chanel in a drape-fronted ivory crepe number topped by a long cable-knit cardigan and pearls. also elegant were lagerfeld's velvet and satin ``medieval'' gowns with very high waists to emphasize the decollete
congress and the reagan administration clashed thursday over who is at fault for recent cuts in postal services and what future would be best for the embattled mail system
federal budget director james c. miller iii and members of the house post office and civil service committee sought to place blame for the postal cutbacks on one another _ with both sides calling the accounting process ``smoke and mirrors.''
the postal service curtailed some window hours and halted sunday collections and some sorting after the federal budget reconciliation bill required it to reduce spending without increasing revenues
postage rate hikes slated for april 3, boosting a first-class stamp price to a quarter, are unrelated to the dispute
in addition to finding fault with one another for the agency's budget crisis, disagreements flared over proposals by miller and others to ``privatize'' the postal service by making it a private firm and opening mail delivery to business competition
miller said that plan would cut costs, imoprove efficiency and probably result in better service and lower costs for consumers
but moe biller, head of the american postal workers union, told the house subcommittee on postal operations that, in his opinion, all miller wants is to destroy the postal service
privatization is only political jargon for ``profitization,'' biller said, terming the idea ``the tale of an idiot, full of sound and fury, signifying nothing.''
rep. frank horton, r-n.y., said he believes that instead of improving service, turning postal services over to private hands could well destroy the service
the prime bone of contention, however, was delegating blame for the federal budget process last december that ended with the postal service being directed to cut spending as part of overall reductions in the federal budget
the office of management and budget is not seeking to manage the postal service and did not impose the cuts, miller told the congressmen. he said that the decision was made by members of congress themselves
miller said he only agreed that the cuts would reduce the federal deficit, because the postal service is counted in the federal budget. ``i did not advocate it,'' he said
who did?'' asked horton, contending that the ``heavy hand'' of the budget office was felt at the session where decisions were made, because that office refused to approve other proposals that had been made instead of the postal cuts
horton and rep. mickey leland, d-texas, both said they are now supporting a bill to take the postal service out of the federal budget so it would not become involved in this type of problem in the future. the postal service, an independent federal agency, was not counted in the overall federal budget until 1985
i think the postal service should be placed off budget,'' miller, who has long opposed the idea, told a momentarily stunned audience. then, he added: ``by making it part of the private sector.''
you take a very crass and insensitive approach to things,'' leland said, stating that he is concerned that privatization would lead to a loss of federal jobs and to the opportunities for minorities that the post office has long provided
why do you think that would end if it were transferred to the private sector?'' miller asked
leland shot back, ``you want to break it up and sell it off and those people who are buying do not necessarily believe in affirmative action. your administration does not believe in affirmative action.''
women may have a better chance of being cured of breast cancer by surgery if they undergo the operation at the right time in their menstrual cycle, a study of mice suggests
even post-menopausal women, who get the most breast cancers, might be helped if such an effect is found and studied in humans, said researcher william hrushesky of the university of minnesota
if scientists could tailor a woman's treatment to reproduce factors responsible for higher cure rates, ``we could do that in any woman, whether she was pre- or post-menopausal,'' hrushesky said
breast cancer will appear in 135,000 american women this year and kill 42,000. surgery can remove the tumor, but cancer cells that escaped before surgery can cause recurrence elsewhere in the body
hrushesky described the mouse experiment wednesday at a science writers seminar sponsored by the american cancer society. the work focused on the 5{-day mouse estrous cycle, which corresponds to the monthly menstrual cycle in women
tumors that grow faster in response to the hormone estrogen, as many human breast tumors do, were implanted in the mice. later analysis showed the timing of the implant in the estrous cycle made no difference in cure rates
but the timing of surgery to remove the tumors markedly influenced the likelihood that cancer would have spread to the lungs by 28 days after the operation, hrushesky said
sixteen of 60 mice that underwent surgery near the fertility peak of the cycle were found to be free of lung involvement, compared with nine of 73 that had surgery during the infertile phase
that translates to 27 percent versus 12.3 percent. under a different method to determine estrous stage, the percentages came to 31.3 percent and 14.9 percent
in human terms, the higher cure rate corresponds to surgery just before and during ovulation, with the lower rate corresponding to surgery around menstruation, hrushesky said
in the mice, fluctuation in the cure rate mirrored changes in activity levels of ``splenocyte natural killer'' cells, which attack cancer cells that have spread from tumors, he said. but that does not prove the cells play a role in the findings, he said
hrushesky said he had no detailed explanation for the results. the trauma of surgery may affect the balance between cancer and the disease-fighting immune system differently at different times in the estrous cycle, he said
he emphasized the results do not imply that cancer cells are spread from the tumor by surgery
the next step is studying hospital records for evidence of any protective pattern in past surgeries, and following the progress of women after they have breast cancer surgery at known points in the menstrual cycle, he said
within a few years we may know if this is true in human beings,'' he said
it certainly deserves study. i think it will get it,'' said benjamin byrd jr., clinical professor of surgery at vanderbilt university medical school
byrd said the evidence so far does not convince him that the stress of surgery plays a role, but that hormone levels may
this is a whole new look'' at appraising or altering immune sytem response to cancer, said byrd, a past president of the cancer society
hrushesky also said a chemotherapy schedule tailored to the natural day-long rhythms of the body prolonged survival in 50 people with cancer that had spread from the kidney
patients received a continuous drug infusion with the dose peaking every night. that let them tolerate twice as much drug per week than if the dose level were fixed, hrushesky said
the former armed forces radio disc jockey portrayed by robin williams in the hit movie ``good morning, vietnam'' says hollywood distorted his original idea for a screenplay and his life
no, i did not try to meet girls on street corners. no, i did not teach american slang to the vietnamese. no, i was not thrown out of vietnam and to my knowledge, no vietnamese friends of mine were viet cong,'' adrian cronauer told students wednesday at mississippi state university
but he praised williams' performance, which has been nominated for an academy award
cronauer, 49, a law student at the university of pennslyvania, bellowed ``goooood mooooorning, vietnam'' at the beginning of his popular ``dawn buster'' 1965 saigon radio show
his trademark sign-on was adopted by succeeding saigon djs, including ``wheel of fortune'' host pat sajak
families should avoid measuring themselves against their television counterparts, who generally are beautiful people in dazzling situation far removed from reality, actress meredith baxter-birney says
you'll never come out on top,'' said ms. baxter-birney, who plays elyse keaton on nbc's ``family ties.''
the lifestyles portrayed on tv are so ``outside the realm of the average person that inevitably unconscious comparisons are made,'' she told wilson college students wednesday
maybe kids would like their own families better if they weren't comparing them to the ones on tv,'' she said
i guess our obligation is to be alert to the messages being sent _ educate our children and ourselves and not measure ourselves'' against television, said ms. baxter-birney, one of several people speaking at wilson this year as part of a discussion on values in american society
teen-age aids victim ryan white will attend ``ryan white day'' activities this week in omaha, neb., and also will visit council bluffs, iowa
ryan, 16, and his mother, jeanne white, will visit father flannigan's boys town on friday in omaha before speaking at a forum on aids and aids education, the indianapolis star reported thursday
in council bluffs, ryan will visit a children's home
ryan's efforts to attend school even though he carries the aids virus divided the community of kokomo
in spite of national health officials' assurances, school officials and worried parents weren't convinced that other children would be safe sitting next to ryan, who contracted aids through infected treatments for hemophilia
the fight eventually drove ryan and his family from kokomo to cicero
rock star michael jackson, reportedly fascinated with ancient egyptians, made a quiet trip to the museum of natural history to see a touring exhibit on the pharaoh ramses ii
since the reclusive star arrived monday for three concerts this week, he has been staying in his hotel suite
but he ventured out tuesday night just long enough to see ``ramses ii, the great pharaoh and his time,'' which leaves the denver museum of natural history after this month
jackson and a party of five or six others arrived shortly before the museum was to close, museum officials said
nightline'' anchor ted koppel has agreed to a long-term contract that will allow him to have his own production company to produce at least four hour-long, prime-time news shows for abc a year, a newspaper says
koppel will get similar benefits as he has now, with abc agreeing to broadcast ``nightline'' five nights a week. koppel will be host for most, but not all of the broadcasts, the new york times reported thursday
koppel had been working without a contract since last year
in addition to the four news programs for abc, koppel's company also will have the right to produce television programs that could be broadcast outside abc, according to unidentified executives quoted by the times
roone arledge, president of abc news, said wednesday the deal was agreed on but not yet signed
david a. stockman, the former white house budget director, is leaving the investment firm salomon bros. to join its smaller rival blackstone group, it was announced thursday
stockman, 41, a managing director at salomon since leaving the white house in 1985, will handle all merchant banking activities and merger transactions for the blackstone group, the company said
my experience at salomon was absolutely agreeable,'' stockman said. ``there's one thing i couldn't do there, which is have my own shop.''
his departure from salomon comes against a background of turmoil within the venerable investment firm, a partial result of the uncertain outlook for wall street in the aftermath of the stock market crash five months ago
several other high-ranking executives also have quit salomon recently. california</head>
a man arrested after police followed a tip generated by a television show was extradited thursday to california to face charges in the poisoning death of a beauty queen
during a three-minute hearing thursday, paul steven mack, 39, told 5th circuit judge paul g. grant he wouldn't fight efforts to return him to sacramento, where he is charged in a felony homicide warrant in the 1987 slaying of karen grace winslett
sacramento county sheriff's department spokewoman sharon telles said mack was expected in sacramento later thursday
mack, who had been working as a chef for eight months under the name sean paul lanier, was arrested tuesday night near his home
california authorities had been seeking mack in the slaying of winslett, 21, of carmichael, calif., who disappeared in february 1987, shortly after winning the title of miss english leather in las vegas, nev
mack was arrested by utah police acting on a tip from a marion, ohio, woman who had watched the sunday night showing of fox broadcasting co.'s ``america's most wanted'' program and recognized mack as having once worked at a country club where she works
the woman also recalled receiving a call from a man in salt lake city who wanted information about a man named lanier prior to entering into a business deal, telles said
ohio authorities contacted sacramento county, which then alerted salt lake city police. a check revealed that a sean paul lanier had been involved in an october 1987 traffic accident and had produced an ohio driver's license
sacramento police allege mack lured winslett to his apartment to be photographed for a possible calendar spread, then killed her with a ``massive dose'' of the painkiller percodan
winslett's decomposed body was found in her sports car in a parking lot
mack also is sought for questioning by ohio authorities in the 1981 slaying of annette huddle, 19, who had worked as a temporary secretary for mack at the marion country club
salt lake city police said mack has used six or more aliases and has been married seven or eight times. a convicted forger and burglar, mack served two prison terms and was paroled in 1985
a justice department official said thursday there are more grand jury investigations under way into price-fixing, bid-rigging and other criminal antitrust violations than at any time in this century
in a speech, assistant attorney general charles f. rule defended the reagan administration's approach to antitrust enforcement which emphasizes price-fixing prosecutions while making it easier for mergers to occur
criminal antitrust enforcement today is at an all-time high,' rule said. he said that in the first seven years of the reagan administration, the justice department's antitrust division, which he heads, has filed 555 criminal antitrust cases. the division filed 531 criminal antitrust cases from 1890 when the sherman act was passed to 1949
the department has vigorously pursued bid-rigging in the roadbuilding and auction industries and other areas of business
reporters don't believe protecting consumers is news unless you block a merger between two steel companies or indict the head of one of the country's biggest corporations,'' rule said. ``in fact, we file cases every week that have more direct impact on consumers than both of those actions together.''
former mayor lee alexander, a one-time leader among the nation's big-city mayors, was sentenced thursday to 10 years in prison for orchestrating a $1.5 million extortion-kickback scheme
alexander, 60, spent 16 years as mayor of new york's fifth-largest city and often was a spokesman for the nation's mayors. he has served as president of the u.s. conference of mayors and the national conference of democratic mayors
in a jan. 6 plea agreement, he admitted to charges of racketeering, conspiracy to obstruct a government investigation and tax evasion
u.s. district judge thomas j. mcavoy also ordered alexander to pay $100,000 in restitution to syracuse in lieu of a $100,000 fine recommended by federal prosecutors
i've brought great pain to my loved ones and the people of my city and stand here now ready for my punishment,'' alexander said at the close of a 10-minute statement. ``the punishment you are about to impose on me ... pales against the pain and remorse i feel.''
alexander offered an explanation for his demise, saying it occurred when an effort to build a political war chest was ``allowed to grow into a cancer.''
before alexander spoke, his attorney, harold boreanaz, made a 50-minute impassioned plea and denied charges that alexander had not cooperated with prosecutors in identifying his assets
while you brought the city national attention and did many fine things for the city, your criminal actions have placed national attention on it again in another light and for that you must pay,'' mcavoy said
there had been speculation alexander was in line for a high-level job in federal government and that he might some day run for governor. democratic party leaders made him their candidate for the u.s. senate in 1974, but he lost the primary to former u.s. attorney general ramsey clark
alexander was indicted july 16, 1986, by a special grand jury empaneled 18 months earlier. he initially denied the charges but later sought a plea bargain
a 40-count indictment accused alexander of 65 acts of extortion. it charged that alexander extorted money from businessmen, professionals and consultants
alexander has already turned over to prosecutors more than $1.4 million in assets the government has linked with the extortion-kickback scheme he admitted running during four terms as mayor from 1970 to 1986
seven others co-conspirators also were to be sentenced thursday
alexander will be eligible for parole afer serving a third of his sentence. u.s. attorney frederick scullin said alexander must surrender by april 14. the prison has not been determined
pakistan has removed a major obstacle to a settlement of the war in afghanistan by withdrawing its demand for formation of an interim government, a senior u.s. official said thursday
the soviet union, charging pakistan with bad faith, had refused to complete an agreement for withdrawal of an estimated 120,000 troops from the war-torn country
initially, the united states supported the demand of its ally, which is negotiating terms of a settlement with the afghan government through a united nations mediator
but the reagan administration subsequently back-pedaled _ while pressing its own demand that the soviets cease their military aid to the marxist government
the u.s. official said pakistan was now willing to have the red army retreat even while the u.n. mediator, diego cordovez, consulted with warring factions on formation of a transition government
the interim government issue, which has been an obstacle, is now swiftly soluble,'' he said
the official, who played a leading role in talks here this week with soviet officials, briefed reporters under rules that gave him anonymity
pakistan had contended that the safe return of millions of afghan refugees to their homeland would not be possible under the current government in kabul
the u.s. official said the only major remaining issue was a u.s.-soviet dispute on military aid
secretary of state george p. shultz on wednesday night ruled out any agreement to end the war in afghanistan unless the soviet union suspended military aid to the pro-moscow government
he said foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze had rejected the proposal, which would include a suspension in u.s. support for the afghan resistance
the moratorium would be in effect during the soviet pullout and for three additional months. the u.s. official said ``it would allow the dust to settle'' without prejudice to u.s. and soviet claims to back rival factions
they didn't feel they could agree to that,'' shultz said
and yet, shultz said, ``those conditions are needed for us to be able to sign as a guarantor'' of the geneva agreement to end the war
shevardnadze told reporters before flying home that the soviet union had no intention of stopping its aid to the afghan government
the aid is required by a soviet-afghan treaty, ``those are legitimate supplies, and we are not going to rescind that treaty,'' shevardnadze said
shultz said the soviets were willing to withdraw the red army by the end of the year, beginning with a 50 percent pullout during the first three months in which the agreement was in effect
the guarantee of a withdrawal filled ``a great big hole'' in the situation, shultz said
but, he said, soviet military aid to the marxist government must cease for stability to return to the war-torn country and for an estimated 5 million refugees to go home
the proposal remains on the table,'' shultz said. ``if our thought or something close to it is accepted we would be pleased to sign on as a guarantor.''
the u.s. official who briefed reporters on thursday said the pullout could be carried out over 7{ months
smokers reacted with irritation thursday to northwest airline's plans to ban smoking on all domestic routes except those to and from hawaii
i think it stinks,'' said dennis kenyon, 43, as he puffed a cigarette in a designated smoking area of minneapolis-st. paul international airport. ``i'll fly any other airline before i fly northwest.''
a frequent business flier, the st. paul park salesman said the ban is unreasonable. ``it's hard for me to believe that cigarette smoke bothers someone 20 rows away,'' he said
northwest, based in eagan, minn., announced the ban wednesday, becoming the first major american carrier to prohibit smoking on extended flights
airline officials said the ban, which also applies to some foreign flights, was a response to employees' and passengers' requests, and they predicted it would attract more people than it would drive away
a.b. ``sky'' magary, northwest's executive vice president for marketing, said in new york wednesday said a survey found that nine out of 10 passengers prefer to sit in the no-smoking section, and that even 30 percent of the smokers supported a ban on smoking in flight
one non-smoker at the minneapolis airport thursday said it didn't make much difference to him
as long as they have a smoking section, it doesn't matter,'' said larry briggs of ashland, ohio
dan bridges of memphis, tenn., said he travels in the non-smoking secion ``and it's never been a problem.''
some analysts believe northwest, the nation's fifth largest carrier, risks losing customers. other major airlines said they have no immediate plans to follow suit
kenyon's wife, joann, who manages an airport gift shop, said she has heard many smokers grumble about northwest's action
they're not going to fly northwest. they're going to do anything they can not to fly northwest,'' she said
when i go to california, there's no way i'm going to sit for six hours and not smoke,'' said todd parron, a college student from the cincinnati suburb of silverton. ``i'd find another flight and take it.''
however, one non-smoker at the cincinnati airport said northwest's move will make her more likely to choose it over other airlines
those airplane cabins are too small. even with smoking only in the back rows, smoke still bothers me,'' said erin weglicki of memphis, tenn. ``it would make a difference to me in choosing an airline. it's a pretty brave move on their part.''
under new federal regulations going into effect april 23, smoking will be banned on all domestic flights of less than two hours. violators will face civil fines of as much as $1,000
northwest's policy will take effect the same day
some smokers said they can live with northwest's policy
it's probably a good idea,'' janice davis, a boston real estate broker, told the st. paul pioneer press dispatch. ``i can get by without smoking.'' 0190</first>
rep. james howard, d-n.j., was hospitalized in very critical condition today after suffering a heart attack while playing golf, the hospital said
howard, the chairman of the house public works and transportation committee, collapsed while golfing at the manor country club in rockville, md., said a woman who answered the club's telephone
he was taken to montgomery general hospital in olney, md., where spokeswoman linda janzik said howard had had a heart attack and his heart had stopped
but his heart was revived and, four hours after the attack, he was ``breathing on his own and talking,'' janzik said
howard was later transferred to the washington hospital center
a former schoolteacher and principal, howard has been in congress since 1965
howard has suffered two heart attacks during his more than two decades in congress. he was hospitalized for several days in 1984 in an episode doctors attributed to fatigue. he is a heavy cigarette smoker
he has been chairman of the public works committee since 1981. the panel considers multi-billion dollar highway and water projects title.</note>
the senate voted 93-2 today to allow republicans to continue delaying action on a bill requiring the government to warn workers about carcinogens and other job hazards
the vote against shutting off a gop filibuster allows members of both parties to start offering amendments to a weakened version of the measure that was substituted wednesday night in an effort to win more support for it
only democratic sens. dennis deconcini of arizona and claiborne pell of rhode island voted to stop the filibuster
once this vote is disposed of, the bill is open to amendments,'' sen. howard metzenbaum, d-ohio, the bill's chief author, said today. ``there is nothing unseemly about making changes in a bill on the floor of the senate.''
however, sen. orrin hatch, r-utah, the leader of the filibuster, called the new, weaker version a ``fire sale'' to special interests made for ``the perception of a political victory.''
hatch, after refusing wednesday to allow democratic amendments to weaken the bill, indicated he is prepared to continue his filibuster
we intend to talk a little more at length to explain the problems with this bill,'' hatch said today. ``you can't do it in a few hours.''
sen. edward m. kennedy, d-mass., chairman of the senate labor and human resources committee, substituted the weaker version at metzenbaum's request in response to hatch's filibuster
the legislation is aimed at what the national institute of occupational safety and health says are the one in every four americans who have been exposed to carcinogens or other hazardous substances on the job
the ``high risk occupational disease notification and prevention act'' would establish a seven-member panel of scientists to determine the biggest hazards in workplaces and identify what groups of workers are most at risk
the government would then have to notify between 100,000 and 300,000 of those workers individually each year, and their employers would have to provide them with annual medical monitoring tests costing up to $250 each
a similar bill was passed by the house on a 225-186, largely party-line vote last october despite vehement opposition from the reagan administration
hatch, voicing the objections of hundreds of business groups, said the bill could open up employers to billions of dollars in liability damages from suits by their workers and former workers placed in the at-risk groups
metzenbaum could muster only 33 votes wednesday to cut off hatch's filibuster, while 59 senators, including 16 democrats, said they wanted the filibuster to continue
they found out that this bill is going nowhere except to the elephant graveyard of legislation,'' said acting senate republican leader alan simpson of wyoming
simpson called kennedy's substitute a ``sweeten-the-pot theory of legislating that i find a little disturbing.''
the new version exempts both companies with fewer than 50 workers and farms from having to continue paying wages and benefits for up to a year to workers ordered off the job because of the danger that might be raised by continued exposure to hazardous substances
it also puts restrictions on what information from the program could be used by workers and former workers in pursuing liability suits against employers
democrats admitted that kennedy's parliamentary maneuver, although allowed by senate rules, could be used to thwart republicans from offering amendments of their own. but they maintained that was not the intent
i don't think it's fair,'' said house democratic leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va. ``the parliamentary landscape has shifted. we've seen now how senators can be shut out from offering amendments circumstantially with no malice intended.''
soldiers shot two palestinians dead in street battles thursday after a night of israeli raids in which arabs were arrested and taken to schools converted into detention centers
seven arabs were wounded in confrontations in the occupied west bank, including a 12-year-old girl shot in the left leg in tamoun, a village 10 miles west of nablus, hospital officials reported
thursday's deaths brought to 109 the number of palestinians killed since the arab rebellion began dec. 8 in the occupied west bank and gaza strip, according to u.n. figures. one israeli soldier has been killed
monsignor michel sabbah, roman catholic patriarch of jerusalem, canceled the traditional palm sunday procession from the biblical mount of olives to jerusalem's old city because of continuing violence
ariel sharon, the hawkish former general who now is industry and trade minister, said palestinians involved in the rebellion might be expelled from israel and the territories it has occupied since the 1967 middle east war
israeli warplanes raided palestinian guerrilla bases on the outskirts of sidon for the second straight day. it was the third israeli air raid into lebanon in a week and the fifth this year
soldiers have rounded up at least 700 palestinians in the past week in nightly sweeps through villages and refugee camps aimed at removing leaders of the rebellion, and about 3,000 since the rebellion began
among those detained wednesday night and early thursday were several men believed responsible for the latest palestine liberation organization leaflet, said nahum mendel, spokesman for the police ministry. he would not identify them or say how many were arrested
an islamic official in hebron said about 200 imams _ moslem religious leaders _ had been arrested in the west bank city this week. he said, on condition of anonymity, that most were members of a fundamentalist group
many of those arrested were taken to half a dozen arab schools the army converted into temporary detention centers, according to mohammed abdel majid melham, a palestinian detained sunday night in halhoul high school, and other arab reports
melham, a 45-year-old pharmacist, said he was held at the school with 12 other villagers from halhoul, 2 miles north of hebron, after a midnight roundup
six soldiers and three intelligence officers came to my house. they handcuffed and blindfolded me, then they took me to the school,'' he said. ``we were held in a large, open room. it was very cold. there were no blankets or mattresses.''
he said the detainees were transfered the next morning to a center near hebron and he was released wednesday
