the national park service says the white house will be a safer place and have a better-looking sidewalk in front of it when a million-dollar-plus construction project is completed in july
the project, a compromise between security requirements of the secret service and aesthetic standards of the commission of fine arts, has gone through several changes since it was first proposed
the first proposal was a 42-inch-high concrete wall, with the white house's existing ornamental iron fence on top of it, according to charles h. atherton, administative officer of the arts panel
it would have made the white house look even more like a fortress,'' atherton said. the commission must approve design changes affecting federal buildings and momuments in the central are of washington
after the terrorist attack on the marine barracks in lebanon in 1983, which killed 241 american servicemen, low concrete walls called jersey barriers were erected around the white house and many other public buildings in washington
that was always regarded as a temporary measure,'' said park service spokesman jim mcdaniel
after the wall was rejected, there were discussions between the arts commission and the park service, with advice from the secret service, resulting in the present plan
it consists of 274 bollards, or thick cement and aggregate posts, each 38 inches high, placed four feet apart and joined by chains, along 832 feet of pennsylvania avenue sidewalk
we, of course, would have hoped that they would be farther apart,'' atherton said of the bollards. ``they're actually awfully close together.''
the secret service, however, determined that this spacing was the most effective way to stop a vehicle of a certain size, going at a certain speed, from crashing into the white house
we certainly agree that the first order of business would be the protection of the president at any cost, and if the aesthetic element has to be compromised, so be it, sad as that may be,'' said atherton
i think the secret service feels that we now have a system that will do the job physically and at the same time we hope will be more acceptable to look at. it certainly, i think, will be more acceptable than the original scheme.''
mcdaniel said the park service, which is in charge of the white house grounds, dealt separately with the secret service and the commission
you play one against the other,'' he said. ``if you work hard at it, you can usually find a solution.''
the first phase of the project is scheduled for completion in july
mcdaniel said the security work will cost $670,000 and the park service is spending an additional $365,000 to replace the sidewalk with a more decorative granite walk with trees and tree boxes
a second phase is expected to be completed about the end of july, but mcdaniel said the cost has not been determined. girl</head>
the police department in this central florida community is in turmoil over allegations by lower-ranking officers that a captain took a teen-age girl along on a confidential stakeout and kissed her against her will
the alleged incident last month resulted in the demotion of capt. doyle hensley, 42, to lieutenant and has led to a state investigation and several internal investigations
hensley had supervised an investigation last month on similar charges against the officer who relayed the latest allegations
the chief of the 45-member force is suspicious
i haven't been able to prove that it's a setup yet,'' chief tom collins said wednesday. ``sooner or later, i'll find out. some officers may be running scared right now.''
the officers who investigated the captain and had pictures taken of him and the 16-year-old girl deny any setup
hensley declined comment
collins said the problems began when hensley asked the girl, who lives with a roommate and works as a waitress, to join him on a stakeout at the local high school on feb. 26
the girl said this week she was interested in police work but was ``half afraid'' of hensley because of his flirtatious comment that it would be cold and she might have to keep him warm. she said she told officer greg horne about the invitation
horne passed the girl's comment on to sgt. jeff ujcic, who then notified his lieutenant, ralph caldwell
last month, horne was the target of an internal investigation, supervised by hensley, into accusations that he was dating another teen-ager
caldwell and ujcic enlisted former police officer gary granttham to take pictures when hensley picked up the girl at the restaurant. also in the parking lot was a carload of the girl's friends, whom she had asked to follow her. hensley realized he was being followed and gave them the slip, collins said
what disturbed me the most is that this was supposedly a confidential mission'' to catch suspected burglars, caldwell said. ``this special operation was no longer a special operation. everybody and their brother knew about it.''
the chief isn't happy that his nightshift officers started investigating a fellow officer on their own. he is investigating horne's role
meanwhile, horne's family has befriended the teen-ager, and she has complained to the state attorney's office that two officers pressured her to withdraw her complaint about hensley
the chief is angry that the officers got civilians involved _ granttham and the horne family
i don't need their help,'' collins said. ``i can take care of my own shop. i will take them to court if they slander my name.''
state attorney robert eagan said in orlando, ``we're looking at a matter involving the police up there. we're taking statements from witnesses.'' it</head> 3rd graf pvs: ``it's a...''</note> ^by freddy cuevas</byline>
honduras said today it filed a protest with nicaragua over an alleged incursion by sandinista soldiers in the same spot where nicaraguan troops fought contra rebels last week
nicaragua denied its troops crossed the border
a foreign ministry communique said a total of nearly 460 sandinistas crossed the border late tuesday. an ``energetic protest'' was filed with nicaragua over the incident, it said
it said 300 heavily armed sandinistas entered about 8 p.m. tuesday in the san andres de bocay region in olancho province, where sandinistas chased contras back across the border last week. it is about 150 miles east of this capital city
at the same time, 50 nicaraguan soldiers entered at the village of pico espanol in el paraiso province. the village is about two miles from the nicaraguan border
the statement, read to the associated press by telephone, did not say if there were any confrontations in the areas or whether the troops were still believed to be inside the country
in managua, the nicaraguan capital, a defense ministry spokesman was asked about the report. ``that's negative,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity
a honduran military official had reported the new incursion on wednesday
we don't know the purpose of this new entry and violation of our country, but the situation is being studied by the high command,'' the official said
it's a matter of small armed groups of sandinistas. because of that, the state of alert continues for all combat units of the armed forces,'' said the source, who spoke on condition of anonymity
the location was given as the san andres de bocay region in olancho province, but no other details were available
in washington, a government source speaking on condition of anonymity, said there had been unconfirmed reports that an estimated 300 sandinista soldiers had entered honduras
the reported incursion did not affect peace talks then under way between top sandinista and contra officials in nicaragua, even though both sides said their forces would stop fighting during the talks. late wednesday, the talks produced an accord calling for a 60-day cease-fire beginning april 1
earlier wednesday, pentagon officials in washington had said that unless the military situation in honduran changes, the approximately 3,200 u.s. troops sent to honduras last week would return home early next week
the u.s. troops were ordered to honduras as a show of force after 2,000 sandinsta soldiers allegedly chased contra rebels from nicaragua into honduras
two education associations called for an end thursday to what they called the growing practice of subjecting kindergarten children to standardized tests to determine promotion to first grade
the groups said the same tests are being used to determine whether a youngster is admitted to kindergarten or advised to spend another year in preschool
our children are being tested too early and failed too soon, and parents should ask for what purpose,'' said sue bredekamp, accreditation director of the national association for the education of young children
her group was joined by the national association of early childhood specialists in state departments of education calling for an end to mass standardized testing of children before the third grade
they said they did not object to testing of individual children whose teachers or parents suspect they have a learning or developmental problem. but for most children, they said, ``parents should trust their own instincts and the observations of trained and experienced preschool and kindergarten teachers.''
leaders of the groups said at a news conference they do not know how many schools are resorting to standardized placement or promotion tests for 4-, 5-and 6-year-olds
but bredekamp said that in some areas, ``it is not unusual now for 20 percent or more of young children to be advised to wait a year before entering kindergarten, or to `flunk' kindergarten, or to be assigned to a special track called `readiness,' `transitional' or `developmental' kindergarten.''
georgia recently became the first state to require standardized testing of kindergarten children. the city of minneapolis began testing kindergarteners in 1984 on basic math and reading skills, and has been holding back 10 percent of the children, most of them minorities
but last september the north carolina legislature voted to discontinue mandatory standardized tests for first and second graders
asa hilliard, an atlanta child psychologist and professor at georgia state university, said the tests are being used to hold children back or track them into remedial programs or special education, despite a lack of evidence that such steps improve their schooling
he said the tests have ``a disproportionate impact on those children who need school the most, the minority children.''
bredekamp said testing ``narrows and misdirects the curriculum.''
the most important things to learn in kindergarten, such as self-esteem, social competence, confidence, self-discipline, desire to learn, cannot be measured on standardized tests,'' she said
louise bates ames, co-founder of the gesell institute, which produces a widely used screening test, said it was ``discouraging that these groups have taken this political position.''
our position is that if there are 25 children in a classroom, all acting at 5-year-old maturity level, the teacher still has to individualize the curriculum to different ability levels. but if you put children together at different maturity and ability levels, then you have differences you can't possibly span,'' she said in a telephone interview from the institute's new haven, conn., headquarters
bredekamp said the testing issue ``is part of the bigger issue of pushing academic subjects at too early an age.''
the association's president is child psychologist david elkind, author of ``the hurried child'' and the leading critic of that trend
the association has 60,000 members, including teachers and others involved in preschool, kindergarten and early elementary education
former rep. john jenrette, who served a prison term for an abscam conviction, says he plans to challenge democrat robin tallon for his old seat from south carolina's 6th district
in new york, meanwhile, john b. levitt, a democratic district leader from manhattan, announced his candidacy thursday for the congressional seat held by republican bill green
i feel there are three urgent and pressing problems and they haven't been addressed,'' levitt, 28, said, citing homelessness, drug abuse and drug trafficking, and the overcrowding of hospitals sparked by the aids epidemic
they haven't been effectively dealt with everywhere in our area or in washington. we really need aggressive leadership and that's what i'm offering in my campaign. i think we need a congressman who will really go down and fight in washington and get dollars in this area.''
green, 58, has represented the 15th congressional district since 1978. he has not made a formal announcement for re-election, but his staff said he will
jenrette, who lost his seat in 1980 after being convicted in the abscam scandal, told the state newspaper in columbia on wednesday that he expects to make a formal announcement of his candidacy early next month
tallon declined comment on jenrette's possible candidacy
jenrette, 51, acknowledged he would be an underdog in a democratic primary against tallon, a 41-year-old clothing store operator elected in 1982
jenrette was convicted in october 1980 of conspiracy and accepting a $50,000 bribe from an fbi agent posing as an arab sheik. on probation after 13 months in federal prison, jenrette is a disbarred lawyer and reformed alcoholic
jenrette said he expects a federal judge to lift his probation before the june 14 primary
his felony conviction apparently does not prohibit jenrette from running for office or taking a seat in congress, although he is barred from voting in elections. according to a 1965 opinion by the south carolina attorney general, a candidate for the u.s. house of representatives does not have to be a qualified elector of the state in order to be seated
smarting from an argument with his mother, 10-year-old andres rascon and his 7-year-old sister headed for mexico in the family car after everyone else was asleep, police report
police were alerted after the boy tried to sell the car to a convenience store clerk tuesday
by the time authorities caught up with the runaways, they had traveled 65 miles south on interstate 19 to nogales on the u.s.-mexican border
our officers were _ how do you call it? _ amused initially, then amazed that he could do it,'' nogales police capt. antonio estrada said wednesday
though the youth said he planned the escapade after an argument with his mother, bertha rascon, she said the only argument she could remember occurred two weeks ago when she scolded andres for watching too much television
the boy apparently waited until everyone in his grandmother's home had gone to sleep, then took $20 and his mother's keys to her 1984 chevrolet sedan and slipped out a bedroom window. he persuaded his sister, maria fernanda, to go along
he told me they were going to have a spin around sonora,'' the mexican state immediately across the border, ``but then they decided to return,'' his mother said
she said she thought the youngsters may have been trying to find their father, who lives in mexico, though neither has any idea just where
andres, who is 4-foot-6, added a pillow to the car seat so he could see over the dash, estrada said. andres learned to drive when he was 6, when his father plopped the boy on his lap and showed him how to maneuver
after closing hospital beds in recent years, new york city faces a crisis because it didn't foresee the virulence and consequences of the narcotics epidemic, according to a study released thursday
from 1985 to 1987, time in hospitals increased for drug users and for victims of the side effects of narcotics use _ aids patients and babies born too puny to go home
psychiatric admissions not related to drugs also increased, but all other categories of patient care followed the predicted downward trend
had it not been for the growth in psychiatry, substance abuse, aids and neonatal services, inpatient hospital use in new york city would actually have fallen roughly 5 percent between july 1985 and july 1987, as was expected by planners and regulators who oversaw the closure of 1,800 hospital beds citywide during that period,'' the survey preparers said in a statement
they described the hospitals knotted in a ``medical gridlock'' in which ``literally hundreds of patients needing acute care services spend each night in emergency rooms because no beds are available on inpatient services.''
various forms of social pathology visible, but inadequately addressed, in many parts of the community are coming home to roost within the city's health care facilities,'' the study said
the study, prepared by the united hospital fund and the bigel institute for health policy at brandeis university, was based on data from 69 of the city's 81 municipal and voluntary hospitals. it covered about 89 percent of the approximately 35,000 certified hospital beds in new york
medical authorities are divided on what must be done, said bruce c. vladeck, president of the united hospitals fund
the greater new york hospital association's position is we need another 1,500 to 2,000 beds in this city fast,'' said vladeck
others, including dr. david axelrod, the state health commissioner, and stuart h. altman, dean of social policy graduate studies at brandeis, suggest a mix of community-based services, nursing care and special housing
during 1985-87, hospital stays grew by 44 percent for acquired immune deficiency syndrome patients, 15 percent each for psychiatric and substance abuse patients and 14 percent for newborns, the study found
the increases have been concentrated in low-income communities, another indicator that the hospital occupancy crisis is grounded in what vladeck called the ``general socio-economic disintegration of parts of the city.''
vladeck said crack, a form of cocaine, accounted for a large part of the problem
in addition to admissions traceable to crack-induced psychosis, ``there's a lot of crack-related respiratory illness _ people literally burn out their lungs smoking crack,'' he said. ``obviously, a lot of those low-birth-weight newborns are to crack-using mothers.''
officials fearing an explosion closed the bridge between pensacola and gulf breeze on thursday after two barges containing highly flammable chemical vapors slammed into a fishing pier
liquid cyclohexane had been unloaded from the barges before the collision but the vessels, being pushed by a towboat, still contained residue and dangerous vapors, said mark snowden, emergency response coordinator for the florida department of environmental regulation
if it were to explode i suspect it would be a catastrophic explosion,'' snowden said. sparks from an autombile ignition or removal efforts might be enough to set off the vapors if they should leak, he said
one of the two barges was removed about two hours after the collision about 9 a.m., but the other remained wedged into the tip of the 1.5-mile-long pensacola fishing pier
the pier is part of an old bridge about 75 feet from and parallel to the u.s. 98 bridge that spans the three miles across pensacola bay in the western end of the florida panhandle
the pier also was evacuated
the bridge was expected to remain closed for at least four hours, and motorists faced a detour of about 50 miles. escambia county administrator gus ellis ordered the bridge closed but he permitted emergency vehicles to cross. the coast guard also ordered all boats to stay clear
authorities were waiting for representatives of capitol towing, owner of the barges, to arrive from houston before making any decision on removing the barge
the vapors also could cause asphyxiation, snowden said. the chemical, composed in part of benzine, is used by monstano textile co. in pensacola to make nylon for carpeting, tires and other things. experts from monsanto also were on the scene
weather was clear but seas were choppy and winds were gusting from the southwest at up to 20 miles per hour when the collision occurred
the wind caught it and blew him into the bridge (pier),'' said grey jewett, risk manager for escambia county, which owns the pier. ``it destroyed the end of the pier, a turnaround.''
only three anglers were at the end of the pier, and there were no injuries. proposal, her comments, update with judge requesting briefs.</note>
less than two weeks before gary michael heidnik goes on trial on rape and murder charges, lawyers are haggling over rights to the story that began with the discovery of three half-naked women chained in a basement
a year ago friday, police found the women, as well as the limbs of a fourth woman in a freezer and then the naked body of a fifth woman in a new jersey forest
heidnik's trial begins april 4, but on wednesday in federal bankruptcy court, attorneys for heidnik's creditors proposed an agreement that would assign movie, book and entertainment rights to the estates of heidnik and his defunct church, the united church of the ministers of god. heidnik and the church are in bankruptcy
in the agreement, heidnik's attorney, a. charles peruto jr., would get one-third of any book and movie profits. the rest would go to heidnik's estate for payment to the alleged victims
but assistant district attorney harriet brumberg argued that state law provides that 100 percent of such profits go to victims of crimes
if anything in the book contains any thoughts, feelings, impressions of mr. heidnik, that belongs to the victims,'' ms. brumberg said
if i bring in money to enhance the estates, i get one-third of what i enhance,'' peruto said. ``the estates would get two-thirds.'' as part of the agreement, peruto would not get fees for defending heidnik
u.s. bankruptcy judge david a. scholl asked for legal briefs in the case by tuesday and said he would issue a ruling after that
one author researching a heidnik book was in court wednesday. and at least one other writer is said to be working on the story. atlanta writer ken englade, who has a contract with st. martin's press in new york to write the book, said the story was ``lurid,'' but facinating. calderon's arrival. picks up 9th graf, `almost all...</note>
gen. manuel antonio noriega was defiant today in the face of a nationwide general strike aimed at his ouster and said his opponents can't overthrow him
as the strike moved into its fourth day with no sign of letup, noriega once again lashed out at the opposition and the united states in a speech to a group of about 500 supporters wednesday night
the united states, noriega said, wants to create a panamanian political system ``in its image and reflecting its plans to subject'' central america
he accused the reagan administration of misjudging the ``patriotic feelings of panamanians'' because they ``are not made of chocolate, nor of sugar.''
washington has been trying to pressure noriega into leaving the country
the general also criticized his opponents for rejecting his offer to resign in exchange for a national dialogue, saying they have neither the ``capacity to represent'' nor to defeat ``the nationalistic forces.''
an organization of 25 latin american nations will hold an emergency meeting monday to discuss the crisis in panama, the group said wednesday. the meeting of the latin american economic system in caracas, venezuela, was requested by panama
a prominent opposition leader, ricardo arias calderon, returned from exile to join in the fight to oust noriega, head of the 15,000-strong panama defense forces and the power behind the civilian government
almost all businesses were shut down across the country again wednesday. lacking food and money, thousands of people lined up at soup kitchens set up by churches throughout the country
also wednesday, the government ordered a u.s. diplomat expelled, but the state department said in washington that economics counselor david miller would not leave as demanded. the state department said it would ignore the order because it considers panama's government illegitimate
it gave the same reason for rejecting an earlier attempt to expel terence kneebone, head of the u.s. information service in panama
in other developments wednesday, a dozen u.s. soldiers were detained by panamanian police, and 100 people shouted anit-noriega slogans after a funeral for a man killed at an earlier anti-government rally
panama is out of cash because washington cut off the supply of u.s. dollars, the panamanian national currency, in a bid to drive noriega into exile. the general was indicted in the united states last month on federal cocaine trafficking charges
jose mulino, an attorney active in the opposition national civic crusade, acknowledged that some action from within the defense forces may be necessary to end the monthlong crisis
there are growing pockets within the defense forces that are against noriega,'' he said. ``what we don't know is if they will act.''
leaders of the crusade _ an alliance of 200 professional, business, labor and other groups formed in june _ suggested some officers might fear acting against noriega because of the fate of 11 military rebels taken into custody after an abortive coup attempt last week
osvaldo velasquez, head of the panamanian committee for human rights, said wednesday, ``we know for certain they are being tortured.''
defense forces members are due to be paid at the end of the week. opposition leaders said their loyalty to noriega could fade if they, like most other panamanians, are unable to cash their checks because of the freeze on the country's deposits in u.s. banks
arias calderon, president of the opposition christian democratic party, told a news conference wednesday in san jose, costa rica, that he would return to panama today because: ``i want to share with the panamanian people in the dramatic days of fighting for democratization of the country.''
authorities refused to allow arias calderon to enter the country last month on his return from a business trip. he said he would be accompanied on an afternoon flight by legislators from central american and european countries
about 300 people attended the funeral wednesday of alcibiades vasquez, 24, a private security guard shot during rioting last week. the panamanian human rights panel said he was killed by a pro-government paramilitary squad
his death was the first in nearly a month of often violent civil unrest that began after president eric arturo delvalle tried to fire noriega on feb. 25 and was dismissed the next day. the united states still recognizes delvalle, who is in hiding in panama
a group promoting the religious freedom clause in the u.s. constitution announced plans thursday to hold a ``first liberty'' summit to call attention to the religious liberties enjoyed by americans
the williamsburg charter foundation said it will hold its summit in williamsburg, va., june 24 and 25. during the summit national political, business and religious leaders will sign a charter that celebrates the religious clause in the first amendment to the constitution and reaffirms freedom on conscience for people of all faiths
the first amendment begins with freedom on conscience, and upon this premise all other freedoms are made possible,'' said foundation chairman alonzo l. mcdonald. ``these clauses allow us to live with our deepest differences and encourage pluralism and diversity of opinion.''
the non-sectarian foundation already has released a survey of american attitudes on religion in public life and is sponsoring a symposium of scholars and religious leaders next month in charlottesville, va
communism suffered its first big mac attack thursday as mcdonald's opened a restaurant in yugoslavia, and police were called in to keep customers who lined up for hours from getting too unruly under the golden arches
i just wanted to taste genuine american hamburgers,'' said milica nikolic, a high school student who waited for three hours to taste her first big mac
people curiously examined the renovated restaurant's plush interior and the back-lit signs depicting the hamburgers, french fries, milk shakes and other fare more familiar in the west. it also featured amber-colored tables and floors, pastel-colored upholstery, modern art paintings and discreet illumination
the fast-food outlet, located on a downtown square, had drawn crowds in recent days, and they began gathering long before it opened thursday
police kept watch on the lines of customers snaking around the block, and they regulated the number who came inside to avoid overcrowding
no opening of a restaurant in belgrade has created such a sensation as this one today,'' one policeman said
i think this restaurant has no competition in belgrade,'' said milica danic, a housewife who treated her son to a cheeseburger. ``it is much cleaner, the service is faster, the interior is nicer and it is not too expensive.''
the belgrade media have suggested that the success of mcdonald's in yugoslavia depends on its acceptance by citizens long accustomed to a hamburger-like fast-food dish called the pljeskavica: ground pork and onions on a bun
in fact, this is a clash between the big mac and pljeskavica,'' said vesna milosevic, an official of genex, a yugoslav state-run enterprise that has contracted a joint venture agreement with mcdonald's
our aim is not to destroy the pljeskavica on the yugoslav market,'' said predrag dostanic, managing director of the genex-mcdonald's. ``we want to change customs of the local people used to completly different eating habits.''
he said that lounging at tables for a long time after a finished meal will draw a warning. also, smoking is forbidden and alcohol will not be served
this contrasts sharply with the balkan and yugoslav custom of sitting with a drink in smoke-filled restaurants and chatting with friends after the meal
the big mac meal, consisting of a hamburger, soft drink and french fries costs the equivalent of $2.57, or about as much the similar meal would cost in numerous pljeskavica joints around town
sadik seljami, a waiter in a small pljeskavica outlet just a few hundred yards from the mcdonald's, suggested that the american restaurant wants to drive yugoslav fast-food outlets out of business
however, we will not give up the fight even if we have to lower the prices,'' said seljami
glen cook, an executive of the mcdonald's corp., said during the opening ceremonies, ``we are very excited about the opening of this restaurant, not only because it is the first one in a communist country, but also because it is one of the nicest in europe.''
mcdonald's and genex contribute $1 million each for the flagship restaurant. they will also share the profits equally even though it will be managed entirely by yugoslavs
the restaurant has 350 seats and employs 110 people capable of serving 2,500 meals per hour. in an effort to keep a high level of services, the management is entitled to fire any employees who fail to perform
the american corporation plans to open five additional restaurants yugoslavia in the next five years. the next east european mcdonald's, and the first in a soviet bloc country, is to open next month in budapest, hungary
a federal appeals court on thursday upheld the convictions of two men found guilty of setting a fire at hotel fire in puerto rico that killed 97 people
the 1st u.s. court of appeals rejected arguments by armando jimenez rivera and jose francisco rivera lopez that the trial judge abused his discretion in sentencing them to 75 years and 99 years in prison, respectively
jimenez rivera and rivera lopez, both workers at the dupont plaza hotel, admitted setting the fire as part of a labor dispute with hotel management
the fire on new year's eve 1986 at the beachfront hotel also injured more than 140 people
in return for their guilty pleas and cooperation in the investigation, the government had recommended a maximum penalty of 25 years in prison for rivera lopez and 24 years for jimenez -rivera
u.s. district judge jose antonio fuste of puerto rico rejected the government's recommendation, saying the crimes amounted to felony murder. the judge also noted that a third man convicted in the case was found guilty of first-degree murder
jimenez rivera and rivera lopez appealed on the grounds that the judge's remarks at sentencing were improper and that fuste failed to consider migating factors
the judge's concern over the deaths that resulted from their crime indicates that he determined the sentence in reference to the particular actions'' of the two men, the appeals court said
the justices did, however, order fuste to hold a new hearing on the rivera lopez sentencing to determine if he relied on inaccurate statements in a pre-sentencing report. if so, the court said he should hold a new sentencing hearing
israeli jets bombed palestinian targets on the outskirts of sidon for the second straight day thursday, hitting a base of abu nidal's guerrilla faction
police said nine people were killed and five wounded in the raid, the third this week near the port city 25 miles south of lebanon
police said most of the casualties were members of nidal's fatah-revolutionary council, and the group issued a statement pledging ``merciless retaliation.''
a police spokesman described the attack as ``very fierce.'' he said six israeli warplanes dropped 30 bombs in six sorties within 55 minutes
lebanese prime minister salim hoss instructed the country's u.n. ambassador, rashid fakhoury, to complain to the world body about the israeli attacks, state radio said
but lebanon did not ask for a security council meeting on the issue, it said
the police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with standing regulations, said the main target of the raid was nidal's guerrilla base, but the jets also hit a position of the marxist democratic front for the liberation of palestine
the israelis plowed the olive groves where the stricken bases are,'' he added
the bases were engulfed by smoke and dust as ambulances arrived to evacuate casualties
the police spokesman said nidal's guerrillas cordoned off the bases in the villages of bekasta, majdelyoun, salhiyeh and abra on the southern and eastern edges of sidon
the attacking jets dropped scarlet balloons to deflect heat-seeking missiles. the guerrillas fired at the roaring jets with soviet-made anti-aircraft guns. no hits were reported
let the enemy wait for coming blows of our revolutionary fighters,'' said a statement issued by the fatah-revolutionary council. ``we shall strike doubly in merciless retaliation.''
abu nidal, whose real name is sabri al-banna, broke away from yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization in 1974. he has since claimed attacks against a series of civilian targets around the world
the elusive terrorist mastermind tops wanted lists in the united states and europe. his whereabouts are not known, altough recent reports said he has been shuttling between libya and algeria
his group had also vowed revenge after wednesday's strike, saying in a statement it would ``severely strike back against the zionist enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the right time and place.''
wednesday's attack also targeted abu nidal and dflp bases, killing seven people and wounding 15
the dflp, headed by nayef hawatmeh, is one of the plo's largest factions
former president chun doo-hwan decided to cut short a visit to the united states after prosecutors linked his brother to a growing government corruption scandal, officials said thursday
the prosecutor general's office said its inquiry of corruption involving the saemaul development group may be expanded to investigate other possible wrongdoings under the chun administration
chun, who has not been implicated, yielded power on feb. 25 to president roh tae-woo. but chun has clung to a measure of power behind the scenes
prosecutors said thursday that about 200 saemaul and government officials had been questioned since monday to find out if chun's younger brother, former saemaul leader chun kyung-hwan, and his aides amassed fortunes by embezzling the group's funds
the former president was on a three-week private visit to the united states in which he met with president reagan on wednesday, but south korean officials said thursday he planned to leave early
the opposition parties contend the government is trying to hide the extent of corruption under chun. they have called for a broader inquiry that would look into any corruption by the chun family and supporters
the ruling democratic justice party has rejected the charges as an attempt to blacken the government's reputation. but its leaders promised to investigate any official corruption
the semi-official saemaul, or ``new community,'' is a group of community leaders that has evolved into a huge organization since it was created in 1971 to promote urban development. it has launched projects from building model communities to organizing neighborhood clean-ups
but critics have said saemaul worked with past authoritarian governments to organize support and dole out patronage
prosecutors said thursday they had uncovered more evidence that saemaul officials embezzled millions of dollars, peddled government patronage and misappropriated property. they said they questioned government officials to find out if they aided corrruption within saemaul
prosecutors also said the younger chun was suspected of diverting saemaul funds to personal land speculation and of making money with influence peddling. local newspapers reported the younger chun and his aides may soon be officially charged with corruption, but prosecutors declined to confirm the reports
many in south korea believe the new government is using the saemaul investigation to discredit the former president
roh, a former general who helped put chun into power with military backing in 1980, has vowed to end authoritarian rule and has been moving to cut ties with the former president. top chun supporters have been removed from the ruling party and the former president's role as a government adviser has been reduced to a largely ceremonial function
however, members of the opposition party for peace and democracy say roe may also have been involved in the corruption when he served as home minister in 1982
a turkey chase left 71-year-old lucille andrews stuck in the mud in her car for two days. ``miss curiosity'' had a wonderful time
when she was located wednesday by frantic relatives, the st. clair county woman said she spent her time spying on wildlife, and wasn't concerned about food and water
i was no more scared than i am right now,'' mrs. andrews said from her home. ``i knew someone would find me.''
the air and ground search began after she was reported missing monday afternoon
mrs. andrews said she had been out driving, and caught site of a turkey
i saw that turkey going out there and i thought, `you fool thing. if you got a nest out there, i'm going to follow you and find you,''' she said
she followed the turkey across a field, but her car got stuck in a swampy ditch
at night, i locked the doors and rolled up the windows and went to sleep. during the day, i looked around and thought, `boy i'd like to have my house up on that hill,''' she said
mrs. andrews didn't see the turkey again, but did see three deer and a bear cub
the moon was shining so bright that i raised my head up and there was a little old bear. he was just a baby,'' she said
while mrs. andrews communed with nature, her eight children, most of her 15 grandchildren and assorted friends and relatives formed a ``family posse'' that combed the woods around her house
we were driving everywhere,'' said grandson mark andrews, 21
andrews said his grandmother, who walks with a cane because of arthritis, is called ``miss curiosity'' by family members because ``she's always doing something.''
i hate housework and all of that stuff, but i do love to drive,'' mrs. andrew said. ``if i had to stay in the house i think i would die.''
a federal plan to allow oil and gas exploration off the florida keys was dropped for five years thursday after state officials agreed to withdraw pending legal challenges
this is to benefit not only the environment, but the tourist industry and the people who live along the shores,'' gov. bob martinez said at a ceremony on a key largo beach. ``i think this decision is a flagship-type decision that other states will use.''
martinez and u.s. interior department secretary donald hodel announced separately the settlement which removes about 11.1 million offshore acres from a five-year leasing plan. the preserved area goes from key largo south around the keys and dry tortugas and north to naples on the gulf coast. the area would extend 60 miles west of dry tortugas
three months of negotiations with hodel and a january snorkeling trip the men took together on the coral reefs off key largo cemented the agreement, martinez said. the republican governor denied that election year politics had any effect, but said hodel was aware of opposition from the florida congressional delegation and environmental groups
u.s. sen. bob graham, a democrat who built a reputation as a defender of florida's environment while preceeding martinez in the governor's mansion, noted that 130,000 people signed petitions opposing oil drilling in the keys of florida, which has 2,200 miles of coastline
this is the first time that (the federal government) have ever deleted significant areas of a lease sale from a plan,'' said charles lee, senior vice president of the florida audubon society. legal challenges similar to florida's have been brought by massachusetts, california and alaska, with little result
florida attorney general bob butterworth had a pragmatic explanation for martinez's negotiating success: ``i think most people thought it was, at best, insane to explore for oil off the florida keys.''
under the settlement, martinez and butterworth agreed to drop as early as monday the lawsuit against the plan, and the state also will drop its challenge to leasing 41,000 acres to the seaward of a protected area planned off cape san blas, in the florida panhandle. in return, interior will impose a one-year moratorium on development of any leases that should be awarded there
that panhandle area is believed to contain gas, not oil. martinez has reserved his rights to object to oil development if any should be found off cape san blas
the interior department last year included the florida straits _ atlantic ocean waters off the keys _ in a five-year plan for developing the oil resources of the outer continental shelf, shallow waters extending 200 miles from the u.s. shoreline
an interior department study released last year concluded that the cumulative danger from drilling, leaking tankers and other sources added up to a 48 percent chance of a major oil spill along florida's coast within 35 years
americans' personal incomes rose at the fastest clip in four months during february while consumer spending was propelled upward by a rebound in car sales, the government reported thursday
the commerce department said personal incomes advanced 0.9 percent, reflecting strong employment gains in the past few months. spending rose 0.7 percent, up sharply from a tiny 0.1 percent january increase
economists said the new figures provided further evidence that the economy has suffered no long-run effects from the october stock market crash. five months ago, analysts feared that consumer worries about the future would cause them to cut back on spending and could push the country into a recession
for people who were worried about a major consumer retrenchment, these numbers are encouraging,'' said sandra shaber, an economist with the futures group. ``as long as income gains hold up, people will continue to spend.''
bruce steinberg, an economist with merrill lynch, said consumer spending will rise by about 3.5 percent in the first quarter of this year, after adjusting for inflation, a major rebound after a spending decline in the final three months of last year
he said consumer spending would be the major factor contributing to expected economic growth during the january-march quarter of around 2 percent, as measured by the gross national product
a few months ago many analysts worried that growth in the current quarter actually would be a negative figure, indicating the country was headed into a new recession
steinberg said the fear now was that consumer spending would spurt ahead at such a fast pace that production bottlenecks could occur and inflation would be rekindled. but ms. shaber said she did not consider this a danger because she believed slower income growth in the months ahead would slow the growth of spending as well
analysts said the february gain in incomes, which followed a 0.3 percent january rise and was the best showing since a 1.9 percent october increase, reflected good employment news. the jobless rate fell to an 8{ year low of 5.7 percent during the month
the key category of wages and salaries climbed by $15.4 billion in february, a 0.7 percent increase which was the fastest advance since november
disposable income, the amount left over after taxes are paid, climbed 1.1 percent in february, almost double the 0.6 percent january increase. it was the best showing since a 2.1 percent rise in october and was credited in part to tax cuts showing up as employers held back less from paychecks
the individual tax cuts were the last round of reductions scheduled under the landmark 1986 tax overhaul legislation
the 0.7 percent increase in personal consumption spending was the biggest advance since a 0.8 percent rise in december. it reflected a jump of $7.4 billion in sales of durable goods as consumers responded to new incentive programs for autos. durable goods sales had fallen $2.4 billion in january
with incomes rising faster than spending, americans' savings rate climbed as well, rising to 5.2 percent of after-tax income last month, the highest level since october
purchases of non-durable goods _ items not expected to last three years _ rose $2 billion in february after having fallen $7.7 billion in january. purchases of services, including housing costs, increased $12.4 billion following a $13.7 billion january increase
farm incomes increased $8.5 billion in february after a decline of $8.2 billion in janaury. the big february gain and the large january decline were both attributed to swings in government subsidy payments to farmers
the cease-fire agreement signed by the nicaraguan government and resistance forces appears to signify the onset of the post-contra era in nicaragua and an entirely new political dynamic in that country
the administration was officially upbeat about the agreement but the contras, with little prospect of receiving more u.s. military aid, were forced to drop virtually all the concessions they had been seeking earlier this year
the agreement clearly falls short of the administration goal of an ``irreversible'' democratic process in nicaragua as its price for suspending aid to the contras
achievement of that objective is apparently dependent on sandinista good will coupled with whatever diplomatic and economic pressures the industrialized democracies can muster to prod the nicaraguans in that direction
in theory at least, the nicaraguan war could be revived if upcoming talks break down. but the short-term prospect is for the dismantling of the contras accompanied by a number of gestures by the sandinistas, including a phased release of prisoners, permission for political exiles to return, participation of contra representatives in a national dialogue and guarantees of free expression
all of this was agreed to in the sandinista-contra cease-fire talks this week. still, the contras have relatively little to show for their six-year effort, particularly when compared with their goals as recently as late january
at the time, they still were receiving u.s. military supplies and were cautiously optimistic about the prospects for more aid when that issue came to a congressional vote in early february. but contra aid foes prevailed on that vote
the contras' settlement terms in late january called for the implementation of 17 democratic reforms during a proposed 30-day cease-fire period. they demanded gradual disarmament of both sides, the repatriation of soviet bloc military advisers, formation of a single ``apolitical'' national army, suspension of compulsory military service and the disbanding of the sandinista militia
these demands received no attention at all or were dismissed with no more than vague references in the communique signed wednesday night
assuming that the contras are dismantled, several questions arise: will president daniel ortega pursue with vigor the communization of nicaragua, as administration hardliners fear? will he strengthen his ties to the leftist insurgency in el salvador? will he proceed with plans to acquire mig jet fighters from the soviets? will he build up the nicaraguan armed forces to 600,000, as his defense minister suggested? will he move toward a uniquely nicaraguan system, which is neither modeled after cuba nor his democratic neighbor, costa rica? or will there be a genuine national reconciliation in nicaragua, as ortega suggests?
secretary of state george p. shultz outlined in generally positive terms the administration's reaction to the cease-fire agreement, calling it an ``important step forward.''
other officials, asking not to be identified, said they preferred not to offer their own assessments of the agreement even on an anonymous basis because to do so would undercut shultz
this suggests continued skepticism within the administration about the terms the contras agreed to and continued anger with the congress for letting the rebels down
ever since the central america peace agreement was signed last aug. 7, the administration had been steadily scaling back on its expectations in central america
last fall, the administration was asking the congress for $270 million in contra aid. faced with congressional opposition, president reagan lowered that figure to $36.2 million, with only 10 per cent of that earmarked for military aid
that proposal was defeated seven weeks ago and congress mandated an end to all aid deliveries by feb. 29. slightly more than three weeks later, the contras settled with the sandinistas, accepting terms that they would have rejected out of hand not long ago
editor`s note _ george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the associated press since 1968
fifty-one illegal aliens smuggled into the country from mexico to sell frozen fruit bars and ice cream from pushcarts were arrested and held for deportation wednesday, authorities said
the aliens, most of whom told authorities they had been brought into the country in the last eight to 10 days, were sleeping on the floor of the warehouse where the carts and products were stored, said ron rogers, spokesman for the immigration and naturalization service
there were beer cans scattered all over the place, and pillows and blankets on the floor,'' rogers said. he said the men told authorities they had been recruited in mexico as street vendors
the operators of the vending company were being sought, he said
the aliens, one a teen-age boy and the rest adult males, were being held for deportation hearings, he said
nearly half a million 1985 cars and light trucks made by general motors corp. must be recalled because they fail to meet federal air pollution standards, the environmental protection agency said thursday
a faulty thermal vacuum switch is part of the reason the vehicles' exhaust contains excess carbon monoxide and evaporated gasoline, the epa said
the vehicles affected by the recall are equipped with 5.0 liter (305 cubic inches) and 5.7 liter (350 cubic inches) engines, the epa said
they were sold as the chevrolet impala, caprice classic, camaro, monte carlo and el camino; the pontiac firebird, bonneville, grand prix and parisienne; and the gmc caballero, epa said. models sold in california, which are built to stricter standards, are also included
earlier, we offered to recall the vehicles to replace the thermostatic vacuum switch,'' said jane mott, gm spokeswoman in detroit. ``we will review the order and determine how best to respond.''
such recall orders by the epa are rare and generally indicate the agency and a manufacturer could not agree on something, such as the cause of the problem, its scope, the necessary repair, terms of the recall or something else. most recalls are made voluntarily
ms. mott said gm told the epa it believed replacing the switch on the vehicles would be sufficient to bring emissions into compliance with federal standards
the epa, however, said its tests showed that ``replacement of the (switch) alone will not completely remedy the problem and that additional repairs may be necessary.''
gm has 45 days either to request a public hearing to contest the order, or to submit a repair plan for epa's approval before notices are mailed to owners
the company last year recalled more than a million vehicles from the 1982 and 1983 model years for similar problems
the savings and loan industry, drained by insolvent institutions in texas, last year recorded its worst loss since the great depression, the government said thursday
the federal home loan bank board said a $3.2 billion loss in the last three months of 1987 pushed the industry's red ink for the year to a record $6.8 billion
that was nearly 50 percent greater than the previous post-depression record of $4.6 billion, set in 1981, when the prime lending rate soared above 20 percent
i hope it's the worst we'll ever see,'' said james w. christian, chief economist of the u.s. league of savings insitutions, the industry's largest trade group
the nation's 3,147 federally insured s&amp;ls lost $1.8 billion in the third quarter of last year and $1.9 billion in the spring. they earned $100 million in the first three months of the year and had a modest $132 million profit for all of 1986
in contrast, the federal deposit insurance corp. said earlier this month that the nation's 13,700 federally insured commercial banks earned $3.7 billion in 1987. still, it was their lowest profit since 1933
despite the overall loss for the s&amp;l industry, 66 percent of the s&amp;ls earned money in the fourth quarter. the $1.3 billion earnings of 2,089 s&amp;ls partly offset the $4.5 billion losses of the remaining 1,058 institutions
for the year, the profitable two-thirds of the industry earned $6.6 billion, which was more than wiped out by the $13.4 billion deficit of the money-losing s&amp;ls
the percentage of institutions earning a profit has declined steadily for two years, from 81 percent in the first quarter of 1986 to 66 percent at the end of last year
james barth, chief economist of the bank board, said s&amp;l losses were heavily concentrated in the southwest, which is dependent on the ailing oil and gas industry
barth said the worst 20 institutions _ most of them in the southwest _ lost a total of $2.1 billion in the final quarter of last year, accounting for two-thirds of the overall industry loss
an unprofitable instituion is not necessarily insolvent. an s&amp;l is considered insolvent when its loans and other assets are worth less than what it owes to depositors and other creditors
the bank board said 345 s&amp;ls were insolvent at the end of 1987 under regulatory accounting principles, 109 of them in texas alone. there were 510 insolvent s&amp;ls under the stricter accounting principles that will be used beginning next year
by another measure of health, return on assets, savings institutions' performance was not quite as bad as 1981 and 1982. the return was negative 0.56 percent last year, compared with negative 0.73 percent in 1981 and minus 0.65 percent in 1982
barth said some of the overall industry loss in 1987 can be attributed to a decrease in the corporate tax rate. he said some s&amp;ls decided to push profits into 1988, when the top tax rate is 34 percent, rather than take them in 1987, when the rate was 40 percent
barth said he believed the industry's problems have ``plateaued out'' and that ``there is some light at the end of the tunnel'' in the southwest
but martin a. regalia, chief economist of the national council of savings institutions, warned that most economists believe interest rates will edge higher and said southwest real estate shows no sign of a sharp rebound
regalia said the performance of the thrift industry this year will depend on how quickly the bank board resolves problems at texas institutions
you have to be as expeditious as possible at getting them closed down. so far i think (the bank board) has recognized the problem. now it's time to get out and do it,'' he said
lack of money to pay depositors had forced the federal savings and loan insurance corp., which insures deposits to $100,000, to keep many insolvent s&amp;ls open. now that money is flowing into the fund from a $10.8 billion recapitalization authorized by congress in august, the bank board is moving to close ailing institutions or merge them with healthier s&amp;ls
last month, the bank board announced a plan to spend $6 billion to $7 billion in texas over the next several years, but it doesn't anticipate announcements on specific s&amp;ls before early april
richard gephardt could run for both the house and the white house if he so chose _ at least temporarily
under missouri law, gephardt could file for re-election by next tuesday's deadline and still remain in the presidential race at least until may 17, the deadline for withdrawing from the state primary ballot. if gephardt withdrew by then and decided to continue his presidential bid, filing for his congressional seat would re-open for five days
gephardt has another option, according to cheri ghan, a spokeswoman for the missouri secretary of state
he could file for re-election and would remain on the aug. 2 missouri state primary ballot even if he somehow managed to win a spot on the democratic presidential ticket in july
in that case, gephardt would have a decision to make after the state primary, if he won. democratic officials would select the congressional nominee if gephardt gave up his congressional seat to be part of the presidential ticket
former national security adviser robert c. mcfarlane testified for three hours thursday before a federal grand jury investigating attorney general edwin meese iii's ties to a $1 billion iraqi oil pipeline
mcfarlane, who declined to comment during a break in the grand jury proceedings, became involved in the pipeline project in the spring and summer of 1985 through contacts with meese, longtime meese friend e. robert wallach and wallach's client, swiss oilman bruce rappaport
mcfarlane was accompanied to the federal courthouse by legal counsel, peter morgan, who said his client is a witness in the grand jury investigation
independent counsel james mckay is investigating whether meese may have violated the foreign corrupt practices act in connection with the pipeline project
in a september 1985 memo to meese relating wallach's conversations with rappaport, wallach said a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would be paid to the israeli labor party of then-israeli prime minister shimon peres
meese has said he doesn't recall reading the reference to labor party payments in the memo, which was found in the attorney general's files at the justice department last year in connection with mckay's investigation
mckay is presenting evidence to the grand jury in an attempt to determine whether there was a conspiracy to pay bribes to israeli politicians to ensure that israel would not bomb the pipeline passing through iraq and jordan close to the israeli border. rappaport has denied making or offering bribes, and denies that there was any plan to do so
wallach went to meese for help on the pipeline in may 1985 and the attorney general referred him to mcfarlane, who then was president reagan's national security adviser
the referral resulted in a meeting in june 1985 between mcfarlane, wallach and rappaport
the pipeline's backers wanted to enlist the support of the u.s. government in assembling an insurance package that would protect the project in the event of an israeli attack
on march 11 in connection with the iran-contra arms and money affair, mcfarlane pleaded guilty to misdemeanor charges that he misled congress in 1985 by assuring lawmakers the reagan administration was not helping arm nicaraguan rebels during a ban on u.s. military aid
angry shouts erupted thursday between 30 supporters of defendants in the iran-contra case and three anti-contra protesters outside the federal courthouse
an elderly woman ripped up signs calling oliver l. north an ``american hero'' and shouted obscenities at demonstrators for addressing her as ``old lady'' and ``communist.''
several police officers stood a few feet away but took no action
the woman, who identified herself as lillian geckter of new haven, conn., boasted that inside the court building where north, john m. poindexter, richard v. secord and albert hakim pleaded innocent to a 23-count indictment, she looked north in the eye and said: ``don't you smile at me, traitor.''
the pro-north demonstrators chanted, ``ollie's right, wright's wrong,'' a slap at house speaker jim wright, d-texas, who led defeat of contra military aid in the house
fund the contras, not the lawyers,'' the group shouted as independent counsel lawrence e. walsh, the prosecutor, told reporters he was pleased that u.s. district judge gerhard gesell intended to handle the case expeditiously
walsh, who said he would not comment on the case now that it is under gesell's control, was booed by the protesters as he got into his car
north emerged from a door far from the demonstrators, but his car was mobbed by supporters and scores of reporters and photographers as it passed slowly in front of the building where the crowd had gathered. north smiled and waved from the back seat but remained in the gray limousine
i think ollie is getting a bum rap out of all this,'' said steve bridgett of greenville, ill., who said he belonged to no political organization
peter flaherty, chairman of citizens for reagan, said his and several other groups were represented. ``we came to show our friendship and support for ollie and our solidarity with him,'' he said
for a time during the arraignment, aron kay of new york city was the lone anti-contra demonstrator
after north passed by and kay shouted, ``ollie north's a liar,'' several pro-north demonstrators taunted him with, ``why don't you get a job?'' and several more caustic suggestions
kay, who described himself as a long-time peace activist, shouted back, ``our job is protesting.''
iran angrily left an islamic conference thursday after fellow moslems decried its failure to heed cease-fire calls in its war with iraq and accused it of instigating rioting in the holy city of mecca
iraq and egypt said the withdrawal proved the ``loneliness'' of iran's stance toward the islamic world
the iranian envoy to the meeting of the organization of islamic conference, mohammed ali taskhiri, flew out of jordan at the head of his five-man delegation
we were not happy,'' taskhiri, his voice quavering with anger, said in a telephone interview. he said his group boycotted meetings wednesday night and thursday
the conference is taking place only to serve the interests of a certain country,'' he said, referring to iraq. ``therefore, we don't see why we should stay at this meeting.''
egypt and other arab countries were drafting a resolution on the iran-iraq conflict to submit to foreign ministers of the 46-member conference
sources close to the conference confirmed that the draft denounces iran's failure to heed last july's u.n. security council resolution 598, which calls for a cease-fire in the 7{-year-old war
the sources, speaking on condition they not be identified further, said the draft also criticizes iran's purported leadership of the violence in mecca, saudi arabia, and calls for future ``security measures'' to protect moslem pilgrims
in a statement to the jordanian government announcing its withdrawl, the iranian delegation specified it was unhappy with the draft ``resolution on the gulf war...and the resolution on the holy places.'' the text of the statement was provided by one of the sources
the conference sources also said the draft of the final communique, likely to be issued by friday, also called for:
_ an immediate soviet withdrawal from afghanistan;
_ support for the 15-week-old palestinian uprising in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip;
_ guaranteed rights for moslem minorities in bulgaria and other countries where they might suffer persecution;
_ unspecified measures against air piracy
iraqi foreign minister tariq aziz said ``iran's withdrawal demonstrates its loneliness'' in the ranks of moslem countries. ``they wanted to express their voice, or better, their lies, to the organization, but they did not find ears.''
egyptian foreign minister esmat abdel-meguid, whose country was the target of iranian criticism earlier in the conference, echoed aziz, saying: ``the voice of the iranian representative is an odd voice and it represents the loneliness in which iran lives.''
the iranians attended the meeting after boycotting last year's summit of islamic heads of state in kuwait, which tehran accuses of aiding iraq's war effort
iran, which is persian and not arab, sent a low-level delegation to the amman meeting. taskhiri is head of the foreign relations department in iran's islamic guidance ministry
iran and iraq have been blasting each other's cities for more than three weeks with missiles and air raids, and the iranians have pushed into northeast iraq
iran was lambasted in amman for allegedly inciting rioting last year in mecca in which 402 moslems, 275 of them iranian, were killed
saudi authorities said the pilgrims were killed in a stampede triggered by iranian rioters, and in subsequent violence. iran claimed police mowed them down with machine guns
the saudi foreign minister, prince saud al-faisal, said his country will restrict the number of pilgrims to mecca this year as a ``temporary measure'' because facilities there needed to be expanded. he did not elaborate
iran has said it will send 150,000 people to this year's pilgrimage
the saudis reportedly have made it clear that mecca and medina, islam's holiest shrines, can accommodate only around 1 million pilgrims at a time. connecticut</head>
democrat richard gephardt, who has fallen on hard times since his iowa victory 45 days ago, will quit the presidential race unless he scores an upset victory in michigan this weekend, aides said thursday. george bush, meanwhile, headed for connecticut expecting to pad his huge lead on the gop side
gephardt said he'd made no decision to drop out, declaring, ``my mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time.'' but the scramble was already on to pick up supporters who would be freed if he withdrew
there's no question there are some union leaders who are now supporting dick gephardt who would find paul simon the most attractive of the alternatives,'' said illinois sen. simon at an appearance in kalamazoo
simon, who is in fourth place in the democratic delegate count, just ahead of gephardt, spoke of getting ``back in the ballgame.''
among the republicans, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, wife of bush's main rival, sen. bob dole, said in oshkosh, wis., that her husband now has merely a ``long shot'' chance, but she added, ``he's got the grit and determination needed to keep him in the running.''
she said neither she nor her husband have discussed the possibility that one of them might be bush's running mate for the general election. ``i'm really not seeking to be on the ticket. i'm going 12 hours a day just trying to carry bob's message,'' she said
vice president bush, holding a commanding lead in the battle for republican convention delegates, was traveling to connecticut, saying he was taking nothing for granted in the primary there next tuesday
however, public opinion polls give him a big lead over dole in the state where bush was born and where his father once served as a u.s. senator
gephardt, just a few weeks ago the victor in iowa's caucuses, now lags behind michael dukakis, jesse jackson, albert gore jr. and simon in delegates to the national convention. he trails dukakis and jackson in public opinion polls preceding saturday's michigan caucuses
he said thursday in detroit, ``rather than trying to guess all the different hypotheticals of what might happen, i just think we have to be patient, wait to see the outcome and then decide what other steps should be taken.''
still, gephardt's wife jane told a radio interviewer in michigan, ``i think dick has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race. ... if we don't do well here, we will not be able to continue.''
the missouri congressman has only until tuesday to file for re-election to his house seat, and one aide, commenting only on condition he not be named, suggested that it was important for the congressman to retain that office in order to raise money. his campaign has been strapped for cash for weeks
money was in the news for several other current and former candidates on thursday:
_gore said in washington he was willing to release information on more than $1 million in loans taken out by his presidential campaign, but members of his staff who heard the senator's remarks said no such decision had been made
gore's pledge to release the material came after a report in a nashville, tenn., newspaper that his campaign had put up the proceeds of future fund-raisers and federal matching funds as collateral for almost $1.5 million borrowed from banks about two weeks ago
_the federal election commission said that gary hart, now that he is no longer a presidential candidate, can use leftover 1988 campaign funds toward retiring his lingering debt of about $1 million from his 1984 race
_the fec agreed to grant federal matching funds to political extremist lyndon larouche's presidential campaign, even though he is standing trial on a charge relating to alleged financial irregularity in his 1984 campaign. larouche is running as a democrat, although the national party has disavowed his candidacy
the democrats, including gephardt, were concentrating on michigan and on wisconsin, which has its primary on april 5
massachusetts gov. dukakis, who spent the first part of the week trading charges with gephardt on foreign-trade policy, a major issue in a state heavily dependent on u.s. auto sales, was in california but planned to spend all day friday in michigan. the detroit free press endorsed him on thursday
dole's aides said he had no campaign events scheduled thursday, and former television evangelist pat robertson was to address a rally in falls church, va., working to shore up his strength in his home state
the federal election commission on thursday declared fringe presidential candidate lyndon larouche eligible for federal matching funds, even as a former aide was testifying elsewhere of being pressured to wring donations out of people for larouche's 1984 campaign
larouche is standing trial in boston federal court on a charge relating to alleged irregularity in his 1984 campaign
while the federal election commission was certifying larouche to receive federal funds for his 1988 campaign, former aide charles tate testified at the trial that larouche solicitors were warned in 1984 that that falling short of daily fund-raising quotas was ``the moral equivalent of treason'' and would result in the collapse of western civilization
the fec, on a 5-1 vote, said that larouche has fulfilled the requirements for eligibility to receive matching funds. but the commission also said special review procedures would be undertaken to evaluate each of his submissions for matching funds, in light of irregularities found in his first submission
larouche spokeswoman mary jane freeman said the ruling was ``terrific.'' she noted the campaign had ``no problem with the conditions'' the fec imposed
in voting with the majority, commissioner scott thomas said, ``presidential candidates and campaigns can come in many different shapes and colors.''
overall it does look like there is substantial support for a presidential campaign from american citizens for mr. larouche,'' he said noting that larouche has raised more than $2 million from contributors
but commissioner joan aikens opposed the majority, saying an fec survey of larouche contributors raised ``a question of patent irregularity'' in fund raising
a survey by the fec's audit staff had indicated that 6 percent of 713 larouche contributors contacted had not intended their checks to go to his campaign
the survey was undertaken because some contributor checks had the letters ``ldc,'' presumably for larouche democratic committee, written over ``sdi'' as the payee. and some checks contained memo notations regarding aids or sdi _ the first referring to the disease and the second referring to president reagan's strategic defense initiative _ suggesting the donors may not have intended to give money to a presidential campaign, but to one of those causes
fec auditors said many people who responded to the survey ``described instances where he@she 1. felt pressured into making a contribution, 2. made contributions believing that the contribution was for a specific purpose other than furthering lyndon h. larouche jr.'s presidential nomination campaign, 3. made loans to the campaign, and 4. had contributed to a number of larouche's interests, while making all checks payable to ldc.''
the auditors had recommended that larouche be found ineligible for matching funds, but the fec legal staff had said ``patent irregularities indicated by the survey results do not justify an unfavorable eligibility report.''
instead of the usual five-day approval period, a review period of 25 days will be allowed in which the fec staff will check for irregularities in the checks he submits to be matched
in addition any checks written out simply to ldc, or those with memo notations ``indicating lack of donative intent'' will not be matched, the commission said
to be certified for matching funds, a candidate must raise $100,000 across 20 states in individual contributions of $250 or less. after becoming eligible, the candidates can receive matching funds for each contribution of $250 or less that they raise privately
larouche is on trial in boston, charged with conspiracy to obstruct a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud and other irregularities in his 1984 campaign
president reagan on thursday lauded a trend toward ``free-market principles'' in education that provide incentives for teachers who achieve superior performance
joining education secretary william j. bennett in a visit to oakton high school just outside washington, reagan said recent tours of this sort ``have strengthened my confidence in our country's future.''
but the president said much work still lies ahead if the nation is to bring about the sort of educational reforms called for in a 1983 government report, ``a nation at risk.''
the president said he expects a status report on american education, which he is to receive next month from bennett, to ``tell us what things we still must do'' as well as what progress has been made
he also said that interest in teaching has increased in recent years, partly because ``we've begun to introduce free-market principles like incentivies and accountability to education.''
he praised fairfax county, in which vienna is located, for initiating a plan in which ``career ladders, performance-based pay and other initiatives help to keep good teachers in the profession.''
but reagan said no improvements in the caliber of instruction or the quality of teachers will be helpful ``if a school has a drug problem.''
if students are using drugs, then no education reform can work,'' the president told several hundred students and teachers in the school auditorium
reagan made several light-hearted references to his boyhood school days, saying he wasn't a particularly good student, and telling how he'd been called to the principal's office once. ``it wasn't an invitation,'' he quipped
when a student asked reagan whether he could attend the seniors' high school graduation june 15, he smiled broadly and said he didn't know if he could make it
some people think i'm the most powerful man in the world,'' he said, (but) ``every day they hand me a piece of paper that tells me everything i'm going to be doing every 15 minutes.''
a broken drawbridge that stranded hundreds of motorists, some holding parties and others asleep in their cars, was fixed just in time for thursday's morning rush-hour, police said
there are a lot of happy people out there,'' said monroe county sheriff's sgt. lee pinder
the snake creek bridge reopened to traffic at 8:10 a.m. after several gears jammed on the bridge wednesday and locked it in the upright position for more than 15 hours, snarling traffic for 30 miles on u.s. 1, the main highway from miami to key west
every hotel room on both sides of the drawbridge at plantation key was taken, and hundreds of people spent the night in their cars. police said motorists were remarkably patient
there were no arrests, no wrecks, no real problems,'' pinder said
one man who suffered a mild heart attack had to be ferried across snake creek to an ambulance, pinder said
a crane arrived from key west at about 1 a.m. thursday, and two barges were brought in to aid state department of transportation workers who fixed the bridge, said monroe county sgt. scott cockrell
james rocheleau, 25, and his friend george kotval, 23, sat in their car at the front of the line going north
you just have to roll with the punches,'' said rocheleau, who said he served with the marines in beirut, lebanon. ``i got it worse in the marine corps anyway. we'll just sit and wait.''
some florida state university students on spring break had a party at the holiday isle hotel
i had 10 rooms and i rented them all in about 10 minutes,'' said alfrieda bressler, night manager at the chesapeake motel in islamorada. ``it's not unusual for the bridge to get stuck, but it's usually only for an hour or two. this is the worst i've ever seen it.''
in florida city, the highway patrol set up a roadblock to turn back southbound drivers
the snake creek bridge is expected to remain closed to boat traffic for two to three weeks, restricting boat traffic to those small enough to move under the span, pinder said
