the chairman of the house finance subcommittee said wednesday he will write legislation reforming the nation's financial markets without waiting for the reagan administration to resolve disputes among warring regulatory agencies
for the investors of this country, justice delayed is justice denied,'' said rep. edward j. markey, d-mass
at a four-hour hearing of his house energy and commerce subcommittee on finance, markey sharply criticized the creation of an administration working group to coordinate recommendations on what should be done to prevent a recurrence of the oct. 19 stock market crash
the panel, headed by treasury undersecretary george d. gould, has the job of trying to resolve a turf fight among the federal reserve board, securities and exchange commission and the commodity futures trading commission over regulating the various financial markets
president reagan signed an order last friday creating the panel and gave it 60 days to report back to him. his spokesman, marlin fitzwater, warned that the issues ``may not be resolved quickly or without considerable reflection.''
markey, however, complained that the recommendations delivered in janaury by a presidential task force headed by former new jersey sen. nicholas brady should have been enough for the administration to make up its mind
he complained that waiting two more months would make it increasingly difficult to pass legislation this year, adding, ``in my judgment congress must act this year.''
the greatest danger facing our financial system is the safe course of delay,'' he said
gould responded that his panel, which will include representatives of the sec, the federal reserve and the commodities commission, is not conducting another study
we are anxious to create action from this, not simply more discussion,'' he said
markey said his committee, with the help of brady, would proceed on a ``parallel track'' without waiting for gould's group to formulate a position
brady's commission called for giving the federal reserve the power to coordinate regulation of the stock, options and futures markets
the sec, which regulates stocks and options, also wants jurisdiction over stock futures, which currently are overseen by the commodities commission. that agency opposes jurisdictional changes, and the fed has rejected taking on the additional responsibility recommended by brady
markey has called for one regulator over stocks and stock futures, but did not say which agency should get that power
brady, who agreed to help markey write his bill, said he did not agree that the creation of the gould group would unduly delay action and said he did not see why congress and the administration could not work simultaneously
meeting with reporters after the hearing, brady moderated earlier remarks on the urgency for reform
in a line that has become much quoted, brady had compared the markets to a gun and said, ``we are looking down the barrel of the same gun, and it is still loaded.''
but on wednesday, he said, ``i didn't say anybody was going to pull the trigger.'' group,' with 2 grafs to fix that talks began wednesday, sted thursday, and to insert dropped word `aid'</note>
congress and the reagan administration warmly welcomed a nicaraguan cease-fire agreement thursday, and some officials said it could usher in a new era of bipartisan u.s. policymaking on central america
we consider this agreement to be an important step forward,'' said secretary of state george shultz, who added that the truce leaves ``no excuse'' for continued soviet-bloc weapons shipments to the leftist managua government
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said the nicaraguan agreement marks ``a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn country'' and vowed to move ahead before easter on a package of humanitarian aid for the contra rebels
this is a bad day for the cynics,'' said sen. christopher dodd, d-conn., a leading contra opponent. ``a piece of paper has been signed by people who many thought would never be able to sit down face to face.''
but the white house and some in congress also said the accord, while a strong sign of new health for the regional peace process, rests heavily on promises of future moves by both sides that could prove difficult
president reagan, getting into his limousine after speaking to high school students in suburban vienna, va., was asked whether he thought the cease-fire agreement would hold up
i don't know. we're looking carefully at it,'' he replied
there is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and i'm trying to balance those two off,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
we're beginning the process. we need to watch it. we've seen processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. ``this seems like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be hopeful. but i do not want to play down the skepticism side of it either because we are skeptical.''
congressional leaders and the administration began conferring on a new package of aid to the contras on wednesday, and more meetings were scheduled for monday. wright said a vote could come later next week and food, clothing and medicine could begin flowing to the rebels by easter
the cease-fire agreement reached wednesday night in sapoa, nicaragua, calls for ``exclusively humanitarian'' aid for the rebels to be channeled through a ``neutral'' organization, presumably the united nations, the red cross, the organization of american states or some similar group
wright said any aid package would have to conform to that language, and democratic leaders on the issue said that would rule out provisions for future military aid to the rebels
but some republicans insisted that any aid bill include provision for a quick vote in congress on new military aid if the sandinistas fail to live up to promises made in the cease-fire agreement, including amnesty and the release of prisoners
i think it is important to keep in there some speeded-up mechanism for the president and congress to get together in case the peace process fails,'' said sen. dan evans, r-wash., a sponsor of a contra aid package that includes such a guaranteed vote
it's a recognition that there is still lots of skepticism, maybe even suspicion, all the way around,'' evans said. ``people have been at each other's throats, and that's not going to dissipate easily.''
but of such suggestions, wright said: ``i think it would be counterproductive to talk about it ... we don't want to rekindle the war.''
house majority whip tony coelho, d-calif., said compromise on language about future contra aid was possible
we are willing to talk to the republicans about anything, but we are not willing to set up a process that the nicaraguans could interpret as allowing for more military aid,'' coelho said
it looks like there may be a pretty good possibility of congress getting together on something the administration could buy,'' evans said
we haven't had a strong voice for american policy in central america in five years'' because of partisan divisions over the administration's contra policy,'' he said. ``we would finally be sending a clear message.''
for heaven's sake, if the nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, surely republicans and democrats can agree,'' wright said
the promises of quick action on a new aid package for the rebels contrasted sharply with the inaction of recent weeks. the issue had been stalled since the house narrowly defeated a $30 million humanitarian aid package on march 3, and the rebels have been without u.s. assistance since feb. 29
coelho said lawmakers had been intentionally moving slowly on the issue since march 17, when contra leaders called wright's office and said they were optimistic about achieving a cease-fire in the talks that began monday and asked that congress hold back on voting for new aid
the state department's chief spokesman said on wednesday that taiwan has been ``repeatedly'' reminded to stick to a pledge against building nuclear weapons, but he declined to comment on a report the united states pressured the asian nation to stop work on a plutonium processing plant
taiwan halted work on the secret plant, which could have processed plutonium, a key component of nuclear weapons, and shut its largest civilian research reactor at u.s. insistence, the new york times reported
it was not clear whether the planned installation, which could have extracted plutonium from spent reactor fuel, indicated a decision to build a bomb or just an attempt to keep open a nuclear option, according to unnamed officials quoted by newspaper
state department spokesman charles e. redman would neither confirm nor deny the report, but he acknowledged that the united states has expressed concerns to taiwan about the proliferation of nuclear weapons. and his comments suggested that if the united states did indeed use pressure to stop the taiwanese program, the pressure worked
we've repeatedly conveyed the importance that the united states, including both the administration and the congress places on taiwan's adherence to its non-proliferation commitments, and we are confident that taiwan understands this,'' redman said
it is our belief that taiwan is not engaged in activities which are inconsistent with its commitments,'' he said
he noted statements by taiwanese leaders that they have no intention of developing nuclear weapons. also, redman said that taiwan has undertaken obligations of the nuclear non-proliferation treaty, in which countries agree to let international inspectors monitor programs to make sure nuclear material is not being diverted to use in weapons
all nuclear materials on taiwan are subject to safeguards applied by the international atomic energy agency,'' redman said. ``we are not aware of any violation of those safeguards.''
according to officials quoted by the times, the united states learned of the project from col. chang hsien-yi, a top-level informant at a taiwanese research institute who left taiwan a few months ago with the help of the central intelligence agency
chang, deputy director of the nuclear energy research center at the military-run chungshan institute of science and technology, has been missing since january
taiwanese newspaper reports said he might have fled to the united states with documents showing that taiwan planned to make nuclear weapons. his whereabouts is unknown
u.s. officials said the effort to build an installation capable of plutonium extraction violated taiwan's secret commitment to the united states that it would not undertake research to develop atomic weapons, the times reported. manufacture</head>
the du pont co., producer of one-quarter of the chemicals destroying the earth's ozone shield, plans to stop making them because of new research showing decay of the ozone, the company said thursday
the company gave no deadline for ending manufacture of the ``fully halogenated chlorofluorocarbons,'' or cfcs. these non-toxic, non-flammable compounds that du pont helped develop in the 1930s are widely used as refrigeration fluids, cleaning solvents, plastic foam blowing agents and, outside the united states, as aerosol propellants
i don't see it in the near term,'' not for five years, but at the end of such a period policymakers and the chemical industry should know ``how rapidly the transition can take place,'' joe steed, environment manager in du pont's freon products division, said in an interview
our intention is to move as smoothly as possible from these compounds into alternatives,'' steed said
du pont announced in january it had developed a substitute foam blowing agent. also, petroferm inc. has announced a replacement solvent for cfcs, and other chemicals are in the works at several companies
on thursday the company began notifying customers, competitors, employees and members of congress of its new policy
environmentalists were quick with praise, hailing du pont's ``courage'' and ``leadership.''
as recently as march 4, du pont said a proposal from three senators that the company immediately stop making cfcs was ``unwarranted and counterproductive.'' the senators _ robert stafford, r-vt.; max baucus, d-mont.; and david durenberger, r-minn. _ had written du pont chairman richard e. heckert calling on him to redeem the company's mid-1970s pledge to end cfc production if a threat to health were shown
a march 15 report of scientists convened by the national aeronautics and space administration found a 2.3 percent decline in ozone at mid-latitudes between 1969 and 1986, most probably the result of cfc accumlations high in the atmosphere. that is ``important new information,'' heckert wrote members of the subcommittee on which the three senators serve
i hope it's clear that it's the science of last week we're responding to,'' steed said
heckert's letter said the company believes ``the short-term risk to health and the environment from cfcs is negligible'' but ``additional actions should be taken.''
ozone, a pollutant at ground level, at high altitudes blocks ultraviolet rays of the sun that cause skin cancer. the environmental protection agency has estimated that a 1 percent decrease in ozone thickness _ it would be only 3 millimeters thick if it were at sea level _ causes a 2 percent to 3 percent increase in ultraviolet and a 4.8 percent to 7.5 percent increase in the most common skin cancers
last fall in montreal, major producers agreed on a treaty, now signed by 31 nations but ratified only by the united states and mexico, agreeing to cut cfc production 20 percent in 1992 and another 30 percent in 1998. the environmental defense fund has estimated that the two cuts could amount to only 35 percent instead of 50 percent if all the exemptions are used
the treaty was accelerated, many experts acknowledge, by a 1985 finding that over antarctica, ozone declines sharply each spring _ by 50 percent last year
du pont plans ``to urge all nations to treat the new scientific information seriously, accelerate ratification of the montreal protocol, and then immediately initiate the protocol's assessment process to consider further global limitations,'' heckert's letter said
richard barnett, chairman of the trade group alliance for a responsible cfc policy, said in a statement president reagan should ``personally contact the heads of government'' of participating countries asking that they ratify the montreal agreement
this is a sterling example of corporate environmental leadership that ought to be emulated worldwide,'' and shows that ``technology can solve environmental problems,'' in this case by coming up with substitutes, said dan dudek, an economist with the environmental defense fund
about 2.3 billion pounds of cfc compounds are made worldwide each year, with more than 2,000 du pont employees producing about 25 percent from plants in canada, japan, brazil, argentina, mexico, the netherlands and the united states. the company says it gets $600 million annually from cfc sales, about 2 percent of total sales revenue
steed said that ``over the long term, it's our goal'' that jobs making replacement compounds should offset lost cfc jobs
the u.s. plants are in antioch, calif.; louisville, ky.; montague, mich.; corpus christi, texas; and deepwater, n.j. ships</head>
the united states belittled soviet technology for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an invitation this week to see the process before the may 29-june 2 summit meeting in moscow, a senior u.s. official said thursday
during three days of pre-summit talks in washington this week, soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze offered to let the united states participate in an experiment to test the system in april
shevardnadze hailed the system as a technological milestone in missile detection that would help the superpowers achieve their goal of a summit agreement to cut long-range nuclear arsenals
the senior u.s. official said, however, ``we're not interested'' because the system doesn't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise missiles, as the soviets claim
the soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell us more than we already know,'' the official said. ``such technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.''
it could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships, the official said
our people know a great deal about the ideas that the soviets have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official said
when they agreed in principle last december to hold a springtime summit in moscow, president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50 percent
with little progress _ notably on the verification issues _ during shevardnadze's visit to washington for three days this week, neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time
the senior u.s. official said, moreover, that until the negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types of weapons involved, they won't know which ones will be covered in a treaty
another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on such explosive issues as afghanistan, the middle east, central america and human rights warned against expecting ``easy solutions'' to u.s.-soviet problems
the official described the most recent talks as ``grueling,'' notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots
at the white house, spokesman marlin fitzwater sought to dispel suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of reagan's presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on substantive accomplishments
during shevardnadze's talks in washington ``we made enough progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters
during the talks this week both sides ``faced all the tough problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he said
the summit ``will be well prepared; there will be substance to discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' fitzwater said
he added that ``there will be a number of important and substantive and meaningful issues to be resolved and all of those things will occur at the moscow summit. it meets all the criteria that needs to be met.''
i think this summit will be quite productive, well defined, well prepared,'' the spokesman said without citing any specific areas of agreement
six weeks after the precinct caucuses that put iowa in the national spotlight and provided the first test of democratic candidates' strength, democrats here are quietly proceeding with the next step in their delegate-selection process
the conventions in the 99 counties this weekend are the second step in the complex process of choosing 52 of iowa's 58 delegates to the democratic national convention
the field has shifted dramatically since feb. 8, when the much-publicized precinct caucuses were held. rep. richard gephardt, the missouri congressman who won the democratic contest, has gone on to weak showings elsewhere
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis, jesse jackson and tennessee sen. albert gore have surged to the front of the democratic pack
supporters who put gephardt on top last month probably won't flee his sagging candidacy for other democratic candidates in county conventions this weekend, democratic leaders said wednesday
dukakis supporters are making a low-key effort to lure supporters from other camps, but working hard to keep their expectations low
it's informal,'' said harry baxter of burlington. ``i'm sure all of the campaigns are trying to lobby.''
at the precinct caucuses, party activists elected delegates to the county conventions, based on the proportion of support for the various presidential candidates
at the county conventions, delegates will be elected to congressional district conventions later in the spring
despite gephardt's slide, baxter said dukakis backers won't be making a major effort to convince his delegates to switch at the county conventions
other activists agreed, saying backers of gephardt and illinois sen. paul simon, who finished second in the precinct caucuses, will wait to see results in tests in michigan and wisconsin before making a decision
michigan is considered a last-ditch effort for gephardt, and that state's caucuses also are saturday
as long as those candidates remain in the race, it's unlikely their supporters will switch, and other campaigns are avoiding a strident pitch soas not to offend potential future supporters
our county chairs and the people we had in place for the campaign are working, contacting supporters from other camps,'' said dukakis backer tom jochum, a state representative from dubuque. ``if i were a gephardt supporter, i'd be waiting to see what the results are in michigan.''
since iowa's precinct caucuses, former arizona gov. bruce babbitt and gary hart have formally dropped from the race. few delegates are at stake there as hart got less than 1 percent while babbitt got 6 percent in the caucuses
people are going to wait to see what happens,'' said iowa democratic party spokesman phil roeder. ``the only people who are going to move are the babbitt people. the gephardt people are going to wait.''
caucus-goers selected 15,000 delegates to the county conventions and 30,000 alternates. they will elect 3,001 delegates to the six congressional district conventions may 14. those delegates will pick 52 of the state's 58 national delegates
the state has six ``super'' delegates, who are elected officials and party leaders. drive</head>
the kremlin laid out an 8-year plan thursday night to pacify a caucasus region shaken by ethnic strife. at the same time, army helicopters were reported circling over the armenian capital to prevent further unrest
the carrot-and-stick approach seemed aimed at cooling feelings inflamed by a noisy armenian campaign to annex the region of nagorno-karabakh from neighboring azerbaijan and to warn armenian activists to end their protests
activists have said specifically that government efforts to improve poor economic and social conditions of armenians in the caucasus mountain region near the soviet border with iran would not meet their demands
armenian newspaper editor regyen sarkisyan said yerevan, capital of armenia and scene of mass pro-annexation demonstrations in february, was being patrolled by red army helicopters and soldiers. he said no violence was reported
sarkisyan told the associated press in a telephone interview that most armenians were showing patience in awaiting resolution of the issue
on feb. 28, rioting broke out in sumgait, azerbaijan, and officials said 32 people were killed
nagorno-karabakh, which is smaller than delaware, has a population that is 75 percent armenian but has been a part of azerbaijan since 1923
the presidium of the supreme soviet, the nation's highest government body, rejected as ``intolerable'' wednesday the campaign for annexation of the region, indicating it would not bend to pressure from mass protests
the presidium, meanwhile, ordered ministries to solve ``pressing problems of the economic, social and cultural development'' of the region. the ruling communist party politburo made public details of their proposals thursday
the plan for 1988-95 calls for stepping up the pace of construction of schools, hospitals, apartments and roads in the region and for increasing the publication of armenian literature
work will also be completed to ensure a steady reception of the national television program, as well as ... telecasts of armenian and azerbaijani television,'' the officia tass news agency said in a report on the politburo meeting
the plan calls for increasing by 50 percent the industrial output of the region
the plan approved by the politburo was formulated by the central committee, the communist party's policy-making body, and the government council of ministers, tass said
it said the politburo deemed it ``essential to resolutely discourage the slightest manifestations of nationalism or disrespect for national sentiments of members of various ethnic groups.''
last week, a prominent soviet journalist writing in the moscow news weekly said residents of nagorno-karabakh suffer cultural and economic disadvantages
karen khachaturov said people there have difficulty getting books in their native language and officials have not made good on pledges to build a sports complex and children's institutions
moscow dissident valery senderov said thursday that a correspondent for an unofficial human rights journal called from yerevan to say soviet army helicopters were patrolling the city, but no widespread disorder was reported
sarkisyan, a senior editor of the armenian communist party newspaper kommunist, confirmed the helicopter report and added that soldiers were deployed around yerevan to ensure order
activists in yerevan had called for another show of support for the annexation drive with demonstrations and strikes beginning saturday, when a group of activists and officials plans to meet to discuss a future course of action
sarkisyan says it is his personal belief that nagorno-karabakh should be united with armenia. he said he does not expect a large turnout at the demonstrations or widespread participation in the strikes called for by activists
moscow-based dissidents say they've been told thousands plan to take to the streets
the presidium did not directly address the question of annexation. last month's mass protests in yerevan subsided after soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev appealed on feb. 26 for calm and promised a party review of the annexation question
demonstrations were held again in yerevan this week after a report in the communist party daily pravda said the annexation drive had a ``clear anti-socialist spirit.'' activists said 7,000 people took part in a protest march monday
