a former nuclear technician who claimed he revealed israel's atomic secrets for the good of humanity was convicted thursday of espionage and treason and could be sentenced to 20 years in prison
mordechai vanunu, 34, was found guilty by a three-judge panel after a trial that had been closed to the public since it began in september. his lawyer said the vanunu would appeal the verdict to israel's supreme court
mordechai is very disappointed,'' said defense attorney avigdor feldman. ``the court decided that he was a traitor, and he had hoped to be seen differently. but he is not broken. he is looking ahead to the appeal.''
the conviction carries a maximum sentence of death. however, prosecutor uzi chasson said he would ask the court for a sentence of life imprisonment, which in israel is limited to 20 years. sentencing is set for sunday
vanunu, who worked nine years at the nuclear facility in dimona, was charged for revealing details of israel's atomic capacity to the sunday times of london in october 1986
the newspaper said vanunu's information showed israel had stockpiled the world's sixth-largest nuclear arsenal
israel never has responded directly to allegations of its nuclear capacity, saying only it would not be the first country to introduce such weapons into the middle east
vanunu has insisted he made his revelations to alert the middle east and the world to the dangers of nuclear weapons. the state argued he intended to harm israel's security
he was kept under heavy security during the trial, which was closed to the public because authorities feared an open hearing would harm state security
vanunu has been held in near isolation for the last 18 months and has been permitted to see only his attorney and family
the precautions were taken after vanunu managed to flash a message to reporters at a pre-trial appearance by scribbling it on the palm of his hand. in the message he said he had been kidnapped in rome, presumably by israeli agents, and brought to israel for trial
vanunu was fired from the dimona nuclear center in 1985 and went to australia, where he became acquainted with a priest and converted to christianity
he later traveled to london, but disappeared in october 1986, just days before the sunday times published his revelations. israeli officials acknowledged several weeks later he was in custody in israel
details of vanunu's journey back to israel were revealed by his brother, meir vanunu, who said vanunu was lured from london to rome by an american woman named cindy, who promised him sex. in rome, he was abducted by israeli agents and spirited home, meir said
during the trial, feldman argued vanunu did not hurt israel's security because information about israel's nuclear capacity was available in the academic world. he said vanunu had in fact helped state security because allegations of israel's nuclear strength served as a deterrent to arab enemies
legislation pushed by archaeologists to save historic shipwrecks won house committee approval wednesday despite complaints from recreational divers that the bill could block their enjoyment of the undersea landmarks
the bill is designed to clear up the murky legal status of shipwreck jurisdiction by giving states authority over certain downed vessels in state waters, preventing salvage operators from destroying historic remains
the house merchant marine and fisheries committee put aside a house version of the measure and passed 29-10, largely along party lines, a bill sponsored by sen. bill bradley, d-n.j., that the senate passed in december
democrats led by rep. charles e. bennett, d-fla., who has advocated a shipwreck preservation law for a decade, said they agreed with an amendment proposed by rep. norman d. shumway, r-calif., mandating that states make shipwrecks accessible to divers
but bennett and others noted that an amended bill would need senate approval again, and they were afraid the measure would die there as it has in past years. this is the first time the senate has approved a shipwreck bill
don't kill this bill by making it perfect,'' bennett urged. ``i'm afraid it's going to be a better corpse.''
shumway, pointing to vocal opposition from sport diving groups, said the legislation should spell out guarantees for divers
i think this bill can be vastly improved,'' he said
bennett retorted that ``if you don't pass this bill, there won't be any shipwrecks to dive on.'' rep. claudine schneider, r-r.i., who said she is a recreational diver, agreed, joining democrats in defeating the shumway amendment 25-14
bennett said later that he expected easy passage on the house floor. the reagan administration supports the measure
the committee agreed to place in a report that accompanies the bill language stating that it is the intent of congress for states to make shipwrecks accessible to divers
under the legislation, states would have jurisdiction over historic shipwrecks within their three-mile state limits. they would be charged with establishing protective areas, allowing recreational exploration and overseeing public and private salvage efforts
under admiralty laws, discoverers of wrecks can salvage abandoned vessels. those laws are at odds with many state statutes
for 58 hours after a toddler tumbled into an abandoned well, hundreds of rescuers worked together to free her, but now an effort to bring their heroism to television has divided them
two groups _ one mostly volunteer rescuers and the other city officials _ are negotiating separately with different tv producers for a movie of the story that captured the nation's attention as it unfolded live on television
both groups are awaiting the endorsement of chip and cissy mcclure, whose 23-month-old daughter jessica became stuck in a 22-foot-deep well for 58 hours in october
one volunteer rescuer, bruce peeler, said he is remaining neutral in the dispute. but he said he wonders whether the story could be told properly in any case
i am wondering if a unified group got together ... if a really true, accurate picture of what took place could ever be put on the screen,'' said peeler, president of midland's airmaster equipment corp., which contributed drilling materials for the rescue
the effort brought praise and a spotlight to midland, an oil town of 97,400 people in western texas
it was a special event. there was so much effort, and everyone had their own story. maybe it should be kept special like that,'' he said thursday
the jessica mcclure rescuer's association, a group of about 30 volunteers, is committed to a movie deal with los angeles producer larry spivey, president of highland communications group inc. the group has asked all rescuers to join them
the association's president, kragg robinson, said 33 members have signed a contract that includes an initial $200,000, plus future payments, to be divided among the membership
the other group, the mcclure rescue association, has narrowed its selection to an unidentified producer but has not signed any commitments. the association, comprising 11 municipal officials including police chief richard czech, fire chief james roberts and paramedic robert o'donnell, wants nothing to do with spivey
we found that he was going around to individual members of our association offering each member side deals that the others didn't know about,'' said martin allday, a lawyer representing the group
spivey says everyone was offered the same deal _ a chance to consult in the production or to act in it
either group or neither group could end up actually making a film. spivey still needs a commitment from a network for his project
my advice to anyone is if they have not signed with the producer to not do so until the mcclures say who they want the movie to be made by,'' said allday
the mcclures have said they don't want to profit by their daughter's story, but do not want to stand in the way of the story being told
peeler said thursday he is concerned that the group of municipal workers will not allow others to help negotiate a movie deal
he said he and other neutral volunteers are working to bring the groups together ``so that the same type of unity and spirit as depicted last october can return.''
i'm sad about this problem,'' he said. ``my concern is that there were several hundred people out there and it is not right that maybe the lady that brought us hamburgers at three in the morning, or the guy who brought the sanitary privvies down _ how do you say they should not be in the movie, too?'' south of lebanon; makes it abu nidal throughout to conform to style; subs last two grafs, wednesday's attack ... updating casualty figures</note>
israeli jets bombed palestinian targets on the outskirts of sidon on thursday for the second straight day, hitting a base of the notorious abu nidal guerrilla faction
police said nine people were killed and five wounded in the raid, the third this week near the port city 25 miles south of beirut
police said most of the casualties were members of abu nidal's fatah-revolutionary council, and the group issued a statement pledging ``merciless retaliation.''
a police spokesman described the attack as ``very fierce.'' he said six israeli warplanes dropped 30 bombs in six sorties within 55 minutes
prime minister salim hoss instructed lebanon's u.n. ambassador, rashid fakhoury, to complain to the world body about the attacks, state radio said
but lebanon did not ask for a security council meeting on the issue, it said
the police official, who spoke on condition of anonymity in keeping with standing regulations, said the main target was abu nidal's guerrilla base, but the jets also hit a position of the marxist democratic front for the liberation of palestine
the israelis plowed the olive groves where the stricken bases are,'' he added
the bases were engulfed by smoke and dust as ambulances arrived to evacuate casualties
the police spokesman said abu nidal's guerrillas cordoned off the bases in the villages of bekasta, majdelyoun, salhiyeh and abra on the southern and eastern edges of sidon
the jets dropped scarlet balloons to deflect heat-seeking missiles. the guerrillas fired at the roaring jets with soviet-made anti-aircraft guns. no hits were reported
let the enemy wait for coming blows of our revolutionary fighters,'' said a statement issued by the fatah-revolutionary council. ``we shall strike doubly in merciless retaliation.''
abu nidal _ real name sabri al-banna _ broke from yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization in 1974. he has since claimed attacks against a series of civilian targets around the world
the elusive terrorist mastermind tops wanted lists in the united states and europe. his whereabouts are not known, altough recent reports said he has been shuttling between libya and algeria
his group also vowed revenge after wednesday's strike, saying in a statement it would ``severely strike back against the zionist enemy's arrogance and barbarism ... at the right time and place.''
wednesday's attack targeted bases of the abu nidal and the democratic front for the liberation of palestine, a plo faction headed by nayef hawatmeh. police said eight people were killed and 15 wounded in the attacks
in all, 48 people have been killed and 63 wounded in five israeli air raids this year, by lebanese police count
clutching a feline named pole cat, mellissa l. sanders climbed into the bucket of a hook-and-ladder fire truck and returned to earth thursday after a record 517 days sitting atop a 43-foot pole
my knees are wobbly but i feel great,'' said miss sanders, who was embraced by her mother, mauri rose sanders. ``without the cat, i would never have made it.''
miss sanders, 19, broke the world record feb. 25 when she overtook the 488-day mark set by mark sutton of victoria, british columbia. she now is in the guinness world book of records
her fiance, keith seal, 25, of monterey, calif., greeted her on the ground. they met after seal read an article about her effort to raise money for cancer research and telephoned her. they announced their engagement in august, before meeting
i've been waiting a year for this,'' he said
about 1,000 people gathered to watch miss sanders' descent from the shack she called home for 1{ years. some handed her bouquets, others made contributions for her cancer fund-raising efforts
all this doesn't seem real,'' said miss sanders' mother, who herself set a record of 211 days atop a pole in 1959. ``we want her back with us, but honestly it seems like only yesterday that she went up there.''
miss sanders said her first activity would be to ``drive around town, then take a good long walk.''
she had said she was proud to have raised $10,000 for cancer research but had hoped to climb down with $100,000. miss sanders' sister, rebecca, has cancer and has been in remission for four years
i'm sure she'll look back on this with fond memories,'' said miss sanders' aunt tanya bowls. ``maybe she saved a life by doing this. and that's about all you can ask for.''
firefighters were on hand to make sure miss sanders made it safely to the ground from the three-story shack
she's going to look up and be lonely when she passes by here next,'' said perry township fire chief david betzner. ``it's been her home and when you take someone out of their home _ no matter how much they want to go _ they're going to look back with longing.''
miss sanders' 6-by-7-by-9-foot shack was equipped with a plastic kiddie pool, television and a telephone that resulted in regular $300 phone bills. for company she had her cat, pole cat
before coming down, miss sanders admitted, ``there were some real sad times, times that were real hard.''
but i always knew i would make it, even when i was scared or going through hard times,'' said the tucson, ariz., native, who rode out 70 mph winds during a major snowstorm in february
seal first contacted miss sanders in november 1986. they communicated, but did not meet face-to-face until november 1987
now that she's getting down we have to start dating,'' said seal. ``i mean we're already engaged and we haven't even gone on a date.'' ruling</head>
supporters of soviet jews tested a new supreme court ruling wednesday that knocked down rules banning peaceful demonstrations within 500 feet of foreign embassies in washington
the dozen demonstrators, accompanied for a time by sens. frank lautenberg, d-n.j., and dennis deconcini, d-ariz., gave speeches on the sidewalk in front of the soviet embassy. then seven of them sat down on the sidewalk, prayed and sang. some taunted soviet officials as they moved freely in and out of the embassy gate
the police, whose numbers rivaled those of the demonstrators, did nothing to impede the protest. they quietly ensured that the driveway and embassy gate remained clear and they steered pedestrians through the maze of protesters and the accompanying phalanx of reporters and photographers. police made no move to arrest anyone
in fact, they stopped traffic on busy 16th street so the demonstrators could move back and forth to the embassy
they can't block the driveway,'' said sgt. gary nelson of the district of columbia police. ``they can't block free passage of the sidewalk.''
rabbi avi weiss of new york, the chairman of the student struggle for soviet jewry, was a leader of wednesday's demonstration. he has been arrested several times for violating the limits on protests near the soviet embassy
there are those who say the (supreme court) ruling takes away the dramatic tool of arrest,'' weiss said before the demonstration began. but he warned, ``if the necessity arises that we'll have to sit peacefully in front of the gates, then that's something i'd be willing to do.''
in tuesday's supreme court ruling, justice sandra day o'connor, writing for the court, said police may disperse groups of three or more congregating near embassies when they ``reasonably believe that a threat to the security or peace of the embassy is present.'' banning such gatherings ``does not prohibit peaceful congregations,'' she wrote, adding that the ban ``is limited to groups posing a security threat.''
weiss said the court's ruling ``allows a far greater voice for soviet jews specifically at a time when so many have been duped by `glasnost.''' glasnost is the russian word for ``openness.''
he condemned an upcoming trip by commerce secretary c. william verity and some 500 business executives to the soviet union
there cannot be an increase of trade, an increase of loans without a concession on human rights on the other side,'' weiss said
as the demonstration commenced in front of the embassy, a dozen soviet officials sat in the patio on the other side of the gates, enjoying the suddenly springlike weather, chatting amongst themselves and occasionally gazing at the demonstrators
as the protestors sang at one point, a soviet official walked into the front gate, barely suppressing a smile
motorola inc.'s electronics group has agreed to pay the government $16.7 million and to plead guilty to a criminal information accusing it of mischarging for labor and materials on navy satellite and missile contracts, the justice department announced thursday
in documents filed in u.s. district court in phoenix, motorola's government electronics group in scottsdale, ariz., was accused of inflating costs for a component of a navy satellite communications and mischarging $2.5 million in labor, materials and other costs. the money actually was spent on other work, the government said
the defense department, relying on the inflated amounts, paid some $5 million more than it should have on a second contract for the satellite communications system, said the government
motorola, one of the nation's top 50 defense contractors, agreed to plead guilty to three counts of making false statements
the firm said in a statement from motorola headquarters in schaumburg, ill., that ``it is now clear in retrospect'' that the electronics group's ``systems were not adequate to ensure total compliance with applicable laws and regulations.''
the conduct of the employees involved in these programs failed to conform to motorola's own internal standards,'' the statement added. the electronics group ``has greatly expanded its compliance efforts'' with reforms which ``are now an integral part of the way geg does business.''
under the agreement, which still must be approved by a court, the government has agreed not to prosecute the company further on the contracts, but reserves the right to prosecute individuals
the court documents also say the firm mischarged labor costs for work on 10 contracts involving production of target detecting devices for the navy's standard missile
the third count in the criminal information said motorola mischarged labor costs on a contract for the production of targeting detecting devices for the navy's phoenix missile
motorola will pay $16.7 million in criminal fines, restitution and civil penalties. the company already has paid $6.8 million to the defense department
the pleas result from an investigation into labor and materials charging and pricing practices by motorola from 1979 to 1984
parts of the northeast basked in record warmth tuesday, with temperatures in the 60s and 70s, while showers and thunderstorms dampened the north-central states
the showers reached from southern michigan across northern iowa, northeast nebraska, eastern south dakota and minnesota. rain also fell from the lower great lakes across east-central new york and along the northern pacific coast
advisories warned of snow and blowing snow across the northern mountains of colorado. winds gusted to 55 mph at pueblo, colo., and 58 mph at cheyenne, wyo
balmy weather held sway across sections of the northeast. record highs included 66 at bridgeport, conn., 72 at newark, n.j., 75 at new york, and 76 in philadelphia
by contrast, klamath falls, ore., had a record low temperature of 19 degrees
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 0.77 inch at boothville, la., 0.60 inch at quillayute, wash., 0.55 inch at astoria, ore., and 0.47 inch at minot, n.d
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 26 degrees at yellowstone, wyo., to 90 degrees at palm springs, calif. the morning low was 4 degrees at yellowstone
friday's forecast called for rain along the northern pacific coast; snow scattered over northeast minnesota, becoming rain over the remainder of eastern minnesota, wisconsin and upper michigan as well as from new york across central and southern new england, and showers and occasional thunderstorms from northeast illinois across lower michigan, the ohio valley, the tennessee valley, and the central gulf coast
temperatures were expected to climb into the 30s and 40s in northern new england, upper michigan, northern wisconsin, the upper mississippi valley, the northern plains and the upper missouri valley; into the 70s from the central atlantic coast across georgia, alabama and the florida panhandle, the central gulf coast, much of texas, and northern california, into the 80s over the florida peninsula, and southern texas; into the 80s to low 90s across southern california and the desert southwest, and the 50s and 60s elsewhere. moreno ...'</note>
the guns were silent thursday, the first day of an agreement between the government and contra rebels that nicaraguans pray will bring peace for the first time since 1981. one man called it a miracle
during three days of negotiations that resulted in agreement wednesday night, both sides had said it was the last chance for peace in nicaragua. the formal, 60-day cease-fire is to begin april 1, but they agreed to extend a truce declared for the talks
virgilio godoy, president of the opposition independent liberal party, said thursday: ``i believe that the agreement is a hope. .. . it is not a question of saying now who won and who lost in the agreement, but that nicaragua and thousands of mothers who have sons in the war won.''
alonso moreno, who owns a shoe store and has three nephews in the army, said: ``this is the most important thing that has occcured since 1979 when the somoza dictatorship was overthrown.''
in a broadcast thursday, the rebel radio liberacion said, ``the (nicaraguan) resistance has taken an initial step to end the hostilities in nicaragua, a very significant step.''
el nuevo diario, a pro-government newspaper, asked a question in its banner headline: ``cease fire! peace explodes?''
enrique bolanos, president of the private enterprise council and staunch government critic, called the pact ``a miracle,'' and added: ``perhaps the sandinista front will finally comply with its word.''
during the negotiations at sapoa, on the costa rican border 90 miles south of managua, president daniel ortega made a suprise visit and said it was time ``to bury once and for all the military confrontation.''
rebel leader alfredo cesar told journalists at the meeting: ``it is not just a chance to achieve peace and harmony, but the only chance.''
leaders of the sandinistas and the u.s.-sponsored contras stood side-by-side on a makeshift dais wednesday night in sapoa, sang the national anthem together and signed the cease-fire
during the three days, both sides retreated from hard positions, especially the sandinistas, who stand to gain the most from an agreement that would virtually end the insurgency
the contras agreed not to accept military aid and to receive non-lethal supplies exclusively from neutral organizations. the reagan administration, which has financed the rebels since they began fighting in late 1981, has been seeking congressional approval of more funds
provisions of the agreement meet requirements of the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by all five central american presidents _ ending the fighting, granting political amnesty and restoring democratic freedoms
opponents of the sandinistas say they promised democracy when overthrew rightist president anastasio somoza in july 1979, but instead established a marxist regime
although the cease-fire does not begin officially until april 1, both sides said they would continue the battlefield truce they declared on monday, the first day of negotiations
beginning monday, also in sapoa, negotiators will draw the lines of areas to which rebels will go during the first two weeks of the official cease-fire
nothing is said in the agreement about the contras laying down their weapons, so that may be another subject taken up in next week's meetings. in past negotiations, the rebels insisted on keeping their weapons until provisions of any accord were carried out
also not mentioned is a reduction of the 80,000-member regular armed forces, largest in central america. the government claims to have 300,000 people under arms, including army, reserves and civilian militia
gradual amnesty is provided for nicaragua's 3,300 political prisoners, beginning sunday. the deal also guarantees ``unrestricted freedom of expression,'' demanded by the rebels, and permits all exiles to return home
with verification that the contras have moved into the truce zones, they can send up to eight delegates to participate in national talks now under way in nicaragua as part of the regional peace plan, the agreement says
the sandinistas agreed that the ``issues related to military service will be dealt with.'' contra negotiators had insisted forced military service be ended
ortega's government granted a rebel request that compliance with the agreement be verified by a commission formed by cardinal miguel obando y bravo and the secretary-general of the organization of american states, joao baena soares
both were witnesses to the talks and it was baena soares who read the final document aloud. obando y bravo had mediated previous negotiations outside the coutnry
richard gephardt, pressing on with his hard-line trade stance, on thursday denied statements from aides that he would shut down his campaign for the 1988 democratic presidential nomination if he does not win saturday's michigan caucuses
amid turmoil over reports that michigan was a do-or-die state for him, gephardt delivered a speech here and denounced a ``dogmatic and outdated'' free trade theology that has cost the nation jobs
gephardt brushed aside questions about the future of his campaign, but aides spoke privately of a decision hinging on the michigan caucus outcome
plans are in motion for the missouri congressman to file for re-election to his house seat by the tuesday deadline, said the aides, if michigan does not give him his first victory since the south dakota primary on feb. 23
that's right. he will be out if doesn't win in michigan,'' said a campaign aide who would not be quoted by name
asked if that aide's comment was accurate, gephardt told reporters:
no. i'm running for president and i've doing very well here in michigan. ... i'm going to win in michigan. i'm going to continue and do well.''
my mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time. that's what i'm trying to do,'' he added. ``rather than trying to guess all the different hypotheticals of what might happen, i just think we have to be patient, wait to see the outcome and then decide what other steps should be taken.''
gephardt aides said publicly that nothing has changed in the past 48 hours, that it has been understood since super tuesday that gephardt would end his race if he does not win here. the candidate's wife put it this way on thursday:
i think dick has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race, because at some point if you don't do well here, it becomes difficult to raise money,''' said jane gephardt in an interview with wtvb radio. ``dick's message will be very popular in the industrial states, but if we don't do well here, we will not be able to continue.''
gephardt is running third in the polls in michigan, behind massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and jesse jackson. later thursday, gephardt mimicked dukakis' claim of turning around the massachusetts economy, adapting it to his campaign by saying ``this saturday we're going to have a miracle in michigan _ the michigan miracle.''
tuesday is the deadline for gephardt to file for re-election for his house seat. a meeting has been scheduled this weekend for the democrats who have filed for the seat
one reason for the withdrawal _ and the congressional race _ would be to take care of any debts left over from the presidential bid
only as rep. gephardt can he raise the money to pay off the debts'' from the presidential campaign, one aide said
but gephardt spokesman mark johnson denied the campaign had a big debt and said that is not a factor
one of gephardt's problems was inadvertantly emphasized by the presence of united auto workers president owen bieber at gephardt's news conference
the uaw has not endorsed any candidate, and bieber refused to say he would vote for gephardt in the caucuses. union backing would be a major boost to a candidate in the low-turnout caucus process, but particularly for gephardt, whose trade policies have had strong uaw backing
i come here today because i want to pay my respects to rep. gephardt and the respects of my union to a person who has fought very hard to bring about fair trade,'' bieber said
gephardt gave a lengthy speech to the detroit economic club, trying to explain again his trade positions and the reasons his ideas have encountered such resistance
we will not open markets abroad until we first open minds here at home,'' the missouri congressman said, adding ``the free market is not sacred.''
he mentioned only one opponent by name, chiding dukakis for now supporting trade legislation that he earlier opposed
i welcome converts,'' gephardt said. ``but we need more than a political tactic _ we need a real policy commitment.''
gephardt laid out in his speech why he thought his trade legislation has been denounced so strongly
the powerful voices ... are dogmatic and outdated,'' he said.``they see things, not as they are, but as they wish them to be.''
`many of our trading partners are using our outdated assumptions _ our theology _ to take advantage of us,'' he said
and gephardt rejected the allegation that his trade policies are somehow racist
those of us who are calling for more realistic trade polices are accused of japanese-bashing,'' he said. ``the issue here is not nationality, but the rationality of our trading arrangements.''
