angry unionized employees of eastern airlines and supporters from other labor organizations rallied outside the capitol on wednesday in an effort to bring attention to their disputes with the carrier
the demonstrators, estimated at 1,200 by their leaders, heard speeches from several union leaders and from sen. tom harkin, d-iowa
i want airline pilots who belong to strong unions, so if they know they have unsafe conditions or unsafe airplanes, they can park that airplane and know they still have their jobs,'' harkin told the crowd
some eastern pilots have complained that they have been pressured by company officials to fly aircraft that they believe need repairs. eastern officials have said they would never allow unsafe planes to fly
unions at eastern have been battling the airline on a number of issues in recent years, aiming much of their fire at frank lorenzo, the chief executive of the miami-based carrier. lorenzo has been trying to reduce costs at the financially ailing airline, but the unions say his goal is to reduce the power of labor
here are some comments thursday by candidates for the presidency:

richard gephardt, asked if he would drop out of the presidential race if he loses michigan: ``no. i'm running for president and i'm doing very well here in michigan. .... my mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time. that's what i'm trying to do.''

paul simon, speculating he will pick up supporters if gephardt withdraws: ``there's no question there are some union leaders who are now supporting dick gephardt who would find paul simon the most attractive of the alternatives.''

michael dukakis, calling for an increase in the minimum wage: ``i don't see how you can support a family on $3.35 an hour.''

jesse jackson, saying a top priority as president would be to stop drugs: ``as president, i will meet with the heads of state where drugs are grown ... and stop the flow of drugs. our borders are exposed to the no. 1 killer of our people.''

albert gore, saying he would have no problem in giving details of more than $1 million in loans taken out by his campaign: ``there's nothing that is in any violation of any laws or regulations and there's no cause for suggesting that there is.''
judge robert h. bork was a victim of ``political muscle and character assassination'' who would have fought excesses by the judiciary had he been seated on the supreme court, attorney general edwin meese iii said thursday
bork's supreme court nomination was turned down 58-42 in the senate on oct. 23 by ``those partisans who would impermissibly seek to reshape the constitution into a vehicle for their own limited political beliefs,'' meese said in remarks prepared for delivery thursday night to the joseph story society, a conservative lawyers' group
a copy of meese's remarks was released at the justice department
no one ... deserves a seat on the u.s. supreme court more than robert h. bork,'' meese said of the appeals court judge who drew strong opposition for his conservative views on the role of the judiciary and other constitutional issues
meese said the forces opposed to bork's nomination ``used political muscle and character assassination to thwart the appointment of a most deserving person.''
bork and legal scholar raoul berger, who were being honored at an awards banquet of the society, have fought unwarranted judicial activism which has been ``advocated by those forces who like to be called `progressive,''' meese said
but ... their version of modern progressivism has passed democracy by, leaving it to today's conservatives to do what yesterday's progressives did: defend democracy,'' the attorney general said
meese cited as an example of judicial activism a federal judge's ruling in kansas city ordering additions to the facilities of local schools, and ``a doubling of the property tax rate to pay for them.''
he also criticized the ruling of a judge in st. louis who decreed a busing scheme for schools and vowed to require higher property taxes to pay for it if the voters failed to do so
meese said judicial activism forecloses opportunities for local expression and leaves ``a drastically reduced scope for the institutions that are representative of citizen views.''
the pattern here is a subtle but dangerous transformation of the constitution, such that it becomes less a plan of government and more an instrument for the regulation of potentially every personal action or policy decision _ regulation that the people themselves become powerless to control,'' meese said
mensa, the nationwide organization of high iqs, is looking for a few good brains
in an attempt to boost enrollment, 43 mensa chapters around the country are using newspaper ads to invite people who think they are among the top 2 percent in intelligence to ``flex those mental muscles'' in a qualifying test
the ad reads: ``if you can score at or above the 98th percentile on a standard iq test, you may be able to join mensa, the society for the highly intelligent.'' the ad then lists how to register for the test, which costs $20
a lot of people haven't got the foggiest notion of what their iq is,'' said philip johnson of yakima, secretary of the central washington chapter
the chapter has about 50 members, and 10 people responded to its newspaper advertising, johnson said
statistically, if you are talking about 2 percent of the population, and assuming yakima is representative, we ought to have 1,000 people in yakima qualify,'' johnson said
don pendley, development officer for american mensa ltd. in new york city, said there are 56,000 members nationally from a pool of about 5 million potential qualifiers
we've been growing about 3 percent per year in the last three years,'' pendley said in a telephone interview. ``growth of 8 to 10 percent per year would make us happy.''
the national headquarters gave $10,000 in february to local chapters to buy advertising. the money was appropriated on a first-come, first-served basis to 43 of the 145 chapters
so far the ads have appeared in washington, d.c.; louisville, ky.; savannah, ga., and st. joseph, mo., she said
in the past, the group has placed ads in specialized magazines, primarily scientific or literary journals, pendley said
obviously people with high iqs read newspapers as much or more than the average joe,'' he said, adding it was too early to judge the response from the newspaper ads
the group was also surprised at the response it got after articles appeared in playboy and reader's digest, pendley said. ``i don't think anybody would qualify those magazines for the superintelligent,'' he said
scoring among the top 2 percent nationally in any standardized iq test is the only requirement for membership, which costs $33 per year, johnson said
it's not uncommon to find people in the top 2 percent in prison,'' he said. ``high iq people tend to frequently be high school dropouts
the only thing mensas have in common other than iq is their diversity,'' said johnson, whose jobs have included police dispatcher, accounting teacher, computer analyst and irrigation canal manager
for the last two years he has operated his own pressure-washer business, which cleans large items like trucks and buildings
in central washington, over half the mensa members work at the federal government's hanford nuclear reservation near richland, he said
with the phasing out of plutonium production there, the local chapter could soon be hurting unless it finds new members, johnson said
mensa, which was founded in england in 1946, is primarily a social organization, promising stimulating activities and conversation, pendley said
the tests measure logical and mathematical reasoning skills and the ability to distinguish relationships between words. ``studying wouldn't help very much,'' pendley said
vice president george bush and gov. michael dukakis run neck-and-neck as favorites for the presidency, while bush outpolls other potential democratic nominees, a cbs news-new york times poll said thursday
among democratic voters alone, dukakis was seen as the candidate with the best chance of beating bush in november, the survey said. bush has a commanding lead in his race for the republican presidential nomination
in a bush-dukakis matchup, 46 percent of all registered voters polled said they favored bush and 45 percent chose dukakis. the margin of error for the survey was plus or minus 3 percentage points
bush polled 51 percent support to 36 percent for sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee and 56 percent to 32 percent for jesse jackson. the poll did not include a matchup of bush vs. rep. richard gephardt of missouri or sen. paul simon of illinois
in a similar poll reported wednesday by abc news and the washington post, dukakis had 50 percent support, bush 45. that survey had a margin of error of plus or minus 4 points, so the spread did not signify a lead
among likely democratic voters in the cbs-times poll, 53 percent said dukakis had the best chance of defeating bush in the general election. twelve percent said jackson, 9 percent gore, 8 percent gephardt and 6 percent simon
when the cbs-times poll asked the same question in a feb. 17-21 poll, far fewer democrats _ 38 percent _ said dukakis has the best chance to beat bush. gephardt was next with 20 percent and jackson had only 5 percent
on super tuesday, however, dukakis and jackson won five states apiece, while gephardt won only his native state. gore also won five states, but in the poll that did not translate into an expectation he was more likely to beat bush
in the democratic primary race, 29 percent of the democratic respondents favored dukakis for the nomination, 22 percent jackson, 14 percent gore, 8 percent gephardt and 6 percent simon. seventeen percent said they didn't know
the support from jackson was up from 13 percent in the february cbs-times poll, while the support for dukakis was up from 21 percent and gore's was up from 8 percent. gephardt previously had 12 percent, simon, 6
the cbs-times poll included telephone interviews of 1,271 randomly chosen registered voters nationwide from saturday through tuesday, of whom 528 were likely democratic primary voters
the sampling error for the democrats was 5 points. loans; no pickup.</note>
sen. albert gore jr.'s presidential campaign confirmed thursday it borrowed more than $1.4 million early this month, putting up collateral that included future federal matching funds and a personal guarantee by the candidate himself
gore, who was questioned about the loans earlier in the day, said he did not object to releasing the details
gore spokesman mark armour said the loans were secured by the campaign's federal matching funds, plus accounts receivable and a personal guarantee totaling $40,000 by gore himself
the campaign issued a statement saying it borrowed $750,000 from sovran-d.c. national bank on march 1, pledging future contributions, federal matching funds and other future income as collateral
the gore campaign also borrowed $400,000 on march 11 from union planters bank in memphis, tenn., secured by a guarantee from gore and future matching funds
the campaign said it borrowed $100,000 from each of three smaller banks in tennessee on march 1, also secured by the candidate's guarantee and future matching funds
armour denied that the banks showed any special favor in granting the loans, stating, ``they were all handled at arm's length through lawyers on both sides.''
there's nothing that is in any violation of any laws or regulations and there's no cause for suggesting that there is,'' gore said at a news conference
the gore campaign previously has acknowledged only that it had established a $1 million line of credit to be used as necessary for television advertising on super tuesday
on thursday, the tennessean newspaper in nashville reported that gore's campaign had put up the proceeds of future fund-raisers and federal matching funds as collateral for almost $1.5 million borrowed from banks about two weeks ago
i have no problem with telling you the amount of the loans and which banks they came from, be glad to,'' gore told reporters
gore said details of the loans would be contained in reports to be filed in the next two or three weeks with the federal election commission ``so if you can wait two or three weeks all of that will be available, but as for now i have no problem with giving you the amount of the loans, the banks et cetera.''
the next fec reporting date is april 20. the loans were taken out after feb. 29 so they did not have to be disclosed march 20
the due date for the gore loans is july 15, three days before the democratic national convention begins in atlanta
the latest gore fec disclosure, made public sunday, covers the period from feb. 1 to feb. 29
it shows that, to date, gore has spent $6 million on his presidential bid, and had $342,964 in cash on hand as of feb. 29
the capaign has taken in $1.5 million this month, armour said
the gore campaign also announced thursday that it has retained media consultant david garth to manage all of gore's media for the critical new york primary on april 19
a 23-year-old investment adviser accused of using $10 million in clients' money to buy himself an art collection, a beach house, fancy cars and other luxuries will probably plead guilty to fraud, his lawyer said thursday
david bloom briefly appeared before a federal magistrate thursday and waived his right to have the case heard by a grand jury. he is charged with mail fraud and securities fraud
although bloom entered an innocent plea at the proceeding, his lawyer, peter morrison, said bloom is expected to plead guilty march 31
prosecutors said bloom, who wasn't licensed as an investment adviser, told clients their funds were invested in the stock market when he actually was pouring the money into private purchases
they included artworks totaling $5.5 million; an $830,000 manhattan apartment; a $1.9 million beach house in east hampton, an aston-martin convertible and mercedes-benz worth a combined $200,000, and home furnishings that cost $800,000
bloom also bought expensive jewelry and deluxe trips to europe and the caribbean for himself, his family and friends, according to the government
he is also accused of falsely telling investors that he managed money for prominent individuals and investors, including the rockefeller family, the sultan of brunei and bill cosby
if found guilty, bloom faces a maximum sentence of five years in prison on each count and a maximum fine of twice the amount lost by investors
bloom was arrested jan. 14. he had begun investing money for friends while at duke university and had 130 clients at the time of his arrest. calderon's arrival, archbishop's meeting with noriega. picks up 9th graf pvs, eleven officers ... with minor editing to conform.</note>
a top opposition leader returned from exile to a hero's welcome thursday and said he will join his countrymen's struggle which he said has ``but one objective _ to get rid of gen. manuel antonio noriega.''
the return of ricardo arias calderon, president of the christian democratic party, came on the fourth day of a nationwide strike aimed at noriega's ouster. the strikers' solidarity seemed unbroken, with panama at a virtual standstill
panama's roman catholic archbishop, marcos g. mcgrath, acknowledged meeting with noriega thursday morning, but denied rumors he was trying to mediate the general's departure
mcgrath told an associated press reporter when stopped outside his home, ``we have met with the general a number of times in the past few months and we will meet with him again soon.''
asked if he was acting as go-between for noriega's exit, mcgrath said, ``no.''
the church's episcopal conference of bishops met wednesday, raising opposition hopes that the bishops would demand noriega's removal. but the closed-door session ended with no communique
there was speculation the bishops remained silent awaiting the outcome of the mcgrath-noriega meeting thursday
a cheering crowd of more than 300 people greeted arias calderon at the airport
arias calderon, who is considered a presidential aspirant in elections scheduled for may 1989, told the crowd: ``i am profoundly moved to be back in my own land. we have but one objective _ to get rid of noriega and build reconciliation and democracy in panama.''
he rejected any talks with the government, as suggested this week by noriega's new, hand-picked civilian chief executive, manuel solis palma
solis palma is simply a voice, the recent voice for noriega. he means absolutely nothing for this country,'' arias calderon said
his flight was delayed more than an hour because the panamanian airline, copa, at first refused to let him board at san jose, costa rica, citing government orders
guillermo cochez, the christian democratic party's vice president, called it an ``attempt to intimidate him, to get him to back down. but it was the government that backed down instead.''
with arias calderon were five christian democratic legislators from venezuela, costa rica and west germany to help ensure his safety. at least 100 journalists covered his arrival
despite virtually unanimous support for the general strike by business and industry, noriega _ head of the 15,000-member defense forces and the power behind the civilian government _ remained defiant
he said his foes at home and in the united states don't ``have the capacity'' to overthrow him
that feeling appeared to be shared by some strike leaders, who said it might take a revolt by fellow officers to remove noriega as military chief
there are growing pockets within the defense forces that are against noriega,'' said jose mulino, an attorney and opposition leader. ``what we don't know is if they will act.''
but in a wednesday night speech, noriega claimed the military was maintaining ``its high moral and patriotic beliefs'' despite a failed barracks coup last week
eleven officers were arrested in that foiled plot. noriega dismissed more than a dozen officers and shifted the assignments of other key personnel
still, the members of the defense forces are due to be paid friday, and opposition leaders said their loyalty to noriega could be tested anew if they don't get their paychecks
panama is out of cash because washington cut off the supply of u.s. dollars, the panamanian national currency, in a bid to drive noriega into exile. the general was indicted in the united states last month on federal cocaine trafficking charges
the government was unable to fully meet a $33 million payroll for 130,000 public employees earlier this month, touching off a series of strikes and massive demonstrations by workers once considered loyal to noriega
the next semi-monthly paychecks for most government employees are due next week, following the military payday, and they could be stirred to renewed fury if the army gets paid and they don't
arias calderon shared second place on a losing presidential ticket in 1984 and has made himself highly visible in the more than nine months of civic demonstrations and protests against noriega
in addition to his party leadership, he is a member of the national civic crusade, a coalition of about 200 business, professional, labor and political groups seeking noriega's removal
arias calderon was denied entry feb. 25 when he sought to return to panama from a business trip to miami. that was the day former president eric arturo delvalle tried to dismiss noriega, but was in turn deposed by the general
the united states still recognizes delvalle, who is in hiding in panama. emergency food relief to panama.</note>
president reagan said thursday the united states is not going to play ``big colossus of the north'' and use military force to get panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega out of power
in a question-and-answer session with high school students in this washington suburb, reagan was asked if he thought it would be necessary to resume u.s. military control in panama to protect the safety of the canal zone
no, we're going to abide by the canal treaty (relinquishing the canal to the panamanians by the turn of the century),'' he replied. ``and we're not going to be the big colossus of the north once again, coming in to ... our smaller neighbors' places of living and business and trying to guide and direct them.''
the president said the panamanians ``have a very difficult problem there. we think that they're moving toward solving it with the reaction of the people to the man that has caused so much of this problem.''
reagan said the united states wants ``to be of help in any way we can, and so we've helped them in that regard in the economic restraints that we've put down there so that there can be pressure focused on this particular individual.''
but there's no danger of us coming in with our power and muscle and saying, `this is the way it has to be.'''
meanwhile, the office of sen. alfonse d'amato, r-n.y., said that the federal agency for international development will provide emergency food to the people of panama, at least $25,000 worth of food per day to be distributed through caritas, a catholic relief agency
the money for the food would come from the federal disaster relief fund, said ed martin, a d'amato spokesman. he said he did not know how long the aid would continue
aid officials could not immediately be reached for comment. a man answering the phone there late thursday said no one was in the agency's latin bureau. the agency was known to be considering such a move
panama is out of cash because washington cut off the supply of u.s. dollars, the panamanian national currency, in a bid to drive gen. manuel antonio noriega into exile. the general was indicted in the united states last month on federal cocaine trafficking charges
the panamanian government was unable to fully meet a $33 million payroll for 130,000 public employees earlier this month, touching off a series of strikes and massive demonstrations by workers once considered loyal to noriega
democrats who had hoped to succeed rep. richard gephardt faced the prospect thursday of having to bow out amid reports gephardt would abandon his presidential bid and seek re-election to the house
i'm a little upset,'' said state rep. phil barry, a st. louis county democrat considered one of the leading contenders to replace gephardt, the 3rd congressional district representative for six terms
i'm saddened. i guess that's a nice way to put it,'' said barry, who has the endorsement of labor and other groups and has raised about $27,000
six democrats have filed for the seat, and at least two others are considering a bid
a gephardt campaign aide who insisted on anonymity said wednesday that if gephardt did not win the michigan caucuses saturday he probably would announce the end of his campaign monday and file for re-election
gephardt later denied that he was considering such a move
missouri democratic party chairman karen schafer said she thought that if gephardt decided to seek re-election the other candidates would not have much choice but to step aside
it's going to be a big blow to some of them but they all knew when they got in that gephardt could come back,'' mrs. schafer said. ``they're prepared for it.''
barry said he most likely would step aside if gephardt wanted to keep his congressional seat
john temporiti, the first democrat to file for the seat and an active campaigner, was out of his office thursday, his secretary said. temporiti is a lawyer and former chief of staff for st. louis mayor vincent c. schoemehl jr
to be a candidate for his congressional seat, gephardt would have to file with the missouri secretary of state's office by the close of business tuesday
he could file for the house seat and remain in the presidential race but would have to withdraw from the congressional race if he were to win the presidential nomination
other democrats to file are george kerry, gephardt's top st. louis aide; james whitt, a house painter; barbara vires, a retired high school teacher, and ed roche, who has run for congress five times
four republicans have filed, but none was expected to be a serious challenge in the heavily democratic district
here are the key points of the cease-fire agreement reached between nicaragua's sandinista government and the contra rebels and some of the issues that remain unsettled:
settled:
-a 60-day cease-fire begins april 1, with a temporary truce in effect until then
_rebels move into specified zones in nicaragua during the first 15 days of april
_creation of a truce verification commission headed cardinal miguel obando y bravo, nicaragua's roman catholic leader, and the secretary-general of the organization of american states, ambassador joao baena soares
_contras will stop taking military aid from the united states
_contras will be represented in sandinista talks with internal opposition known as the national dialogue and will take part in the electoral process
_amnesty for political prisoners, return of political exiles, release of 1,400 jailed contras and 1,800 former national guardsmen imprisoned since the 1979 sandinista revolution
_government guarantees freedom of expression without restrictions, in accordance with a regional peace plan signed last august by president daniel ortega and the presidents of four other central american countries
unsettled:
_details of a permanent truce. negotiations begin april 6 in managua
_location of the rebel zones. negotiations begin monday in sapoa
_laying down of contra arms
_military conscription. this will be discussed as part of the national dialogue between the sandinistas and the opposition, including the contras
_contra delegates to the national dialogue
_which neutral organizations will channel humanitarian aid to the contras
_precise dates for prisoner releases
the government agreed to free 100 contra prisoners on sunday. half of the remaining 1,300 will be freed after rebels are in specified zones. the other half and the former guardsmen will be freed after a permanent truce is in place. statement by howard's office.</note>
rep. james howard suffered a heart attack thursday and was hospitalized in very critical condition, officials said
howard, 60, chairman of the house public works and transportation committee, collapsed on a maryland golf course near washington at about 10 a.m., his office said
the new jersey democrat was taken to montgomery general hospital in olney, md., where doctors revived him after two hours, hospital spokeswoman linda janzik said
he had suffered a heart attack, which stopped his heart, and he was listed in very critical condition, ms. janzik said
he later was taken by helicopter to the cardiac unit of the washington hospital center, she said
he was breathing on his own,'' ms. janzik said
howard's office said wednesday night he was in ``critical condition'' and under intensive care. his wife, marlene, and daughter, marie, were with him
howard, the victim of two previous heart attacks, collapsed at the manor country club in rockville, md
coleman plecker, a golf pro at the club, told the montgomery (md.) journal that he saw howard collapse. the pro said he ran over and started administering cardiopulmonary resuscitation
two montgomery county firefighters who happened to be golfing at the time then took over resuscitation efforts until a rescue squad arrived, plecker said
if anything could be done for that guy, he was lucky to have those guys right there,'' plecker said
howard was hospitalized for several days in 1984 in an episode doctors attributed to fatigue. he is a heavy cigarette smoker
a former schoolteacher and principal, howard has been in congress since 1965
he gained his congressional seat on the coattails of president johnson's 1964 victory. during the reagan landslide of 1980, howard retained his seat by a margin of only about 2,000 votes over his gop challenger
in 1986, the democrat won re-election with 59 percent of the vote in a largely republican district
he has been chairman of the public works committee since 1981. the panel considers multibillion-dollar highway and water projects update with additional shultz, wright comments; picks up 5th graf pvs bgng, `but the'</note>
congress and the reagan administration warmly welcomed a nicaraguan cease-fire agreement thursday, and some officials said it could usher in a new era of bipartisan u.s. policymaking on central america
we consider this agreement to be an important step forward,'' said secretary of state george shultz, who added that the truce leaves ``no excuse'' for continued soviet-bloc weapons shipments to the leftist managua government
house speaker jim wright, d-texas, said the nicaraguan agreement marks ``a new chapter in the unhappy history of that war-torn country'' and vowed to move ahead before easter on a package of humanitarian aid for the contra rebels
later, appearing on pbs' macneil-lehrer ``newshour,'' shultz indicated the administration might ask congress to include in any humanitarian aid package a provision guaranteeing a speedy vote on a military aid request if the peace process breaks down
i do think there is great merit ... to have in it a mechanism for a fast-track vote,'' shultz said
such a provision, he said, would help ``to have a little strength visible in the picture even though it isn't there.''
but wright, appearing on the same program, suggested he would oppose such a provision
he said the package should include food, clothing and medical assistance for the contras. asked whether the legislation should ensure an early vote on military aid if president reagan asks for it, wright said, ``i want to emphasize positive things, and not anticipate failure.''
sen. christopher dodd, d-conn, a leading contra opponent, said, ``this is a bad day for the cynics. a piece of paper has been signed by people who many thought would never be able to sit down face to face.''
but the white house and some in congress also said the accord, while a strong sign of new health for the regional peace process, rests heavily on promises of future moves by both sides that could prove difficult
reagan, getting into his limousine after speaking to high school students in suburban vienna, va., was asked whether he thought the cease-fire agreement would hold up
i don't know. we're looking carefully at it,'' he replied
there is a lot of room for encouragement here, yes, but there's also a lot of room for skepticism, and i'm trying to balance those two off,'' said white house spokesman marlin fitzwater
we're beginning the process. we need to watch it. we've seen processes like this start before and fail,'' he said. ``this seems like a more concrete step, and there certainly reason to be hopeful. but i do not want to play down the skepticism side of it either because we are skeptical.''
congressional leaders and the administration began conferring on a new package of aid to the contras on wednesday, and more meetings were scheduled for monday. wright said a vote could come later next week and food, clothing and medicine could begin flowing to the rebels by easter
the cease-fire agreement reached wednesday night in sapoa, nicaragua, calls for ``exclusively humanitarian'' aid for the rebels to be channeled through a ``neutral'' organization, presumably the united nations, the red cross, the organization of american states or some similar group
wright said any aid package would have to conform to that language, and democratic leaders on the issue said that would rule out provisions for future military aid to the rebels
but some republicans insisted that any aid bill include provision for a quick vote in congress on new military aid if the sandinistas fail to live up to promises made in the cease-fire agreement, including amnesty and the release of prisoners
i think it is important to keep in there some speeded-up mechanism for the president and congress to get together in case the peace process fails,'' said sen. dan evans, r-wash., a sponsor of a contra aid package that includes such a guaranteed vote
it's a recognition that there is still lots of skepticism, maybe even suspicion, all the way around,'' evans said. ``people have been at each other's throats, and that's not going to dissipate easily.''
but of such suggestions, wright said: ``i think it would be counterproductive to talk about it ... we don't want to rekindle the war.''
house majority whip tony coelho, d-calif., said compromise on language about future contra aid was possible
we are willing to talk to the republicans about anything, but we are not willing to set up a process that the nicaraguans could interpret as allowing for more military aid,'' coelho said
house republican leader robert michel of illinois, in houston for a gop issues conference, said he had discussed with wright on wednesday a $48 million, one-year aid package that provided an expedited vote on further aid in june, although the rules for that vote remained to be worked out
added republican whip trent lott of mississippi: ``the contras are still in the field. they still have got to exist ... in case this thing collapses.''
wright aide wilson morris said terms discussed wednesday before the cease-fire agreement was concluded _ including the $48 million figure and any process for a quick later aid vote _ would have to be reviewed in light of the sandinista-contra accord. ``i think that can be worked out,'' morris said
it looks like there may be a pretty good possibility of congress getting together on something the administration could buy,'' evans said
we haven't had a strong voice for american policy in central america in five years'' because of partisan divisions over the administration's contra policy,'' he said. ``we would finally be sending a clear message.''
for heaven's sake, if the nicaraguans, who have been shooting at each other, can agree, surely republicans and democrats can agree,'' wright said
the promises of quick action on a new aid package for the rebels contrasted sharply with the inaction of recent weeks. the issue had been stalled since the house narrowly defeated a $30 million humanitarian aid package on march 3, and the rebels have been without u.s. assistance since feb. 29
coelho said lawmakers had been intentionally moving slowly on the issue since march 17, when contra leaders called wright's office and said they were optimistic about achieving a cease-fire in the talks that began monday and asked that congress hold back on voting for new aid
speeding through stiff winds and heavy seas early thursday, we closed in on an iranian landing craft that served as mother ship for speedboat attacks on neutral ships in the strait of hormuz
the decks were lashed by 15-foot waves and winds gusting to 50 knots but cmdr paul x. rinn, skipper of this 445-foot guided missile frigate, covered the the 45 miles to the hengham-class landing craft and halted his pursuit 4,600 yards from his quarry
while there was no actual confrontation, not even a radio exchange, the presence of the american warship appeared to distract the landing craft tomb from its mission. u.s. officers said that mission apparently was to serve as a floating base for speedboats that attack ships with machine-gun and rocket grenade fire
he now knows we know where he is. we can come back now and find him any time we want,'' rinn told reporters in a pentagon news pool aboard the roberts
increasingly, warships such as u.s. navy fast frigate no. 88 are closely monitoring the activities of iranian warships in the southern persian gulf
their purpose apparently is to discourage iranian attacks on neutral shipping in the waterway, where iran and iraq have been at war since september 1980
such missions may reflect a subtle but potentially significant shift in navy policy under rear adm. anthony a. less, who took command of the joint task force middle east and its gulf component last month
american officers say there is no change in the ``rules of engagement.'' those permit navy ships to offer ``humanitarian assistance'' to neutral ships in distress that request help but prohibit them from interceding to stop an attack on a ship not flying the stars and stripes
however, with the success of its primary mission to escort convoys of u.s.-flagged kuwaiti tankers through these hazardous waters, the navy may be adopting a more visible role to deter iranian attacks
rinn, a 40-year new yorker who now lives in summerville, s.c., parried questions about any new mission. his instructions concerning iranian activity remain clear, he said: ``do not close (on) him; do not harass him; leave him alone.''
the first sign of a shift in approach comes at a time when iran and iraq have resumed attacks on gulf shipping
iraq uses warplanes to strike shuttle tankers carrying iranian oil through the gulf. tehran retaliates with raids by speedboats and larger vessels on neutral shipping
nearly 500 ships have been damaged since the war began and more than 300 sailors have been killed
after the dash to draw within close range of the iranian craft, rinn said it tried to turn the tables by approaching to within 1,200 yards of the roberts soon after dawn thursday. the american warship abruptly changed course, wheeling on the approaching iranian, and it altered course
the tomb kept to a parallel course as the roberts sailed into the strait of hormuz, the narrow southern gate to the persian gulf, and joined its sister ship jack williams and the frigate uss bagley
they sailed westward into the teeth of a continuing shamal, a gulf storm that blows from the northwest and typically lasts about 24 hours. winds exceeded 25 knots most of the day. seas ran more than 15 feet, rolling the ships on their beams
under clear skies, the roaring winds churned the relatively shallow persian gulf into a white-capped maelstrom. waves crashed over the bows of the warships and their hulls were exposed to view as they hobby-horsed up the hormuz
although routine for the 202 crew members, pursuit of the iranian vessel had considerable minute-by-minute drama. the roberts combat information center, its computer screens aglow like a video arcade, tracked a variety of unidentified air and sea ``contacts'' as the ship headed south
rinn ordered his second gas turbine engine fired up to help drive the ship at up to 26 knots, then varied speed as the tomb became a visible light in the distance
huge waves were illuminated by phosphorescent plankton and jellyfish, glowing like submerged flashlights of green, blue and white
the 4,200-ton roberts rolled as much as 35 degrees during the dash down the gulf, causing equipment not lashed down to clatter across the decks, tipping over chairs in the officers' wardroom and spilling some off-duty sailors from their berths
the seas became so rough that the lookout stationed in a chair on the ship's ``bullnose'' was pulled in for fear he might be washed overboard. confirmation from aid.</note>
president reagan said thursday the united states is not going to play ``big colossus of the north'' and use military force to get panamanian strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega out of power
in a question-and-answer session with high school students in this washington suburb, reagan was asked if he thought it would be necessary to resume u.s. military control in panama to protect the safety of the canal zone
no, we're going to abide by the canal treaty (relinquishing the canal to the panamanians by the turn of the century),'' he replied. ``and we're not going to be the big colossus of the north once again, coming in to ... our smaller neighbors' places of living and business and trying to guide and direct them.''
the president said the panamanians ``have a very difficult problem there. we think that they're moving toward solving it with the reaction of the people to the man that has caused so much of this problem.''
reagan said the united states wants ``to be of help in any way we can, and so we've helped them in that regard in the economic restraints that we've put down there so that there can be pressure focused on this particular individual.''
but there's no danger of us coming in with our power and muscle and saying, `this is the way it has to be.'''
meanwhile, the federal agency for international development has agreed to release $250,000 in emergency funds to buy food for the poor in panama
the food will be purchased in panama if it is available and distributed through caritas, a catholic relief agency said aid spokesman jim kunder
panama is out of cash because washington cut off the supply of u.s. dollars, the panamanian national currency, in a bid to drive gen. manuel antonio noriega into exile. the general was indicted in the united states last month on federal cocaine trafficking charges
the panamanian government was unable to fully meet a $33 million payroll for 130,000 public employees earlier this month, touching off a series of strikes and massive demonstrations by workers once considered loyal to noriega
one of two british soldiers killed by the irish republicn army at a funeral last week was buried thursday with full military honors
cpl. derek wood, 24, of the royal corps of signals was buried next to his mother's grave at st. peter's church, carshalton, near london, where he was christened
army comrades carried his casket, which was draped in the british flag and had wood's army cap resting on it. a lone bugler sounded taps and an army firing party shot off three volleys in the air toward his grave
wood and cpl. david howes, 23, also of the royal corps of signals, were attacked by members of the roman catholic procession when they drove up to the funeral cortege of ira guerrilla kevin brady in west belfast last saturday
an inscription on an unsigned card with a floral spray at wood's funeral read: ``corporals derek wood and david howes died heroes whilst amongst cowards. god bless and rest in peace.''
in scenes that shocked television audiences around the world, members of the enraged crowd were seen to drag the two soldiers from their car, strip them and beat them with iron bars. the two were then taken to a nearby gaelic football ground where ira gunmen shot them to death
fallen financier ivan f. boesky on thursday spent his first full day at a minimum-security prison nicknamed ``club fed,'' where he was sent to serve a three-year sentence for insider trading
boesky's arrival wednesday received more attention than anyone else's since white house aide h.r. haldeman reported to serve time for his part in the watergate scandal, said chuck laroe, the warden's executive assistant
boesky, 51, pleaded guilty to conspiracy to lie to the securities and exchange commission. the earliest he can be released from prison is march 22, 1989
the federal prison camp is situated 150 miles north of los angeles. it is on 44,000 acres of heavily forested land
it has earned a reputation as a country club among prisons because it offers cable television, tennis, weightlifting, boccie, billiards and other activities to inmates
jobs open to boesky include work in the prison's furniture factory, dairy farm or cattle ranch. the once high-flying wall street speculator could also take a clerical job, laroe said. pay ranges from 11 cents to $1.10 an hour
boesky has declined all contact with the news media and signed a statement requesting privacy, laroe said. he cannot conduct business while in prison but can receive visitors for up to 50 hours a month
boesky paid the sec a record $100 million fine in 1986 to settle civil charges of insider trading, the use of confidential information to profit in securities deals. he has cooperated extensively with federal investigators
the prison, designed to hold 450 inmates, houses 630. overcrowding has forced double-bunking, laroe said. trial</head> reorganizes throughout. no pickup.</note>
testimony from a former arizona attorney general that gov. evan mecham broke the law in borrowing $80,000 from a ``protocol fund'' for his auto dealership was likened to a ``nuclear explosion'' by a lawmaker thursday
the lawmaker, republican sen. tony west, said that according to former attorney general jack lasota's analysis, mecham's action constituted a felony punishable by up to five years in prison and a $150,000 fine
lasota testified wednesday that the $80,000 was public money and thus an illegal loan
the testimony from lasota came shortly before the prosecution rested thursday on the second impeachment charge against the first-term republican governor. lasota served under mecham's predecessor, democrat bruce babbitt
we have seen some hand grenades go off here. we have seen some bombshells,'' west told the witness. ``but i think your testimony, if accurate, is either a nuclear explosion or at least devastating.''
why do we not have the proper prosecutorial authorities investigating this?'' demanded west
impeachment charges against mecham include misusing or embezzling public funds through the loan in july from a fund intended to promote the image of arizona
senators, who are sitting as judge and jury, previously heard testimony on a charge that mecham tried to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat by an aide. still to be heard is a charge that mecham concealed a $350,000 campaign loan
mecham is the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades. he also faces a may 17 recall election and an april 21 trial april 21 on felony charges that he concealed the $350,000 loan
the protocol fund was set up with $92,000 raised by mecham's inaugural ball. state law barred its intended use to pay off campaign debts, and an agreement was reached to place it in a fund for promoting the image of arizona
the prosecution has contended the fund was public money, while the defense has contended it was private
mecham's lawyer jerris leonard has said mecham will testify that his car dealership did not need the money and that his only motive was to increase the protocol fund by borrowing from it at higher interest than it was then receiving
as the defense opened its case on the loan thursday, the governor's banker testified he would have given mecham an $80,000 loan with no collateral because he was a trusted customer
roger hagadorn, a valley national bank vice president who said he has done business with mecham, his dealership and his brothers for 20 years, said the mechams had good credit and had never defaulted on a loan
hagadorn said that if he had been asked last summer, he would have given mecham an $80,000 loan without collateral and would have charged him interest of 9.5 or 10 percent. the governor borrowed from the protocol fund at 9 percent
later, during cross-examination hagadorn appeared stunned when prosecutor paul eckstein produced a letter showing that mecham in fact had defaulted on a loan from valley national for $101,905. hagadorn conceded he might have thought twice about granting another loan if he had known
the bank's letter demanding payment was written on the same day that mecham received the $80,000 loan from the protocol fund
earlier, prosecution witness jeffrey colville, who said he has never done business with the governor, said he would have refused the loan based on financial records of mecham pontiac. colville, a developer and mortgage banker, said the company was encumbered by liens for more than the business' appraised value
colville cited liens for $3.7 million and said the most recent appraisal of the business put its value at $3.35 million
leonard suggested that colville did not have the complete records, was misinterpreting the record he did have and didn't know the banking business well enough to give expert testimony. he also suggested the appraisal of mecham pontiac was too low
mecham's former chief of staff, jim colter, has testified he processed the $80,000 loan without checking the financial condition of mecham pontiac
later in the day, mecham's former special assistant, sam steiger, testified he thought the loan was ``stupid politically'' but not illegal. he said he had advised mecham's chief of staff that the funds could not be construed as public funds
the argument i used then was these are not taxes; these are not fees; these are not licenses,'' he said. ``by no stretch of the imagination would be it be possible to construe these were public funds.''
asked whether he thought mecham's loan broke the law, steiger said, ``i thought it was stupid politically, but i at no time considered it would be illegal.''
long-term use of birth-control pills, even by women who began taking them as teen-agers, does not increase the risk of breast cancer, a new study of more than 9,000 women concludes
the findings were reported in friday's journal of the american medical association
previous studies disagreed over whether the pill increases the risk of breast cancer for women through middle age. some researchers have suggested the conflicting conclusions might be the result of a long-term latent effect from early use
but we found no direct human evidence for such a latent effect,'' said dr. bruce stadel, one of the study's authors. stadel was at the national institutes of health when the study was conducted and now is with the food and drug administration in bethesda, md
this was a very, very large study ... and these data are immensely reassuring,'' he said. ``nonetheless, everyone in the field believes additional large studies should be conducted in the 1990s, when the women we interviewed will be in their mid-60s.''
early and prolonged use were defined as using oral contraceptives for at least six years before age 25, according to stadel and his colleagues, who were from the uniformed services university of the health sciences at bethesda, md
researchers collected case histories and interviewed 4,714 women through age 54 who had developed breast cancer, then matched them with a control group of 4,540
we looked at many different facets, and broke the subjects into many different groups to isolate other factors,'' said stadel
but the thing we consistently found is that women who used the pill for a long time, whether they were young when they began ... the relative risks were the same when compared to women who never used the pill when young.''
the study did not examine the effects of short-term use
for women in general, the risk of developing breast cancer during one's lifetime is about one in 10, stadel said. more than 50 million women worldwide are on the pill, he said. soldiers now out. picks up 10th graf pvs, foreign minister ...</note>
honduras filed an ``energetic protest'' with nicaragua over what it said were new incursions this week by 350 nicaraguan troops, the foreign minstry said thursday
ministry spokesman eugenio castro later said the nicaraguan troops had pulled out
nicaragua had denied that its soldiers penetrated honduran territory
castro said honduran air force reconnaissance flights on thursday found there were no longer sandinista troops on the honduran side of the border
the situation at the border apparently is calm,'' he told the associated press by telelphone
a ministry communique earlier thursday said 300 heavily armed sandinista soldiers crossed the border in the san andres de bocay region, scene of fighting last week when nicaraguan troops drove contra rebels back into honduras. the area is about 150 miles east of tegucigalpa
the latest incursion occurred about 8 p.m. tuesday, about the same time as 50 other sandinista soldiers entered honduras near pico espanol, a village in el paraiso province about two miles from the border, the communique said
it did not say if there was any combat
in managua, nicaragua's capital, a defense ministry spokesman was asked about the honduran report. ``that's negative,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity
honduran president jose azcona hoyo declined thursday to discuss the reported incursions.``we continue to act with prudence,'' he said
foreign minister carlos lopez contreras was in guatemala on thursday for a meeting with other central american foreign ministers
the government said last week there were up to 2,000 sandinista troops in honduras and later said all had retreated back to nicaragua
honduran jets raided nicaraguan targets in the bocay region twice last week and azcona said then that he would send more warplanes to attack nicaraguan troops if they did not leave
that incursion and a request for help by azcona hoyo resulted in the emergency deployment of 3,200 u.s. troops to honduras last week
the americans, who are conducting joint training exercises with honduran soldiers, are expected to leave this country early next week, the pentagon said
meanwhile, honduras has asked u.s. ambassador everett briggs for a clarification on reported comments by u.s. defense secretary frank carlucci about the reason american soldiers are in honduras
in a news release late wednesday, lopez contreras said he wanted to know why u.s. authorities were saying the americans were here to protect contra rebels in honduras
these (american) troops that came to honduras were requested by the government of president jose azcona hoyo regarding the threat of incursions from the sandinista army against the national territory ... and not for the principal objective of fortifying or protecting the nicaraguan insurgents who are struggling against the sandinista regime,'' lopez contreras said
he proposed the creation of a peacekeeping force along the border region
briggs refused to meet leaders of seven citizens organizations at the u.s. embassy in tegucigalpa thursday
the leaders, whose groups are united under the umbrella coordinating committee for popular organizations, later met at a plaza where about 200 people had gathered and read a letter protesting u.s. troops in honduras
the letter said the presence of u.s. troops in honduras meant ``that our country has been converted into a battle platform in the central american region.''
iran and iraq fired missiles into each other's capitals thursday and tehran threatened to use chemical bombs in the war unless the united nations punishes iraq for using poison gas
iran said its troops advanced farther into iraq's northeastern kurdistan province, killing or wounding 1,000 iraqi soldiers, in a week-old offensive. iraq denied the claim
shipping executives in the persian gulf said the captain of the 267,589-ton friendship l supertanker reported a fire in the engine room, raising speculation the vessel may have been raided
they said a later report from the ship, which is on charter to iran, reported the fire extinguished and denied there had been an attack
in amman, jordan, iran left an islamic conference after other delegates criticized it for not heeding calls to accept a cease-fire in the war, which began in september 1980, and accused it of instigating bloody riots last year in the holy city of mecca, saudi arabia
dispatches from iraq said 13 people were killed and 68 wounded in two missile explosions in downtown baghdad. iran said four missiles were fired at baghdad
one victim was a woman who was breast-feeding her newborn baby in a hospital bed. the infant survived, the official iraqi news agency reported
nine houses were demolished in the attacks and two other children were among the victims, it said
the iraqis said they launched six long-range missiles at tehran. iran reported 10 civilians killed and 100 wounded, and said the rockets hit two schools, two mosques and two hospitals
iraq has fired 42 missiles into tehran since march 15. iran says it has fired 16 missiles into baghdad and dozens of short-range rockets at other iraqi cities
hashemi rafsanjani, speaker of iran's parliament, said iran would use chemical weapons if no action was taken against iraq
we asked the u.n. to send experts to the halabja region (in northeast iraq) to inspect the effects of the chemical weapons,'' he said on tehran radio
if the international organizations refuse to take any step to punish iraq, we shall not remain idle. we have the technology to produce chemical weapons, and although we have not exploited this yet, we will not remain idle forever.''
he said iran has decided ``to punish the aggressor ourselves,'' renewing warnings that iranian troops along the 733-mile border would launch an all-out offensive
at present we have forces and operational plans all over the battlefront, and should the u.n. security council refuse to take any step towards condemning the aggressor, we shall begin our operation,'' rafsanjani declared
iran has said 5,000 people were killed and 5,000 wounded when iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs on halabja, khormal and dojaila, three kurdish towns captured by the iranians last week
most of iraq's 3.5 million kurds live in the northeast and iran supports them in a struggle for autonomy
western reporters flown to halabja by the iranians earlier this week reported seeing hundreds of dead civilians, unmarked by wounds. they said many had died of asphyxiation, apparently caught unaware in their homes
u.s. state department spokesman charled redman said wednesday in washington that iraq had used chemical weapons, banned under a 1925 geneva agreement, and urged the u.n. security council to protest. he called the iraqi action ``a particularly grave violation.''
turkey's semi-official anatolia news agency said iranian planes thursday inadvertently violated turkish airspace and dropped two bombs over southeastern turkey near the harbur border post, breaking windows but causing no casualties
foreign ministry spokesman inal batu confirmed the area was bombed but said the planes' nationality was not known yet
anatolia said the iranian jets were raiding northern iraq when they strayed over turkey
on tuesday, two iraqi jets violated turkish airspace when they bombed kurdish guerrilla bases in a joint security zone along the border. talks, reax from arias; edits to tighten; picks up 8th graf pvs, during the ...</note>
the guns were silent thursday, the first day of an agreement between the government and contra rebels that nicaraguans pray will bring peace for the first time since 1981. one man called it a miracle
in three days of negotiations that resulted in agreement wednesday night, both sides called it nicaragua's last chance for peace. the formal, 60-day cease-fire is to begin april 1, but they agreed to extend a truce declared for the talks
nicaragua's vice president sergio ramirez, in mexico city to brief mexican president miguel de la madrid on the agreement, told a news conference ``direct negotiation with the united states government is more necessary than ever'' to ensure a truce in nicaragua
the reagan administration rejected previous sandinista calls for direct talks, saying the nicaraguan government and the rebels must negotiate first
now that we have ... a signed document with the contras,'' ramirez said, ``we are disposed to begin direct negotiations with the united states.''
in nicaragua, dozens of women marched to juigalpa on thursday, gathered in the city's main catholic church and ``lighted candles to the virgin mary'' to mark the agreement, a defense ministry official said
he spoke on condition of anonymity
alonso moreno, who owns a shoe store and has three nephews in the army, said: ``this is the most important thing that has occcured since 1979 when the somoza dictatorship was overthrown.''
enrique bolanos, president of the private enterprise council and staunch critic of the government, called the pact ``a miracle.''
in costa rica, president oscar arias said the cease-fire offers ``a new and firm hope that all central americans can live in peace.''
arias won the 1987 nobel peace prize for devising the central american peace agreement that calls for cease-fires in the region's wars
during the negotiations at sapoa, on the costa rican border 90 miles south of managua, president daniel ortega made a suprise visit and said it was time ``to bury once and for all the military confrontation.''
rebel leader alfredo cesar told journalists at the meeting: ``it is not just a chance to achieve peace and harmony, but the only chance.''
leaders of the sandinistas and the u.s.-sponsored contras stood side-by-side on a makeshift dais wednesday night in sapoa, sang the national anthem together and signed the cease-fire
during the three days, both sides retreated from hard positions, especially the sandinistas, who stand to gain the most from an agreement that would virtually end the insurgency
the contras agreed not to accept military aid and to receive non-lethal supplies exclusively from neutral organizations. the reagan administration, which has financed the rebels since they began fighting in late 1981, has been seeking congressional approval of more funds
provisions of the agreement meet requirements of the regional peace plan signed aug. 7 by all five central american presidents _ ending the fighting, granting political amnesty and restoring democratic freedoms
opponents of the sandinistas say the sandinistas promised democracy when they overthrew rightist president anastasio somoza in july 1979, but instead established a marxist regime
although the cease-fire does not begin officially until april 1, both sides said they would continue the battlefield truce they declared on monday, the first day of negotiations
beginning next monday, also in sapoa, negotiators will draw the lines of areas to which rebels will go during the first two weeks of the official cease-fire
nothing is said in the agreement about the contras laying down their weapons, so that may be another subject taken up in next week's meetings. in past negotiations, the rebels insisted on keeping their weapons until provisions of any accord were carried out
also not mentioned is a reduction of the 80,000-member regular armed forces, largest in central america. the government claims to have 300,000 people under arms, including army, reserves and civilian militia
gradual amnesty is provided for nicaragua's 3,300 political prisoners, beginning sunday. the deal also guarantees ``unrestricted freedom of expression,'' demanded by the rebels, and permits all exiles to return home
with verification that the contras have moved into the truce zones, they can send up to eight delegates to participate in national talks now under way in nicaragua as part of the regional peace plan, the agreement says
the sandinistas agreed that the ``issues related to military service will be dealt with.'' contra negotiators had insisted forced military service be ended
ortega's government granted a rebel request that compliance with the agreement be verified by a commission formed by cardinal miguel obando y bravo and the secretary-general of the organization of american states, joao baena soares
both were witnesses to the talks and it was baena soares who read the final document aloud. obando y bravo had mediated previous negotiations outside the country. connecticut</head> being born in connecticut</note>
democrat richard gephardt, who has fallen on hard times since his iowa victory 45 days ago, will quit the presidential race unless he scores an upset victory in michigan this weekend, aides said thursday. george bush, meanwhile, headed for connecticut expecting to pad his huge lead on the gop side
gephardt said he'd made no decision to drop out, declaring, ``my mother always told me to cross one bridge at a time.'' but the scramble was already on to pick up supporters who would be freed if he withdrew
there's no question there are some union leaders who are now supporting dick gephardt who would find paul simon the most attractive of the alternatives,'' said illinois sen. simon at an appearance in kalamazoo
simon, who is in fourth place in the democratic delegate count, just ahead of gephardt, spoke of getting ``back in the ballgame.''
among the republicans, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, wife of bush's main rival, sen. bob dole, said in oshkosh, wis., that her husband now has merely a ``long shot'' chance, but she added, ``he's got the grit and determination needed to keep him in the running.''
she said neither she nor her husband have discussed the possibility that one of them might be bush's running mate for the general election. ``i'm really not seeking to be on the ticket. i'm going 12 hours a day just trying to carry bob's message,'' she said
vice president bush, holding a commanding lead in the battle for republican convention delegates, was traveling to connecticut, saying he was taking nothing for granted in the primary there next tuesday
however, public opinion polls give him a big lead over dole in the state where bush grew up and where his father once served as a u.s. senator
bush said at a news conference that it would be premature to discuss pardons for any of the defendants in the iran-contra affair, and that he did not think fallout from the arms-for-hostages deal would hurt his campaign
if it was going to have an impact, i think it would have before now,'' he said
a cbs-new york times poll suggested thursday night that a general election matchup of bush and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis would be a close race. in the poll, with a 3 percentage-point margin of error, 46 percent picked bush and 45 percent chose dukakis, who did the best of any of the democrats against bush in the poll
dukakis was in los angeles, campaigning in english and spanish
he denounced u.s. support of nicaragua's contra rebels, said he favored a one-year extension in the deadline for illegal aliens to apply for amnesty and said when asked about the possibility of a hispanic running mate, ``tal vez. ... vamos a ver (perhaps. ... we'll see).''
democratic rival jesse jackson campaigned in madison, wis., telling the wisconsin legislature that if he wins the nomination and election, ``as president, i will meet with the heads of state where drugs are grown ... and stop the flow of drugs.''
albert gore jr.'s spokesman said david garth, a well-known media consultant who has previously worked for new york gov. mario cuomo, had been hired to handle the tennessee senator's advertising for the new york primary
gephardt, just a few weeks ago the victor in iowa's caucuses, now lags behind dukakis, jackson, gore and simon in delegates to the national convention. he trails dukakis and jackson in public opinion polls preceding saturday's michigan caucuses
he said thursday in detroit, ``rather than trying to guess all the different hypotheticals of what might happen, i just think we have to be patient, wait to see the outcome and then decide what other steps should be taken.''
still, gephardt's wife jane told a radio interviewer in michigan, ``i think dick has to come in first or a real strong second to remain in the race. ... if we don't do well here, we will not be able to continue.''
the missouri congressman has only until tuesday to file for re-election to his house seat, and one aide, commenting only on condition he not be named, suggested that it was important for the congressman to retain that office in order to raise money. his campaign has been strapped for cash for weeks
money was in the news for several other current and former candidates on thursday:
_gore's campaign confirmed thursday it borrowed more than $1.4 million early this month, putting up collateral that included future matching funds and a personal guarantee by the candidate himself
the move followed a report in the nashville tennessean newspaper about the details of gore's borrowing
_the federal election commission said that gary hart, now that he is no longer a presidential candidate, can use leftover 1988 campaign funds toward retiring his lingering debt of about $1 million from his 1984 race
_the fec agreed to grant federal matching funds to political extremist lyndon larouche's presidential campaign, even though he is standing trial on a charge relating to alleged financial irregularity in his 1984 campaign. larouche is running as a democrat, although the national party has disavowed his candidacy
the democrats, including gephardt, were concentrating on michigan and on wisconsin, which has its primary on april 5
dukakis, who spent the first part of the week trading charges with gephardt on foreign-trade policy, a major issue in a state heavily dependent on u.s. auto sales, was in california but planned to spend all day friday in michigan. the detroit free press endorsed him on thursday
dole's aides said he had no campaign events scheduled thursday
pat robertson, meanwhile, urged 700 supporters in falls church, va. to turn out in force at local republican precinct meetings to select delegates to the state and natonal gop conventions
noting that easter is ten days away, robertson said the press declared his candidacy dead after super tuesday. ``i don't think they are aware of the resurrection,'' he said
in the next few weeks, as these caucuses unfold, we are going to win the majority of delegates in the republican party in virginia,'' predicted robertson, who was beaten soundly by bush in his home state's non-binding primry on march 8. ships</head> regarding space-based weapons systems; picks up 4th graf pvs bgng: the senior ..., editing to tighten.</note>
the united states belittled soviet technology for detecting nuclear missiles aboard ships and snubbed an invitation this week to see the process before the may 29-june 2 summit meeting in moscow, a senior u.s. official said thursday
during three days of pre-summit talks in washington this week, soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze offered to let the united states participate in an experiment to test the system in april
meanwhile, the united states offered some new proposals of its own regarding space-based weapons systems
one was the exemption of spy satellites from treaty restrictions, an idea that the soviets apparently found interesting
we think they're useful to our security,'' a senior administration official said thursday. ``they think they're useful to theirs.''
the other idea was that u.s. and soviet negotiators make a special effort to define space-based testing and deployment
then we could also work on the idea of having confidence-building measures or what we call predictability measures which could reduce the difficulties between the two sides with respect to other types of systems that might be tested or other kinds of devices,'' the official said
details of that proposal have not been settled, but officials said the most likely approach would be to allow only a limited number of space weapons prototypes to be tested in a region of space where they would have little value in an actual missile defense
the two proposals were intended to resolve the contentious battle over the u.s. strategic defense initiative, known also as star wars, which is possibly the biggest obstacle to reaching agreement to cut long-range nuclear weapons
secretary of state george p. shultz said wednesday that the two issues would be negotiated separately but that agreements in the two areas should be ``completed more or less at the same time so the two things move in parallel.'' the united states has long said that the two issues should be handled separately
shevardnadze, meanwhile, said wednesday night that ``of course there is'' a linkage between resolving the defense in space issues and the treaty to reduce long-range strategic weapons
there will be no treaty on the 50 percent reduction in strategic offensive arms if there is no observance of the abm treaty, at least for an agreed period of time,'' shevardnadze said. the soviets, as well as some in congress, say sdi would violate the 1972 anti-ballistic missile treaty
shevardnadze hailed the system to detect nuclear missiles on ships as a technological milestone in missile detection that would help the superpowers achieve their goal of a summit agreement to cut long-range nuclear arsenals
the senior u.s. official said, however, ``we're not interested'' because the system doesn't detect nuclear sea-launched cruise missiles, as the soviets claim
the soviets could not explain how this experiment would tell us more than we already know,'' the official said. ``such technology would not be effective under realistic conditions.''
it could not, for example, tell the difference between nuclear warheads and atomic propulsion systems used on many surface ships, the official said
our people know a great deal about the ideas that the soviets have advanced, and we've looked into it carefully,'' the official said
when they agreed in principle last december to hold a springtime summit in moscow, president reagan and soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev said they wanted to sign an agreement to cut the numbers of long-range nuclear missiles and bombers by 30 percent to 50 percent
with little progress _ notably on the verification issues _ during shevardnadze's visit to washington for three days this week, neither side predicted the agreement would be ready in time
the senior u.s. official said, moreover, that until the negotiators prove they can verify elimination of the various types of weapons involved, they won't know which ones will be covered in a treaty
another official, noting that the two nations also disagree on such explosive issues as afghanistan, the middle east, central america and human rights warned against expecting ``easy solutions'' to u.s.-soviet problems
the official described the most recent talks as ``grueling,'' notably in the 11 hours of discussion on the regional hot spots
at the white house, spokesman marlin fitzwater sought to dispel suggestions that the summit meeting _ in the twilight of reagan's presidency _ would be a ceremonial and symbolic visit short on substantive accomplishments
during shevardnadze's talks in washington ``we made enough progress to keep going and presumably we will make more in the days ahead,'' the spokesman told reporters
during the talks this week both sides ``faced all the tough problems'' and left no confusion about where both sides stand, he said
the summit ``will be well prepared; there will be substance to discuss; there will be good prospects for success,'' fitzwater said
u.s.-soviet talks on the middle east were extended thursday while arabs and israelis continued to delay a response to an american plan for negotiations
vladimir polyakov, a specialist in the soviet foreign ministry, met with assistant secretary of state richard w. murphy despite what u.s. officials described as a fundamental difference in the two superpowers' positions
the soviets are seeking an active role in any peace conference, while secretary of state george p. shultz said wednesday night he did not want any interference in arab-israeli negotiations
it's quite clear the soviet concept of how to go about this is really sharply different from ours,'' shultz told reporters after three days of talks with foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze
israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir also objects to an active soviet role, but king hussein of jordan is seeking soviet participation in the negotiations
shevardnadze left polyakov behind to continue the discussions with murphy and flew home to moscow. u.s. envoy philip c. habib, meanwhile, completed talks in amman with hussein and returned to washington to report to shultz
shultz said that despite having no direct reply from the israelis or arabs to his plan to open negotiations by may 1 he would not give up
we will continue to work with the parties directly involved, and we will continue to try, in every way we can, to find our way to the direct, face-to-face negotiations that we believe are the only way in which you can really resolve these issues,'' he said
now how to get there is difficult, and we will continue to push for and, at the same time, maintain the limitations on the kind of conference we've called for. and, we'll just have to see how that goes.''
shultz said ``nobody seems to be ready to climb on our bandwagon, including the soviet union. on the other hand, everybody wants to keep it rolling, so we'll keep it rolling.''
asked if he planned to return to the middle east, shultz said he had not made a decision. he said his lengthy talks with shevardnadze had made it difficult for him ``to come up for air'' and evaluate reports from the region
shultz presented his plan for negotiations to arab and israeli leaders three weeks ago and asked for a reply by mid-march
i am ready to go to the middle east anytime it seems as though there is even a remote chance of being constructive,'' shultz said. ``i don't have to have a high probability.''
the u.s. plan excludes the palestine liberation organization from proposed negotiations but provides for a joint jordanian-palestinian delegation
meantime thursday, murphy told the house appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations ``it's a tough question but i don't think it's insuperable'' to find a credible palestinian leader to participate without driving israel away from the bargaining table
murphy added that the plo ``remains for palestinians, by and large, the only leadership they accept.'' but he did not say a palestinian participant would necessarily have to be a plo representative
five demonstrators wearing t-shirts reading ``stop u.s. aid to israel'' stood silently against a hearing room wall throughout most of murphy's testimony and left without incident after about an hour
murphy said ``it would be the dangerous to the peace process'' for the united states to reduce its annual payment of $2.2 billion in military and economic aid to israel to protest its handling of palestinian unrest on the occupied west bank and the gaza strip
the state department official said any such aid reduction might be interpreted in arab capitals as a weakening of ties between the united states and israel and might invite a renewal of military assaults against the jewish state
under questioning, murphy said the united states had assurances from ``the highest levels'' in saudi arabia and china that the medium-range missiles that china recently agreed to provide to the saudis contain conventional and not nuclear warheads
the washington post reported in friday's editions that the israeli air force has been conducting unusually intensive low-level bombing practice runs at the same time saudi arabia is digging in its new missiles
the newspaper quoted u.s. intelligence officials as saying that the bombing could be in preparation for a pre-emptive strike against the missiles, as a senior israeli official warned sunday. however, the officials said they had no hard evidence that an israeli strike was imminent
satellite photography and other intelligence have revealed that israel has been flying f-15 fighter bombers in attack profiles and that saudi arabia has been building shelters for its missiles, the post reported
saudi arabia has sent a warning through the united states that it will retaliate with its surviving missiles with a range of up to 1,500 miles if israel tries to bomb its missiles, diplomatic sources told the newspaper. first reference to gardner and to delete extraneous material, picking up 9th graf `gardner declined ...' and inserts 1 graf after 24th graf `under the ...' to add background on pvs raises.</note>
nearly all of charleston's police officers and firefighters called in sick thursday to protest a 2 percent pay raise, then ignored back-to-work orders from a judge and the city council
less than an hour before an emergency council meeting thursday afternoon, kanawha county circuit judge patrick casey issued a temporary injunction ordering firefighters to work immediately and police to report at their next scheduled shift
the missing police officers did not report for the 3 p.m. shift, however, and firefighters also refused to report
we just want an honest living,'' said fire department lt. walt cavender, who was on duty at the city's station no. 1. ``we're going backward in pay.''
the ``blue flu'' in west virginia's capital and largest city began wednesday night when officers began refusing to show up for work
at the 6 a.m. shift change, 16 of 17 uniformed police officers and 42 of 44 firefighters scheduled to report failed to show up
firemen and police officers who were on duty overnight were retained on overtime, giving the fire department a full complement of men, and process servers took return-to-work orders to the absent personnel thursday afternoon, said mayor chuck gardner
gardner declared a state of civil emergency earlier in the day, saying the policemen and firefighters must return because ``the safety of the citizens of charleston is not a bargaining chip.''
police chief ed garnett told an emergency meeting of the city council that only 13 officers, covering all grades, showed up thursday morning, ``most of them supervisors.'' he said only three cars were on patrol thursday morning, with two officers in each car
garnett also told the council members that since wednesday night 68 officers and 42 firemen had called in sick as of 9 a.m
the city budget, approved monday night, includes appropriations for 165 policemen, 147 firefighters and 10 paramedics for the city of 63,000
garnett said the firefighters who were on the job had been there since 8 a.m. wednesday and were tiring quickly
i don't know how long they can stay there,'' he said
the council unanimously suspended the city's sick-leave policy, meaning that any more officers calling in sick would have to have a doctor's excuse to get paid for any additional days absent from work
gardner, facing his first crisis since taking over as mayor four months ago, said it wasn't illegal to call the council into emergency session on less than four hours' notice and suspend sections of the city code. the code requires two days' notice of emergency meetings
no police or firefighters picketed thursday, but about 20 police wives marched in front of city hall and carried signs. passing motorists honked their horns in support and some _ aware that patrols were down _ took the opportunity to run red lights
we have several police officers that qualify for welfare,'' said police wife val lockard
kanawha county sheriff danny jones said his department would provide assistance to the city only ``if there's a murder or something.''
we don't have the manpower to work the city,'' jones said
state police superintendent w.f. donohoe said gardner had asked the governor for state police help. ``we will answer calls on a priority basis to the very best of our ability,'' donohoe said
the police officers believe their 2 percent raise will be eaten up by a higher deductible on their health insurance and an increase in the city's incinerator fee from $30 to $85
it's not easy to raise the incinerator fee. but without a raise in the incinerator fee, we didn't have money to increase salaries,'' said councilwoman maggie mccoy
under the budget approved this week, salaries for uniformed police officers range from $27,673 for a captain with 20 years' experience to $18,589 for a patrol officer with three years' experience
mayoral aide ed esposito said that no raises had been given this year but that police and firefighters had received a 3 percent raise in the 1986-87 fiscal year and raises totaling 8 percent over the past five years
by comparison, at the kanawha county sheriff's department, where deputies have gotten raises totaling 25 percent over the past 3{ years, a deputy with three years' experience will make $21,720 as of july 1, jones said
city firefighters' pay ranges from $27,673 for an assistant fire chief with 20 years' experience to $18,409 for a first-year firefighter
neil kinnock, leader of britain's opposition labor party, will be challenged for the post by veteran leftist tony benn at the party conference in the fall, a labor coalition said wednesday
the campaign group, composed of about 40 leftist party lawmakers, said kinnock's deputy, moderate roy hattersley, will be challenged by leftist eric heffer
the announcement came after a meeting of the party's national executive committee
kinnock, 46, and hattersley are considered not as left wing as benn and heffer
benn, 62, a former cabinet minister, has accused kinnock of watering down socialism after the party's three defeats in nine years by the conservative party of prime minister margaret thatcher
kinnock and hattersley have worked for a united party and cracked down on militants in hopes of making a broader appeal to voters. they say a leadership contest will distract the party from opposing the government
kinnock and hattersley denounced the challenge in a joint statement as ``futile and selfish'' and predicted ``massive defeat'' for benn and heffer
benn told reporters: ``democracy is about choice.''
heffer said: ``the time has come for a crusade for socialism. the working people of this country are getting a worse and worse deal.''
a state appeals court wednesday rejected as too low a $3,500 damage award to a salesman left with a perpetual frown after an auto accident
such scars are of a greater consequence to a 24-year-old single man who has chosen a career in sales than that amount reflects,'' a two-judge panel ruled in ordering a new trial on the issue of damages for robert tronolone
tronolone was a passenger in a car that struck a utility pole in bridgewater township
a jury found the driver, peter palmer, negligent and awarded tronolone $750, but the judge at the trial found it inadequate and raised it to $3,500. tronolone appealed. justice ministry ...' to fix spelling of ochoa.</note>
gunmen ambushed and killed on wednesday the security chief for a newspaper that had urged the government not to back down in its war on drug traffickers, police said
jorge alberto stefan gomez was hit by five bullets fired by three men on motorcycles, police said in a news release. his 10-month-old daughter was grazed by a bullet and hospitalized in satisfactory condition, police said
colombia's council of state meanwhile ordered the temporary suspension of arrest orders for five members of the medellin cartel, a group said to dominate cocaine trafficking in colombia
the suspension of the arrest orders wednesday is almost certain to bring an angry reaction from u.s. authorities, who have begun to question the colombian government's position on rounding up drug traffickers
stefan and family were waiting for a taxi near their home when three men on motorcycles opened fire with pistols and a submachine gun, the police said. his wife was not hurt
police said they didn't know who was responsible for stefan's killing
stefan was chief of security for medellin's el colombiano newspaper, which has urged the government not to give in to drug traffickers. he also served as security chief for the newspaper's publisher, juan gomez martinez, who was elected mayor on march 13. gomez takes office june 1
on march 10, two bombs were thrown from a speeding car into the entryway of el colombiano. a guard threw the bombs back into the street and a passer-by was killed
in november, gunmen shot up gomez's home. the gunmen apparently were trying to kidnap gomez in an attempt to get the government to suspend extraditions of colombians to the united states to face drug trafficking charges
many drug traffickers live and process cocaine base in medellin
colombian drug traffickers have killed a justice minister, an attorney general, 21 judges, two newspaper editors and scores of policemen and soldiers in the last four years
the suspension of arrest orders for the medellin cartel was announced by supreme court justice samuel buitrago, a member of the council of state
the justice ministry in january ordered the arrest of alleged medellin cartel members pablo escobar, gonzalo rodriguez gacha and three brothers, jorge luis ochoa, juan david ochoa and fabio ochoa
buitrago, making the announcement during an interview by the bogota radio station caracol, said the arrest orders were being suspended while the government studies possible charges in colombia against the five men
buitrago said the suspension of the arrest orders is temporary until the council decides if it will permanently cancel the orders. it could be up to two months before the council makes its final decision
meanwhile, escobar's wife and 25 of his guards appeared before a judge in medellin after a shootout at escobar's home near that northwest colombian city
escobar apparently was at home when the shootout began but escaped. the u.s. drug enforcement administration says escobar is among the world's biggest cocaine traffickers. he is wanted for trial in the united states
army troops surrounded the escobar home tuesday, setting off a sophisticated alarm system of sirens and flashing lights, the army's 4th brigade headquarters in medellin said in a news release
a gunbattle ensued, and one escobar guard was wounded, the army said
the army found numerous guns, lots of ammunition and sophisticated communications equipment, the colombian radio chain rcn said
escobar's wife, maria victoria henao de escobar, was released by the medellin judge, rcn said, quoting a source with the attorney general's office
two new mexico state university history professors said wednesday that government documents indicate army intelligence officers attempted to kill mexican revolutionary pancho villa by poisoning in 1916
charles h. harris iii and louis sadler presented the findings in a paper submitted at a monthly meeting of the latin american studies forum at new mexico state
they said the attempt came during an american expedition into mexico in pursuit of villa and his men. the expedition followed a raid by villa on the new mexico community of columbus that left 17 american soldiers and civilians dead
the attempt was made in the town of jimenez, mexico, four months after the raid on columbus, according to sadler and harris
the plot called for two japanese men who were employed as secret agents for the american government to put poison in a cup of coffee intended for villa, the professors said
the two agents posed as peddlers and wanted villa to think they were sympathetic to his revolutionary cause. villa foiled the assassination attempt by pouring part of the coffee into another man's cup, the professors said
the fate of the man into whose cup villa poured the coffee was not known, the professors said. the poison was supposed to be odorless and tasteless and cause death three days after ingestion
historians consider the columbus raid a turning point in the mexican revolution because it rallied american public opinion against villa and his men. gen. john j. pershing led the retaliatory expedition
we can't prove it but there is no doubt in my mind that he knew'' of the plot, sadler said
the professors said that while there were official inquiries into the alleged plot, pershing denied any knowledge of it. the assassination attempt, according to the professors, was covered up
the telling and retelling of a story of rape and murder from various points of view makes for little suspense, but good acting and direction keep up interest in an off-broadway revival of the 1959 stage version of ``rashomon.''
the play by fay and michael kanin is based on the 1951 japanese movie of the same name and on stories by ryunosuke akutagawa published in 1915
it is the story of a samurai and his wife who encounter a bandit in the forest. the wife is raped and the samurai is found dead. but the circumstances vary depending on who does the telling
knowing the rape and death will be depicted several times, the audience can focus on how each person tells the story to paint himself or herself to best advantage
the husband's ghost, conjured up in a courtroom, tells of suicide, while the bandit and the wife both confess to murder. the bandit figures he'll be executed anyway; the wife thinks she'll be pardoned. it would shame them more to be publicly revealed as lacking in the personality they've presented to the world than to proclaim that they were driven to kill
the final version, told by a woodcutter who witnessed the encounter from a hiding place, is hilarious as husband and wife bicker and the honorable samurai and daring bandit are afraid to fight
the entire cast is asian in this first major revival of the play since it played on broadway in 1959 starring claire bloom, rod steiger, noel willman and oscar homolka
the cast includes james saito as the bandit who turns somersaults during swordfights; kiya ann joyce, who can take on many womanly aspects depending whose story she is acting; philip moon, who usually is bound and gagged as the husband; peter yoshida, the woodcutter, and thom sesma, a priest
david leong expertly directed fights and movement. mina albergo's setting is a forest clearing, alabaster with bamboo-leaf tracings, with the rashomon gate at one side. the set enhances the openness with which director robert kalfin places this ``rashomon'' before the audience. the play will run through may 8
