the investment group pursuing koppers co. has proposed a negotiated buyout at $60 a share, topping its current hostile offer of $56 a share, while hundreds of koppers employees demonstrated against the ongoing takeover attempt
the new proposal has an indicated value of about $1.68 billion, compared with $1.57 billion for the alternative hostile bid. it was made in a letter sent late wednesday to koppers chairman charles r. pullin from british investor brian c. beazer
beazer has teamed with shearson lehman hutton inc., the new york investment banker, in its attempt to acquire the pittsburgh building materials, paving services and chemical company. the hostile tender offer remains in effect, said beazer spokeswoman lissa perlman
koppers spokesman robert j. o'gara said the company had no immediate comment on the latest proposal
kopper's board of directors has rejected beazer's $56 a share offer as inadequate, and reiterated it was exploring a possible defensive recapitalization that would include a one-time payment to shareholders
we believe we are able to offer greater value to your stockholders than any plan you are presently considering,'' beazer stated in his letter to pullin. ``if you have a recapitalization plan that provides your stockholders and employees with more benefits than we are prepared to provide, we, and your other stockholders, are anxious to see it.''
separately, about 250 of the company's employees cut up an estimated 175 charge cards from american express co., which owns 60 percent of shearson, during a downtown protest
we're damn mad,'' said koppers vice president j. roger beidler. ``we want american express to know that this gathering is just the tip of the iceberg.''
management also has canceled its american express account, through which the company had been buying about $1.5 million per year in goods and services, said o'gara
koppers has accused shearson lehman of offering to defend the company from hostile takeovers at the same time that it was plotting its attack with beazer
that's quite a deal, and we're saying no,'' beidler said. ``we're going to send our cards back to american express in pieces.''
american express and shearson also have come under fire from state officials for their role in the hostile bid
lotus development corp.'s stock could remain depressed for some time following the company's announcement of a six-month delay in the release of a new version of its high-selling 1-2-3 software, industry watchers say
wall street analysts this week scaled back their earnings estimates for the company after it delayed the new release 3 software. in addition, lotus executives sold off large blocks of stock and a top executive resigned
i think the stock is going to underperform until we get closer to the release date on shipment of the 1-2-3 release 3,'' david j. readerman, an analyst with smith barney &amp; co., said wednesday
lotus fell $3.50 a share to $25.25 a share in over-the-counter trading wednesday, a 12 percent drop in market value
last month, lotus president jim p. manzi sold 250,000 shares of company stock, and several vice presidents sold between 12,800 shares and 95,800 shares. charles j. digate, senior vice president in charge of software development, left the company last week
lotus said some of the stock sales occurred because executives exercised stock options last august and had to wait six months before selling to meet tax payments
but readerman said: ``the timing of the sales just raises a credibility issue. that is as much a reason why the stock is down. if it was just the product slip date, i don't think you'd see the stock where it is.''
analysts said lotus is trailing its competitors in developing new spreadsheet programs and said they expected some of the 3.5 million lotus 1-2-3 users to defect to other brands
for some reason lotus just hasn't kept pace with the industry in bringing out new products,'' said rick sherlund of goldman, sachs &amp; co. ``they've been long on promise in announcing new products but short on delivery.''
analysts cut lotus' 1988 earnings per share estimates to between $1.55 and $1.65 from about $1.95. they also trimmed revenue forecasts for the year to about $400 million from $465 million
lotus last year reported net income of $72 million, or $1.58 per share, on revenue of $395.6 million
the upgraded 1-2-3 software originally was expected in june. the company said the new program, which promises to print better graphs, work faster and combine many spreadsheets, will be available in the fourth quarter
analysts said the delay would give borland international corp. of scotts valley, calif., and microsoft corp. of redmond, wash., a chance to gain market share with new software products designed to compete with 1-2-3
last november, borland released its quattro spreadsheet, which has been praised as better than 1-2-3, and microsoft, the leading personal computer software maker, released its windows excel software
martin fahey, lotus' investor relations director, said the company needs more time to make the new 1-2-3 programs small enough to work with personal computers
we obviously are concerned about the delay,'' fahey said. ``any time a product slips it's not good. (but) we think it's going to be worth waiting for.''
the new 1-2-3 will cost $495, same as the old one. people who have an authorized copy of the current 1-2-3 can upgrade for $150. analysts project $100 million to $150 million in sales in the first 12 to 18 months of its release
lotus on wednesday named w. frank king iii, a former vice president of development for international business machines corp.'s personal computer division, to replace digate. network</head>
cable news network will produce spanish-language news programming for broadcast exclusively on the television network operated by telemundo group inc., company officials have announced
the programming, slated to begin by may 31, will include a 30-minute national and international newscast, an hourlong week-in-review program, and news briefs to appear five times daily, monday through friday
the newscasts' correspondents will be based in new york, washington d.c., miami, los angeles and key cities in latin america, the network said wednesday
telemundo group, based in new york, owns and operates stations in four of the five largest hispanic markets in the united states _ los angeles, new york, miami and san francisco-san jose _ and reaches about 60 percent of u.s. hispanic households
telemundo also has affiliates in eleven other hispanic markets
the wine in the $3,200 bottle was an acclaimed 1984 merlot, but there was something even rarer about the cuvaison magnum that texan steven schwartz bought at a recent dallas charity auction
the grape art label on the napa valley wine was believed to be the first work designed for wine by the pop art pioneer andy warhol, who died last year in new york at age 58
warhol donated the art to the cuvaison winery in the late 1970s. it is a striking, bias-cut piece based on a stylized vision of what warhol thought nature should have made grapes look like: the six grapes are in hues of red and deep green
the overall label, which was placed on just 84 bottles, has warhol's name cut in above the art. it was designed and completed last year by california graphic artist channing rudd under commission by cuvaison president manfred esser
said rudd, ``the label was at first considered to be very strange,'' but, like the wine, the work improved with age and came into increasing favor. esser finally ordered the art made into a finished label, and rudd readied it for reproduction in a week
warhol did many commercial things, but basically warhol was a fine artist,'' said rudd. ``he was a painter who experimented with silk-screening and avant-garde techniques. i tried to do the same thing, only convert it into something marketable.''
still under wraps are warhol's creations for two other labels, one for white wine, the other for rose. no plans for them have been announced
as a memorial to warhol's talent, switzerland's industrialist schmidheiny family, which owns cuvaison, ordered the current labeling limited to 84 bottles
alexander and christina schmidheiny were friends of warhol's, and thought to use his work to evoke a fine-arts theme for special wines
we intended this label to be one of a series of artist's labels for cuvaison's special bottlings,'' mrs. schmidheiny said. ``when the 1984 cuvaison merlot was released, we decided to use his label only on 84 magnum bottles on the occasion of the 15th anniversary of the winery.''
as it turned out, the wine itself was very well received...hopefully a small memorial to mr. warhol's great talent.''
the dollar steadied at lower levels early in europe today after a sell-off during asian trading
gold prices rose
traders said the dollar was driven downward in asia by trading benefitting the yen and british pound
u.s. economic indicators due later today, including personal income for february, were not likely to move the market since an upward revision of the u.s. gross national product for the fourth quarter was disregarded wednesday, dealers said
the growth rate was revised to an annual rate of 4.8 percent, up from the previously reported 4.5 percent
there is still room for the yen and the pound to strengthen,'' said a trader in frankfurt. that means the dollar could fall a little lower during the course of the day, he said
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen
later, in london, it was quoted at 126.00 yen
other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late wednesday's rates, included: 1.6858 west german marks, down from 1.6915; 1.3940 swiss francs, down from 1.3990; 5.7305 french francs, down from 5.7450; 1.8943 dutch guilders, down from 1.9005; 1,248.95 italian lire, down from 1,253.25; 1.2440 canadian dollars, up from 1.2434
