convicted stock speculator ivan f. boesky, who made millions trading on inside information, would earn a maximum of 44 cents an hour at tasks ranging from landscaping to milking cows as an inmate in the prison recommended by his sentencing judge
boesky, 51, arrived wednesday afternoon at the lompoc, calif., prison camp, to begin serving his three-year term, the prison said
u.s. district judge morris lasker, who sentenced boesky on dec. 18, had given him until today to surrender
the lompoc facility, a 700-inmate minimum security facility about 150 miles northwest of los angeles near the pacific coast, is located on about 44,000 acres of heavily forested countryside and contains a dairy, slaughterhouse and furniture factory. inmates sleep in a former army barracks
lompoc warden richard rison said in a telephone interview last week that if boesky would have no special privileges or cushy prison jobs
our people are assigned based on where our needs are,'' said rison. ``he could be in the slaughterhouse, he could be in the landscape crew, he could be working in the dairy operation. he will be required to work a fulltime assignment.''
rison said the pay scale ranged from 11 cents to 44 cents an hour for a 40-hour week. as in other federal prison facilities, the money is credited to an account at the prison commissary, where inmates can buy toiletries, cigarettes and candy
during off hours, rison said, inmates can play tennis on a single concrete court, lift weights, roll boccie ball, shoot billiards or watch cable television at a half-dozen sets placed around the facility. inmates have access to eight telephones but rison said there's a 15-minute limit on calls
lompoc has been home to some other famous convicts, including former nixon administration aide h.r. haldeman and fireworks magnate w. patrick moriarty, who was convicted in a major government-bribery and influence-peddling scandal. convicted spy christopher boyce was incarcerated in lompoc's maximum-security section but escaped and led authorities on a chase for several months before he was seized in the northwest
boesky, formerly one of wall street's best known speculators, stunned the financial world in november 1986 when he paid the securities and exchange commission a record $100 million fine to settle civil charges of insider trading, the misuse of confidential information to profit in securities deals
since then he has cooperated extensively with federal investigators. in exchange, he was allowed to plead guilty to a single criminal count of conspiracy to lie to the sec
boesky's revelations reportedly have led to death threats against him, and there was speculation he had sought federal custody early because he feared for his life
last month, john mulheren, a former boesky friend and fellow speculator, was arrested on charges he threatened to kill boesky and boesky's former head trader, michael davidoff, who also has pleaded guilty to securities fraud and is cooperating with investigators
stock prices were sharply lower at midday thursday as the market's budget-related rally finally ran out of steam
the financial times-stock exchange index of 100 stocks was off 27.8 points, or 1.5 percent, at 1,804.4
volume was 297.3 million shares at midday, up from 211.2 million shares at the same time a day earlier
dealers said the market was marked down heavily soon after trading started
the 100-stock index had moved well above the 1,800-point level prior to chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson's march 15 budget statement. investors predicted the budget would include major tax cutting measures and bullish forecasts on the british economy
the announcement of the budget met those expectations, but since then, the market has been unable to push much higher
having seen not much follow-through since the budget in terms of buying, the question was whether there would be selling,'' said chris chaitow, an analyst at morgan grenfell securities. ``today has shown that there is selling.''
dealers said the market's nervousness was exacerbated by rumors of a major selling program by county natwest securities. but dealers at the brokerage firm denied there had been such a program thursday. terms</head>
the future chairman of first city bancorporation of texas inc. says the banking concern's restructuring plans, and the economic well-being of texas, are being jeopardized by a group of dissident debtholders
it's not in their best interest to hang onto the bonds if they're going to crater the deal in the process,'' a. robert abboud said wednesday before the french-american chamber of commerce
abboud, a chicago investor who would become of first city under a federal bailout plan, is seeking to complete a $1.5 billion restructuring of the houston company
the restructuring deal requires 90 percent participation by the close of business next tuesday. but as of late tuesday only about 51 percent of the holders of first city notes totaling $225.9 million had tendered their securities
senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35 cents
on a liquidation basis, their investment is worth zero,'' abboud said, referring to the $100 million in subordinated debt. ``once the preconditions are established, we have to stick to them.''
abboud is trying to restructure first city using $970 million in assistance from the federal deposit insurance corporation, and another $500 in privately raised capital
abboud said he was optimistic a deal could be closed. first city shareholders already have voted to support the abboud plan
