japan seeks an agreement with the united states by the end of march on opening the japanese market wider to american beef and citrus fruit, but there still are conflicting opinions in japan on the issue, a government official said thursday
the current agreement on japan's quotas on those items expires march 31
separately, a senior aide to prime minister noboru takeshita left for washington thursday for talks aimed at a political solution to a dispute over u.s. access to japan's construction market
on the agricultural issue, u.s. trade representative clayton yeutter said this week the united states wants all quotas dropped by april 1, or it will take the issue to the general agreement on tariffs and trade, an international forum for settling trade disputes
yoshifumi matsuda, spokesman for the foreign ministry, said thursday, ``our interest is to have a coordinated result, an agreement between the two governments by the end of the month.''
asked how far japan was willing to go to compromise short of total liberalization, he said there were conflicting opinions and the government was not ready to make a statement
the united states refuses to negotiate unless japan sets a clear timetable for liberalization, something japan has been unwilling to do. members of japan's ruling liberal-democratic party have expressed strong opposition to liberalization
gatt is a good place to fight this out,'' said tsutomu hata, head of the ldp's agriculture committee, after arguing in a meeting wednesday that producing beef and oranges is essential to domestic farmers, and these must be protected
a country should be able to produce basic food items on its own,'' said mitsuru yoshida of the livestock industry promotion corp. ``the united states is a very big country and so can produce a lot. but japan is very small and thus needs to protect itself.''
while farmers and many consumers fear liberalization will destroy the domestic beef and citrus industry, leading to unemployment and a dangerous dependence on foreign sources of food, yeutter commented: ``if it did mean some structural adjustment, that's the price we pay for a free and open trading system. we've had some adjustment, too.''
last month, a senior economic planning agency official predicted that imports of beef would be liberalized within two years, with a lifting of restrictions on citrus fruit even sooner
tentative moves to appease foreign critics include proposals announced thursday by an advisory council to the ministry of agriculture, forestry and fisheries for a revision of the upper and lower ceilings on domestic beef and pork price supports, said a ministry official who requested anonymity
deputy chief cabinet secretary ichiro ozawa, who is traveling to the united states to discuss agricultural issues, is scheduled to meet with u.s. commerce secretary william verity and other u.s. officials
an aide to ozawa declined to specify what new offers, if any, ozawa would make to u.s. officials in an attempt to settle the dispute
following the failure of working-level negotiations earlier this month, u.s. officials gave japan two weeks to come up with a satisfactory proposal to end the dispute. otherwise, they said the united states may invoke a law calling for compensation from japan
