a british labor union delegation left thursday for detroit in hopes of persuading ford motor co. to change its mind and locate an electronic components plant in scotland
we have a monumental task ahead of us,'' gavin laird, head of the amalgamated engineering union, said before the five-member delegation left london's heathrow airport
the delegation left a day after the trades union congress, britain's national labor federation, agreed to ford demands for a single-union deal at the proposed plant in dundee, scotland
the group included tuc general secretary norman willis
after five months of squabbling among british unions about the deal, ford announced this week it would not locate the $73 million plant in britain
prodded by this, the trades union congress' general council on wednesday voted 23-15 for the single-union deal. the transport and general workers' union, britain's largest union, remained opposed
the tgwu represents two-thirds of ford's more than 32,000 british workers and was insisting on being allowed into the dundee plant
the plant was expected to employ 450 workers
grain and soybean futures prices opened narrowly mixed today in quiet trading on the chicago board of trade
wheat futures were slightly lower. the market is caught in a tug-of-war between traders expecting seasonal price weakness to develop and those looking for new export business to push prices higher, said walter spilka, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
the corn and soybean markets were quiet and likely will stay that way through next thursday, when the agriculture department releases its first estimates of this year's planted acreage, spilka said
recent volatility in the precious metals and currency futures markets has had surprisingly little impact on grain futures prices, probably because grain traders are beginning to look more at supply-and-demand fundamentals and paying less attention to the prices of other commodities, he said
in early trading, wheat was } cent to 1{ cents lower with the contract for delivery in may at $3.06{ a bushel; corn was unchanged to } cent higher with may at $2.06{ a bushel; oats were \ cent higher across the board with may at $1.68 a bushel; soybeans were } cent to 1} cents higher with may at $6.40{ a bushel
