guinness plc, the british brewing company, said thursday its earnings more than quadrupled in 1987 due to extraordinary items
guinness said it earned 474 million pounds, or $867 million, up from 113 million pounds in 1986
the company attributed the increase to one-time gains of 217 million pounds, including 29 million pounds of unauthorized payments relating to the april 1986 takeover of distillers co
sales fell 9 percent to 2.82 billion pounds from 3.1 billion pounds
police have charged six people, including former guinness chairman ernest saunders, for alleged offenses related to the distillers takeover
on thursday, police arrested british stockbroker anthony parnes in connection with the guinness scandal when he voluntarily returned to london after being held in a los angeles jail for six months for extradition proceedings
parnes, 42, who was arrested at heathrow airport, faces 19 charges including aiding and abetting the theft of money from the brewing company. he is accused of setting up and operating an illegal share support operation during the guinness takeover bid for distillers in 1986
guinness has admitted it paid outsiders millions of pounds to buy guinness stock to make the brewer's cash and stock offer for distillers, a gin and whisky maker, more attractive than a rival bid
the company did not break down its quarterly or six-month results. corporations are not required to do so under british law. spelling of gutfreund.</note>
former white house budget director david a. stockman is quitting the wall street giant salomon brothers inc. to join the blackstone group, the smaller rival announced today
stockman, a managing director at salomon since leaving the white house in 1985, will handle all merchant banking activities and merger transactions for the blackstone group, the company said
his departure from salomon comes against a background of turmoil within the venerable investment firm, a partial result of the uncertain outlook for wall street in the aftermath of the stock market crash five months ago
several other high-ranking executives also have quit salomon recently, although stockman was quoted by the new york times today as saying his departure was unrelated to the company's problems
my experience at salomon was absolutely agreeable and i have a high regard for (salomon chairman) john gutfreund,'' stockman was quoted as saying. ``...there's one thing i couldn't do there _ which is have my own shop.''
former commerce secretary peter g. peterson, chairman of blackstone, said in a press statement that stockman will take charge of a jointly owned firm called ``stockman &amp; co. _ a blackstone group affiliate.''
peterson said he wanted stockman to bolster blackstone's emerging merchant banking business in japan
dave stockman will be an immensely valuable asset in meeting that goal,'' he said. ``he brings a global perspective on business and financial issues as well as intimate familiarity with both u.s. and japanese government policies.''
blackstone recently represented sony in a $2 billion acquisition of cbs records late last year and represented firestone tire &amp; rubber co. in its $2.6 billion acquisition by japan's bridgestone corp
stockman, 41, was white house budget director from 1981 to 1985
the for sale sign on chrysler motors corp.'s acustar subsidiary has been taken down, but chrysler is pushing the parts-making company farther from the corporate nest
the objective is to have it be much more independent, especially in the administration, so you don't have a lot of people in acustar filing reports to chrysler about what they will be doing,'' said baron bates, vice president of public relations
the idea came up when chrysler was reviewing whether to sell the $3 billion subsidiary, bates said. the company backed away from selling acustar after the united auto workers union revolted and threatened strikes at acustar plants where local contracts were unresolved
the 10-month-old subsidiary has continued as a part of the company's structure and functioned almost as a chrysler motors department
one of the things we're contemplating in-house is ... why don't we pretend we sold acustar and really treat them as a completely self-contained business responsible for their own bottom-line results and let them do whatever they have to do to get there?'' acustar chairman robert lutz said
acustar financial results would be reported with chrysler's, and chrysler still would handle the company's labor relations, but acustar no longer would report to chrysler administratively, bates said
one reason chrysler corp. chairman lee iacocca said chrysler considered selling acustar was the expense of research and development necessary for competitive parts technology
lutz said part of acustar's strategy would involve buying new technology and forming partnerships with parts companies rather than developing new technology on its own
the idea has been endorsed by chrysler's executive committee and lutz has been urged to complete the change quickly, he said. he declined to be more specific about a timetable
of the big three automakers, chrysler purchases more of its parts from outside suppliers than industry leader general motors corp. or ford motor co
chevron corp. plans to add more than 1,500 workers by the end of the year, the largest annual increase in staff since the oil company bought gulf in 1984
the addition would include more than 300 workers in the san francisco bay area, according to an article in an employee magazine
the company, the fourth-largest oil company in the nation, has 13,400 workers in the san francisco area, including 2,748 at its headquarters in san francisco
nearly half of the new employees will work in exploration. the company will hire 400 workers to help find and produce oil in the united states alone. in addition, 100 people will be involved in exploration work in canada and 160 will be hired for other nations
