treasury secretary james a. baker iii told congress on thursday that disclosing names of foreign investors would damage the united states
proposals for some disclosure are in trade bills now before congress
if enacted, the ... provision would have a chilling effect on foreign investment in the united states _ thereby costing jobs, raising interest rates, lowering productivity, closing off opportunities for technological and managerial improvements, and undermining our efforts to liberalize investments abroad,'' baker said
his opposition was in a written statement sent to the senate commerce committee. sponsors of the proposal, sen. tom harkin and rep. john bryant, came to a committee hearing and said they were sorry baker did not appear in person
not one of the g-7 countries (united states, japan, west germany, britain, france, canada, italy) has a publicly available national register of foreign investments of the type prescribed by bryant,'' baker wrote
not one discloses to the public ongoing information about the status of specific private investors and their investments; not one requires systematic reporting by foreign investors or domestic firms for this purpose.''
baker's views were challenged by harkin, though he did not refer to baker. harkin said most countries require more information than his bill is seeking, and in addition require their governments to clear investments in advance. his proposal does not seek that kind of clearance
even switzerland keeps a public registry of swiss companies with foreign ownership,'' he said
japan's preclearance process seems one of the most stringent, in part because it is the most explicit ... japan flatly prohibits foreign ownership of more than 25 percent in any of its high-tech companies.''
domestic automakers were scheduled to produce 233,594 cars and trucks this week, up from last week's 230,813, ward's automotive reports said thursday
automakers produced 241,104 cars and trucks during the same week a year ago. they were were scheduled to make 147,063 cars this week, compared with 147,039 a week ago and 164,212 in the same week in 1987
truck production for the week was scheduled at 86,531, compared with last week's 83,774 and last year's 76,892
canadian automakers were to build 26,445 cars this week, compared with 18,884 last week and 17,709 in the same week last year. canadian truck production was scheduled at 19,864, compared with 20,262 last week and 18,734 in the same week last year. australia; uppicks 2nd graf: brierly made...</note>
new zealand investor ronald brierly is offering $988 million to take over calmat co., a major construction materials and real estate concern with operations in southern california and arizona
brierly made his unsolicited $40-per-share offer for the 81 percent of calmat he does not already own through a subsidiary of australia-based industrial equity (pacific) inc., calmat said wednesday
calmat has 30.5 million shares outstanding
los angeles-based calmat was created in 1984 by the merger of two construction industry giants _ california portland cement co. and conrock co. the merged companies' core businesses are in cement, ready-mixed concrete, aggregate, hot-mixed asphalt and real estate holdings
brierly's offer sent calmat's stock soaring by $13.50 per share to $45.37{ in heavy trading wednesday on the new york stock exchange. the stock was up $1.87| on tuesday amid speculation the company might become a takeover target
in a brief statement, calmat chief executive a.f. gerstell said that in the past three years the company ``has taken significant steps...to enhance shareholder value through the disposition of assets and the reallocation of proceeds to the company's higher-margin core businesses.''
in addition, gerstell said, the company and its investment adviser, j.p. morgan &amp; co., have for some time been looking at ``additional, more aggressive steps which the company can take to continue this ongoing process.''
calmat intends to convene a special board meeting to compare brierly's offer with its own restructuring options, gerstell said
in 1987, the company earned $78.1 million on revenue of $658.9 million. the profit included a $24 million gain on the sale of assets. in 1986, calmat earned $44.1 million on revenue of $619 million
gerstell has been calmat's chief executive, president and chief operating officer since the company was created. for the previous three years, he was presdient of california portland cement
calmat's chairman, william jenkins, was president of conrock before the merger
brierly, whose holdings range from real estate to oil and gas to financial services, characterizes himself as a long-term investor but not necessarily a passive one
in 1986, he made an unsuccessful bid to acquire control of beverly hills-based wrather corp., best known as the operator of the disneyland hotel in anaheim and the spruce goose and queen mary tourist attractions in long beach
subsequently, a joint venture of brierly and burbank-based walt disney co. bought wrather for $152 million. disney has become manager of the disneyland hotel, which sits on its property, but no agreement has been reached on how the assets will be split
the justice department today charged a former texas savings and loan executive with providing sexual payoffs to the institution's officers and board members in a conspiracy to violate the federal bank and bribery statute
john hill, former vice president of vernon savings and loan association, arranged for paid female companionship for officers and directors at a three-day june 1985 board meeting in solana beach, calif., said a one-count felony information
hill, who the justice department said has agreed to plead guilty, intended that sexual favors would be available to the executives in connection with their service to the institution, said court papers filed in u.s. district court in dallas
according to a justice department statement, hill and others created false board minutes on the renewal and extension of some commercial real estate loans. the bogus minutes indicated the renewals and extensions had been approved by the board when no such approval had occurred
hill falsified documentation justifying $100,000 in payments to a consultant in connection with a loan from an s&amp;l, according to papers filed in federal court in dallas
in addition, according to the felony information, hill conspired with a vernon official to make $5,400 in illegal state and federal campaign contributions to specific candidates, based on the understanding that he would be reimbursed through false expense vouchers submitted to vernon
the contributions allegedly included $1,000 to former texas congressman thomas loeffler in february 1986, $2,000 to the loeffler for government campaign in april 1986, $400 to the campaign of u.s. rep. martin frost, d-texas, in september 1985, and $2,000 to citizens for jack kemp in june 1986
there were no allegations that any of the campaign organizations or candidates knew the contributions were actually coming from the s&amp;l
disguising payments to the consultant and concealing reimbursements for the illegal campaign contributions impeded the internal revenue service in determining the amount of income taxes due by the consultant, by hill, by vernon and by the association's holding company, dondi financial corp
hill, who has agreed to cooperate in an ongoing probe of vernon, could be sentenced to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on the conspiracy charge
