rolls-royce plc, the airplane engine maker privatized by the government last year, on thursday reported a 12 percent increase in its net profit for 1987
strong gains in the group's civil aviation division more than offset a sharp rise in research and development costs, the company said
rolls-royce, which is a separate company from the luxury car maker, reported 1987 net profit of 134 million pounds, or $247 million, up from 120 million pounds, or $221 million a year earlier
per share earnings came to 20.1 pence, or 37 cents, compared with 18.9 pence, or 35 cents, a year earlier
sales increased 14 percent to 2.06 billion pounds, or $3.8 billion, from 1.8 billion pounds, or $3.3 billion in 1986
rolls-royce chairman sir francis tombs said: ``our order book is strong and our wide stable of competitive engines gives us an excellent opportunity to consolidate our existing customer base and secure some of the attractive new sales opportunities which are appearing around the world.''
the company did not break out quarterly or six-month results. it isn't required to under british law
world ouptut of wheat is projected to rise in 1988, but could still fall short of demand for the second consecutive year, the international wheat council said thursday
in its first forecast of 1988 prospects, the council tentatively put 1988 world output at 525 million metric tons _ 17 million above last year's estimated total and 10 million below the 1986 record
production of 525 million metric tons would fail to satisfy projected demand for 1988, but current stocks could be used to make up the shortfall, the council said
in the short- to medium-term, there should be no need for great anxiety,'' it added
soybean futures prices closed sharply higher thursday on the chicago board of trade due to a late surge of speculative buying. grain futures closed mixed
the soybean runup in the last 1{ hours of trading coincided with a rally in silver futures prices that may have sparked buying interest in soybeans, said walter spilka, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
there was no new fundamental news during the session but sometimes the soybeans will trade with the precious metals markets,'' he said
the grain markets had looked strong before today and the rise in silver prices may have led to inflationary ideas,'' spilka said
the dollar also weakened thursday, making u.s. goods cheaper overseas. expectations that the dollar will remain weak against other currencies may also have supported the soybean market, he said
