delaware management co., a philadelphia-based money management firm that oversees $18 billion in assets, said thursday it was being acquired in a leveraged buyout valued in excess of $200 million
delaware's management joined with legend capital l.p. in acquiring the company for ``a price in excess of $200 million in equity and debt,'' said charles storer, a spokesman for the companies. further details were not available
legend capital is a private investment firm formed last year by john castle, the former chief executive of donaldson lufkin &amp; jenrette, and partner leonard harlan, who heads a real estate investment firm
delaware management handles $15 billion in pension money for 225 corporate and public pension funds, including those of international business machines corp. and amoco corp. the firm also manages $5 billion in assets in 16 mutual funds
legend had $125 million in investments from pension funds, endowments and indviduals as of last november
stock prices fell sharply today as the dollar slumped in foreign exchange and u.s. interest rates headed higher
as the dollar lost ground, prices of long-term government bonds dropped about $5 for each $1,000 in face value today, putting their yields in the 8.75 to 8.8 percent range
at their best recent levels, yields on treasury bonds were as low as 8.3 percent
analysts said pressure on the dollar prompted concern in markets around the world. prices fell in both the london and tokyo stock markets
against that background, brokers said, investors moved quickly to cash on the u.s. market's gains since late last year
business phone costs held steady in the first three months of 1987, the first quarter since 1984 in which they have have not fallen, according to a report thursday
a 10 percent rise in rates for interstate private lines offset declines of 7 percent in rates for both wats and toll calls, said ccmi-mcgraw-hill, which conducts the quarterly survey
the firm's telecommunications price index remained level at 77.3, down from a base of 100 in 1984
the big three long-distance companies seem to be adjusting their rates to make it attractive for business customers to switch from private lines to wats and toll service, said george christie, chief economist for mcgraw-hill information systems co
american telephone &amp; telegraph co. dominates the interstate long-distance market, with mci communications corp. and us sprint communications co. trailing
the cost of local business calling remained stable during the period
christie said any changes in phone rates in the final days of the month would have an insignificant effect on the first-quarter index
a court challenge to a florida tax on insurance premiums and annuities will decide whether the department of revenue owes out-of-state insurance companies $140 million in refunds
the companies don't like the way the state currently assesses taxes on money that consumers pay to insurers _ a 2 percent tax on premiums and 1 percent tax on annuities
the tax is paid only by out-of-state companies, not by florida-based insurers. the out-of-state companies say that isn't fair, and many of them have asked for refunds
the law was changed last year to require all insurance companies, including those based in florida, to pay the premium insurance tax, but that change won't take effect until july 1
the state targeted one case _ continental insurance co. _ to be a test case in circuit court
if (the case) comes down in our favor, we'll be all right financially,'' said walter wood, an attorney in the department of banking and finance, one of three state agencies in the case. ``if not, there's a lot of money involved.''
new york-based continental sought a refund of $1.5 million that it paid in taxes in 1983, 1984 and 1985. it is one of 210 companies that have filed for a total of $140 million in refunds _ an amount roughly equal to the entire budget for the department of banking and finance
it's substantial,'' said daniel brown of the department of legal affairs, which is handling the case
in its refund claim, continental argued that the u.s. supreme court ruled in 1985 that such disriminatory taxing policies were unconstitutional
according to the state comptroller's office, out-of-state insurance companies have filed claims to recover taxes paid as long ago as the mid-1970s
brown argued on the state's behalf that the florida tax law should be considered legal until courts rule on its constitutionality
brown also claimed that the out-of-state insurance companies passed along the tax to consumers through its premiums and refunding the money would unjustly enrich the companies
the department of banking and finance is involved because the comptroller rules on requests for tax refunds. the department of revenue both collects the tax and makes the refunds, while the department of insurance regulates the insurance industry
stock prices took a sharp drop thursday as the dollar slumped in foreign exchange and u.s. interest rates headed higher
the dow jones average of 30 industrials fell 43.77 points to 2,023.87
declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 5 to 1 on the new york stock exchange, with 269 up, 1,379 down and 347 unchanged
big board volume totaled 184.91 million shares, against 167.37 million in the previous session. the nyse's composite index dropped 2.82 to 149.00
as the dollar lost ground, prices of long-term government bonds fell about $5 for each $1,000 in face value during the morning, putting their yields in the 8.75 to 8.8 percent range. at their best recent levels, yields on treasury bonds were as low as 8.3 percent
bonds later recovered a good part of their early losses, but stocks did not follow suit
analysts said pressure on the dollar prompted concern in markets around the world. prices fell in both the london and tokyo stock markets
against that background, brokers said, investors moved quickly to cash on the u.s. market's gains since late last year
thursday's session marked the fourth time the dow jones industrial average came close to, but did not quite reach, the 50-point plus or minus limit set by the nyse feb. 4 at which restrictions go into effect on the use of its computer trading facilities for so-called index arbitrage trading
though this ``collar,'' as exchange officials call it, has never been activated, many wall streeters say it appears to have become a sort of de facto limit on daily price swings, and possibly a target for traders as well
among actively traded blue chip and technology issues, general electric dropped } to 41~; international business machines 1~ to 109}; digital equipment 3} to 107|, and american telephone &amp; telegraph { to 27}
digital equipment, which has a wide following among investing institutions as a leading technology company, dropped below its lowest point in the october crash
in the securities industry group, merrill lynch fell } to 23{; salomon 1[ to 21\; first boston 1[ to 25; morgan stanley } to 59\, and charles schwab ] to 8\
some stocks involved in takeover developments bucked the downtrend. irving bank, which jumped 6| to 66\, said that it was negotiating with unnamed ``third parties'' about a possible merger, restructuring or sale of assets as an alternative to a hostile bid by bank of new york
international clinical laboratories climbed 8 to 33} in over-the-counter trading. smithkline beckman made a $32-a-share bid for the company, which had agreed to an acquisition by corning glass works for $26 a share
as measured by wilshire associates' index of more than 5,000 actively traded stocks, the market lost $46.65 billion, or 1.75 percent, in value
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 215.22 million shares
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials fell 6.72 to 305.31, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index was down 5.56 at 263.35
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market dropped 4.49 to 375.60. at the american stock exchange, the market value index closed at 297.30, down 3.11
the dollar continued to slide thursday, reaching levels against the japanese yen and west german mark not seen for two months as a bearish sentiment pervaded currency markets
gold prices firmed. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price for gold of $453.15 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. est, up from wednesday's late bid of $451.15 an ounce
traders said the dollar continued to suffer from comments made wednesday by martin feldstein, former chief economic advisor to the president, who said the currency should fall to 120 yen in the near term
in an address at new york university, feldstein also predicted the dollar would decline against other currencies over the next several years
those comments are not new, but they triggered losses'' in the dollar, said earl johnson, a vice president at irving trust co
the dollar, which closed at 125.575 yen in new york, last traded at that level in mid-january. traders said the yen continues to strengthen ahead of the close of the japanese fiscal year on march 31 and on the expectation that the japanese economy will forge ahead
the dollar also weakened somewhat on government reports that personal income grew 0.9 percent in february and that personal consumption expenditures grew 0.7 percent during the month
the figures indicated that consumer spending is picking up again, which likely will result in wider trade deficits, said nigel green, a trader at ebc-amro bank in london
johnson echoed that sentiment, saying that the ``mildly bearish sentiment'' toward the dollar is being spurred by ``the realization that there will be larger trade deficits later in the year.''
in tokyo, where the business day ends as europe's begins, the dollar closed at 126.30 yen, down 0.85 yen. later in london, it was quoted at a lower rate of 125.75 yen
in london, the british pound rose to $1.8435 from wednesday's $1.8358. in new york, it cost $1.8420 to buy one pound, more expensive than wednesday's $1.83725
other late dollar rates in new york, compared to late wednesday, included: 1.67725 west german marks, down from 1.6916; 1.38625 swiss francs, down from 1.3985; 5.7045 french francs, down from 5.7470; 1,242.50 italian lire, down from 1,251.875, and 1.2421 canadian dollars, down from 1.2430
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late wednesday, included: 1.6800 west german marks, down from 1.6915; 1.3885 swiss francs, down from 1.3990; 5.7120 french francs, down from 5.7450; 1.8980 dutch guilders, down from 1.9005; 1,246.95 italian lire, down from 1,253.25, and 1.2426 canadian dollars, down from 1.2434
gold prices moved mostly higher. on the new york commodity exchange, gold closed at $454.10, up from $451.10 an ounce wednesday
in london gold fell to a late bid price of $452 a troy ounce, compared with late wednesday's $453. in zurich, gold rose to close at a bid $452, compared with $450.50 late wednesday. earlier, in hong kong, gold rose $3.34 to close at $455.40 an ounce
silver closed at $6.735 an ounce on new york's comex, up from $6.610 on wednesday. in london, the metal was trading at a late bid price of $6.61 a troy ounce, compared with wednesday's $6.63
the two broadest measures of the nation's money supply jumped in mid-march, the federal reserve board reported thursday
the report had no impact on interest rates in the credit markets, however
the fed said the measure known as m2 rose $11.2 billion to a seasonally adjusted $2,965.5 billion in the week ended march 14 from $2,954.3 billion the previous week
an even broader measure, m3, increased $14.8 billion to a seasonally adjusted $3,740.3 billion from $3,725.5 billion
the narrowest measure of the money supply, m1, rose $4.7 billion to a seasonally adjusted $760.5 billion from $755.8 billion. for the latest 13 weeks, m1 rose 2.6 percent to an average of $755.7 billion
m1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. m2 is m1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. m3 is m2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $100,000
in setting its monetary policy, the fed has indicated it is monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short- and long-term interest rates. it also has shifted its attention from m1 to the two broader money supply measures
the fed said in early 1988 that it would like annual growth for m2 and m3 to be between 4 percent and 8 percent, which is slightly lower than the 1987 target of 5.5 percent to 8.5 percent. the fed has not set a specific target range for m1 since early 1987
in other reports:
_the federal reserve bank of new york reported commercial and industrial loans at major new york city banks fell $48 million in the week ended march 16 compared with a decline of $1.24 billion a week earlier
_the federal reserve said bank borrowings from the federal reserve system averaged $325 million a day in the week ended wednesday, up from $153 million in the previous week
_the federal reserve bank of st. louis reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at federal reserve banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $274.2 billion in the two-week period ended wednesday, up from $272.1 billion two weeks earlier
prices for future delivery of silver and copper posted steep gains thursday on expections of increasing demand among industrial users of the metals
gold futures prices also advanced on perceptions of rising inflation
on other markets, soybean futures surged while grain futures were mixed; stock-index futures fell; energy futures and livestock and meat futures were mixed
wednesday's government figures showing the economy grew at a higher-than-expected 4.8 percent rate in the fourth quarter of 1987 had a delayed impact on silver and copper futures on new york's commodity exchange, said bernard savakl, a metals analyst for painewebber
silver and copper are industrial metals that have to play catch-up on the upside now following the gnp report,'' savakl said. ``what the government is saying is contrary to the majority of expectations: the economy did not slow to a grinding halt but gathered upward momentum, and that's very positive for industrial metals.''
silver, which is also a precious metal and thus perceived as an investment hedge against inflation, also gained in reaction to generally higher futures prices for other commodities, savakl said
the commodities research bureau's index of 21 commodity markets gained 1.25 points thursday, a moderate advance
analyst stephen w. platt of dean witter reynolds inc., attributed the silver rally to far eastern buying of the metal and to the dollar's decline in value against foreign currencies
platt also noted that copper is in short supply. tight supplies of copper have been cited to explain the metal's steady increase in value since late february
copper settled .50 cent to 6.25 cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $1.1395 a pound
gold settled $2.20 to $3 higher with april at $454.30 a troy ounce; silver was 12.5 cents to 13.4 cents higher with march at $6.735 a troy ounce
the silver rally may have sparked buying interest in soybean futures, which gained as much as 9{ cents a bushel on the chicago board of trade. grains were mixed
there was no new fundamental news during the session but sometimes the soybeans will trade with the precious metals markets,'' said walter spilka, an analyst in new york with smith barney, harris upham &amp; co
the grain markets had looked strong before today and the rise in silver prices may have led to inflationary ideas,'' he said
expectations that the dollar will remain weak, making u.s. goods cheaper overseas, may also have supported the soybean market, he said
wheat settled unchanged to 2 cents lower with may at $3.06} a bushel; corn was } cent to 1\ cents higher with may at $2.07 a bushel; oats were } cent to 1\ cents higher with may at $1.68{ a bushel; soybeans were 7 cents to 9{ cents higher with may at $6.49\ a bushel
stock-index futures tumbled on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for june delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled 6.30 points lower at 264.10
stock and stock-index futures prices opened sharply lower in reaction to the dollar's weakness and continued to fall throughout the session, said john mitchell, an analyst for elders futures inc
oil prices finished mixed in moderate trading on the new york mercantile exchange, reflecting uncertainty over the opec pricing committee's ability to calm the turbulent market, analysts said
the group meets next month to discuss stabilizing sagging prices
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 2 cents to 10 cents higher with may at $16.96 a barrel; heating oil was .16 cent to .41 cent lower with april at 47.40 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .20 cent lower to .08 cent higher with april at 47.33 cents a gallon
cattle futures finished mostly lower and pork futures were mostly higher in a day of choppy trading on the chicago mercantile exchange
traders were wary of the sharp drop in stock prices, fearing a repeat of the cattle market collapse that followed the stock market's historic plunge in october, said charlie richardson, an analyst in denver with lind-waldock &amp; co
everbody was keeping an eye on the indexes and what the stock market was doing,'' he said
live cattle settled .53 cent lower to .05 cent higher with april at 74.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .25 cent to .65 cent lower with march at 82.20 cents a pound; hogs were .20 cent lower to .40 cent higher with april at 46.07 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .35 cent to .60 cent higher with march at 55.45 cents a pound
the losing side vowed to fight on thursday after a federal bankruptcy judge approved an $11 million settlement in a case involving three zeros accidentally dropped from some financial documents
we have not given up the ship, so to speak,'' said sandra mayerson, a lawyer representing a major creditor in the chapter 11 proceedings of united states lines, a moribund shipping company, and its parent mclean industries inc
prudential insurance co. of america agreed this week to pay about $11 million to united states lines to settle legal claims stemming from a clerical error in which a mortgage lien prudential held on eight ships, worth $92,885,000, was recorded as worth $92,885
prudential agreed to pay the money to keep united states lines and other creditors from challenging the full amount of the lien
ms. mayerson said her client, general electric capital corp., which shared a second mortgage on the ships, would press its challenge in admiralty court and might even appeal the ruling thursday by u.s. bankruptcy judge howard buschman iii
if general electric capital can convince a judge that prudential's lien is really worth only $92,885, it will get a bigger portion of the more than $60 million in net proceeds raised by the sale of the eight ships
the oddity of a clerical error costing prudential more than $11 million attracted widespread attention to the case. but it was not a major case in the legal annals, said sheldon hirshon, a lawyer for another creditor, sea-going benefit plans, which went along with the settlement
this is not brown vs. board of education,'' hirshon said, referring to the landmark 1954 school desegregation case
pharmaceutical giant smithkline beckman corp. on thursday launched a $32-a-share tender offer for international clinical laboratories inc., which already has accepted a bid from corning glass works
smithkline valued its offer for the clinical testing firm at $340 million, which includes the assumption of debt. smithkline owns about 1 percent of icl's 7.6 million outstanding shares
in over-the-counter trading, icl jumped $8 to close at $33.75 a share
icl, based in nashville, tenn., announced earlier this month that it reached a definitive agreement to be acquired by corning's metpath inc. subsidiary for $26 a share, or about $260 million
a spokesman at corning headquarters in corning, n.y., had no comment on whether the company might increase its bid
analysts said, however, that corning, which earned $162.2 million last year, is financially capable of challenging smithkline
corning can go considerably higher if they found it worthwhile,'' said charles k. ryan, an analyst with merrill lynch &amp; co. in new york
under terms of its merger agreement, corning has an option to buy 3 million unissued icl shares as well as ``all the shares owned by certain directors and officers'' for $26 each
ryan said the directors and officers hold 800,000 shares, which would value the options at about $99 million. companies sometimes grant such ``lock-up'' options to keep others at bay by making a subsequent bids more expensive
henry wendt, chairman and chief executive officer of philadelphia-based smithkline, said in a statement that the offer is ``consistent with our corporate strategy to invest in our key businesses and will build on the success of our clinical laboratories network.''
smithkline bio-science laboratories, the company's clinical laboratory segment headquartered in king of prussia, pa., operates 22 regional laboratories. it reported sales of $431 million last year
smithkline is ``no. 1, and they want to get even bigger'' by acquiring icl, said david lippman, an analyst with drexel burnham lambert inc
corning's metpath subsidiary, which is headquartered in teterboro, n.j., operates a testing laboratory there as well as 12 others nationwide
icl's 13 clinical testing laboratories are located in the south and west. the company has a substantial contract to conduct aids tests on 27,000 federal prisoners in 47 prisons and recently announced the opening of a new division in nashville to market its laboratory testing service to the insurance industry nationwide
for the fiscal year ended last aug. 31, icl reported profits of $4.8 million on sales of $205.5 million
as a condition of its offer, which expires at midnight april 20, smithkline said that two tennessee laws governing takeovers must be found invalid or inapplicable
corning's offer expires april 5
lufthansa german airlines has ordered 20 boeing 737 airliners and taken options on 20 more of the twin-engined jets, boeing commercial airplanes said wednesday
under terms of the order, worth approximately $535 million, lufthansa will begin receiving the new aircraft in october 1990, with deliveries continuing through may 1991, said boeing spokesman tom cole
cole said the jets will be a mix of 141-passenger 737-300s and 98-passenger 737-500s, but the number of each type of plane has not yet been decided
the 737-500 is the smallest commercial jet boeing sells. it is now under development and is scheduled to be introduced in february 1990
the 737-500 is nearly identical to the 737-300, except that at 97 feet, 9 inches it is 7 feet, 10 inches shorter. crews rated for one model can also fly the other
lufthansa plans to use the new aircraft to replace older aircraft in its fleet, cole said. the new planes will be powered by cfm56-3b1 engines made by general electric of the united states and snecma of france
lufthansa, which bought the first 737 from boeing in 1965, now has ordered 90 of the planes
boeing has now received 2,028 orders for all 737 models, the most-popular commercial jetliner ever made
investor marvin davis, snubbed in his $770 million takeover bid for lorimar telepictures corp., sought wednesday to turn up the heat in his fight for the entertainment concern
davis said he would consider other ``alternative courses of action'' if lorimar continues to hold merger talks only with warner communications inc., the new york-based entertainment conglomerate
a lorimar spokesman said those options included filing suit against lorimar or making a hostile tender offer
noting that the price of lorimar stock has risen more than 50 percent since lorimar disclosed on march 3 that it was talking with warner, davis said, ``i believe you have passed the point of no return ... it is time to quickly and efficiently provide equal access (to non-public information) to all serious bidders.''
he added, ``it is upsetting to me, as it must be to all shareholders, that only one of the parties interested in acquiring lt has had the opportunity to inspect its books and records.''
davis is offering $17 per share for lorimar's 45.3 million shares. no details of the price being discussed by warner has been disclosed, but analysts have estimated could fetch a price in the high teens
the company's stock closed unchanged at $15 a share wednesday on the american stock exchange
davis also indicated that he owned a ``substantial block'' of lorimar stock. a spokesman said it was less than the 5 percent which an investor must disclose and most, if not all, of the stock was acquired before davis made his takeover proposal on march 7
lorimar spokeswoman sue binford said wednesday that the company had no comment on davis' announcement and declined to comment on the status of talks with warner
lorimar dismissed davis' proposal in rather summary fashion just hours after it was disclosed two weeks ago, saying only that it ``would bear davis' letter in mind.''
lorimar, based in suburban culver city, is a leading producer of original television programming, but in recent years has been troubled as its ambitious plans to expand into other areas have disintegrated and sometimes caused hevy losses for the company
in the first nine months of its current fiscal year, lorimar lost $82.6 million on revenues of $616.8 million. the deficit included $45 million in writedowns on five movies and $22 million in reserves for possible future losses in its home-video unit
motorola inc.'s electronics group has agreed to pay the government $16.7 million and to plead guilty to a criminal information accusing it of mischarging for labor and materials on navy satellite and missile contracts, the justice department announced thursday
in documents filed in u.s. district court in phoenix, motorola's government electronics group in scottsdale, ariz., was accused of inflating costs for a component of a navy satellite communications and mischarging $2.5 million in labor, materials and other costs. the money actually was spent on other work, the government said
the defense department, relying on the inflated amounts, paid some $5 million more than it should have on a second contract for the satellite communications system, said the government
motorola, one of the nation's top 50 defense contractors, agreed to plead guilty to three counts of making false statements
the firm said in a statement from motorola headquarters in schaumburg, ill., that ``it is now clear in retrospect'' that the electronics group's ``systems were not adequate to ensure total compliance with applicable laws and regulations.''
the conduct of the employees involved in these programs failed to conform to motorola's own internal standards,'' the statement added. the electronics group ``has greatly expanded its compliance efforts'' with reforms which ``are now an integral part of the way geg does business.''
under the agreement, which still must be approved by a court, the government has agreed not to prosecute the company further on the contracts, but reserves the right to prosecute individuals
the court documents also say the firm mischarged labor costs for work on 10 contracts involving production of target detecting devices for the navy's standard missile
the third count in the criminal information said motorola mischarged labor costs on a contract for the production of targeting detecting devices for the navy's phoenix missile
motorola will pay $16.7 million in criminal fines, restitution and civil penalties. the company already has paid $6.8 million to the defense department
the pleas result from an investigation into labor and materials charging and pricing practices by motorola from 1979 to 1984
here are the yearly profits or losses for federally insured savings institutions from 1978 through 1987, according to the federal home loan bank board
1987 _ $6.8 billion loss
1986 _ $132 million profit
1985 _ $3.7 billion profit
1984 _ $1.0 billion profit
1983 _ $1.9 billion profit
1982 _ $4.1 billion loss
1981 _ $4.6 billion loss
1980 _ $781 million profit
1979 _ $3.6 billion profit
1978 _ $3.9 billion profit
a federal bankruptcy court judge rejected on thursday a financial reorganization plan for elsinore corp.'s atlantis casino hotel, but attorneys for the gaming hall say they are confident they can amend the proposal to the judge's satisfaction
judge rosemary gambardella, in a 90-page decision, objected to a proposal that elsinore would be free from future claims if any were filed
the present release and discharge provisions of the plan stand as an obstacle to confirmation of the plan as presently constituted,'' she wrote
she said, however, she would consider amendments to the plan if the company wanted to submit changes
marvin e. jacob, attorney for the atlantis, said he will move to eliminate the offending provision of the reorganization plan, perhaps as early as friday
the atlantis, a casino hotel in atlantic city, has been operating under chapter 11 bankruptcy protection since november 1985
after the court ruling, atlantis president jeanne hood told the state casino control commission he was confident the reorganization plan is still viable. the commission is in the midst of relicensing hearings for the atlantis
the atlantis has more than 15,000 creditors, but the pay-back plan concentrates on about 700 main creditors
under the reorganization plan, elsinore will raise $70 million by refinancing its two nevada casinos and will receive about $20 million from the sale of a note
a new york television station said thursday it was dropping wpp group plc's lord, geller, federico, einstein unit as its advertising agency, and another lord geller client said it would review its ad assignment
meanwhile, a new york state court judge set a hearing for monday on the agency's request for an injunction against a half-dozen former top lord geller executives who left the agency abruptly last week to start their own ad firm
the executives have indicated they felt constrained under the management of wpp group, the british firm that acquired lord geller in july 1987
since the executives quit, about 20 other lord geller employees have followed their former bosses to the new agency, lord, einstein, o'neill &amp; partners
lord geller has filed suit in new york state supreme court to try to prevent the former executives from signing its clients and hiring its workers for their new agency
lord geller employs more than 300 people and handles billings of about $245 million. billings are what companies spend on advertising; agencies usually get a percentage of billings for their work
wnbc-tv, a new york television station that has been a client of lord geller for four years, said it had notified wpp group's chief executive, martin sorrell, that it was assigning its ad business to the new agency
linda lipman, director of advertising and promotions for the station, said station executives felt they had built up a special relationship with richard lord, the former chairman and chief executive of lord geller who resigned to start the new firm, and would be ``better serviced'' at the new agency
separately, fuji photo film usa inc., based in elmsford, n.y., said it was planning to review its advertising accounts now being handled by lord geller
lord geller is the agency for fuji divisions that market audio and video tape and floppy disks
gene kern, advertising manager for fuji's magnetic products division, said the decision was made ``after studying recent changes at the agency.''
he said fuji planned to invite specific agencies to participate in the review but declined to say if lord geller or lord einstein would be invited
neither wnbc-tv nor fuji would say how much they billed through lord geller. a third lord geller client, new yorker magazine, has already indicated that it plans to drop the agency and sign on with the new firm
lord geller's biggest account is international business machines corp., based in armonk, n.y. ibm reportedly accounts for about half of lord geller's total billings, and has said it is ``concerned'' about recent events at the agency and has told the agency so
the u.s. dollar slid further against the japanese yen in early trading friday in tokyo following an overnight decline in new york, and stock prices fell sharply
the dollar opened at 125.68 yen, down from thursday's close of 126.30 yen
ken iiya of the bank of tokyo, said buyers were supporting the dollar somewhat, keeping the currency above its overnight close of 125.575 yen in new york, its lowest level there since mid-january
he said trading was quiet due to the absence of market-affecting news on the week's final day of currency dealings
on the tokyo stock exchange, the nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues, down 113.95 points on thursday, fell another 252.84 points, or 0.98 percent, to 25,528.44 in the first 25 minutes of trading
share prices in the first section were lower across the board as almost all issues posted losses, dealers said
southdown inc. has increased its offer to take over moore mccormack resources inc. to $40 in cash and securities per share, the company said thursday
southdown, which previously had offered $35 cash a share to acquire the connecticut-based cement and energy company, made the sweetened offer in a letter to paul r. tregurtha, chairman and chief executive officer of stanford, conn.-based moore mccormack
southdown offered to pay $35 cash plus debt securities valued at $5 for each of moore mccormack's 12.8 million common shares outstanding, an indicated total value of $512 million. southdown also has offered to acquire moore mccormack preferred stock and subordinated debt
the proposal came one day after moore mccormack unveiled a defensive recapitalization plan under which it would borrow up to $420 million and sell assets to finance a special dividend to shareholders of $24.60 per share in cash and debt securities with a face value of $6.62 per share
in the letter to moore mccormack, southdown president and chief executive clarence c. comer said the securities contained in its sweetened offer would carry the same financial terms as those offered under moore mccormack's recapitalization plan
moore mccormack's board has rejected southdown's $35 a share cash offer and an earlier $31 a share bid that began the takeover battle on feb. 23
officials from moore mccormack could not be reached for comment thursday afternoon
both firms are in the cement and concrete businesses, with minor holdings in oil and gas
also thursday, a southdown subsidiary, sdw inc., amended its pending tender offer to increase the price to be paid for share of common stock of moore mccormack to $40 per share. sdw offered to decrease the maximum number of common shares that it would purchase in the tender offer to about 11.4 million shares, on a fully diluted basis
southdown's offer expires at midnight on wednesday, april 6, unless extended
